     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "THE DETECTION LOGIC. Now the host stops merely tolerating the microbe and starts detecting it. The trick is pattern recognition: PAMPs (pathogen-associated molecular patterns) are conserved structures a whole class of microbes must keep — LPS on every gram-negative, viral nucleic acids, CpG-rich DNA. PRRs (pattern-recognition receptors) read them. The payoff Gregg stresses: find one way to detect LPS and you detect every gram-negative with a single receptor — and because the microbe needs that structure to live, it can’t discard it to escape. PRRs split into two jobs: endocytic receptors that drive uptake (phagosome formation), and Toll-like receptors that drive cytokine signaling."
     },
     {
      "t": "cq",
      "x": "PAMPs = conserved microbial patterns; PRRs detect them. Endocytic PRRs → uptake; TLRs → cytokine signaling. (detection logic)"
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "TLRs are a family of ~13 PRRs: an extracellular leucine-rich-repeat domain for PAMP binding and a cytoplasmic TIR signaling domain."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "TLR localization: some on the cell surface (membrane PAMPs), some in endosomes (engulfed nucleic acids)."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "TLRs and the PAMPs they recognize — surface vs endosomal placement maps to membrane components vs nucleic acids."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "THE FOUR TLRs TO MEMORIZE. Gregg narrows the whole family to four. TLR4 recognizes LPS (gram-negatives) and sits on the surface of macrophages, dendritic cells, and mast cells — he flags it as having shown up on COMLEX. The other three are endosomal nucleic-acid sensors: TLR7 (viral RNA, on plasmacytoid dendritic cells), TLR8 (viral RNA, on NK cells), and TLR9 (CpG-rich DNA from bacteria and DNA viruses, on plasmacytoid dendritic cells). Note the pattern: surface TLRs read membrane PAMPs; the nucleic-acid TLRs live in endosomes where engulfed RNA/DNA gets exposed — and pDCs, sensing both RNA (TLR7) and DNA (TLR9), respond the same potent way to either."
     },
     {
      "t": "cq",
      "x": "TLR4 = LPS, surface, macro/DC/mast. TLR7 = viral RNA, pDC. TLR8 = viral RNA, NK. TLR9 = CpG DNA, pDC. (the four flagged TLRs)"
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "WHERE THE TWO RECEPTOR CLASSES MEET. The two jobs cooperate. An endocytic receptor can bind a pathogen and start uptake; as the phagosome forms, TLRs get inserted into its membrane, and now the compartment signals as well as digests. So “uptake receptor” and “signaling receptor” are not mutually exclusive — a single phagosome can do both."
     },
     {
      "t": "key",
      "x": "Sort every PRR by output: endocytic → uptake (no cytokines), TLR → cytokine signaling. Then sort the four TLRs by location: TLR4 surface (LPS); TLR7/8/9 endosomal (nucleic acids)."
     },
     {
      "t": "pearl",
      "x": "TLR4 = LPS is the single most board-flagged receptor here (“shown up on COMLEX”). If a stem says gram-negative sepsis or LPS recognition, TLR4 + CD14/MD2 is the answer."
     },
     {
      "t": "confusion",
      "x": "Don’t memorize all ~13 TLRs — Gregg wants four (4/7/8/9). And keep cells straight: viral RNA splits into TLR7 (pDC) vs TLR8 (NK); CpG DNA is TLR9 (pDC)."
     },
     {
      "t": "p",
      "x": "ReClaude A: PAMPs are conserved microbial patterns; PRRs detect them. The four TLRs: TLR4 (LPS, surface, macrophage/DC/mast), TLR7 (viral RNA, pDC), TLR8 (viral RNA, NK), TLR9 (CpG DNA, pDC). Surface TLRs read membrane PAMPs; TLR7/8/9 are endosomal nucleic-acid sensors. Endocytic PRRs drive uptake; TLRs drive cytokine signaling."
     }
