      "x": "DIVISION OF LABOR. Each has a signature beyond the shared triad. TNF-α is the dominant driver of endothelial activation — “if I had to pick one,” Gregg says, it’s TNF-α (developed in LO 3.5). IL-1β is the primary fever cytokine: it raises prostaglandin E2, which acts on the hypothalamus to raise the temperature set point (and drives the muscle aches via PGE2). IL-6 has three primary jobs: it drives the acute-phase response (LO 3.7), boosts neutrophil output from marrow, and produces the local warmth by ramping glucose metabolism so incoming cells have ATP — “soldiers need energy.”"
