      "t": "p",
      "x": "THE ANTIBODY IS THE BCR WITHOUT ITS TAIL. When a B cell meets its antigen it becomes a plasma cell, a dedicated protein factory that makes antibody. The trick is simple: the plasma cell takes the B-cell receptor, removes the transmembrane domain, and secretes it. Same two heavy and two light chains, same variable regions, same antigen specificity — it just loses the membrane anchor so it can float free. So the difference between BCR and antibody is location, not specificity: one is membrane-bound, the other secreted."
