      "t": "p",
      "x": "IC clearance in spleen/liver: RBC CR1 binds C3b-tagged complexes; Factor I cleaves C3b to release the complex to fixed macrophages. Partial deficiency of Factor I, C1, or C3 reduces clearance → Type III susceptibility. THE PARTIAL-DEFICIENCY PARADOX. Here is the subtlety Gregg was careful about, and it makes a great question. A deficiency in Factor I, C1, C3 (or a CR1 defect) reduces complex clearance and predisposes to Type III disease — but it must be a partial deficiency, a lower-than-normal level, not complete loss. Why? Because the pathology of Type III depends on complement activation. If you completely ablated these factors, complement could not be activated, so no frustrated phagocytosis, no disease. A reduced level is the worst of both worlds: enough complement to drive inflammation, too little clearance to remove the complexes. So you can predict that a patient with recurrent Type III disease likely carries a partial deficiency in one or more of these factors."
