      "x": "Normal apoptotic-body clearance: C1q/MBL/pentraxins opsonize apoptotic bodies; macrophages engulf them and release IL-10/TGF-β (anti-inflammatory, Treg-inducing) — the baseline SLE loses. SLE — APOPTOSIS IS THE KEY. The lupus story is best told upstream-to-downstream, and the upstream event is a clearance failure, not the autoantibodies themselves. Normally apoptotic bodies are opsonized by C1q, MBL, and pentraxins (CRP, SAP, PTX3) and quietly engulfed by macrophages, which release IL-10 and TGF-β to keep the process anti-inflammatory and even induce Tregs. In SLE there is a deficiency in one of these opsonins — C1q is the classic culprit. Apoptotic bodies are not cleared efficiently; their weakened membranes collide and rupture into secondary necrosis, spilling nuclear antigens and TLR ligands. This is why the rash is photosensitive and falls on sun-exposed skin — UV drives apoptosis, and the lupus patient cannot clear the resulting bodies."
