      "x": "THE FOUR-STEP SPINE. Gregg's model generalizes to any autoimmune disease; T1D is the worked example (a Type IV hypersensitivity, with some Type II/III antibody contribution). Step I — generate a pool of self-reactive lymphocytes (failure of central tolerance: self-reactive T cells escape thymic deletion, usually HLA-driven; anergic self-reactive B cells sit in the lymph-node paracortex). Step II — release and chronic presence of self-Ag (the triggering event: tissue damage liberates self-Ag and matures DCs via PAMP/cytokine signaling — e.g. a Coxsackie-A virus link to beta-cell antigen release). Step III — activation of self-reactive lymphocytes (failure of peripheral tolerance: clonal expansion and differentiation proceed; anergic B cells are rescued into autoantibody producers). Step IV — destruction of target cells: Th cytokines drive inflammation and innate action, CTLs kill, autoantibodies add complement/ADCC/opsonization."
