const LO_ANSWERS = {
 "1_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Name the two branches of the immune system and give the single defining feature that separates them.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Davis opens the whole course from 30,000 feet, and the single idea she wants you to carry out of this lecture is that the immune system is built in two branches — the innate system at the top of Dr. Gregg’s master figure and the adaptive (also called acquired) system at the bottom. Almost everything in the next fifteen-odd lectures hangs off this one split, so the goal here is to install the scaffolding, not to memorize details you haven’t earned yet.</p><p>The purpose of the whole apparatus is narrower than it sounds: prevent or control infection, and patrol for things that shouldn’t be there. Davis makes the point vividly — 100% of us have a tumor right now, and almost none of us will ever need treatment for it, because the immune system clears it before it declares itself. That patrol-and-clear job is carried out by cells, organs, tissues, and molecules working together, which is the cast of characters the rest of the course introduces one at a time.</p><p>The two branches of immunity are innate and adaptive (acquired). (branch dichotomy — the course spine)</p><p>Every response is two activities: recognize that something is non-self, THEN respond to it.</p><p>Role of the immune system: defense against infection and tumors, immunosurveillance, and the autoimmunity/transplant flip side.</p><p>Layering — within each branch there are multiple means of protection (barriers, enzymes) and effector mechanisms.</p><p>TWO ACTIVITIES, IN ORDER. Before any branch can do anything, the response has to clear a two-step bar. First, recognize that something is non-self — distinguish “us” from “them.” Then respond to it, whether that means an innate response or an adaptive one. Hold onto the order, because it explains the system’s two failure modes: fail to recognize non-self and you get infection; mistakenly react against self and you get autoimmunity. The same recognition machinery that protects you is the thing that, turned the wrong way, attacks you.</p><p>LAYERING AND REDUNDANCY. Davis keeps returning to the word layering: within each branch there are multiple, overlapping ways to fight the same pathogen. Staphylococcus aureus is her running example — it causes skin infections, pneumonia, osteomyelitis, even meningitis, so the body needs different defenses in different tissues that can all recognize and clear it. That redundancy is deliberate: a defense available in the skin (say, the oxidative burst) may not be available across the blood–brain barrier, so the system layers physical barriers, enzymes, effector mechanisms, cells, and molecules so that something can respond wherever the pathogen lands.</p><p>An immune response has two steps in fixed order: recognize non-self, then respond. (recognition precedes response) CQ Failure to recognize non-self → infection; reaction against self → autoimmunity. (the two failure modes)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The innate/adaptive split is the organizing axis of the entire course. Map every later cell, molecule, and pathway onto “which branch, and what does it do there.”</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> “Two branches” = innate vs adaptive. It does NOT mean humoral vs cell-mediated (that’s a split WITHIN adaptive) or cells vs molecules (a component split).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> “100% of us have a tumor right now” — immunosurveillance runs constantly; you only need clinical help when a tumor escapes it. A memorable anchor for why the system patrols, not just defends.</p><p>ReClaude A: The two branches are innate (fast, generic, no memory) and adaptive/acquired (slow on first exposure, antigen-specific, memory-forming). They are defined by speed, specificity, and the presence or absence of memory — not by anatomy or by the cells-vs-molecules split.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "1_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>For speed, specificity, and memory, which branch owns which property — and why does &quot;specific&quot; not mean &quot;fast&quot;?</em></p><p>THE CONTRAST. If LO 1.1 named the two branches, this LO is about telling them apart on the dimensions that actually get tested: specificity, speed, memory, and what does the recognizing. Davis’s framing device is military — innate is a grenade (generic, hits everything in the vicinity, causes collateral damage), adaptive is a sniper or marksman (one precise target). That single image carries most of the distinction, and the collateral-damage half of it is where immunopathology comes from.</p><p>Innate immunity: rapid but generalized — acts within minutes to hours on the first encounter.</p><p>Innate = the grenade: non-specific, present at birth, always on, responds to conserved PAMPs, no memory.</p><p>Adaptive = the sniper: specific and targeted, acquired on encounter, improves and remembers — but slower.</p><p>HOW EACH BRANCH RECOGNIZES. This is the heart of the distinction. Innate immunity reads conserved patterns, not identities. Faced with a gram-negative Klebsiella, the innate system does not say “Klebsiella” — it says “I see LPS, and LPS isn’t human, so this is non-self.” The same goes for teichoic acid on gram-positives and mannose on fungi. These conserved structures are pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs), and the receptors that read them are pattern-recognition receptors (PRRs). So the rule is short: PRRs recognize PAMPs, and the answer they return is always generic — “bacterium” or “fungus,” never the species. Adaptive immunity, by contrast, recognizes the specific pathogen through B-cell and T-cell receptors, so only the cells that match that pathogen respond.</p><p>Innate PRRs recognize conserved PAMPs (LPS, teichoic acid, mannose) and report non-self/bacterium, never the species. (PRR–PAMP recognition)</p><p>BORN WITH IT vs ACQUIRING IT. You are born with your innate defenses — skin, tears, mucus, lysozyme — and they are always on at basal levels. The adaptive system is called acquired precisely because you are immunologically naive to a given pathogen until you encounter it; only then do you develop (acquire) immunity to it. This is why the flu shot is annual: the virus undergoes antigenic drift, so last year’s acquired immunity no longer matches, and the vaccine must be updated. The textbook calls it adaptive for a second reason — it gets better with each exposure, a point Dr. Gregg will unpack when he covers how antibodies improve over a response.</p><p>THE TIMING PAYOFF — MEMORY. The crown jewel of the adaptive branch is the memory cell. A primary (first-time) adaptive response takes about 7–10 days to develop — far too slow to be your only defense, which is exactly why innate has to act first and buy time. But once memory cells exist, a re-exposure is handled in about 2–3 days (the anamnestic response). That is the entire logic of vaccination: manufacture memory now so the real encounter is fast. Memory is faster than a primary response but still never as instant as the always-ready innate barriers — your skin is already there.</p><p>Primary adaptive response ≈ 7–10 days; memory (anamnestic) response ≈ 2–3 days; innate is faster still (already present). (the timing hierarchy) CQ Annual flu vaccination is needed because influenza undergoes antigenic drift. (why “acquired” immunity must be updated)</p><p>Representative PAMPs by class — nucleic acids, cell-wall lipids (LPS, teichoic acid), carbohydrates (mannose). Conserved, non-self, broadly shared.</p><p>Clonal expansion: one antigen-specific naive cell proliferates into many identical clones — one cell isn’t enough.</p><p>Clones differentiate into effector cells (act now, terminal) and memory cells (persist, re-activatable).</p><p>CLONAL EXPANSION AND THE EFFECTOR/MEMORY SPLIT. Here is the mechanical core of how the specific branch scales up. A naive lymphocyte (one that has never seen its pathogen) carries an antigen receptor; when that receptor finds its match, the cell undergoes clonal expansion (also called clonal proliferation) — it makes many copies of itself, all with the same specificity, because one B cell making antibody is not enough when you need billions of molecules. The expanded clones then differentiate into two fates: effector cells that do the job right now (and are terminally differentiated — they act, then die by apoptosis) and memory cells that persist, sometimes for decades, ready to re-activate. Every time you re-encounter the antigen, you remake both — so you always keep a memory bank for the next round.</p><p>HUMORAL vs CELL-MEDIATED. The adaptive branch itself splits in two by where the pathogen lives. Humoral immunity — antibodies made by plasma cells — handles extracellular threats. Davis’s room analogy is worth keeping: if the cell is this room and the hallway is outside it, antibody can stick to anything in the hallway but cannot pass through the wall. Cell-mediated immunity — cytotoxic T cells — handles intracellular threats like viruses, which must live inside a host cell to replicate. Critically, the T cell does not reach inside and kill the virus; it kills the infected host cell, and the pathogen dies with it. The kill is indirect — a point the exam loves.</p><p>Humoral immunity (antibody/plasma cells) = extracellular pathogens; cell-mediated immunity (cytotoxic T cells) = intracellular pathogens. (the where-it-lives split) CQ Cytotoxic T cells kill the infected host cell, not the pathogen directly. (indirect kill — high-yield)</p><p>Innate vs adaptive at a glance: non-specific/specific, rapid/slow, no-memory/memory, PAMP-sensing cells vs lymphocytes.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Specificity, speed, and memory are the three axes that separate the branches. Innate = generic, fast, no memory. Adaptive = specific, slow-then-fast, memory.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Do NOT equate “specific” with “fast.” Adaptive is the specific one but the SLOW one on first encounter (7–10 days). Innate leads because it’s already on.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Pathogen inside a cell (virus) → think cell-mediated (CTL kills the host cell). Pathogen outside (extracellular bacterium, toxin) → think humoral (antibody neutralizes/opsonizes).</p><p>ReClaude A: Innate is generic (PRRs read conserved PAMPs, returning “non-self,” never the species), fast, present at birth, and memoryless. Adaptive is antigen-specific (BCR/TCR recognize the exact target), slow on first exposure (7–10 days) but fast on recall via memory (2–3 days), and improves with each encounter. Grenade vs sniper.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "1_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Give one way innate signaling shapes the adaptive response and one way adaptive output redirects innate cells.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This is the conceptual heart of the lecture: the two branches do not act in a vacuum. They talk to each other constantly, in both directions, using secreted molecules — chiefly cytokines and complement — as the language. One branch tells the other “here’s what we’ve got, here’s what I need you to do.” Getting the direction of each example right (innate→adaptive vs adaptive→innate) is exactly what the exam tests, so we’ll keep flagging which way the arrow points.</p><p>WHO GOES FIRST. On a first-ever (naive) encounter, the innate system always responds first, and the adaptive system follows only if the innate response can’t contain the pathogen. The reason is timing: a primary adaptive response needs 7–10 days, and “we’d be sick and dying all the time” if that were our first line. Innate is the right-there, ready-to-go response that buys the days adaptive needs. The one twist: on a re-exposure, adaptive memory can effectively lead, then recruit innate — so “innate first” is a first-encounter rule, not an absolute.</p><p>On a naive encounter, innate responds first; adaptive follows (7–10 days) only if innate fails to contain the pathogen. (innate-first timing)</p><p>Dr. Gregg’s master figure — innate at top, adaptive at bottom; the through-line for the first ~15 lectures.</p><p>Inflammation is initiated in the innate response and can carry over into the adaptive response; it both clears and contains pathogens.</p><p>The two branches do not act in isolation — innate generally responds first and then informs/regulates the adaptive response.</p><p>IMMUNOPATHOLOGY — WHEN THE GRENADE HURTS YOU. Before the directional examples, anchor the cost side. When you have the flu and feel achy, feverish, and chilled, that is not the bug — that is your immune system. The body aches and fever are your cytokines at work; the inflammation that clears pathogens also damages your own tissue, and that damage is immunopathology. Davis notes you’ll meet it again throughout pathology — a great deal of organ damage in disease is the immune response, not the pathogen. Even fever is a deliberate immune tactic: pathogens grow best at 37°C, so raising body temperature slows their replication — the same logic as a refrigerator slowing food spoilage — buying the adaptive system time to catch up.</p><p>Flu malaise (aches, fever, chills) is host cytokine activity — immunopathology, not direct viral damage. (“that’s not the bug”) CQ Fever slows pathogen replication (optimal growth ≈ 37°C), buying the adaptive response time. (fever ≈ refrigerator analogy)</p><p>INNATE REGULATES ADAPTIVE. Now the first arrow. Innate outputs shape the adaptive response in two concrete ways. First, complement proteins can activate B cells — they lower the B-cell activation threshold, so less antigen is needed to switch a B cell on. Second, phagocytes (macrophages, neutrophils) and infected cells secrete cytokines that direct which way B and T cells differentiate — whether a CD4 cell becomes a TH1, TH2, or TH17, and which antibody isotype a B cell should make (IgA in the mucosa, IgG in tissue). In other words, the innate response doesn’t just buy time; it instructs the adaptive response on what to become.</p><p>ADAPTIVE REGULATES INNATE. The reverse arrow runs whether it’s a first encounter or a memory response. T cells produce cytokines that order macrophages and neutrophils to be more aggressive — “you’re not killing fast enough, ramp it up.” And antibodies bound to a pathogen act as handles: macrophages and neutrophils (innate cells) grab those antibody handles to phagocytose and destroy the pathogen by oxidative burst. So the specific branch reaches back and makes the generic branch both harder-hitting and better-aimed. The whole point: the branches form one integrated, mutually-regulating system, not two parallel machines.</p><p>Innate→adaptive: complement lowers the B-cell activation threshold; innate cytokines steer B/T differentiation and isotype. (direction: innate regulates adaptive) CQ Adaptive→innate: antibody handles let phagocytes grab pathogens; T-cell cytokines push macrophages to kill harder. (direction: adaptive regulates innate)</p><p>The innate response can inform and regulate the adaptive response, and vice versa — a two-way regulatory loop.</p><p>Innate regulates adaptive: complement activates B cells; innate-cell cytokines guide B/T activation and differentiation.</p><p>Adaptive regulates innate: T-cell cytokines boost phagocyte killing; antibodies opsonize — “handles” for phagocytes.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The branches form one integrated system that regulates itself in BOTH directions. The exam tests which way the arrow points, so tag every example innate→adaptive or adaptive→innate.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Fever as a refrigerator: pathogens grow best at body temp, so a fever slows them like a fridge slows spoilage — immunopathology that’s actually working for you.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Innate→adaptive = complement activating B cells + innate cytokines steering differentiation. Adaptive→innate = antibody opsonization + T-cell cytokines driving phagocytes. Don’t flip them.</p><p>ReClaude A: Innate→adaptive: complement proteins activate B cells and lower their activation threshold, and innate cytokines direct B/T differentiation and antibody isotype. Adaptive→innate: T-cell cytokines make phagocytes more aggressive, and antibody bound to a pathogen opsonizes it, giving phagocytes handles to grab. The two branches continuously regulate each other.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "1_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What does a lymph node filter versus the spleen, and why is the node called &quot;the lymphocyte bar&quot;?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The last LO situates immunity in its two transport-and-filter systems: the blood and the lymphatics. The cells and proteins of immunity circulate through blood, traffic into the lymphatic system, and get filtered at two great checkpoints — the lymph nodes and the spleen. Dr. Gregg devotes an entire later lecture to the lymphatic system, so here Davis just plants the roles you’ll build on.</p><p>BLOOD AS THE HIGHWAY. Every immune cell and protein circulates in and out of the bloodstream. The cast: myeloid cells (neutrophils, macrophages, dendritic cells, basophils, eosinophils, mast cells), lymphocytes (T cells, B cells, and — don’t forget — NK cells), erythroid cells (red cells and platelets), and soluble proteins (complement, clotting factors). And every one of them traces back to a single origin: the pluripotent hematopoietic stem cell (HSC), which commits down a lymphoid, myeloid, or erythroid path. “Pluripotent” is the operative word — it can become anything, which is why HSC transplants can rebuild a whole blood system.</p><p>All blood cells arise from the pluripotent hematopoietic stem cell, committing to lymphoid, myeloid, or erythroid lineages. (single origin of blood cells)</p><p>Everything begins at the pluripotent HSC (upper left) → lymphoid / myeloid / erythroid commitment.</p><p>Immune cells/proteins circulate in and out of blood: myeloid, lymphoid (incl. NK), erythroid, plus complement and clotting factors.</p><p>LYMPH vs INTERSTITIAL FLUID — ONLY LOCATION DIFFERS. The lymphatic system is a network of vessels and nodes that circulates and filters plasma-derived fluid. Davis’s clean rule: the only difference between interstitial fluid and lymph is location. Fluid that bathes the tissues is interstitial fluid; the instant it drains into a lymphatic vessel, the same fluid is called lymph. The lymphatic vessels carry it to lymph nodes for filtering. This matters because it sets up the two-filter division you’ll use constantly: lymph nodes filter the tissue-derived lymph; the spleen filters the blood.</p><p>Interstitial fluid and lymph are the same fluid — the only difference is location (lymph = once it’s inside lymphatic vessels). (lymph vs interstitial fluid) CQ Lymph nodes filter tissue fluid (lymph); the spleen filters blood. (the two great filters)</p><p>THE NODE AS COMMAND CENTER. Lymph nodes do more than strain debris — they are where the adaptive response is initiated. When you get a paper cut on a finger, the response does not start at the cut; antigen drains to the nearest lymph node (for a finger, the axillary node), where it is presented to T cells and the response is organized. The node is also where B cells and T cells interact — Davis quotes a colleague calling it “the lymphocyte bar”, where B and T cells “hook up.” T cells help activate B cells (B cells can self-activate, but it’s far less common), and activated B cells proliferate and differentiate in the follicles, forming germinal centers. For blood-borne pathogens, the same initiation happens in the spleen instead.</p><p>The adaptive response to a tissue pathogen is initiated in the nearest draining lymph node (finger → axillary), not at the wound. (where the response starts) CQ Lymph nodes are where B and T cells interact (“the lymphocyte bar”); T-cell help activates B cells in germinal centers. (node = B/T meeting place)</p><p>The lymphatic network: vessels and nodes that circulate and filter lymph; interstitial fluid drains in and is returned to blood.</p><p>Lymphatic vessels run alongside the vasculature; tissue fluid enters, is filtered at nodes, and rejoins the bloodstream.</p><p>Lymph nodes filter interstitial fluid/lymph, remove antigens, present to T cells, and host the B–T interactions that start adaptive responses.</p><p>Inside the node: B-cell follicles, surrounding T-cell zones, and germinal centers where activated B cells proliferate and differentiate.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two filters, two fluids: lymph nodes filter tissue-derived lymph; the spleen filters blood. The node is also the site where the adaptive response is actually initiated.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Tissue/skin infection → nearest draining lymph node organizes the response (finger → axillary). Blood-borne infection → spleen does the same job.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> “The lymphocyte bar” — the lymph node is where B and T cells meet and hook up to launch the adaptive response. A memorable handle for why nodes are command centers, not just filters.</p><p>ReClaude A: Blood is the highway: all immune cells/proteins circulate through it, arising from the pluripotent HSC. The lymphatic system carries tissue-derived lymph (same as interstitial fluid, only the location differs) to lymph nodes, which filter it, remove antigen, and — critically — initiate the adaptive response by hosting B–T interactions. Nodes filter lymph; the spleen filters blood.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "2_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Name the skin and mucosal physical barriers and the one job they all serve.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Gregg runs this whole lecture as a thought experiment: you are the pathogen, walking up on a human host that is, frankly, excellent real estate — and everything you meet first is already in place before any immune cell wakes up. These are the standing defenses, not induced ones. The physical barriers are the literal walls you have to breach to colonize, and colonization is the whole game: get a foothold, grow, build a biofilm, and you win. The host’s entire barrier strategy is aimed at denying that foothold.</p><p>SKIN. The cutaneous barrier is layered. The stratum corneum — the outer dead keratinocyte layer — constantly sloughs off and carries attached microbes with it, so the surface keeps shedding its colonizers. Tight junctions between epithelial cells are the load-bearing seal: they physically block microbes from slipping into deeper tissue. That seal is such a good target that toxins are built to break it — Clostridioides difficile toxins disrupt tight junctions, which lets the organism into tissue but also lets fluid pour into the gut lumen, producing diarrhea. Tight junctions are also the door the host itself opens later to move immune cells across epithelium.</p><p>Tight junctions block microbial invasion into deep tissue and are a virulence-toxin target (e.g. C. difficile). (physical seal + toxin target)</p><p>Epithelial barriers of skin and mucosa: stratum corneum shedding, tight junctions, and the mucus layer keep microbes out of deep tissue.</p><p>MUCUS AND THE ESCALATOR. On mucosal surfaces, mucus does two jobs. First, it traps inhaled or ingested material; in the respiratory tract the mucociliary escalator then sweeps the trapped load up to the pharynx, where you swallow it down to gastric acid — which, Gregg points out, is why you swallow all day long. Second, mucus creates distance: a microbe binding the mucus surface still has to cross that gap to reach a host cell, which is exactly why pili exist (long fibers that reach through mucus to the cell surface). In cold season, thinner mucus plus people huddling indoors hands respiratory pathogens an easier reach — a concrete reason colds spread when they do.</p><p>The mucociliary escalator traps microbes in mucus and sweeps them to the pharynx to be swallowed into gastric acid. (respiratory physical clearance)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Standing barriers exist to deny colonization — the microbe’s foothold-and-grow step. Every barrier mechanism is best read as “how does this stop a microbe from establishing here?”</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> A tight-junction–disrupting toxin (e.g. C. difficile) means two things at once: tissue entry for the microbe AND fluid efflux → diarrhea. Read the symptom as the barrier being breached.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Biofilms are ~99% of real infections — usually multi-organism communities under a shared shield, which is why the immune system (and antibiotics) struggle once one forms. Stop colonization, stop the biofilm.</p><p>ReClaude A: Physical barriers are the skin (stratum-corneum shedding, tight junctions) and the mucosal system (mucus trapping + the mucociliary escalator, plus the spacing that forces pili). They block colonization mechanically before any immune cell is involved.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "2_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>How does the defensin mechanism differ from the lysozyme mechanism?</em></p><p>THE UNIFYING IDEA. Almost every chemical barrier in this lecture kills the same cheap way: it disrupts or perforates the membrane, and then ordinary physiologic fluid shifts do the rest by osmotic lysis. Gregg keeps returning to this — “you just create a pore and a cell lyses” — because it explains why so much of innate immunity (defensins, cathelicidins, fatty acids, and later the complement MAC) converges on pore formation: it is low-energy, you let chemistry finish the kill. Lysozyme is the one enzymatic exception, and it is the one he says shows up on boards constantly.</p><p>DEFENSINS. Defensins are antimicrobial peptides (AMPs). In the gut they are produced largely by Paneth cells in the intestinal crypts at a constitutive basal level (epithelial cells and neutrophils can be induced to make more). For the exam, the one thing to lock down is the mechanism: defensins create pores in microbial membranes. Once the pore is open the microbe cannot control fluid movement, and osmotic lysis follows. Gregg said it almost verbatim — what you need to know for the exam is that they create pores.</p><p>Defensins (Paneth cells, constitutive) kill by creating pores in membranes → osmotic lysis. (defensin mechanism — exam-flagged)</p><p>Defensins (AMPs) from Paneth cells insert into the microbial membrane and form pores; loss of fluid control → osmotic lysis.</p><p>Lysozyme hydrolyzes the β(1–4) bond between NAM and NAG in peptidoglycan, weakening the wall so the cell lyses.</p><p>Other chemical barriers: phospholipase A2, cathelicidins (LL-37), lactic/fatty acids, lactoferrin/transferrin (iron), and HCl.</p><p>LYSOZYME — the board favorite. Lysozyme is the enzyme in saliva, tears, and mucus that targets peptidoglycan. It hydrolyzes the linkage between N-acetylmuramic acid (NAM) and N-acetylglucosamine (NAG), the repeating backbone of the wall. Weaken peptidoglycan and the cell can no longer resist its own osmotic pressure, so it lyses. Because gram-positives carry thick, exposed peptidoglycan, they are the most susceptible; gram-negatives have peptidoglycan too, but it sits behind an outer membrane. Gregg flagged this one specifically — it is one he sees on the board exam all the time.</p><p>Lysozyme hydrolyzes the NAM–NAG bond in peptidoglycan; gram-positives (thick exposed wall) are most susceptible. (lysozyme target + mechanism)</p><p>THE REST OF THE CHEMICAL TOOLKIT. Phospholipase A2 clips a fatty acid off membrane phospholipids, distorting the membrane toward a leaky micelle and also generating the very fatty acids that coat skin. Cathelicidins (the human one is LL-37, a 37-amino-acid peptide) do the same membrane-disrupting, micelle-forming job, concentrated in mucosa. Lactic and fatty acids in sebaceous and sweat secretions disrupt membranes and even limit bacterial conjugation (plasmid transfer), slowing the spread of resistance. Lactoferrin (secretions/tissue) and transferrin (blood) lock up iron, a nutrient bacteria depend on — driving a literal arms race where bacteria deploy siderophores to steal iron back and the host counters with “stealth siderophores.” And hydrochloric acid in the stomach wrecks the structure of anything swallowed.</p><p>Lactoferrin/transferrin sequester iron; bacteria counter with siderophores, host counters with stealth siderophores. (iron arms race)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Defensins make pores; lysozyme is an enzyme that cleaves the NAM–NAG peptidoglycan bond. Different mechanism, different target — don’t blur “antimicrobial peptide” with “wall enzyme.”</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The recurring innate killing motif is membrane perforation/disruption → osmotic lysis. Defensins, cathelicidins/LL-37, fatty acids, and the complement MAC all use it; lysozyme is the enzymatic exception.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Two board-flagged items live here: lysozyme (“on the board exam all the time”) and the pore principle. If a stem describes peptidoglycan-bond cleavage, think lysozyme; if it describes membrane pores, think defensins/AMPs.</p><p>ReClaude A: Defensins form pores in the membrane (osmotic lysis); lysozyme is an enzyme that cleaves the NAM–NAG peptidoglycan bond (most effective against gram-positives). One perforates the membrane, the other digests the wall — both end in osmotic lysis.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "2_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>How does the microbiota act as a barrier, and what variable tracks with less inflammation?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The normal flora is itself a barrier — a biological one. By occupying surfaces and consuming resources, resident microbes deny incoming pathogens the space and nutrients they need to colonize (“colonization resistance”). Gregg’s sharpest evidence is the germ-free animal: raise an animal with no normal flora and it develops a catalog of health problems and dies readily from infection. The flora is not passive scenery; it is load-bearing innate defense.</p><p>YOU ACQUIRE IT, AND LIFESTYLE SHAPES IT. You are not born with a normal flora — you pick it up from everyone (and everything) handling you. Early colonizers (Enterobacteriaceae like E. coli) give way to Bifidobacterium, then Clostridia, and by about two to three years of age Bacteroides dominates the gut anaerobes. What tunes diversity afterward is lifestyle: a Westernized diet (high saturated fat, high carbohydrate, low fiber) lowers diversity, and lower diversity is associated with more inflammation and worse pathology when you do get infected. Aging and physical inactivity also reduce diversity — which is part of why you tell patients to eat fiber and exercise.</p><p>Greater microbiota diversity (high-fiber diet, exercise) is associated with less inflammation on infection. (diversity → less pathology)</p><p>Normal flora as a biological barrier: occupying surfaces and consuming nutrients denies pathogens the foothold they need to colonize.</p><p>A student asked Gregg about birth route, and his answer is worth keeping: a study comparing vaginal vs C-section delivery found vaginally-born infants acquired flora resembling the mother’s vaginal microbes, while C-section infants’ diversity looked more skin-derived. Whether that difference translates into disease the study didn’t establish — so hold it as an association, not a proven outcome.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> The vaginal-vs-C-section microbiome difference is real but its disease consequence is unproven — don’t overclaim it as causing specific illness.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The microbiota is a biological barrier that works by colonization resistance — occupying niches and nutrients. Diversity is the health-associated variable.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> When a stem ties diet/age/inactivity to infection severity, the bridge is microbiota diversity → inflammation: lower diversity, more inflammatory pathology on infection.</p><p>ReClaude A: The microbiota is a biological barrier providing colonization resistance — it occupies surfaces and consumes nutrients so pathogens cannot establish. Higher diversity (fiber, exercise; lower with Westernized diet, aging, inactivity) is associated with less inflammation during infection.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "2_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What are the alternative C3 and C5 convertase formulas, and what flips one into the other?</em></p><p>THE UNIFYING IDEA. Complement is a set of &gt;30 proteins, made mostly in the liver and always present in blood and tissue. Gregg’s framing of the alternative pathway is the key to not drowning in it: it is spontaneous. There is no antibody, no pattern receptor, no “detection” — C3 is constantly ticking over on its own, and the only reason it doesn’t destroy your tissues is that your cells carry regulators to shut it down. On a microbe (no regulators), the same process runs to completion. He warns you up front: complement is extremely important and extremely annoying to learn — both are true.</p><p>C3 TICKOVER. The pathway starts when water hydrolyzes C3, exposing a reactive site and producing iC3(H2O) (the text also calls it soluble C3b — same thing). This hydrolyzed C3 binds factor B; wherever B goes, factor D follows and cleaves B into Ba and Bb. (Convention: the small ‘b’ fragment is the larger piece, small ‘a’ the smaller — counter-intuitive, but Gregg admits he didn’t design it.) The result, iC3Bb, is the soluble (fluid-phase) C3 convertase. It is transient — it hovers, deposits the first C3b covalently onto a nearby surface, and dissipates. That first surface-bound C3b is the seed of everything downstream.</p><p>The alternative pathway begins with spontaneous C3 tickover: water-hydrolyzed C3 + factor B (cleaved by factor D) = the soluble C3 convertase. (spontaneous initiation)</p><p>Complement: &gt;30 proteins, made in the liver, constitutively present; three functions — lysis, opsonization, inflammation.</p><p>C3 tickover: water hydrolyzes C3 (iC3/H2O), which binds factor B; factor D cleaves B → soluble C3 convertase deposits the first surface C3b.</p><p>Alternative pathway overview — spontaneous on any surface, stopped only on host cells that carry regulators.</p><p>THE TWO CONVERTASES — the formulas to memorize. Once a C3b is fixed to the surface, it binds factor B, D cleaves B, and you get the surface-bound alternative C3 convertase = C3bBb. This enzyme cleaves more C3 into C3a + C3b, depositing still more C3b, which forms more C3bBb — a positive-feedback amplification loop that coats the microbe in C3b. Add one more C3b right next to the convertase and its active site shifts: now it grabs and cleaves C5. That is the alternative C5 convertase = C3bBb3b. Two formulas, one extra C3b apart — that single addition is the whole difference between “make more C3b” and “start the membrane attack complex.”</p><p>Alternative C3 convertase = C3bBb; add one C3b → C5 convertase = C3bBb3b (active site shifts to C5). (convertase formulas)</p><p>Surface C3bBb cleaves more C3 → more C3b → more convertase: the amplification loop that coats the microbe.</p><p>Properdin (factor P) binds and stabilizes surface C3bBb, prolonging C3 cleavage and C3b deposition.</p><p>Factor H binds C3b and recruits factor I to cleave it to iC3b — capping amplification so C3 isn’t exhausted on a few cells.</p><p>PROPERDIN, AND THE FIRST REGULATORS. Two opposing forces tune the loop. Properdin (factor P) binds the surface C3bBb and stabilizes it, extending its half-life so it deposits more C3b — it pushes amplification up. Pulling the other way, factor H binds C3b and lets factor I cleave it to iC3b (and on to C3d), which can no longer bind factor B. Gregg’s point about factor H/I is economic: if amplification ran unchecked you</p><p>would dump all your C3 onto a handful of bacteria when there are millions, so H/I ration C3b per cell to spread limited C3 across the whole population. (We’ll see in LO 2.6 that the same iC3b→C3d cleavage is what lets B cells respond — remember this when we get there.)</p><p>Properdin stabilizes the convertase (amplifies); factor H + factor I cleave C3b to iC3b (rations C3). (amplify vs throttle)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> C3 convertase = C3bBb; C5 convertase = C3bBb3b. One extra C3b shifts the active site to C5. Do NOT import C4b2a / C4b2a3b — those are the classical/lectin convertases (Lec 3).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Gregg’s naming pain made simple: little ‘b’ = the BIG fragment, little ‘a’ = the small one. So C3b/C5b are the surface-builders, C3a/C5a the soluble messengers.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Read the alternative pathway as one amplification loop with two control knobs: properdin turns it up, factor H/I turn it down. Everything else (opsonization, MAC) hangs off how much C3b that loop deposits.</p><p>ReClaude A: The alternative C3 convertase is C3bBb (surface-bound, made via spontaneous C3 tickover + factor B/D); it amplifies C3b deposition. Adding one more C3b gives the C5 convertase C3bBb3b, which cleaves C5 to begin the MAC. Properdin stabilizes the convertase; factor H/I cleave C3b to ration it.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "2_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What are complement’s three functions, and which complement defect causes recurrent Neisseria?</em></p><p>THE THREE FUNCTIONS. Everything complement does sorts into three jobs, and Gregg wants them cold: lysis (kill the microbe outright), opsonization (tag it for phagocytes), and inflammation (recruit the cells that do the killing). They work hand in hand — inflame to bring in phagocytes, opsonize so those phagocytes can grab on, and lyse what you can directly. The two phagocytes that get recruited are the same ones from micro: neutrophils and macrophages.</p><p>Complement’s three functions: lysis (MAC), opsonization (C3b/CR1), inflammation (C3a/C5a). (three functions — memorize)</p><p>OPSONIZATION NEEDS A RECEPTOR. Coating a microbe in C3b only matters because phagocytes carry complement receptor 1 (CR1), which is essentially a C3b receptor. CR1 binds the surface C3b, giving the cell a handle to engulf the organism into a phagosome that fuses with a lysosome. Gregg defines it crisply — opsonization is enhancing phagocytosis through the complement system. This is exactly why encapsulated bacteria are complement-dependent: a capsule exists to mask the surface so phagocytes have nothing to grab; C3b deposited on the capsule restores a handle. The C3a released during cleavage is the chemotactic signal pulling neutrophils and macrophages in.</p><p>Opsonization = C3b coats the microbe and phagocyte CR1 binds it → why encapsulated bacteria depend on complement. (C3b/CR1 + capsule logic)</p><p>Macrophage CR1 (C3b receptor) binds surface-bound C3b on the bacterium, driving complement-mediated phagocytosis (opsonization).</p><p>The phagosome fuses with a lysosome; H+ pumped in lowers the pH and activates hydrolytic enzymes that destroy the microbe.</p><p>Adding one C3b to C3bBb makes the C5 convertase (C3bBb3b), which cleaves C5 → C5a (chemotaxis) + C5b (seeds the MAC).</p><p>LYSIS — THE MEMBRANE ATTACK COMPLEX. The C5 convertase (C3bBb3b) cleaves C5 into C5a (a potent chemoattractant, even stronger than C3a) and C5b, which stays near the surface and seeds the terminal cascade. The assembly order is pure recruitment, only one cleavage having happened: C5b → C6 → C7 (C7 inserts into the membrane and anchors the complex) → C8 (solidifies the insertion) → C9, which polymerizes into a pore. Pores again — fluid rushes in and out and the cell dies by osmotic lysis, the free kill. That terminal C5b–C9 structure is the membrane attack complex (MAC).</p><p>MAC assembles C5b→C6→C7 (membrane insertion)→C8→C9 (polymerizes into the lytic pore). (MAC order)</p><p>Membrane attack complex: C5b–C8 anchors the complex; polymerized C9 forms the transmembrane pore → osmotic lysis.</p><p>C3a/C5a as anaphylatoxins: locally recruit neutrophils/macrophages and activate mast cells to promote inflammation.</p><p>Complement-deficiency table: terminal (C5–C9/MAC) defects → recurrent Neisseria; early defects → broad encapsulated-organism susceptibility.</p><p>NEISSERIA, AND THE ANAPHYLATOXIN PARALLEL. The deficiency table has one board-critical row: a defect anywhere in C5–C9 wrecks the MAC and gives recurrent Neisseria meningitidis — Gregg says remember that for boards, because the MAC is the primary way you kill meningococcus. Separately, C3a and C5a are anaphylatoxins: locally they recruit phagocytes and activate mast cells (which sit around blood</p><p>vessels) to release histamine and drive inflammation. Let them go systemic and you activate mast cells body-wide → vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, adhesion-molecule upregulation → anaphylactic shock. That is the same three-effect vascular collapse TNF-α produces in septic shock (LPS-driven) — different trigger, identical hemodynamics, and a comparison worth holding onto for Lec 3.</p><p>A C5–C9 (MAC) defect → recurrent Neisseria meningitidis. (terminal-complement board flag) CQ Systemic C3a/C5a → mast-cell histamine → anaphylactic shock (same triad as TNF-α septic shock). (anaphylatoxin ↔ septic-shock parallel)</p><p>Anaphylactic shock: systemic mast-cell activation → vasodilation, capillary leak, bronchoconstriction → hypotension and airway compromise.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three functions, three mediators: lysis = MAC (C5b–C9), opsonization = C3b–CR1, inflammation = C3a/C5a. Anchor every complement detail to which of these three it serves.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Terminal (C5–C9 / MAC) deficiency → recurrent Neisseria. Don’t default to “C3” for this stem — early-component loss gives broad encapsulated-organism problems, not the meningococcal signature.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Anaphylatoxin shock (C3a/C5a) and septic shock (TNF-α) converge on the SAME three vascular effects. If a stem lists vasodilation + capillary leak + adhesion upregulation, identify the trigger, not a new mechanism.</p><p>ReClaude A: Lysis (the MAC, C5b–C9 forming a pore), opsonization (C3b bound by phagocyte CR1), and inflammation (C3a/C5a recruiting neutrophils/macrophages and activating mast cells). The cells involved are neutrophils and macrophages (phagocytes) and mast cells (anaphylatoxin targets).</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "2_6": {
  "answer": "<p><em>How do the early regulators (DAF vs MCP/factor H) differ from the late one (CD59)?</em></p><p>THE UNIFYING IDEA. Complement runs spontaneously on every surface, so the question that keeps you alive is: why doesn’t it destroy your own cells? The answer is a panel of host-cell regulators that either decay the convertase or block the MAC. Two jobs at once: protect self, and ration C3 so amplification doesn’t exhaust it. Lose these regulators and the failure is not weaker defense — it is self-lysis.</p><p>EARLY REGULATORS — DAF and MCP (and factor H/I). On host surfaces, DAF (decay-accelerating factor) dissociates Bb from the convertase, decaying C3bBb so it stops cleaving C3. MCP (membrane cofactor protein) works differently — it is a cofactor that recruits factor I to cleave the surface C3b. (Soluble factor H does the H-side of the same job in fluid phase, again with factor I.) The distinction is the testable point: DAF decays the enzyme; MCP/factor H recruit factor I to cleave C3b. A student asked whether C3b inactivated by DAF can still opsonize — Gregg’s answer: DAF acts so early (on the first convertase) that you never amplify enough C3a/C3b to actually recruit and feed phagocytes, so it dies down fast.</p><p>DAF dissociates Bb (decays the convertase); MCP/factor H recruit factor I to cleave C3b. (decay vs cofactor — distinguish)</p><p>Host regulators DAF and MCP on the human cell surface: DAF dissociates Bb; MCP recruits factor I to cleave C3b — stopping the convertase on self.</p><p>PNH: a GPI-anchor synthesis defect prevents DAF/CD59 from sitting on the RBC surface, so complement lyses the red cells.</p><p>LATE REGULATORS — blocking the MAC. If the cascade reaches C5b–C8 on a host cell, two more checkpoints stop the pore. CD59 (and HRF) block C9 from joining and polymerizing, so no pore forms. S-protein, clusterin, and factor J (three distinct proteins, three sites on C7) prevent C7 from anchoring the complex to the membrane in the first place. Five molecules total guard the terminal step on self.</p><p>CD59 blocks C9 from joining C5b-8 (no MAC pore) on host cells. (late-stage MAC regulator)</p><p>PNH AND FACTOR I DEFICIENCY — the two clinical mirrors. Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria (PNH) is the regulator-loss disease: a defect in GPI-anchor synthesis means DAF and CD59 cannot be tethered to the cell surface, so complement lyses the most numerous blood cells — red cells. The lesion is the missing anchor, not a missing complement protein. The other clinically loaded regulator is factor I: deficiency both depletes C3 (unchecked consumption) and blunts the antibody response, because factor I generates the C3b cleavage product C3d, and C3d lowers</p><p>the B-cell activation threshold. That is the promised payoff from LO 2.4 — lose factor I and you become highly susceptible to encapsulated bacteria from both a complement and an antibody direction.</p><p>PNH = GPI-anchor defect → no surface DAF/CD59 → complement lyses RBCs. (PNH mechanism) CQ Factor I deficiency → depleted C3 + blunted antibody response (no C3d to lower the B-cell threshold). (factor I → antibody link)</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> PNH is a GPI-anchor defect, not a missing complement component. The regulators (DAF, CD59) are present in the body but can’t attach, so the patient’s own complement lyses their RBCs.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Recurrent encapsulated-bacteria infection + low C3 + poor antibody response → think factor I deficiency (C3d link). Recurrent Neisseria alone → think terminal MAC (C5–C9).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Regulators do two jobs: protect host cells and ration C3. Sort them by stage — early (DAF decays Bb; MCP/factor H + factor I cleave C3b) vs late (CD59 blocks C9; S-protein/clusterin/factor J block C7).</p><p>ReClaude A: Early regulators act on the convertase — DAF dissociates Bb; MCP and factor H recruit factor I to cleave C3b. Late regulators block the MAC — CD59 stops C9 polymerizing; S-protein/clusterin/factor J block C7 anchoring. They protect host cells and ration C3; losing the GPI anchor for DAF/CD59 causes PNH.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "3_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Give the ligand, location, and primary cell for TLR4, TLR7, TLR8, and TLR9.</em></p><p>THE DETECTION LOGIC. Now the host stops merely tolerating the microbe and starts detecting it. The trick is pattern recognition: PAMPs (pathogen-associated molecular patterns) are conserved structures a whole class of microbes must keep — LPS on every gram-negative, viral nucleic acids, CpG-rich DNA. PRRs (pattern-recognition receptors) read them. The payoff Gregg stresses: find one way to detect LPS and you detect every gram-negative with a single receptor — and because the microbe needs that structure to live, it can’t discard it to escape. PRRs split into two jobs: endocytic receptors that drive uptake (phagosome formation), and Toll-like receptors that drive cytokine signaling.</p><p>PAMPs = conserved microbial patterns; PRRs detect them. Endocytic PRRs → uptake; TLRs → cytokine signaling. (detection logic)</p><p>TLRs are a family of ~13 PRRs: an extracellular leucine-rich-repeat domain for PAMP binding and a cytoplasmic TIR signaling domain.</p><p>TLR localization: some on the cell surface (membrane PAMPs), some in endosomes (engulfed nucleic acids).</p><p>TLRs and the PAMPs they recognize — surface vs endosomal placement maps to membrane components vs nucleic acids.</p><p>THE FOUR TLRs TO MEMORIZE. Gregg narrows the whole family to four. TLR4 recognizes LPS (gram-negatives) and sits on the surface of macrophages, dendritic cells, and mast cells — he flags it as having shown up on COMLEX. The other three are endosomal nucleic-acid sensors: TLR7 (viral RNA, on plasmacytoid dendritic cells), TLR8 (viral RNA, on NK cells), and TLR9 (CpG-rich DNA from bacteria and DNA viruses, on plasmacytoid dendritic cells). Note the pattern: surface TLRs read membrane PAMPs; the nucleic-acid TLRs live in endosomes where engulfed RNA/DNA gets exposed — and pDCs, sensing both RNA (TLR7) and DNA (TLR9), respond the same potent way to either.</p><p>TLR4 = LPS, surface, macro/DC/mast. TLR7 = viral RNA, pDC. TLR8 = viral RNA, NK. TLR9 = CpG DNA, pDC. (the four flagged TLRs)</p><p>WHERE THE TWO RECEPTOR CLASSES MEET. The two jobs cooperate. An endocytic receptor can bind a pathogen and start uptake; as the phagosome forms, TLRs get inserted into its membrane, and now the compartment signals as well as digests. So “uptake receptor” and “signaling receptor” are not mutually exclusive — a single phagosome can do both.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Sort every PRR by output: endocytic → uptake (no cytokines), TLR → cytokine signaling. Then sort the four TLRs by location: TLR4 surface (LPS); TLR7/8/9 endosomal (nucleic acids).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> TLR4 = LPS is the single most board-flagged receptor here (“shown up on COMLEX”). If a stem says gram-negative sepsis or LPS recognition, TLR4 + CD14/MD2 is the answer.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Don’t memorize all ~13 TLRs — Gregg wants four (4/7/8/9). And keep cells straight: viral RNA splits into TLR7 (pDC) vs TLR8 (NK); CpG DNA is TLR9 (pDC).</p><p>ReClaude A: PAMPs are conserved microbial patterns; PRRs detect them. The four TLRs: TLR4 (LPS, surface, macrophage/DC/mast), TLR7 (viral RNA, pDC), TLR8 (viral RNA, NK), TLR9 (CpG DNA, pDC). Surface TLRs read membrane PAMPs; TLR7/8/9 are endosomal nucleic-acid sensors. Endocytic PRRs drive uptake; TLRs drive cytokine signaling.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "3_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Trace LPS recognition through to cytokine transcription, naming each molecule.</em></p><p>THE RECOGNITION COMPLEX. TLR4 doesn’t touch LPS directly — it needs accessory molecules. LBP (LPS-binding protein) grabs LPS and delivers it to CD14, which sits near the TLR4 homodimer. Then MD2 stabilizes the LPS on TLR4. That assembled complex (LPS·CD14·MD2·TLR4) changes the shape of TLR4’s cytoplasmic TIR domain, and the conformational change is what lets the adaptor MyD88 dock. Recognition is therefore a small committee, not a single handshake.</p><p>TLR4 recognizes LPS via accessories: LBP → CD14, with MD2 stabilizing LPS → TIR-domain change → MyD88 docks. (TLR4 recognition complex)</p><p>TLR signaling output: the NF-κB–induced cytokines that drive the inflammatory response.</p><p>LPS recognition by TLR4: LBP hands LPS to CD14; MD2 stabilizes it on the TLR4 homodimer, changing the TIR domain.</p><p>Signaling cascade: MyD88 → IKK → phosphorylates IκB → frees NF-κB → nucleus → cytokine transcription.</p><p>THE NF-κB CASCADE. Once MyD88 binds, the cascade is worth knowing as a clean chain: MyD88 → activates IKK (IκB kinase) → IKK phosphorylates IκB → phosphorylated IκB releases NF-κB. Free NF-κB, a cytoplasmic transcription factor, translocates through the nuclear pore, binds gene promoters, and drives cytokine production. The one inhibitor to keep straight is IκB — it holds NF-κB hostage until IKK phosphorylates it. The five cytokines this produces are the subject of LO 3.4: IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8, IL-12.</p><p>Cascade: MyD88 → IKK → phosphorylates IκB → releases NF-κB → cytokine transcription. (NF-κB cascade order)</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> If a stem gives “LPS recognition needs which helper molecules?” the answer set is LBP, CD14, MD2 (not a kinase, not a cytokine).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Read it as one inhibitor being removed: NF-κB is chained to IκB; IKK phosphorylates IκB, NF-κB is freed, cytokines get transcribed. This same cascade later triggers NLRP3.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> IKK (the kinase) phosphorylates IκB (the inhibitor). Students invert these or phosphorylate NF-κB itself — it’s IκB that gets phosphorylated and lets NF-κB go.</p><p>ReClaude A: LPS is presented by LBP→CD14 with MD2 stabilizing it on the TLR4 dimer, changing the TIR domain so MyD88 docks. Cascade: MyD88 → IKK → phosphorylates IκB → releases NF-κB → nucleus → transcription of IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8, IL-12.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "3_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What do NLRs vs RLRs sense, where, and what does each signal toward?</em></p><p>CYTOPLASMIC SENSORS. TLRs watch the surface and endosomes; two more PRR families watch the cytoplasm, where intracellular pathogens hide. NLRs (NOD-like receptors), chiefly NOD1 and NOD2, detect degraded peptidoglycan fragments inside the cell. When NOD binds its ligand it dimerizes and signals through a CARD domain to RIPK2, which activates TAK1 → IKK → NF-κB — converging on the same cytokine output as TLR signaling. The point: the cell has cytoplasmic backup for bacteria that get inside.</p><p>NLRs (NOD1/2) are cytoplasmic sensors of intracellular peptidoglycan, signaling via RIPK2 → NF-κB. (NLR localization/ligand)</p><p>NOD-like receptors: cytoplasmic sensing of degraded peptidoglycan; NOD dimerizes, recruits RIPK2 → TAK1 → IKK → NF-κB.</p><p>RIG-I-like receptors: cytoplasmic viral-RNA sensors (RIG-I, MDA-5) signaling via IRF3 → type I interferon (antiviral state).</p><p>RLRs AND THE ANTIVIRAL TURN. RLRs (RIG-I-like receptors) — RIG-I and MDA-5 — sense viral RNA free in the cytoplasm. Their signature output is different from the NF-κB cytokines: they activate IRF3, which drives type I interferon (IFN-α/β) and the antiviral state. Gregg flags IRF3 specifically — “that one you should remember.” So cytoplasmic sensing forks: NLRs feed the inflammatory NF-κB cytokines, while RLRs feed the interferon/antiviral program (developed in LO 3.4 and again in Lec 4).</p><p>RLRs (RIG-I/MDA-5) sense cytoplasmic viral RNA → IRF3 → type I IFN (antiviral state). (RLR output + IRF3 flag)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three locations, three PRR sets: surface/endosome (TLRs), cytoplasm-bacteria (NLRs → NF-κB), cytoplasm-virus (RLRs → IRF3 → type I IFN).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> IRF3 is the flagged transcription factor for the antiviral state (RLR → type I IFN). Pair it mentally with NF-κB (inflammatory cytokines) as the two PRR endpoints.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> NLRs sense peptidoglycan (bacteria); RLRs sense viral RNA. Don’t confuse the cytoplasmic NLR with the NLRP3 inflammasome — related family, but the inflammasome is LO 3.6.</p><p>ReClaude A: NLRs (NOD1/2) are cytoplasmic sensors of intracellular peptidoglycan, signaling via RIPK2 to NF-κB. RLRs (RIG-I, MDA-5) are cytoplasmic viral-RNA sensors signaling via IRF3 to type I interferon — the antiviral state. Both extend detection into the cytoplasm.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "3_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Name the five NF-κB cytokines and one defining function of each.</em></p><p>THE BIG FIVE. The NF-κB cascade outputs five cytokines Gregg wants memorized: IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8, and IL-12. Three of them — IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α — do the same job C3a/C5a did: drive increased vascular permeability, vasodilation, and adhesion-molecule upregulation. Endothelial cells contract and pull apart, tight junctions thin, fluid (and some red cells) leak into tissue (the swelling and redness), and adhesion molecules appear to recruit blood leukocytes. It is local — confined to where the cytokines are made — unless a cell carries the signal into the bloodstream.</p><p>The five NF-κB cytokines: IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8, IL-12. The first three drive local vascular inflammation. (the big five)</p><p>IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α from macrophages → vascular permeability, dilation, and adhesion molecules: the local inflammatory triad.</p><p>IL-6 functions: acute-phase response, increased neutrophil output, and local heat via glucose metabolism.</p><p>IL-8 (CXCL8) recruits neutrophils; IL-12 from macrophages activates NK cells — the macrophage–NK loop.</p><p>DIVISION OF LABOR. Each has a signature beyond the shared triad. TNF-α is the dominant driver of endothelial activation — “if I had to pick one,” Gregg says, it’s TNF-α (developed in LO 3.5). IL-1β is the primary fever cytokine: it raises prostaglandin E2, which acts on the hypothalamus to raise the temperature set point (and drives the muscle aches via PGE2). IL-6 has three primary jobs: it drives the acute-phase response (LO 3.7), boosts neutrophil output from marrow, and produces the local warmth by ramping glucose metabolism so incoming cells have ATP — “soldiers need energy.”</p><p>TNF-α = dominant endothelial activator; IL-1β = fever (↑PGE2 → hypothalamus); IL-6 = acute phase + neutrophil output + local heat. (cytokine division of labor)</p><p>IL-8 AND IL-12, THEN THE ANTIVIRAL BEAT. IL-8 (CXCL8) is the neutrophil chemokine — it recruits and arrests neutrophils (LO 3.8). IL-12, made by macrophages, activates NK cells once they reach the tissue, and activated NK cells make IFN-γ that boosts macrophage killing — the macrophage–NK loop (Lec 4). Separately runs the type I interferon antiviral state: RLR/IRF3-driven IFN-α/β makes neighboring cells refractory to viral replication — the mechanism to remember is PKR phosphorylating eIF2 to halt protein synthesis. Type I IFN is its own beat, not a member of the big five.</p><p>IL-8 = neutrophil chemokine; IL-12 → NK activation. Type I IFN (antiviral, PKR→eIF2) is separate from the big five. (IL-8/IL-12 + IFN beat)</p><p>Type I interferon antiviral state: IRF3-driven IFN-α/β acts on neighboring cells to block viral replication.</p><p>Mechanism: PKR phosphorylates eIF2 (protein-synthesis arrest); 2′,5′-oligoadenylate synthetase degrades viral RNA.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Type I IFN is NOT one of the big five — it’s the RLR/IRF3 antiviral beat. Don’t swap IL-12 out for IFN when listing the NF-κB cytokines.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Memorize the five, then attach one signature each: TNF-α (endothelium/shock), IL-1β (fever/PGE2), IL-6 (acute phase + neutrophils + heat), IL-8 (neutrophil chemokine), IL-12 (NK activation).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> IL-6 warmth = metabolic heat (“soldiers need energy”), distinct from IL-1β fever (set-point change via PGE2). Two different temperature mechanisms in the same lecture.</p><p>ReClaude A: IL-1β (fever via PGE2), IL-6 (acute phase, neutrophil output, local heat), TNF-α (dominant endothelial activator), IL-8/CXCL8 (neutrophil chemokine), IL-12 (NK activation). Type I IFN is the separate antiviral state (PKR→eIF2 halts viral protein synthesis), not part of the five.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "3_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Same three TNF-α effects — why is local protective but systemic lethal (shock + DIC)?</em></p><p>ONE CYTOKINE, TWO OUTCOMES. TNF-α is the lecture’s clearest dose/location lesson, and it parallels the C3a/C5a anaphylatoxin story from Lec 2. Locally, TNF-α produces the three vascular effects — vasodilation, increased permeability, adhesion-molecule upregulation — which is exactly the inflammation you want: fluid, complement, and neutrophils delivered to the infected tissue. Confined to one spot, it is protective. The molecule is the same in both settings; only scale and location change the outcome.</p><p>Local TNF-α = the three vascular effects confined to infected tissue → protective inflammation. (local effect)</p><p>Local TNF-α: vasodilation, permeability, and adhesion molecules confined to the infection site — beneficial inflammation.</p><p>Systemic TNF-α: body-wide endothelial activation → septic shock, plus consumed clotting factors → disseminated intravascular coagulation.</p><p>WHEN IT GOES SYSTEMIC. If infected cells circulate or LPS floods the blood, macrophages make TNF-α body-wide, and the same three effects everywhere become catastrophic: widespread vasodilation and capillary leak drop blood pressure → septic shock. Worse, the body-wide endothelial activation engages platelets and consumes clotting factors, producing disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) — the paradox of bleeding because the clotting factors are used up, leading to organ failure. Gregg’s headline: TNF-α alone can produce septic shock, which is why it is the dominant endothelial-activation cytokine. The septic-shock/anaphylatoxin parallel is worth holding: same vascular triad, different trigger (TNF-α/LPS vs C3a/C5a).</p><p>Systemic TNF-α → septic shock + clotting-factor consumption → DIC; TNF-α alone can cause septic shock. (systemic effect)</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Sepsis + paradoxical bleeding with depleted clotting factors → DIC from systemic TNF-α (consumption, not marrow failure).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Local vs systemic is the entire LO: same molecule, same three effects — confined = useful, body-wide = septic shock + DIC. Decide by location/scale, not mechanism.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> TNF-α alone can produce septic shock — the dominant endothelial-activation cytokine. Pair it with the Lec 2 anaphylatoxin (C3a/C5a) shock as the same physiology from a different trigger.</p><p>ReClaude A: Locally, TNF-α causes vasodilation, increased permeability, and adhesion-molecule upregulation — beneficial, targeted inflammation. Systemically (circulating infected cells or LPS in blood) the same effects cause septic shock, and endothelial activation consumes clotting factors → DIC. Same molecule; scale and location decide the outcome.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "3_6": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What does the NLRP3 inflammasome activate, and what does CAPS result from?</em></p><p>WHY YOU NEED IT. IL-1β is made as an inactive pro-IL-1β — NF-κB transcribes the pro-form, but it won’t bind its receptor or do anything until it is cleaved. The job of the inflammasome is to perform that cleavage. Gregg adds it explicitly because NLRP3 started appearing on COMLEX about three years ago, so it earned a place in the curriculum.</p><p>IL-1β is made as inactive pro-IL-1β; the inflammasome exists to cleave it into the active form. (why the inflammasome)</p><p>CAPS (cryopyrin-associated periodic syndrome): a gain-of-function NLRP3 mutation → excess IL-1β → recurrent fever, hives, and joint pain.</p><p>NLRP3 inflammasome: assembled on NF-κB priming + a microbial trigger, it recruits and activates caspase-1, which cleaves pro-IL-1β to active IL-1β.</p><p>THE MECHANISM. The receptor is NLRP3. It is primed by NF-κB signaling (e.g. from TLR4) and triggered by diverse microbial components. Triggered NLRP3 nucleates the inflammasome, a platform that recruits pro-caspase-1 and converts it to active caspase-1. Caspase-1 then cleaves</p><p>pro-IL-1β into bioactive IL-1β — the main fever driver (via PGE2). The chain to keep is two-stage: NF-κB makes the pro-form; the inflammasome→caspase-1 arms it.</p><p>NLRP3 assembles the inflammasome → activates caspase-1 → cleaves pro-IL-1β to active IL-1β. (inflammasome mechanism)</p><p>CAPS — THE DISEASE. The associated disease is a gain-of-function, not a loss. There is no described inhibitory NLRP3 mutation, but an overactive NLRP3 gene causes cryopyrin-associated periodic syndrome (CAPS): excess IL-1β produces recurrent fever, hives, and joint pain — the predictable consequences of chronically elevated PGE2. It’s rare (~1 in 3 million) and treated by lowering IL-1β signaling (anti–IL-1β antibody, or low-dose receptor agonist).</p><p>CAPS = gain-of-function NLRP3 → excess IL-1β → recurrent fever/hives/joint pain. (CAPS = gain-of-function)</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> CAPS is gain-of-function (too much IL-1β). There is no inhibitory NLRP3 mutation — don’t describe it as a deficiency.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> NLRP3 was added because it shows up on COMLEX. If a stem describes caspase-1 cleaving pro-IL-1β or periodic fever responsive to IL-1 blockade, think inflammasome/CAPS.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two stages: priming (NF-κB → pro-IL-1β) then activation (NLRP3 inflammasome → caspase-1 → cleaves pro-IL-1β). The inflammasome’s product that matters is caspase-1.</p><p>ReClaude A: The NLRP3 inflammasome (primed by NF-κB, triggered by microbial components) assembles to activate caspase-1, which cleaves inactive pro-IL-1β into bioactive IL-1β. A gain-of-function NLRP3 mutation causes CAPS — excess IL-1β → recurrent fever, hives, and joint pain.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "3_7": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Which cytokine drives the acute phase, and where do CRP, MBL, and SAA each route?</em></p><p>IL-6 REPROGRAMS THE LIVER. The acute-phase response is IL-6 telling hepatocytes to switch production: up with acute-phase proteins (pentraxins) and complement, down with transport proteins like albumin — more immune reactivity, less housekeeping. The three acute-phase proteins to know route into three different effector arms: C-reactive protein (CRP) → classical complement, mannose-binding lectin (MBL) → lectin complement, and serum amyloid A (SAA) → TLR signaling and phagocytosis. Pentraxins also flag apoptotic cells for clearance — a detail that returns with lupus, where faulty apoptotic-cell uptake matters.</p><p>IL-6 drives the acute phase: ↑ pentraxins (CRP, SAA, MBL) + complement, ↓ albumin. (acute-phase driver)</p><p>IL-1β (with IL-6, TNF-α) raises PGE2 → hypothalamic set point → fever; PGE2 also drives myalgia/arthralgia.</p><p>Acute-phase proteins: CRP → classical pathway, MBL → lectin pathway, SAA → TLR signaling/phagocytosis; albumin falls.</p><p>All three complement pathways (alternative, lectin, classical) converge on a C3 convertase and the membrane attack complex.</p><p>THE LECTIN PATHWAY. Once the acute phase is running, MBL becomes biologically meaningful (basal level is low). MBL complexes with the serine proteases MASP and binds surface mannose (and similar carbohydrates) on pathogens. MASP then cleaves C4 — C4b attaches to the surface (just as C3b did in the alternative pathway) — and cleaves C2. Here the nomenclature is deliberately confusing: the larger fragment is C2a. C2a binds C4b to form C4b2a, the classical C3 convertase. So the lectin pathway builds the classical convertase. From there it behaves like any C3 convertase: cleave C3, deposit C3b, and the presence of C3b lets the alternative pathway amplify alongside — two systems now spreading C3b together.</p><p>Lectin: MBL+MASP binds mannose → cleaves C4 (C4b attaches) + C2 → C4b2a = classical C3 convertase. (lectin pathway → C4b2a)</p><p>Lectin pathway: MBL+MASP binds mannose, cleaves C4 (C4b attaches) and C2 → C4b2a, the classical C3 convertase.</p><p>Classical pathway (innate-triggered here): CRP binds phosphocholine → recruits C1 → cleaves C4/C2 → the same C4b2a convertase.</p><p>THE CLASSICAL PATHWAY (innate-triggered). CRP closes the loop. CRP binds phosphocholine head groups on pathogen surfaces; bound CRP then recruits C1 (the C1q architecture plus serine proteases C1r/C1s, made by dendritic cells). C1 does exactly what MASP did: cleave C4 and C2 to build C4b2a, the classical C3 convertase — and everything proceeds to opsonization and the MAC. So three pathways, one convergence:</p><p>alternative (spontaneous, Lec 2), lectin (MBL→mannose), and classical (here, CRP→C1) all build a C3 convertase. The board-flagged corollary recurs: MBL or any complement deficiency → encapsulated-bacteria susceptibility, with terminal C5–C9 → Neisseria.</p><p>Classical (innate-triggered): CRP binds phosphocholine → C1 → C4/C2 cleavage → same C4b2a convertase. (classical via CRP/C1)</p><p>BAND NEUTROPHILS — the practical readout. Because IL-6 also drives neutrophil output, an overwhelming infection forces the marrow to release immature band neutrophils. Gregg’s rule: more than 5% bands means you are losing — the microbe is outpacing the response. It is the clinical “left shift,” and neutrophil elevations track bacterial infection.</p><p>&gt;5% band (immature) neutrophils = left shift = the infection is winning. (band-neutrophil rule)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> IL-6 is the acute-phase conductor. Route the three proteins: CRP → classical, MBL → lectin, SAA → TLR/phagocytosis — and remember lectin + classical both build C4b2a.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Watch the C2 nomenclature: the LARGER fragment is C2a, so the classical/lectin C3 convertase is C4b2a (not C4b2b). Different from the alternative pathway’s C3bBb.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> &gt;5% bands = you’re losing. A clean, testable readout of an overwhelming (usually bacterial) infection driven by IL-6 boosting neutrophil output.</p><p>ReClaude A: IL-6 drives the acute-phase response: hepatocytes make CRP (→ classical), MBL (→ lectin), and SAA (→ TLR/phagocytosis) while albumin falls. Lectin (MBL+MASP→mannose) and classical (CRP→C1) both cleave C4/C2 to build C4b2a, the classical C3 convertase. &gt;5% band neutrophils signals a losing infection.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "3_8": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Put the trafficking steps in order and name the board-flagged integrin/ligand pair.</em></p><p>THE THREE-STEP. Getting a blood leukocyte into infected tissue is a fixed sequence, and the cytokine-activated endothelium makes it possible. Step 1 — rolling: selectins on activated endothelium bind carbohydrate ligands on the leukocyte, a weak interaction that lets the cell tether and roll along the vessel wall, slowing down. Step 2 — firm arrest: a chemokine signal flips the leukocyte’s integrins to high-affinity, and they grip endothelial ligands to stop the cell. Step 3 — diapedesis: the arrested cell squeezes between endothelial cells (through the thinned tight junctions TNF-α loosened) into the tissue.</p><p>Trafficking: selectin rolling → integrin firm arrest → chemokine signal → diapedesis. (the three-step)</p><p>Step 1 — rolling: selectins on activated endothelium bind leukocyte carbohydrate ligands, a weak tether that slows the cell.</p><p>Step 2 — firm arrest: chemokines raise integrin affinity; LFA-1 binds ICAM-1 to stop the cell on the endothelium.</p><p>Step 3 — diapedesis: the arrested cell follows the chemokine gradient and transmigrates between endothelial cells into tissue.</p><p>THE BOARD PAIR. The integrin/ligand interaction to lock down is LFA-1 (on the leukocyte) binding ICAM-1 (on endothelium) — Gregg flags it as the one that shows up most on boards, with the bonus that ICAM-1 is also the rhinovirus receptor. The chemokine that activates integrins and arrests neutrophils is IL-8/CXCL8, made by the same macrophages. Neutrophils go first — they are 50–70% of blood leukocytes and arrive within about two hours — with monocytes and NK cells following. This three-step is previewed here and detailed as extravasation in Lec 4; the molecules (selectin/integrin/chemokine) are the takeaway.</p><p>Board pair: LFA-1 (leukocyte) → ICAM-1 (endothelium); ICAM-1 is also the rhinovirus receptor. (LFA-1/ICAM-1)</p><p>Summary table — the major innate cytokines (IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8, IL-12, type I IFN): releasing cell, target, and primary effects.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> LFA-1 → ICAM-1 is the board-flagged firm-arrest pair, and ICAM-1 is the rhinovirus receptor — a frequently tested two-for-one.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three molecules, three steps, in order: selectins (rolling) → integrins (arrest) → chemokine (activation/diapedesis). Neutrophils lead because they’re most abundant and fastest.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> If a stem describes weak, reversible tethering/rolling, that’s selectins; firm stop is integrins (LFA-1/ICAM-1); the cell then transmigrates (diapedesis).</p><p>ReClaude A: Selectins on activated endothelium mediate rolling (weak), chemokines (IL-8) then raise integrin affinity for firm arrest (LFA-1–ICAM-1), and the cell undergoes diapedesis into tissue. Neutrophils traffic first (most abundant, fastest), followed by monocytes and NK cells.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "4_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>For neutrophil, macrophage, mast cell, eosinophil, and NK cell — name one defining physical trait and the cell’s primary job.</em></p><p>THE CAST, AND WHO MAKES WHAT. The induced cellular response brings in the working cells, and the first thing to fix is which cell produces which cytokines, because it ranks their importance. Macrophages (tissue-resident) make all five key cytokines — IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8, IL-12 — which is why they are the central first responder. Epithelial cells make only IL-1/IL-6/IL-8. Mast cells make four (IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8) but not IL-12 — IL-12 is reserved for macrophages because it talks to NK cells (LO 4.8).</p><p>Macrophages make all five cytokines; epithelial = IL-1/6/8; mast = four (no IL-12). (cytokine source ranking)</p><p>The induced cellular response: tissue-resident macrophages/mast cells/pDCs plus recruited neutrophils, monocytes, and NK cells.</p><p>Neutrophils (PMNs): 50–70% of blood leukocytes, 3–5 nuclear lobes, short-lived, first to infiltrate (~2 h).</p><p>Neutrophil infiltration is the histologic marker of acute inflammation — they only enter tissue when called.</p><p>THE PLAYERS. Neutrophils (PMNs) are 50–70% of blood leukocytes, multi-lobed (3–5), short-lived (2–3 days), and the first responders (~2 h) — elevations suggest bacterial infection. Monocytes are the blood precursor that converts into a tissue macrophage (or dendritic cell). Macrophages are the tissue-resident phagocyte — Gregg’s “undertakers of the body,” always present to clear debris and dying cells. Mast cells (tissue-resident) and basophils (blood; a support cell for mast cells) drive inflammation via histamine. Eosinophils target parasites. Plasmacytoid dendritic cells (pDCs) make type I IFN. NK cells kill abnormal cells.</p><p>Neutrophils first (most abundant); monocytes→macrophages in tissue; NK later; pDC = type I IFN. (arrival order + identity)</p><p>Macrophage polarization: M1 (IFN-γ) are inflammatory phagocytes making the big five; M2 (IL-4/IL-10/IL-13) favor suppression and tissue repair — interconvertible.</p><p>M1 vs M2 POLARIZATION. Once a monocyte becomes a macrophage it can polarize. M1 macrophages form in an inflammatory environment (IFN-γ present): phagocytic, producing the big-five cytokines — the cell we’ve been describing. M2 macrophages form with the suppressive cytokines IL-4, IL-10, IL-13 (4 and 13 travel together): they damp inflammation and drive tissue repair (fibroblast/stem-cell support, angiogenesis). The two are interconvertible, and the M1/M2 balance becomes central later in disease and especially cancer immunity.</p><p>M1 (IFN-γ) = inflammatory phagocyte; M2 (IL-4/10/13) = repair/suppression; they interconvert. (M1 vs M2)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Mast cells make four cytokines but not IL-12 — IL-12 is the macrophage’s NK-activating signal. Don’t hand IL-12 to mast cells or epithelium.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Rank the cells by cytokine output: macrophage = all five (the key cell), epithelial = three, mast = four (no IL-12). Then know arrival: neutrophils first, NK later.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Macrophages = “undertakers of the body” (always resident, clear apoptotic cells). M1 = inflammatory (IFN-γ), M2 = repair (IL-4/13) — the split that matters for tumor immunity.</p><p>ReClaude A: Macrophages (tissue, all five cytokines, M1/M2 polarizable), neutrophils (50–70%, first responders, premier phagocyte), monocytes (→ macrophages/DCs), mast cells/basophils (histamine, inflammation), eosinophils (anti-parasite), pDCs (type I IFN), and NK cells (kill abnormal cells). M1 are inflammatory (IFN-γ); M2 are reparative (IL-4/10/13).</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "4_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Which receptors drive microbial vs apoptotic-cell uptake, and what cytokine tone follows each?</em></p><p>TWO KINDS OF UPTAKE. Phagocytosis sorts by what the cell is eating and what tone it sets afterward. Opsonic uptake of microbes runs through Fc receptors (binding antibody Fc) and complement receptor 1 (CR1) (binding C3b) — both label a microbe for receptor-mediated engulfment and a pro-inflammatory response. Opsonization just means enhanced, receptor-mediated phagocytosis, and both antibody and C3b accomplish it. TLR4 and mannose receptors can also drive uptake (TLR4 additionally signals; mannose is endocytic-only, no cytokines).</p><p>Opsonic uptake: FcR (antibody) + CR1 (C3b) → pro-inflammatory. Opsonization = enhanced receptor-mediated phagocytosis. (opsonic receptors)</p><p>Phagocytosis receptors: Fc receptor (antibody), CR1 (C3b), TLR4, mannose, and the PS-receptor — clustering triggers Syk signaling.</p><p>Apoptotic cells flip phosphatidylserine to the outer leaflet (the “eat-me” signal); the PS-receptor mediates a quiet clearance.</p><p>Overview: microbe engulfed into a phagosome → lysosome fuses → phagolysosome digests; some peptides feed later adaptive priming.</p><p>THE APOPTOTIC EXCEPTION — PS-RECEPTOR AND TGF-β. Clearing the body’s own dying cells is different. Phosphatidylserine normally sits on the inner leaflet of the membrane; when a cell undergoes apoptosis it loses that asymmetry and PS appears on the outer leaflet — the “eat-me” signal. The PS-receptor (mainly on macrophages — the undertakers) binds it and engulfs the cell, but crucially the macrophage then releases TGF-β, an anti-inflammatory cytokine. Apoptotic clearance is meant to be a quiet funeral: no inflammation, no drama. Faulty PS-mediated clearance leaves apoptotic debris around and is a problem in lupus — a detail that returns later.</p><p>PS-receptor binds phosphatidylserine (“eat-me” on the outer leaflet) → TGF-β (anti-inflammatory “quiet funeral”). (apoptotic clearance → TGF-β)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Phosphatidylserine flips outward = eat-me. Faulty PS clearance → lupus. The cytokine that keeps the funeral quiet is TGF-β.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Split uptake by target + tone: microbes via FcR/CR1 → inflammatory; apoptotic self via PS-receptor → TGF-β (suppressive). Same machinery, opposite inflammatory outcome.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Mannose receptor = uptake only (no cytokine). TLR4 = uptake AND signaling. CR1 (C3b) and FcR (antibody) are the opsonic pair — don’t lump the PS-receptor in with them.</p><p>ReClaude A: Microbial (opsonic) uptake uses FcR (antibody Fc) and CR1 (C3b), driving pro-inflammatory phagocytosis. Apoptotic-cell uptake uses the PS-receptor, which binds outer-leaflet phosphatidylserine (the eat-me signal) and triggers anti-inflammatory TGF-β — a quiet clearance whose failure contributes to lupus.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "4_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Trace the respiratory burst from NADPH oxidase to HOCl, naming each enzyme and product.</em></p><p>THE MOST IMPORTANT REACTIVITY OF THE SEMESTER. Gregg says it outright — phagocytosis is the single most important immune reactivity of the whole unit, and “everything is geared towards it.” The killing happens in two stages with a clear logic: paralyze first, then digest. Stage one is the respiratory burst (oxygen-dependent); stage two is acid digestion in the phagolysosome.</p><p>Phagocytosis logic: paralyze replication first (respiratory burst), then digest (acid hydrolases). (two-stage logic)</p><p>Late reactions: the vacuolar ATPase pumps H+ in to acidify the phagosome — required for the next step.</p><p>Phagosome–lysosome fusion delivers acid hydrolases (active at low pH) plus defensins and lysozyme to digest the microbe.</p><p>Early O2-dependent reactions (respiratory burst): NADPH oxidase → superoxide; SOD → H2O2; catalase → water; MPO → HOCl; iNOS → NO (RNS).</p><p>THE RESPIRATORY BURST. Once a microbe is in the phagosome, the cell takes a big breath of oxygen to fuel a cascade of reactive oxygen species (ROS). NADPH oxidase (phagocyte oxidase) makes superoxide (O2−); SOD converts it to H2O2; catalase detoxifies H2O2 to water, while myeloperoxidase (MPO) converts H2O2 to hypochlorous acid (HOCl) (bleach). Separately, iNOS makes nitric oxide and downstream</p><p>reactive nitrogen species (RNS). All of these damage nucleic acid — the point is to stop replication so the microbe can’t out-grow the response. (Clinically, NADPH-oxidase deficiency is the lesion behind chronic granulomatous disease — a good one to remember.)</p><p>ROS chain: NADPH oxidase→O2−; SOD→H2O2; catalase→water; MPO→HOCl; iNOS→NO (RNS). (respiratory-burst enzymes)</p><p>EVASION, AND THE IFN-γ COUNTER. Bacteria that live with oxygen carry the same protective enzymes. Staphylococcus is catalase-positive (and SOD-positive), so it detoxifies ROS and resists the early burst. The host’s answer is volume: NK-derived IFN-γ ramps ROS production to overwhelm the bacterium’s finite catalase/SOD — the macrophage–NK loop (LO 4.8). A second evasion is anatomical: Mycobacterium tuberculosis blocks phagosome acidification AND lysosome fusion, which is exactly why it survives inside macrophages.</p><p>Staph (catalase+) resists the burst; IFN-γ overwhelms it. M. tuberculosis blocks acidification + lysosome fusion. (evasion + counter)</p><p>ACIDIFY, THEN DIGEST. Before the lysosome fuses, the vacuolar ATPase pumps H+ into the phagosome to acidify it — critical, because the next step depends on low pH. The lysosome then fuses and delivers acid hydrolases (the “acid” means they work at low pH): nucleases, proteases, lipases, glycosidases — enough to dismantle every macromolecule of the now-paralyzed microbe — along with more defensins and lysozyme for good measure. No acidification, no digestion: that single dependency is what M. tuberculosis exploits.</p><p>Vacuolar ATPase acidifies the phagosome → acid hydrolases (low-pH nucleases/proteases/lipases) digest the microbe. (acidify → digest)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two stages, in order: burst (ROS/RNS) paralyzes the microbe by damaging nucleic acid; then acidification + acid hydrolases digest it. Memorize the ROS enzyme chain as the spine.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Keep the enzymes distinct: NADPH oxidase makes superoxide (deficiency → CGD); SOD → H2O2; catalase detoxifies H2O2; MPO → HOCl. Bacterial catalase/SOD is what blunts the burst.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Recurrent catalase-positive infections → think failed respiratory burst (NADPH-oxidase / CGD). A bug surviving inside macrophages by blocking acidification → M. tuberculosis.</p><p>ReClaude A: The respiratory burst (NADPH oxidase→superoxide; SOD→H2O2; catalase→water; MPO→HOCl; iNOS→NO/RNS) damages nucleic acid to paralyze replication. The vacuolar ATPase then acidifies the phagosome, and the fused lysosome delivers low-pH acid hydrolases (plus defensins/lysozyme) to digest the microbe. Paralyze first, then digest.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "4_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>List the granules in developmental order and say why band neutrophils can kill but not migrate.</em></p><p>WHY GRANULES MAKE THE NEUTROPHIL SUPERIOR. Macrophages phagocytose and that’s it; the neutrophil is the premier phagocyte because it adds granules. Granule biology is organized around development: granules appear in a fixed order, and the order maps onto neutrophil maturity. Appearance order is azurophilic (primary) → specific (secondary) → gelatinase (tertiary) → secretory/ficolin. On activation, release runs the reverse, gated by intracellular calcium — highest calcium fires the secretory/ficolin granule first.</p><p>Development order: azurophilic → specific → gelatinase → secretory/ficolin; release reverses it (calcium-gated). (granule order)</p><p>Granule appearance maps to neutrophil maturity: azurophilic → specific → gelatinase → secretory/ficolin (bands lack the last).</p><p>First released (highest Ca2+): secretory/ficolin — supplies selectin ligands and integrins for adhesion/extravasation.</p><p>Last released (lowest Ca2+): azurophilic fuses with the phagolysosome — acid hydrolases, defensins, MPO (kept inside to protect host tissue).</p><p>RELEASE ORDER = FUNCTION. At activation (highest calcium) the secretory/ficolin granule fuses first, placing selectin ligands and integrins on the neutrophil surface for adhesion/extravasation. As calcium falls, gelatinase (MMP-9) is released to break down CD31 and loosen tight junctions for transit (arginase-1 then helps reseal the junctions behind it). Specific granules supply chemokine receptors (to follow the gradient) plus lactoferrin and NGAL (which blocks bacterial siderophores, denying iron). Finally azurophilic granules fuse with the phagolysosome — not the surface — delivering acid hydrolases, defensins, and MPO; keeping them internal protects host tissue.</p><p>Secretory/ficolin = adhesion (selectin ligands/integrins); azurophilic = phagolysosome killing (kept internal). (first vs last granule)</p><p>THE BAND-NEUTROPHIL DEFECT. This is the high-yield payoff. Band (immature) neutrophils stop at the gelatinase stage — they have not yet made the secretory/ficolin granule, so they lack the selectin ligands and integrins needed to roll and arrest. The consequence: bands can phagocytose and kill, but they can’t migrate out of the blood to where the microbe is. That is why a left shift (&gt;5% bands) signals trouble — the marrow is dumping cells that can’t reach the fight.</p><p>Band neutrophils stop at gelatinase → no secretory/ficolin → can kill but can’t migrate. (band-neutrophil defect)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Development = azurophilic→specific→gelatinase →secretory/ficolin; release reverses it. First out (secretory/ficolin) = adhesion molecules; last out (azurophilic) = phagolysosome killing.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Bands CAN kill — they just can’t migrate. The missing secretory/ficolin granule means no selectin ligands/integrins, so they’re stuck in the vessel. The defect is trafficking, not killing.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Azurophilic granules fuse with the phagolysosome, not the membrane — their toxic contents are kept internal to avoid damaging host tissue (frustrated phagocytosis dumps them out — seen later in rejection).</p><p>ReClaude A: Granules appear azurophilic → specific → gelatinase → secretory/ficolin during development; release reverses this, gated by calcium. Secretory/ficolin (first) supplies selectin ligands/integrins for migration; azurophilic (last) fuses with the phagolysosome to kill. Band neutrophils stop at gelatinase, lack secretory/ficolin, and so can kill but cannot migrate.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "4_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What is a NET made of, when is it used instead of phagocytosis, and what happens to the cell?</em></p><p>THE SPIDER-MAN MOVE. When a neutrophil meets a microbe too big to swallow — a fungal hypha, a clump of bacteria — it has a last resort: it throws its own DNA. The cell extrudes a web of decondensed chromatin studded with the contents of its granules (elastase, myeloperoxidase, defensins) and the whole net traps and kills microbes extracellularly. These are neutrophil extracellular traps (NETs), and the process — a distinct programmed cell death — is NETosis. Gregg’s image was the cell flinging a sticky web like Spider-Man; the dead neutrophils plus trapped debris are what you see clinically as pus.</p><p>NETs = extruded chromatin + granule enzymes that trap/kill microbes extracellularly; the death program is NETosis. (NETs = thrown DNA web)</p><p>A neutrophil extrudes a web of chromatin coated in granule enzymes — a NET — trapping bacteria too numerous or too large to phagocytose.</p><p>WHY IT MATTERS ON THE EXAM. NETosis is the neutrophil’s answer to targets it cannot engulf, and it is destructive to host tissue too — the same enzymes that kill the microbe chew up surrounding tissue, which is why exuberant NET formation shows up in thrombosis and autoimmune flares later in the course. The key distinction to hold: phagocytosis is intracellular killing of things you can swallow; NETosis is extracellular killing of things you can’t, and it costs the neutrophil its life.</p><p>Phagocytosis = intracellular killing of engulfable targets; NETosis = extracellular killing of un-engulfable targets, at the cost of the cell. (intra vs extracellular killing)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> “Throwing DNA like Spider-Man.” The web is decondensed chromatin coated in elastase, MPO, and defensins — toxic to microbes and host tissue alike.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> NETosis is not just “messy phagocytosis.” It is a distinct, programmed neutrophil death that kills extracellularly. Confusing it with intracellular phagolysosomal killing is the classic miss.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> NETs handle what phagocytosis can’t — targets too big/numerous to swallow. Chromatin + granule enzymes form an extracellular trap; the neutrophil dies (NETosis). Dead neutrophils + debris = pus.</p><p>ReClaude A: NETosis is a programmed neutrophil death in which the cell extrudes decondensed chromatin coated with granule enzymes (elastase, MPO, defensins) as a neutrophil extracellular trap. It kills microbes too large or numerous to phagocytose — extracellular killing at the cost of the cell, and the source of pus.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "4_6": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Give the full-activation trigger for the mast cell and the anti-helminth mechanism of the eosinophil.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Three granulocytes share one theme — they store pre-formed mediators and dump them fast — but they answer to different triggers and different threats. Mast cells guard tissue barriers; eosinophils hunt helminths (worms); basophils are the circulating echo of the mast cell. The exam tests the activation routes and the signature cytokines.</p><p>Mast-cell activation routes: TLR (partial), IL-33 (partial), C3a/C5a (anaphylatoxins, partial), and IgE–FcεRI cross-linking (full degranulation).</p><p>Degranulation releases pre-formed histamine plus newly made mediators — a barrier alarm that recruits and increases vascular permeability.</p><p>Mast-cell mediators overlap functionally with TNF-α: vasodilation, increased permeability, and leukocyte recruitment.</p><p>MAST CELLS — FOUR ROUTES, ONE FULL TRIGGER. Mast cells can be partially activated by TLR ligands, by the alarmin IL-33, and by the complement anaphylatoxins C3a and C5a — but the route that produces full degranulation is IgE cross-linking on FcεRI. Antigen bridges two adjacent IgE molecules bound to the high-affinity receptor, and the cell empties. The dominant pre-formed mediator is histamine, and functionally the mast-cell output mimics TNF-α — vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, and recruitment. This is the cell at the center of immediate hypersensitivity / allergy, a thread that returns in the adaptive unit.</p><p>Mast cells: partial activation by TLR / IL-33 / C3a-C5a; full degranulation by IgE–FcεRI cross-linking. Histamine ≈ TNF-α functionally. (mast activation routes)</p><p>EOSINOPHILS — THE ANTI-HELMINTH CELL. Eosinophils are recruited and activated by IL-5 and attack worms too big to phagocytose by antibody-dependent cellular cytotoxicity (ADCC): IgE coats the helminth, the eosinophil binds the antibody Fc, and it dumps its toxic granule proteins (major basic protein) directly onto the parasite surface. This is the same throw-the-toxin-outward logic as NETosis — you can’t swallow a worm, so you poison it from outside. Basophils are the circulating counterpart of the mast cell: similar mediators, also IgE-responsive, contributing to allergy and to anti-parasite responses in the blood.</p><p>Eosinophils: IL-5 + IgE-mediated ADCC vs helminths (toxic granule proteins released onto the worm). (eosinophil = anti-helminth)</p><p>Eosinophils use IL-5 and IgE-dependent ADCC to release major basic protein onto helminths — extracellular killing of un-engulfable parasites.</p><p>Innate cells operate as a network — mediators from one cell recruit and license the next, amplifying the early response.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> See helminth/worm → think eosinophil + IL-5 + IgE ADCC. See allergy / anaphylaxis → think mast cell + IgE–FcεRI + histamine.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Mast cells have four routes but only IgE cross-linking gives full degranulation; TLR/IL-33/C3a-C5a are partial. Don’t treat the anaphylatoxins as a full trigger.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three granulocytes, three jobs: mast = barrier alarm (allergy), eosinophil = anti-helminth, basophil = circulating mast cell. Memorize each cell’s full-activation trigger and signature cytokine.</p><p>ReClaude A: Mast cells are partially activated by TLR, IL-33, and C3a/C5a but fully degranulate only on IgE–FcεRI cross-linking, releasing histamine (functionally TNF-α-like) — the allergy cell. Eosinophils use IL-5 and IgE-dependent ADCC to kill helminths extracellularly. Basophils are the circulating counterpart of the mast cell.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "4_7": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What do pDCs make, against what threat, via which receptors — and how do they differ from cDCs?</em></p><p>THE INTERFERON FACTORY. Plasmacytoid dendritic cells (pDCs) are specialists in one job: making type I interferon (IFN-α and IFN-β) against viruses. They are the body’s dominant source — Gregg put them at 80–90% of circulating type I IFN during a viral infection. Their internal TLR7 and TLR9 (sensing viral RNA and unmethylated CpG DNA) drive the IRF pathway to pour out interferon, which then induces the antiviral state in neighboring cells (the PKR / RNase L / Mx program from the induced-response slides).</p><p>pDCs = dominant source of type I IFN (IFN-α/β), ~80–90% during viral infection, via internal TLR7/TLR9. (pDC = type I IFN factory)</p><p>Plasmacytoid dendritic cells sense viral nucleic acids on TLR7/TLR9 and secrete the bulk of type I interferon, establishing the antiviral state.</p><p>WHY THEY EARN THEIR OWN LO. Conventional dendritic cells are the great antigen presenters that bridge to the adaptive system; pDCs are different — they are poor presenters but prodigious interferon producers. Keep the contrast crisp: cDC = present antigen / prime T cells; pDC = type I IFN / antiviral. That single distinction is the testable core of this objective.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> pDC = the type I interferon factory (80–90% during viral infection), driven by internal TLR7/TLR9. Distinct from conventional DCs, whose job is antigen presentation.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> cDC presents antigen; pDC makes interferon. Don’t merge the two dendritic-cell jobs — the exam separates the antigen-presenting DC from the interferon-producing pDC.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> pDCs sense virus with the same internal TLRs (7/9) used elsewhere for nucleic-acid sensing — endosomal location keeps them away from host cytoplasmic RNA/DNA.</p><p>ReClaude A: Plasmacytoid dendritic cells are the dominant producers of type I interferon (IFN-α/β, roughly 80–90% during viral infection), sensing viral nucleic acids via internal TLR7/TLR9 and establishing the antiviral state. They are poor antigen presenters — the opposite emphasis from conventional dendritic cells.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "4_8": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Why does a cell that loses MHC class I get killed by NK but hide from cytotoxic T cells?</em></p><p>THE MISSING-SELF DETECTIVE. NK cells solve a problem antibodies and T cells can’t: a virus or tumor that hides by switching off MHC class I. Cytotoxic T cells need to see peptide on MHC I to kill; a cell that drops MHC I becomes invisible to T cells. NK cells do the opposite — they read MHC I as a “don’t kill me” license, so a cell missing MHC I gets killed. This is the missing-self hypothesis, and it is the conceptual heart of the objective. Surface markers: CD56+, CD16+, CD3− (the CD3-negative is what separates NK from T cells).</p><p>NK missing-self: loss of MHC I (which licenses “don’t kill”) → NK kills. Markers CD56+ CD16+ CD3−. (missing-self + NK markers)</p><p>NK cells: CD56+ CD16+ CD3− lymphocytes that survey MHC class I and kill cells that have lost it.</p><p>Missing-self: normal MHC I delivers an inhibitory “don’t kill” signal; virus/tumor downregulation of MHC I removes the brake.</p><p>Killing uses perforin to breach the membrane and granzymes to trigger apoptosis — the same lethal hit cytotoxic T cells use.</p><p>HOW THEY KILL — AND THE TWO BALANCING SIGNALS. NK killing is governed by a balance of activating and inhibitory receptors. MHC I engages the inhibitory receptor and shuts the NK cell off; stress ligands engage activating receptors. When a cell loses MHC I, the inhibitory brake is released and activation wins. The lethal hit is the same one cytotoxic T cells use: perforin punches pores and granzymes enter to trigger apoptosis. NK cells also kill by ADCC through CD16 (FcγRIII), binding antibody-coated targets.</p><p>NK killing = perforin + granzyme → apoptosis; also ADCC via CD16. Balance of activating vs inhibitory (MHC I) receptors decides. (perforin/granzyme + ADCC)</p><p>THE IL-12 → NK → IFN-γ LOOP. Don’t lose the cytokine circuit Gregg stressed: macrophages and dendritic cells make IL-12, IL-12 drives NK cells to secrete IFN-γ, and IFN-γ activates macrophages (the M1 program) to kill what they’ve eaten. It is a feed-forward amplifier linking the phagocyte and the NK cell before adaptive immunity arrives — and the same IFN-γ later becomes the signature Th1 cytokine.</p><p>IL-12 (macrophage/DC) → NK secretes IFN-γ → M1 macrophage activation. Feed-forward innate amplifier. (IL-12→NK→IFN-γ loop)</p><p>The IL-12 → NK → IFN-γ → M1 loop: dendritic cells and macrophages and NK cells amplify each other ahead of adaptive immunity.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> NK = the missing-self killer. MHC I licenses “don’t kill”; lose it (virus/tumor) and NK kills via perforin/granzyme. CD56+ CD16+ CD3−. Also ADCC via CD16. IL-12 → NK → IFN-γ → M1.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> See downregulated/absent MHC I on a virus-infected or tumor cell → think NK killing. See antibody-coated target → think NK ADCC via CD16.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> NK is the mirror image of cytotoxic T cells. CTLs kill cells that show the wrong peptide-MHC; NK kills cells that lack MHC I. A cell hiding from T cells by dropping MHC I walks straight into the NK cell.</p><p>ReClaude A: NK cells (CD56+ CD16+ CD3−) kill by missing-self recognition: MHC class I engages an inhibitory receptor that licenses “don’t kill,” so cells that lose MHC I (virus/tumor) are killed via perforin/granzyme-induced apoptosis. They also perform ADCC through CD16, and the IL-12 → NK → IFN-γ loop activates M1 macrophages.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "5_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>From the hematopoietic stem cell, which cells come from the lymphoid vs the myeloid progenitor — and which lineage is the NK cell?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Before the adaptive system arrives, Gregg pauses to map the anatomy of the immune system — where cells are born, where they mature, and where they respond — because compartmentalization is the through-line of everything that follows. Everything starts in the bone marrow: the red marrow is the factory (the yellow marrow is fat/energy reserve), and a single hematopoietic stem cell (HSC) seeds every blood cell you own.</p><p>Red marrow (spongy bone of flat bones and long-bone epiphyses) is the hematopoietic factory; yellow marrow is fat/energy reserve.</p><p>Bone-marrow stroma: the niche where pre-B and pre-T cells develop — and where macrophages enucleate developing red cells.</p><p>The hematopoietic stem cell differentiates into the common lymphoid progenitor and the common myeloid progenitor.</p><p>THE TWO LINEAGES — AND THE ONE FACT TO NEVER MISS. Through transcription factors and cytokines, the HSC gives rise to two progenitors. The common lymphoid progenitor (CLP) makes exactly three cell types: NK cells, B cells, and T cells. The common myeloid progenitor (CMP) makes everything else — red cells, neutrophils, monocytes, mast cells, basophils, eosinophils, and megakaryocytes (platelets). The high-yield trap Gregg hammered: NK cells are lymphocytes. They function in innate immunity, but their lineage is lymphoid, right alongside B and T cells.</p><p>CLP → NK, B, T. CMP → everything else (RBC, neutrophil, monocyte, mast, megakaryocyte). NK is a lymphocyte. (two lineages + NK lineage)</p><p>The common lymphoid progenitor yields only NK, B, and T cells — NK is lymphoid despite acting in innate immunity.</p><p>The common myeloid progenitor yields granulocytes, monocytes, red cells, and megakaryocytes — “everything else.”</p><p>Marrow macrophages remove the nucleus from developing red cells before the reticulocyte exits — why mature RBCs are anucleate.</p><p>PRIMARY VS SECONDARY ORGANS. Primary lymphoid organs are where cells are made and mature — and “maturation” here means generating the antigen receptor. The bone marrow makes all cells; B cells start in marrow and finish maturation in the spleen; T cells are made in marrow but mature in the thymus. Secondary lymphoid organs (spleen, lymph nodes, MALT) are where mature cells actually respond to antigen. The macrophage cameo to remember: developing red cells are nucleated, and a marrow macrophage plucks out and eats the nucleus before the reticulocyte leaves — if a cell is being remodeled or removed, a macrophage is behind it.</p><p>Primary = made/mature (marrow all; B finishes in spleen, T in thymus). Secondary = respond (spleen, node, MALT). (primary vs secondary organs)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One HSC → two progenitors. Lymphoid = NK/B/T (NK is a lymphocyte!); myeloid = everything else. Primary organs make and mature cells; secondary organs host the response.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> NK cells are NOT myeloid. “Innate” describes function, not lineage — NK comes from the common lymphoid progenitor alongside B and T. This is the most-flagged hematopoiesis fact.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Macrophages enucleate developing red cells in the marrow — the reason mature RBCs lack a nucleus. “Major modification or removal? A macrophage did it.”</p><p>ReClaude A: Both arise from the hematopoietic stem cell: NK, B, and T cells come from the common lymphoid progenitor (so NK is a lymphocyte), while red cells, granulocytes, monocytes, mast cells, and megakaryocytes come from the common myeloid progenitor. Bone marrow makes all cells; B cells finish in the spleen and T cells in the thymus.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "5_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Match each splenic and nodal compartment to its resident cells and primary function.</em></p><p>THE COMPARTMENTALIZATION PRINCIPLE. Immature B cells leave the marrow and travel to the spleen, which has two zones with two jobs. The red pulp is the blood-handling zone: it filters blood, holds a blood reserve for trauma, and is where macrophages remove aged (~120-day) red cells. Dendritic cells and macrophages there also survey for microbes — a TLR hit triggers cytokines and phagocytosis on the spot, and dendritic cells carry captured microbes to the white pulp to prime T cells.</p><p>Red pulp = blood filter + aged-RBC removal (macrophages) + blood reserve. (red pulp function)</p><p>Newly formed naive B cells exit the bone marrow and enter the spleen as transitional cells.</p><p>Red pulp filters blood, stores a blood reserve, and is where macrophages remove aged red cells.</p><p>White pulp is the immune tissue: follicles (B cells), PALS (T cells), and the marginal zone (rapid-IgM B cells).</p><p>WHITE PULP — FOLLICLE, PALS, MARGINAL ZONE. The white pulp is the immune tissue, and B and T cells are kept separate. Follicles = B cells; the periarteriolar lymphatic sheath (PALS) = T cells. Surrounding both is the marginal zone, home to marginal-zone B cells — the emergency cell. They recognize mostly carbohydrate, respond to blood-borne antigen within hours (a normal B cell takes 7–10 days), and make only IgM, the complement-activating antibody. Something dangerous in the blood needs a response now; the marginal-zone B cell provides it.</p><p>White pulp: follicle = B, PALS = T. Marginal-zone B cell = rapid IgM vs blood-borne carbohydrate (hours, not days). (white pulp + emergency IgM)</p><p>Splenic white-pulp anatomy around the central arteriole: follicle, PALS, and marginal zone.</p><p>T cells arriving from the thymus populate the PALS (T-cell zone).</p><p>Transitional B cells become follicular (FO) or marginal-zone (MZ) B cells — and are tested for self-reactivity here.</p><p>THE LYMPH NODE — SAME LOGIC, NEW NAMES. The lymph node compartmentalizes B and T cells just like the spleen, but the names change. Follicle = B cells; paracortex = T cells; and when cells get activated they move into the medulla and exit through the efferent lymphatics into the blood, where they circulate until they find inflamed tissue. Antigen arrives the other way — via afferent lymphatics, carried almost entirely by dendritic cells (a few macrophages), which deliver microbial components to the paracortical T cells. One clinical aside Gregg flagged: damaged lymph nodes do not regenerate, though new lymphoid aggregates can form at sites of chronic infection.</p><p>Lymph node: follicle = B, paracortex = T, activated cells exit via medulla → efferent. Antigen enters via afferent (dendritic cells). (node compartments + flow)</p><p>Lymph-node compartments: B cells in follicles (germinal centers), T cells in the paracortex, and activated cells exiting through the medulla.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> PALS (spleen) = paracortex (node) = T-cell zone. Follicle = B-cell zone in both. Don’t put lymphocytes in the red pulp — red pulp is blood-handling, white pulp is immune tissue.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Marginal-zone B cell = the emergency cell. Blood-borne carbohydrate → IgM within hours. It’s why splenectomy raises the risk from encapsulated (polysaccharide-coated) bacteria.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two organs, one rule: B cells in follicles, T cells in the T-zone (PALS in spleen, paracortex in node). Red pulp filters blood; white pulp mounts the response; the marginal zone holds the emergency-IgM B cell.</p><p>ReClaude A: Spleen red pulp filters blood, removes aged RBCs (macrophages), and stores a blood reserve; white pulp is immune tissue with follicles (B cells), PALS (T cells), and a marginal zone (rapid-IgM B cells). In the lymph node, the follicle holds B cells, the paracortex holds T cells, and activated cells exit via the medulla into efferent lymphatics.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "5_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Name the three functions of the lymphatic system and one effect of OMM lymphatic-pump techniques.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW — THREE JOBS, NO PUMP. The lymphatic system is a network of vessels that drains fluid from tissues to lymph nodes, and it does three things: maintain fluid balance, absorb dietary fat, and provide immune surveillance. The key mechanical fact: unlike the cardiovascular system, the lymphatics have no heart pump. Flow is driven by skeletal-muscle movement, breathing, and a little smooth muscle, and kept one-directional by a valve system. Sedentary patients move lymph slowly — which is exactly why activity (and osteopathic manipulation) matters.</p><p>Lymphatics: no heart pump — muscle/breathing/smooth muscle + one-way valves drive flow. Backup → edema. (lymph propulsion)</p><p>One-way valves keep lymph moving forward; muscle/respiratory movement supplies the force.</p><p>Lymph is a clear, multi-component fluid — mostly interstitial fluid drained from tissues back toward the blood.</p><p>Fluid balance: afferent lymphatics drain interstitial fluid to prevent edema — the lymphatics are the tissue’s drain.</p><p>FAT ABSORPTION. Dietary lipids can’t simply diffuse into blood capillaries. They’re packaged into chylomicrons (triglyceride wrapped with cholesterol and other lipids), released, and picked up by gut lacteals — the intestinal lymphatic vessels. The lymphatics then deliver them to the blood for transport to the liver. After a fatty meal the mesenteric lymphatics run milky-white with chylomicrons. So the lymphatic system isn’t just immune plumbing; it’s the absorptive route for fat.</p><p>Dietary fat → chylomicrons → gut lacteals (lymphatics) → blood → liver. (fat absorption route)</p><p>Osteopathic manipulation can drive lymph flow — a central reason to keep patients moving.</p><p>Abdominal lymphatic-pump treatment measurably increases lymph flow (thoracic-duct data).</p><p>Dietary fat is packaged into chylomicrons and absorbed by intestinal lacteals, then delivered to the blood.</p><p>OMM AND THE LYMPHATICS — the osteopathic hook. Because lymph depends on movement, osteopathic lymphatic-pump techniques (thoracic, abdominal, pedal pumps) exaggerate respiratory motion to push lymph through. This isn’t hand-waving — Gregg cited data: pump techniques increase thoracic-duct flow (measured in dogs), improve vaccine efficacy, and reduce the duration of infectious disease. In his own mouse cancer work, the lymphatic pump mobilized NK cells into the blood and blocked cancer development in about half the animals. The takeaway for boards: OMM lymphatic techniques promote lymph movement, which clears waste, reduces edema, and improves immune surveillance.</p><p>OMM lymphatic pumps ↑ thoracic-duct flow, ↑ vaccine efficacy, ↓ infection duration; mobilize NK cells. (OMM pump evidence)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three lymphatic jobs: fluid balance (drain → prevent edema), fat absorption (chylomicrons via lacteals), immune surveillance. No heart pump — movement + valves drive flow.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Stem about a sedentary or post-op patient with swelling → think impaired lymphatic drainage → edema, and OMM lymphatic-pump techniques as a movement-promoting intervention.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> OMM lymphatic-pump data are board-relevant: increased thoracic-duct flow, improved vaccine efficacy, reduced infection duration, and NK mobilization. Damaged lymph nodes, by contrast, do not regenerate.</p><p>ReClaude A: The lymphatic system maintains fluid balance (draining interstitial fluid to prevent edema), absorbs dietary fat (chylomicrons via gut lacteals), and provides immune surveillance. It has no heart pump — muscle/respiratory movement and one-way valves drive flow — which is why OMM lymphatic-pump techniques (shown to raise thoracic-duct flow, improve vaccine efficacy, and shorten infections) help.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "5_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Which duct drains which body region, and into which subclavian vein does each empty?</em></p><p>TWO DUCTS, TWO SUBCLAVIANS, ONE ASYMMETRY. All that drained lymph eventually has to rejoin the blood, and it does so at the subclavian veins through two unequal ducts. The right lymphatic duct collects only the right upper quadrant — the right side of the head and neck, the right arm, and the right chest — and empties into the right subclavian vein. The thoracic duct collects everything else — both legs, the abdomen, and the entire left side of the body — and empties into the left subclavian vein. So most of the body drains through the thoracic duct; the right duct handles one small quadrant.</p><p>Right lymphatic duct → right subclavian (right upper quadrant only). Thoracic duct → left subclavian (everything else). (drainage ducts)</p><p>Asymmetric drainage: the right lymphatic duct → right subclavian (right upper quadrant); the thoracic duct → left subclavian (everything else).</p><p>The thoracic duct ascends from the cisterna chyli and empties into the left subclavian vein, returning most of the body’s lymph to the blood.</p><p>WHY THE EXAM LIKES THIS. The split is clean and memorable, which makes it easy to test with a single regional stem: “lymph from the left leg returns to the blood where?” The answer is the thoracic duct → left subclavian, because the legs are outside the right upper quadrant. The only territory the right duct owns is the right head/neck, right arm, and right chest — anything else routes left.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Regional drainage stem → ask “is this the right upper quadrant?” If yes → right lymphatic duct; if anything else → thoracic duct → left subclavian.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Right lymphatic duct = right upper quadrant → right subclavian. Thoracic duct = the rest of the body (legs, abdomen, left side) → left subclavian. Both endpoints are subclavian veins.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Don’t flip the ducts. The right duct drains a small region (right upper quadrant only); the thoracic duct drains most of the body. A lower-body or left-side stem is always thoracic duct.</p><p>ReClaude A: Lymph rejoins the blood at the subclavian veins. The right lymphatic duct drains only the right upper quadrant (right head/neck, right arm, right chest) into the right subclavian vein; the thoracic duct drains everything else — both legs, the abdomen, and the left side — into the left subclavian vein.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "5_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>How do afferent and efferent vessels differ, and what does a naive cell need to cross an HEV?</em></p><p>AFFERENT IN, EFFERENT OUT. A lymph node has two kinds of lymphatic connection. Afferent vessels bring lymph — and antigen — into the node from the tissues. Crucially, very few cell types make that trip; the predominant courier is the dendritic cell (a few macrophages too), delivering microbial components to the paracortical T cells. Efferent vessels carry activated cells out of the node — they exit through the medulla, travel the efferent lymphatics, and eventually reach the blood to circulate until they find inflamed tissue.</p><p>Afferent = antigen in (mostly dendritic cells). Efferent = activated cells out (via medulla → blood). (afferent vs efferent)</p><p>Afferent lymphatics carry antigen from tissue into the node — predominantly via dendritic cells, with a few macrophages.</p><p>High endothelial venules (HEVs) let blood-borne naive B and T cells cross directly into the node — L-selectin + integrin + CCR7 required.</p><p>HEV — HOW BLOOD-BORNE CELLS ENTER THE NODE. Here’s the problem the high endothelial venule (HEV) solves: cells made in the marrow are in the blood, not in tissue, so they can’t use the afferent route. HEVs are specialized venule segments inside the node where naive B and T cells cross directly from blood into the node’s compartments. The crossing uses the same rolling-and-arrest machinery as inflammation: L-selectin (rolling), an integrin (arrest), and — the requirement Gregg flagged outright — CCR7. “You have to have CCR7” to enter the node. Resting B and T cells carry CCR7; once activated, a cell swaps CCR7 for receptors that target inflamed-tissue endothelium, so it leaves the node and homes to the</p><p>HEV entry = L-selectin + integrin + CCR7 (“you have to have CCR7”). Activation drops CCR7 to redirect to inflamed tissue. (HEV + CCR7)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Afferent = antigen in (dendritic cells); efferent = activated cells out. Blood-borne naive cells enter the node through HEVs using L-selectin + integrin + CCR7 — CCR7 is the flagged requirement.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Two entry routes, don’t merge them: antigen enters via afferent lymphatics (dendritic cells); naive lymphocytes enter from blood via HEVs (CCR7-dependent).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CCR7 is the lymph-node entry passcode. Resting cells have it (enter node); activated cells drop it and gain inflamed-tissue homing receptors (exit to periphery).</p><p>ReClaude A: Afferent lymphatics bring antigen into the node (carried mainly by dendritic cells); efferent lymphatics carry activated cells out via the medulla toward the blood. High endothelial venules let blood-borne naive B and T cells cross directly into the node using L-selectin, an integrin, and CCR7 — CCR7 being the required chemokine receptor.</p><p><em>What is the sole job of the M cell, and which cells screen blood-borne antigen in the liver?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Beyond the spleen and lymph nodes, several other tissues host immune responses — less organized, but functional when needed. The headline examples are the liver and the mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) family (gut = GALT, bronchial = BALT). Each places the same cast — macrophages, dendritic cells, B/T cells, NK cells — at a site where antigen tends to arrive.</p><p>The liver screens blood-borne antigen arriving via the portal vein — the largest gland, full of immune cells.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Portal-triad sinusoids carry flow toward the central vein, exposing blood to resident immune cells.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Hepatic sinusoids are sites of immune reactivity — lined by Kupffer cells (liver macrophages) with dendritic cells, NK, and B/T cells.</p><p>THE LIVER. Gut infections release agents into the bloodstream that travel up the portal vein to the portal triads and dump into the hepatic sinusoids. Those sinusoids are lined with Kupffer cells (the liver’s macrophages, with all the usual macrophage functions) plus dendritic cells, NK cells, and B/T cells — every player needed for a response. The liver isn’t as organized or efficient as a lymph node, but it will mount a response to blood-borne antigen when called on.</p><p>Liver: portal vein → portal-triad sinusoids lined by Kupffer cells (+ DC, NK, B/T) screen blood-borne antigen. (liver = Kupffer/sinusoid)</p><p>MALT, GALT, AND THE M CELL. MALT is the diffuse lymphoid tissue guarding mucosal surfaces — aggregates of B cells, T cells, macrophages, and dendritic cells just beneath the epithelium. In the gut (GALT), the organized clusters are Peyer’s patches (the tonsils and appendix carry similar tissue). The cell to know is the microfold (M) cell: it sits in the epithelium over a Peyer’s patch and does one job — capture luminal material and transfer it across to the macrophages and dendritic cells waiting underneath. It makes no cytokines and mounts no response of its own; it is purely a conveyor. The surveying is done by the phagocytes behind it.</p><p>M (microfold) cell = capture + transfer luminal antigen across the epithelium ONLY — no cytokines, no response. (M cell = conveyor only)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Peyer’s patches (GALT): aggregated lymphoid tissue in the intestinal lamina propria.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Skin immune components: epidermal Langerhans cells and dermal dendritic cells survey the barrier.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Tonsils: ringed mucosal lymphoid tissue with crypts that capture inhaled or ingested antigen for sampling.</p><p>General MALT organization: a B-cell zone with scattered T cells, macrophages, and dendritic cells beneath the mucosa.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Microfold (M) cells ferry luminal antigen across the epithelium to underlying phagocytes — capture and transfer only. Kupffer cells = liver macrophages. Same phagocyte lineage as red-pulp and tissue macrophages, positioned in hepatic sinusoids to catch portal (gut-derived) antigen.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Other response sites: the liver (portal-triad sinusoids, Kupffer cells) and MALT/GALT/BALT (mucosal lymphoid aggregates). Less organized than nodes, but fully staffed with macrophages, DCs, NK, B/T.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> M cells don’t respond — they transfer. Microfold cells capture and ferry antigen across the epithelium; the macrophages and dendritic cells behind them do the cytokine production and priming.</p><p>ReClaude A: Secondary lymphoid tissues beyond the spleen and nodes include the liver — where portal-vein antigen meets Kupffer cells, dendritic cells, NK, and B/T cells in the sinusoids — and the MALT family (GALT in the gut, BALT in the bronchi). In GALT, microfold (M) cells over Peyer’s patches capture and transfer luminal antigen to underlying phagocytes without responding themselves.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "6_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>How do antigen, immunogen, and epitope differ — and where does a hapten fall?</em></p><p>DEFINITIONS — three words you must keep straight. Gregg opens the antigen unit with vocabulary, and the distinctions are testable. An antigen is anything that can interact with a component of the immune response — a B-cell receptor, a T-cell receptor, or a secreted antibody. An immunogen is an antigen that goes one step further and actually induces an immune response. So every immunogen is an antigen, but not every antigen is an immunogen — the classic exception being a hapten, which binds but can’t trigger a response until it’s coupled to a carrier. An epitope is the specific region of the antigen that a receptor actually recognizes — for a protein, a short stretch of amino acids.</p><p>Antigen = binds an immune receptor. Immunogen = antigen that induces a response. Epitope = the recognized region. (the three definitions)</p><p>An antigen carries multiple epitopes (here, three) — each a distinct site recognized by a separate B- or T-cell response.</p><p>Adaptive cells express receptors (BCR/TCR) that bind antigen; immunogens are the antigens that successfully induce a response.</p><p>ONE ANTIGEN, MANY EPITOPES. Here’s the concept Gregg flagged for later: a single protein antigen carries multiple epitopes, so a single antigen can drive several distinct responses at once — three epitopes can mean three different T-cell responses to the same protein, each using a different piece. This matters downstream: when tolerance breaks and the response broadens to additional epitopes over time, that’s epitope spreading, a mechanism you’ll meet again in autoimmune disease. Two factors also shape how strongly you respond to any given antigen: previous exposure (adaptive memory lasts ~30–40 years and responds faster the second time) and the status of the immune system (age, immunocompromise, medications).</p><p>One antigen = multiple epitopes → multiple parallel responses; broadening over time = epitope spreading (autoimmunity). (epitopes → epitope spreading)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Antigen ≠ immunogen. A hapten is an antigen (it binds) but not an immunogen (no response alone). The inducing step is what separates the two terms.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Antigen binds; immunogen induces; epitope is the recognized piece. All immunogens are antigens, not vice versa (haptens). One antigen carries many epitopes → many parallel responses.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Multiple epitopes → multiple responses. The later-course payoff is epitope spreading in autoimmunity — the response broadens from one epitope to neighbors over time.</p><p>ReClaude A: An antigen is anything that binds an immune receptor or antibody; an immunogen is an antigen that actually induces a response (so all immunogens are antigens, but haptens are antigens that aren’t immunogens); an epitope is the specific region of the antigen that a receptor recognizes. One antigen carries multiple epitopes.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "6_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What distinguishes a superantigen from a mitogen, and what is an alloantigen?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW — a slide-sourced objective. Gregg ran out of time and deferred alloantigens, superantigens, mitogens, and haptens to the start of the T-cell lectures — so the depth here is built from his slides plus the framework you need, flagged as such. The objective names five special immunogen categories beyond “ordinary” antigen. Alloantigens are antigens that differ between individuals of the same species (the basis of transplant rejection). Autoantigens are self-antigens (the targets in autoimmunity). Heterophile antigens are shared across species (cross-reacting).</p><p>Allo = differs within a species (transplant). Auto = self (autoimmunity). Heterophile = shared across species. (allo/auto/heterophile)</p><p>Superantigens cross-link the TCR Vβ region directly to MHC II, polyclonally activating up to ~20% of T cells (toxic-shock mechanism).</p><p>Mitogens drive polyclonal lymphocyte proliferation by binding stimulatory receptors (e.g., TLR), independent of antigen specificity.</p><p>Haptens are small molecules that need a carrier protein to become immunogenic — the mechanism behind contact (type IV) hypersensitivity.</p><p>SUPERANTIGENS AND MITOGENS — the two polyclonal activators. A superantigen bypasses normal peptide specificity by bridging the TCR Vβ region directly to MHC class II, outside the peptide groove. The result is polyclonal activation of up to ~20% of all T cells at once — a cytokine storm, the mechanism behind toxic-shock syndrome. A mitogen also causes polyclonal proliferation, but through stimulatory receptors such as TLR, driving cell-cycle progression independent of antigen specificity. And a hapten is the small-molecule case: too small to be immunogenic alone, it must couple to a carrier protein to provoke a response — the basis of contact dermatitis (a type IV hypersensitivity).</p><p>Superantigen = TCR Vβ–MHC II bridge → ~20% T cells (toxic shock). Mitogen = TLR-type polyclonal proliferation. Hapten = needs carrier. (superantigen vs mitogen vs hapten)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Superantigen vs mitogen: both polyclonal, different routes. Superantigen bridges TCR Vβ to MHC II directly; mitogen acts through stimulatory receptors like TLR — not via Vβ–MHC.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> This LO is slide-built — Gregg deferred it. He covers superantigens, mitogens, and haptens at the start of the T-cell lectures; the definitions here come from his slides, not the recorded lecture.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Five categories: alloantigen (within species), autoantigen (self), heterophile (across species), superantigen (Vβ–MHC II bridge, polyclonal), mitogen (TLR-type polyclonal). Hapten = needs a carrier.</p><p>ReClaude A: The five types: alloantigens differ between individuals of the same species (transplant), autoantigens are self-antigens (autoimmunity), heterophile antigens are shared across species, superantigens bridge the TCR Vβ region to MHC II for polyclonal activation of ~20% of T cells, and mitogens drive polyclonal proliferation via stimulatory receptors like TLR. (Slide-sourced — Gregg deferred this to the T-cell lectures.)</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "6_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Name the features that raise immunogenicity — and why a metal implant is weakly immunogenic.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW — what makes a strong immunogen. Several properties decide how vigorously the immune system responds to an antigen, and they add up. Chemical complexity: complex, branched heteropolymers beat simple homopolymers — a branching heteropolymer draws the strongest B-cell response, while a single repeating subunit is weak. Degradability: the antigen must be digestible into peptides for T cells to see it on MHC; non-degradable materials like metal implants are weakly immunogenic (handy — you don’t want a response to your hip replacement).</p><p>Complexity (branched heteropolymer &gt; homopolymer) and degradability (must be digestible for T cells) raise immunogenicity. (complexity + degradability)</p><p>Chemical complexity: branched heteropolymers are more immunogenic than simple homopolymers.</p><p>Epitope density: more repeated or more varied epitopes generate more B- and T-cell responses.</p><p>Degradability: antigens must be digestible into peptides for T-cell presentation — metal implants resist this and are weakly immunogenic.</p><p>CHARGE, FOREIGNNESS, EPITOPE DENSITY, AND SIZE. Charged or hydrophilic antigens are more immunogenic than neutral/hydrophobic ones. Epitope density matters — many repeats of an epitope, or many different epitopes, generate more responses. Foreignness is central: the more an antigen differs from self, the stronger the response, because self-resembling antigens are suppressed by tolerance — which is why microbial structures like peptidoglycan and flagellin (things we never make) are highly immunogenic. And size — Gregg said he likes to “throw a question in on size” — bigger is more immunogenic, with proteins &gt;10 kDa the most immunogenic of all (they engage both B and T cells).</p><p>More immunogenic: charged/hydrophilic, high epitope density, more foreign, larger size (proteins &gt;10 kDa strongest). (charge/foreign/density/size)</p><p>Size matters (Gregg’s flagged question): larger antigens are more immunogenic, with proteins &gt;10 kDa topping the scale because they engage both B and T cells.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Degradability cuts the other way from durability: a non-degradable implant is weakly immunogenic precisely because it can’t be processed into peptides for T cells.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Immunogenicity rises with complexity, degradability, charge/hydrophilicity, epitope density, foreignness, and size. They add up — a large, complex, foreign, charged protein is maximally immunogenic.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Watch the ‘size’ question — Gregg flagged it. Bigger = more immunogenic; proteins &gt;10 kDa top the scale because they recruit both B and T cells. Don’t pick a small or homopolymeric antigen as ‘strong.’</p><p>ReClaude A: Immunogenicity increases with chemical complexity (branched heteropolymers), degradability (must be digestible for T-cell presentation), charge/hydrophilicity, epitope density, foreignness (unlike self), and size (proteins &gt;10 kDa are most immunogenic). These factors add together.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "6_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Rank the four antigen classes and state which class T cells can respond to.</em></p><p>FOUR CLASSES, ONE HIERARCHY. Antigens come in four chemical classes, and their immunogenicity ranks proteins &gt; polysaccharides &gt; nucleic acids &gt; lipids. Proteins are the most immunogenic and the only class T cells respond to — and they must be larger than about 10 kDa. Polysaccharides are second-strongest but are B-cell only (T cells can’t see carbohydrate). The rule to anchor: T cells respond ONLY to protein (as processed peptide); B cells respond to all four classes.</p><p>Immunogenicity: protein &gt; polysaccharide &gt; nucleic acid &gt; lipid. T cells = protein only (&gt;10 kDa); B cells = all four. (antigen-class hierarchy)</p><p>Proteins are most immunogenic (B + T cells, &gt;10 kDa); polysaccharides are second but B-cell only.</p><p>Nucleic acids and lipids are B-cell only — lupus anti-DNA antibodies show B-cell response to nucleic acids; lipids respond best with protein.</p><p>NUCLEIC ACIDS AND LIPIDS — B-cell territory. Nucleic acids are B-cell only, and you already know the proof: systemic lupus erythematosus, where B cells make antibodies against DNA. T cells can’t respond to DNA. Lipids are also B-cell only, and they respond best when associated with protein — if a lipid carries some protein, you can pull T-cell involvement in, but the T cell is still only seeing the protein part. The single unifying rule for the whole lecture: T cells never respond to anything but protein.</p><p>Nucleic acids (lupus anti-DNA) and lipids = B-cell only; lipids respond best protein-associated. T cells: protein only, always. (nucleic acids + lipids)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Lupus anti-dsDNA is the board-favorite proof that B cells answer nucleic-acid antigens — something T cells can never do.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Protein &gt; polysaccharide &gt; nucleic acid &gt; lipid. The load-bearing rule: T cells respond ONLY to protein (processed peptide); B cells respond to all four classes.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Lipids CAN pull in T-cell help, but only when protein-associated — and even then the T cell sees the protein, not the lipid. T cells never recognize lipid, carbohydrate, or nucleic acid alone.</p><p>ReClaude A: Antigen classes rank protein &gt; polysaccharide &gt; nucleic acid &gt; lipid in immunogenicity. Proteins are most immunogenic, must exceed ~10 kDa, and are the only class T cells respond to (as processed peptide); polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and lipids are B-cell only (lupus anti-DNA proves the nucleic-acid case).</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "6_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Name the recognition and signaling parts of the TCR and the chains of the BCR.</em></p><p>NEARSIGHTED T CELLS, PERFECT-VISION B CELLS. Before the receptors themselves, hold the metaphor Gregg leaned on. T cells are nearsighted: they cannot see free antigen — it must be processed into peptide and displayed on MHC by an antigen-presenting cell, which holds it up close so the TCR can read it. B cells have perfect vision: the BCR binds native, unprocessed antigen directly, no helper needed. That difference shapes the structure and behavior of both receptors.</p><p>T cells nearsighted (need peptide on MHC via APC); B cells perfect vision (bind native antigen directly). (T vs B antigen access)</p><p>B cells recognize native antigen directly through the BCR — no processing or presentation required.</p><p>T cells express a TCR that reads antigen only as peptide displayed on MHC by an antigen-presenting cell.</p><p>TCR components: an αβ recognition heterodimer plus CD3 and zeta (ζ) signaling chains that dock ZAP-70 on activation.</p><p>THE TCR — recognition plus signaling. The T-cell receptor has two functional parts. The α and β chains form the antigen-recognition heterodimer; each chain has a variable region (changes to recognize different antigens) and a constant region (fixed), anchored by a transmembrane segment. Bolted alongside are the CD3 and zeta (ζ) signaling chains — when the αβ dimer engages peptide-MHC, the CD3/zeta cytoplasmic tails get phosphorylated and dock adaptors like ZAP-70, launching activation → proliferation → effector function. The whole αβ receptor is assembled by random V(D)J recombination in the thymus, then tested against self.</p><p>TCR: αβ = recognition (variable + constant); CD3 + zeta = signaling (dock ZAP-70). Built by V(D)J in the thymus. (TCR components)</p><p>BCR components: two heavy and two light chains, each with a variable (antigen-binding) and a constant region.</p><p>THE BCR — heavy and light chains. The B-cell receptor is built from two heavy chains and two light chains, each chain again split into a variable (antigen-binding) region and a constant region. The variable regions of the heavy and light chains together form the antigen-binding site; the constant region is fixed. Like the TCR, a transmembrane segment anchors it in the membrane — and that anchor is exactly what gets removed when the B cell becomes a plasma cell and secretes the receptor as antibody (LO 6.9).</p><p>BCR: two heavy + two light chains, each with variable (antigen-binding) + constant regions. (BCR components)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Don’t mix the chains: αβ belong to the TCR; heavy/light belong to the BCR. CD3 and zeta are TCR signaling chains, not recognition chains.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> TCR = αβ recognition + CD3/zeta signaling. BCR = 2 heavy + 2 light chains, each variable + constant. Both assembled by random V(D)J; both have a transmembrane anchor.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Nearsighted T, perfect-vision B is the single best way to remember why T cells need an APC + MHC and B cells don’t — and it explains the whole presentation story in Lec 7.</p><p>ReClaude A: The TCR has an αβ heterodimer for antigen recognition (each chain with variable and constant regions) plus CD3 and zeta chains for signaling. The BCR has two heavy and two light chains, each with variable (antigen-binding) and constant regions. T cells need processed peptide on MHC; B cells bind native antigen directly.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "6_6": {
  "answer": "<p><em>How do B- and T-cell epitopes differ, and which MHC class does each T-cell subset read?</em></p><p>PROCESSED PEPTIDE VS NATIVE STRUCTURE. The cleanest way to separate B-cell and T-cell epitopes is to ask what the receptor is allowed to see. T-cell epitopes are linear processed peptides: the protein is chopped into fragments and the peptide is displayed on MHC, so the TCR only ever reads a short, linear stretch. B-cell epitopes can be linear OR conformational (discontinuous): because the BCR binds the native,</p><p>folded antigen directly, residues that are far apart in sequence but close in 3-D can together form the binding site. Conformational is in fact the usual case for B cells, since native antigen arrives unprocessed at the follicle.</p><p>T-cell epitope = linear processed peptide on MHC. B-cell epitope = linear OR conformational on native antigen. (B vs T epitope nature)</p><p>T-cell epitopes: the protein is processed into linear peptides held in the MHC groove by anchor residues for the TCR to read.</p><p>B-cell epitopes: the BCR binds native antigen — epitopes are often conformational (discontinuous), assembled by 3-D folding.</p><p>Star-and-memorize: CD4 reads peptide on MHC II (DCs/B cells/macrophages); CD8 reads peptide on MHC I (every nucleated cell).</p><p>THE STARRED CD4/CD8 SLIDE — MHC restriction. [Off-syllabus graft — professor emphasized (“star and memorize this slide”); full MHC mechanism is Lec 7, Dr. Davis.] Because T-cell epitopes are presented on MHC, the slide Gregg told you to star ties the two T-cell subsets to the two MHC classes. CD4 helper T cells read peptide on MHC class II, which is restricted to the three professional APCs — dendritic cells, B cells, and macrophages. CD8 cytotoxic T cells read peptide on MHC class I, expressed by every nucleated cell in the body — which is precisely why any virus-infected cell can be flagged and killed. The mnemonic is the rule of 8: CD4 × MHC-II = 8, and CD8 × MHC-I = 8. The CD4/CD8 molecule itself grips the MHC to hold the complex steady so the nearsighted TCR can read the peptide.</p><p>CD4 → MHC II (DC/B/mac only); CD8 → MHC I (every nucleated cell). Rule of 8. (CD4/CD8–MHC restriction)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> T-cell epitope = processed linear peptide on MHC; B-cell epitope = native, often conformational. CD4→MHC II (professional APCs), CD8→MHC I (all nucleated cells) — the rule of 8.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Don’t flip CD4/CD8 with their MHC class. Rule of 8: CD4×II = 8, CD8×I = 8. MHC II is restricted to DCs/B cells/macrophages; MHC I is on every nucleated cell.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Why any infected cell can be killed: MHC class I is universal, so a CD8 cell can inspect essentially any nucleated cell’s internal (viral) peptides — the basis of cytotoxic surveillance.</p><p>ReClaude A: T-cell epitopes are linear peptides generated by processing and displayed on MHC; B-cell epitopes can be linear or conformational because the BCR binds native antigen directly. The starred restriction: CD4 T cells read peptide on MHC II (dendritic cells, B cells, macrophages), and CD8 T cells read peptide on MHC I (every nucleated cell).</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "6_7": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What are the four classes of antigens, and which is the only one T cells respond to?</em></p><p>CROSS-REFERENCE — see LO 6.4 for the full treatment. This objective restates the antigen classes, fully developed under LO 6.4: the four chemical classes rank proteins &gt; polysaccharides &gt; nucleic acids &gt; lipids in immunogenicity, with proteins (&gt;10 kDa) the most immunogenic and the only class T cells respond to, and B cells responding to all four. The one-line anchor for this LO: know the four classes and that protein is the only T-cell class. Everything else lives in LO 6.4.</p><p>Four classes: protein, polysaccharide, nucleic acid, lipid — protein is the only T-cell class (full detail in LO 6.4). (antigen classes (cross-ref))</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> This LO overlaps LO 6.4 by design — the syllabus lists antigen classes twice. There’s one fact set: don’t expect a different list here.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> If a stem just asks you to name the four antigen classes, this is the LO — protein, polysaccharide, nucleic acid, lipid, in descending immunogenicity.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Same four classes as LO 6.4: protein &gt; polysaccharide &gt; nucleic acid &gt; lipid. Protein is the only class T cells see; B cells see all four. (Primary treatment under LO 6.4.)</p><p>ReClaude A: The four classes of antigens are proteins, polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and lipids, ranked by immunogenicity in that order; proteins are most immunogenic and the only class T cells respond to, while B cells respond to all four. (Developed fully under LO 6.4.)</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "6_8": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What is the difference between affinity and avidity, and why is IgM the classic example?</em></p><p>ONE SITE VS THE WHOLE GRIP. Two strength terms get confused constantly, and the exam knows it. Affinity is the strength of a single antigen-binding site for one epitope — one handshake. Avidity is the total combined strength of all the binding sites acting together — the whole multivalent grip. The higher the affinity, the more specific and tightly a single site holds its epitope; the higher the avidity, the harder it is to pull the whole antibody off, because breaking one bond still leaves the others engaged — the released arm just re-binds before the antibody can diffuse away.</p><p>Affinity = one site for one epitope. Avidity = total strength of all sites (multivalent). (affinity vs avidity)</p><p>Affinity is the strength of a single binding site; avidity is the combined strength of all sites — multivalency makes the whole hard to dislodge.</p><p>WHY IT MATTERS — IgM is the classic case. A pentameric IgM has ten binding sites but relatively modest affinity at each one; together they give it high avidity, so it grips repetitive antigens (like bacterial carbohydrate) tightly even though no single arm binds hard. That’s exactly the marginal-zone emergency IgM logic from Lec 5: low-affinity, high-avidity, fast, complement-fixing. Don’t let a stem trick you — “weak at each site but hard to remove overall” is the signature of high avidity, modest affinity.</p><p>IgM = modest per-site affinity, high avidity (10 sites) — grips repetitive antigen tightly overall. (IgM = high avidity)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Affinity = single-site strength; avidity = total multivalent strength. IgM is the textbook case: low affinity per arm, high avidity from ten arms.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Stem with a pentameric IgM on a repetitive carbohydrate → think high avidity; stem about a single high-strength interaction → think affinity.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> “Weak per site but hard to dislodge” = high avidity, not high affinity. Multivalency, not single-site strength, is doing the work — a re-binding arm covers for a released one.</p><p>ReClaude A: Affinity is the strength of a single antigen-binding site for one epitope; avidity is the total combined strength of all binding sites acting together. IgM illustrates the difference: modest affinity at each of its ten sites but high overall avidity, gripping repetitive antigen tightly.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "6_9": {
  "answer": "<p><em>How does a BCR become an antibody, and what do papain and pepsin each yield?</em></p><p>THE ANTIBODY IS THE BCR WITHOUT ITS TAIL. When a B cell meets its antigen it becomes a plasma cell, a dedicated protein factory that makes antibody. The trick is simple: the plasma cell takes the B-cell receptor, removes the transmembrane domain, and secretes it. Same two heavy and two light chains, same variable regions, same antigen specificity — it just loses the membrane anchor so it can float free. So the difference between BCR and antibody is location, not specificity: one is membrane-bound, the other secreted.</p><p>Antibody = BCR minus the transmembrane domain, secreted by a plasma cell. Same specificity, now soluble. (BCR → antibody)</p><p>A plasma cell secretes the BCR without its transmembrane domain — the soluble antibody, with the same antigen specificity.</p><p>Functional regions: the two Fab arms bind antigen; the Fc tail mediates effector functions (opsonization, ADCC) and isotype identity.</p><p>Each variable region has three hypervariable (CDR) loops — three from the heavy and three from the light chain form the antigen contact surface.</p><p>HYPERVARIABLE LOOPS, ISOTYPES, AND LIGHT CHAINS. Within each variable region sit three regions of hypervariability (the CDRs) — three on the heavy chain, three on the light — and these six loops are the actual contact points for antigen. The heavy-chain constant region determines the isotype, and there are five options, after their Greek letters: μ, δ, γ, ε, α (giving IgM, IgD, IgG, IgE, IgA). The light chain constant</p><p>region has only two options: kappa (κ) or lambda (λ). The isotype sets the antibody’s job — a γ heavy chain (IgG) drives opsonization; an ε heavy chain (IgE) drives eosinophil ADCC against helminths (both from Lec 4).</p><p>Heavy-chain isotypes: μ δ γ ε α (M/D/G/E/A). Light chains: κ or λ. Three CDRs per chain bind antigen. (isotypes + CDRs)</p><p>FAB, FC, AND THE TWO ENZYMES. Structurally, the antibody is a Y. The two arms are the Fab (fragment antigen-binding) regions; the stem is the Fc (fragment crystallizable) region, which mediates effector functions and is bound by Fc receptors. A flexible hinge lets the arms splay to grab epitopes at varying distances. Two enzymes (Nobel-winning work) map the pieces: papain cuts above the hinge, yielding two separate Fab fragments + one Fc; pepsin cuts below the hinge, yielding a single F(ab’)₂ (both arms still joined, so it still cross-links antigen) plus a chewed-up Fc. Opsonization is the headline Fc function: Fab grips the microbe, the projecting Fc engages a macrophage Fc receptor, and uptake follows — the antibody version of C3b opsonization (Lec 2).</p><p>Fab = antigen-binding arms; Fc = effector tail. Papain → 2 Fab + Fc; pepsin → F(ab’)₂. (Fab/Fc + papain/pepsin)</p><p>Papain cuts above the hinge → two Fab + one Fc; pepsin cuts below → one F(ab’)₂ (still cross-links antigen) + a degraded Fc.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Antibody = secreted BCR (no transmembrane domain). Three CDRs/chain bind antigen; heavy-chain isotype (μ/δ/γ/ε/α) sets function; light chains are κ or λ. Fab binds, Fc effects.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Papain → two separate Fab + Fc; pepsin → one F(ab’)₂. Only the pepsin product still cross-links antigen (both arms joined). Don’t swap the two enzymes’ products.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Fc ties back to Lec 4: IgG-Fc → macrophage opsonization; IgE-Fc → eosinophil ADCC vs helminths. The isotype (heavy-chain constant region) decides the effector job.</p><p>ReClaude A: A plasma cell makes antibody by secreting the BCR without its transmembrane domain — same two heavy/two light chains and specificity, now soluble. Three hypervariable CDRs per chain bind antigen; the heavy-chain isotype (μ/δ/γ/ε/α) sets function and light chains are κ or λ. Fab arms bind antigen; the Fc tail mediates effector functions (papain → 2 Fab + Fc; pepsin → F(ab’)₂).</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "7_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Two siblings share the same two parents — why are they still usually unsuitable as each other’s transplant donors?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Davis’s whole framing of MHC is that these molecules are billboards bolted to the surface of your cells, constantly advertising to passing T cells whether the cell is healthy or sick. Every nucleated cell carries them, and what they hold up for inspection is a short peptide. The entire lecture hangs on one question: how does a peptide get onto that billboard, and which T cell reads it? Before any of that, you need the cast of molecules and where they come from — and that starts with the genetics.</p><p>THE LOCI. In humans the MHC molecules are called HLA (human leukocyte antigens). There are two structural classes. Class I is encoded at three loci — HLA-A, HLA-B, HLA-C — and sits on essentially all nucleated cells. Class II is encoded at three loci — HLA-DP, HLA-DQ, HLA-DR (Davis’s memory hook: “Dairy Queen, and the letter before and after”) — and is restricted to antigen-presenting cells: dendritic cells, macrophages, and B cells. You inherit a full set of all six loci from each parent, and both parental copies are expressed side by side. That co-dominant expression is why you end up with six class I and six class II molecules on the cells that carry them.</p><p>A person expresses six class I (HLA-A/B/C from each parent) and six class II (HLA-DP/DQ/DR from each parent). (MHC inventory + inheritance) CQ Class I is on all nucleated cells; class II is restricted to APCs (dendritic cells, macrophages, B cells). (class I vs II tissue distribution)</p><p>MHC class I (all nucleated cells) vs class II (APCs) — the two structural classes and where each is found.</p><p>MHC as “billboards” — the molecules most responsible for graft/transplant rejection when donor and recipient differ.</p><p>Haplotype inheritance worked example: two children of the same parents share only 4 of 12 HLA alleles (red).</p><p>Anchor residues: the peptide is held by a few residues, not its whole length — the basis of promiscuous binding.</p><p>Class I structure: one polymorphic α chain (α1/α2/α3) paired with non-polymorphic β2-microglobulin; 8–10-mer in a closed cleft.</p><p>POLYMORPHISM AND THE HAPLOTYPE. The MHC loci are the most polymorphic in the entire genome — thousands of alleles exist at each locus across the population (Davis’s analogy: different alleles are like different influenza strains, H1N1 vs H3N2). An allele is just a version, written as a number after the locus: HLA-B2 is class I molecule B, version 2. The particular combination of alleles you inherit on one chromosome is your haplotype. Because each parent passes one haplotype, and because the population pool is so deep, two unrelated people almost never match. Even full siblings, as the worked slide shows, may share only 4 of 12 HLAs.</p><p>WHY IT MATTERS CLINICALLY. Foreign MHC is the dominant trigger of transplant rejection — your immune system reads a non-identical donor’s MHC as non-self, which is why a non-twin transplant means lifelong immunosuppression. Matching thresholds scale with the organ: a kidney wants a high degree of HLA match while a liver tolerates less. The same polymorphism is also what forces developing T cells to be educated in the thymus to recognize your MHC specifically — a concept Davis names here and unpacks in the ontogeny lecture: MHC restriction (remember this when we hit positive selection in LO 10.4).</p><p>MHC loci are the most polymorphic in the body; foreign MHC drives transplant rejection. (polymorphism → rejection link) CQ MHC restriction = your T cells recognize antigen only on your own MHC; foreign MHC reads as non-self. (MHC restriction definition)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> MHC restriction (T cells see antigen only on self-MHC) is NOT the same as class restriction (CD4→class II, CD8→class I). Two different “restriction” ideas — don’t blur them.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Organ-match stringency tracks the stakes: a kidney needs a high HLA match, a liver tolerates fewer matched alleles. Siblings are often the closest — but rarely identical — donors.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> MHC molecules are surface billboards: every nucleated cell holds up a peptide on class I so passing CD8 cells and NK cells can judge “healthy or sick.” Everything else in this lecture is about how the peptide gets onto the billboard.</p><p>ReClaude A: Because MHC loci are the most polymorphic in the genome and each parent contributes one haplotype, two siblings inherit largely different allele combinations — often sharing only ~4 of 12 HLAs — so the donor MHC still reads as foreign and triggers rejection.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "7_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A bacterium is growing inside a macrophage’s phagosome. Is its antigen endogenous or exogenous, and why does the answer NOT depend on the fact that it is “inside a cell”?</em></p><p>THE UNIFYING DISTINCTION. There are two presentation pathways, and the single fact that sorts every antigen between them is where the protein is made or held — cytosol versus vesicle. The endogenous pathway handles protein synthesized in the cytosol (your own proteins, or a</p><p>virus replicating in the cytoplasm), routes it through class I, and shows it to CD8 cells for cell-mediated killing. The exogenous pathway handles protein taken into a vesicle — either phagocytosed from outside or growing inside a phagosome — routes it through class II, and shows it to CD4 cells for help. Hold onto the location rule and the rest follows.</p><p>Endogenous = cytosolic protein → class I → CD8; exogenous = vesicular protein → class II → CD4. (the master sorting rule)</p><p>T cells are MHC-restricted AND class-restricted: CD4→class II, CD8→class I (“it always has to equal 8”).</p><p>APC presenting on class I is recognized by a CD8 cell → clonal proliferation into cytotoxic T lymphocytes.</p><p>APC presenting on class II is recognized by a CD4 cell → differentiation into helper subsets that license B cells.</p><p>CLASS RESTRICTION — the “equal 8” hook. T cells are not only restricted to self-MHC, they are class-restricted: a CD4 cell reads class II, a CD8 cell reads class I, and they cannot cross over. Davis’s mnemonic is the one students actually remember on exam day — the numbers always multiply to 8: 4×2 and 8×1. The architectural reason the pairing is enforced is the set of “knobs” on the MHC that engage the correct co-receptor, but the test reward is just getting the direction right under pressure.</p><p>THE TWO ENDPOINTS. Once a naive cell is activated in the lymph node or spleen, it undergoes clonal proliferation and differentiation. A class I–activated CD8 becomes a cytotoxic T lymphocyte (CTL) that circulates and kills any cell displaying the same peptide-MHC that activated it — this is cell-mediated immunity. A class II–activated CD4 becomes a helper subset (Th1, Th2, Th17, Treg) that licenses B cells and shapes which antibody isotype they make — this is the gateway to humoral immunity. Recall from the first lecture that this is the same clonal-proliferation-then-differentiate logic; we will see CD8 effector killing again in LO 12.3 and CD4 differentiation in LO 12.1.</p><p>Class restriction: CD4→class II, CD8→class I — “it always has to equal 8” (4×2, 8×1). (class-restriction mnemonic) CQ Activated CD8 → CTL (cell-mediated); activated CD4 → helper subsets (gateway to humoral). (pathway endpoints)</p><p>Endogenous pathway overview: cytosolic protein → proteasome → TAP → class I in ER → surface → CD8.</p><p>Exogenous pathway overview: phagocytosed antigen → phagolysosome → class II loading → surface → CD4.</p><p>Class I vs class II side by side — the single best summary slide: uptake, processing, loading compartment, and which T cell reads each.</p><p>THE CYTOSOL-VS-INSIDE TRAP. Here is where the exam loves to set you up. “Inside the cell” is not the same as “in the cytosol.” Mycobacterium and Listeria grow inside a macrophage, but they sit in a vesicle, making their proteins in the phagosome rather than the cytosol. That makes them exogenous / class II / CD4, even though they are physically intracellular. Davis calls these intravesicular pathogens and contrasts them with a cytosolic virus, which is endogenous. If a stem stresses that the organism is “growing inside the phagosome,” the location rule — vesicle, not cytosol — gives you class II.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One rule sorts everything: location of the protein. Cytosol → endogenous → class I → CD8. Vesicle (phagocytosed OR intravesicular) → exogenous → class II → CD4.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> “Inside a cell” ≠ “in the cytosol.” Intravesicular pathogens (Mycobacterium, Listeria) grow inside the cell but in a vesicle → exogenous → class II / CD4. Only cytosolic protein is endogenous / class I.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> On a vignette, find the antigen’s compartment first. Cytosolic virus → CD8/CTL answer. Phagocytosed or intravesicular bug → CD4/helper answer. Decide compartment, then everything else falls out.</p><p>ReClaude A: Exogenous. Although the bacterium is physically inside the cell, it resides in a vesicle (phagosome) and makes its proteins there, not in the cytosol — and the pathway is decided by compartment (cytosol vs vesicle), not by whether the antigen is intracellular. Vesicular location → class II → CD4.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "7_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>HLA-DM carries the “HLA-D” name of the class II family — so why is it a mistake to call it an MHC class II molecule, and what does it actually do?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Each pathway is a little assembly line, and the testable content here is the named worker at each station. The trap the exam exploits is that several of these workers are accessory molecules — chaperones and transporters — not MHC molecules themselves. Keep the class I line and the class II line on separate tracks in your head and assign each molecule to one.</p><p>THE CLASS I LINE (endogenous). A cytosolic protein is tagged with ubiquitin and fed into the proteasome — Davis’s “wood chipper,” big protein in, small peptides out. During infection, IFN-γ remodels it into the immunoproteasome, which preferentially cuts after hydrophobic or basic</p><p>residues so the fragments carry good class I anchors. Those peptides then cross from cytosol into the ER through TAP1/TAP2, the ATP-dependent transporter associated with antigen processing. Waiting in the ER, the empty class I α chain is held by the chaperone calnexin, which stabilizes it until β2-microglobulin binds and also keeps empty molecules from leaving prematurely; tapasin then tethers the class I molecule near the TAP channel so peptides can be tried on as they arrive.</p><p>Class I peptides are made by the proteasome/immunoproteasome; IFN-γ induces the immunoproteasome for better anchors. (class I peptide generation) CQ TAP1/TAP2 moves peptides cytosol→ER (ATP-dependent); calnexin stabilizes class I until β2m binds; tapasin docks it at TAP. (class I ER machinery)</p><p>Calnexin stabilizes the class I α chain in the ER; tapasin positions it at the TAP gateway for loading.</p><p>Endogenous antigen processing: cytosolic protein degraded by the proteasome into peptides for class I.</p><p>IFN-γ converts the proteasome to the immunoproteasome; IFN-α/β drive the antiviral state.</p><p>Full class I trafficking: proteasome → TAP into ER → assembly with β2m/chaperone/tapasin → surface → CD8.</p><p>THE CLASS II LINE (exogenous). Antigen taken into a vesicle meets the phagolysosome, where the pH is dropped and cathepsins — enzymes, not a structure — do the cutting that the proteasome does on the other track. Meanwhile class II is also built in the ER (both classes are), so the cell must stop cytosolic peptides from loading into class II by mistake. It does this with the invariant chain (Ii), which has three jobs: it chaperones class II folding, blocks the binding cleft from endogenous peptide, and routes the class II molecule to the endosomal compartment. In the vesicle the invariant chain is trimmed down to a remnant called CLIP still sitting in the groove.</p><p>HLA-DM — the molecule Davis flags hardest. The class II molecules are DP, DQ, DR. HLA-DM shares that “HLA-D” naming but is not an MHC class II molecule — it is an accessory molecule, “kind of like tapasin or calnexin.” Its job is to remove CLIP and facilitate peptide loading into the now-open class II cleft. Davis stops and says “now remember this is important” precisely because the name invites you to mis-file it as a presenting molecule. Once loaded, the class II–peptide complex moves to the APC surface for a CD4 cell.</p><p>Class II peptides are cut by cathepsins in the phagolysosome (the enzyme analog of the proteasome). (class II peptide generation) CQ Invariant chain (Ii) chaperones class II, blocks the cleft, and routes it to the vesicle; its remnant is CLIP. (invariant chain three roles) CQ HLA-DM is an accessory molecule (NOT a class II molecule) that removes CLIP and loads peptide. (HLA-DM identity + job)</p><p>In the vesicle, invariant chain is trimmed to CLIP, which still blocks the binding cleft until exchange.</p><p>Invariant chain occupies the class II cleft in the ER, blocking endogenous peptide and routing class II to the vesicle.</p><p>HLA-DM removes CLIP and facilitates loading of antigenic peptide — then class II moves to the surface for CD4.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> HLA-DM is NOT an MHC class II molecule. The class II presenting molecules are DP/DQ/DR. HLA-DM is an accessory molecule (like tapasin/calnexin) that swaps out CLIP. The shared “HLA-D” name is the bait.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Same job, different track: proteasome (class I, cytosol) and cathepsins (class II, vesicle) both cut protein into peptides. TAP (class I) and HLA-DM (class II) both make loading possible — on opposite lines.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Both class I and class II are built in the ER. The difference is where they load — class I in the ER, class II in the vesicle — which is exactly why the invariant chain has to guard the class II cleft until it reaches the vesicle.</p><p>ReClaude A: HLA-DM shares the HLA-D family name but is an accessory molecule, like tapasin or calnexin — not a peptide-presenting class II molecule (those are DP/DQ/DR). Its job is to remove CLIP from the class II cleft and facilitate loading of antigenic peptide in the acidic vesicle.</p><p><em>A cytotoxic T cell finds a virally infected epithelial cell in the throat. Trace why this is “cell-mediated immunity” and how it differs from what a CD4 cell would have done.</em></p><p>THE TWO ARMS. The pathway you load determines the kind of immunity you get. Class I → CD8 → CTL → killing of infected cells is cell-mediated immunity. Class II → CD4 → helper subsets → B-cell licensing is the gateway to humoral immunity. Davis returns to her day-one line here as the anchor: “T cells don’t kill pathogens, they kill infected cells.” A CTL does not chase a free virus; it recognizes the peptide-MHC on a host cell that has been hijacked and destroys that cell.</p><p>Class I/CD8 → cell-mediated immunity (CTL kills infected cells); class II/CD4 → humoral (B-cell help). (pathway → immune arm) CQ CTLs kill infected cells, not free pathogens — they recognize peptide-MHC on a hijacked host cell. (core CTL principle)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Class II peptide binding: longer peptides in an open-ended cleft — the CD4/humoral arm.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> MHC class I molecules (HLA-A/B/C) on all nucleated cells — the cell-mediated arm read by CD8 cells.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Class I peptide binding: ~8–10 aa held by anchor residues, optimal length 9, ends pinned in a closed cleft. Anchor residues with defined chemistry (hydrophobic/basic/charged) let one groove bind many peptides.</p><p>WHY HEALTHY CELLS STILL PRESENT. Every nucleated cell constantly shows self-peptide on class I even when uninfected. That is not wasted effort — it is the signal NK cells read. A cell that downregulates class I to hide from CD8 surveillance (a favorite viral and tumor trick) triggers the NK “missing-self” response and gets killed anyway. Davis frames it as plan A (CTL) and plan B (NK): lose your MHC to dodge the T cell, and the NK cell finishes the job. On the CD4 side, the helper cell that recognizes class II goes on to license B cells and steer isotype switching — IgA at mucosa, IgG in tissue, IgE in allergy/parasite settings — which is how presentation choice ultimately shapes the antibody response.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> “T cells don’t kill pathogens — they kill infected cells.” Davis’s day-one line and the spine of LO 7.4. Class I/CD8 = cell-mediated killing; class II/CD4 = humoral help.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Constant self-peptide on class I is the NK “billboard.” Downregulate class I to dodge CD8 (plan A) and you trip NK missing-self (plan B). Evasion of one arm exposes you to the other.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Stem says “kills the infected cell directly” → CD8/CTL/class I. Stem says “helps B cells / drives antibody isotype” → CD4/class II. Match the verb to the arm.</p><p>ReClaude A: The virus is made in the infected cell’s cytosol → class I → the CD8 CTL recognizes peptide-MHC on that host cell and lyses it: killing an infected host cell is cell-mediated immunity. A CD4 cell, by contrast, would have read class II on an APC and helped B cells make antibody — it would not itself kill the infected cell.</p><p><em>If a patient loses TAP function entirely, which arm of adaptive immunity collapses, which is spared, and what infection pattern results?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This is the LO Davis builds toward with the self-study prompt on the class I-vs-II slide: “what happens if a mutation prevents class I or class II expression on the APCs?” The way to answer any presentation-deficiency question is to ask which line is broken and then read off the downstream arm. Break the class I line and you lose CD8/cell-mediated immunity; break the class II line and you lose CD4 help, which takes the antibody response down with it because most antibody responses are T-dependent.</p><p>WORKED CASES. Lose TAP and peptides never reach the ER → class I cannot be loaded → low CD8/CTL responses and recurrent viral infections, while the class II/CD4/antibody arm — which loads in the vesicle independent of TAP — is comparatively spared. Lose class II (bare lymphocyte syndrome, class II) and CD4 cells are not primed → low CD4 and failed T-dependent antibody responses, with class I/CD8 relatively intact. The pattern is always the same: a presentation defect knocks out the arm it feeds, and the spared arm tells you which line stayed open. NK cells can blunt but not replace antigen-specific CTL immunity, so “NK fully compensates” is never the right answer.</p><p>TAP loss → no class I loading → low CD8/CTL → viral susceptibility; CD4/antibody spared (TAP-independent). (TAP-deficiency phenotype) CQ Class II loss (bare lymphocyte syndrome II) → no CD4 priming → low CD4 + poor T-dependent antibody. (class II-deficiency phenotype)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CD1 follows the class II vesicular pathway but has a class I-like structure including β2-microglobulin. CD1 is recognized by invariant NKT cells (invariant α chain + β chain TCR); also involved in anti-tumor surveillance.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Nonclassical antigens: lipid/glycolipid/phospholipid presented on CD1 (not classical MHC) — relevant to mycobacterial cell-wall lipids.</p><p>NONCLASSICAL FOOTNOTE. Davis closes with a brief, low-emphasis aside (Tier 1): not every antigen is a protein. Lipid and glycolipid antigens — think mycobacterial cell wall — are too hydrophobic for the classical grooves and are instead presented on CD1, a non-polymorphic molecule with a class I-like structure (including β2m) that nonetheless trafficks through the class II vesicular pathway. CD1 is read by invariant NKT cells. It is worth recognizing, not memorizing in depth.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> CD1 presents lipid antigen to invariant NKT cells: class I-like structure (with β2m) but class II-style vesicular trafficking. Recognize it; don’t over-study it (Tier 1).</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Presentation-defect question? Ask which line broke. Class I line down → CD8/cell-mediated fails (viral infections). Class II line down → CD4 help fails → antibody fails. The spared arm reveals the open line.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> “NK cells fully compensate for absent class I” is a distractor. NK cells exploit missing-self and help, but they do not replace antigen-specific CTL immunity — TAP/class I patients still get sick with viruses.</p><p>ReClaude A: Cell-mediated immunity collapses: no TAP → no peptide into the ER → no class I loading → deficient CD8/CTL responses and recurrent viral infections. The class II/CD4/antibody arm is spared because class II loads in the vesicle independent of TAP. NK cells help via missing-self but cannot fully substitute for antigen-specific CTLs.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "8_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A naive B cell displays both IgM and IgD on its surface without having rearranged its DNA twice. How is that possible — and what role does exclusion play in keeping the receptor monospecific?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Where LO 8.3 distinguished the two exclusion mechanisms, this LO is about what they accomplish: a single lymphocyte ends up with one antigen specificity. That monospecificity is non-negotiable — a cell that recognized two different antigens would make clonal selection meaningless. Allelic and isotypic exclusion together guarantee one heavy-chain allele and one light-chain isotype, so every clone is one receptor, one specificity.</p><p>ONE CELL, ONE RECEPTOR. When a B or T cell is activated and clonally expands, every daughter carries the same receptor as the original — the thread from the very first lecture’s clonal-proliferation slide. Allelic exclusion ensures the cell commits to the maternal OR paternal allele; isotypic exclusion ensures the light chain is kappa OR lambda. The functional payoff is that antigen selection acts on a population where each clone speaks for exactly one specificity.</p><p>Exclusion’s role = one cell, one receptor, one specificity; all clonal daughters share it. (functional role of exclusion)</p><p>Heavy chain rearranges first; light-chain rearrangement follows ONLY if the heavy chain succeeds (checkpoint).</p><p>IgM/IgD alternative splicing: one primary transcript → VDJ-Cμ (IgM) or VDJ-Cδ (IgD); how a naive B cell shows both.</p><p>Isotypic exclusion in light chains: kappa first, suppressing lambda — the role that fixes one light-chain isotype.</p><p>IgM AND IgD — the splicing role. A naive B cell co-expresses IgM and IgD, and it does so without re-rearranging DNA. A single primary RNA transcript spanning both Cμ and Cδ is alternatively spliced: splice the VDJ to Cμ and you get IgM; splice it to Cδ and you get IgD. The variable region — the specificity — is identical either way, so co-expressing both isotypes never violates monospecificity. Class switching to IgG/IgA/IgE is a separate, later, DNA-deleting event that happens only after activation; the naive default is always IgM/IgD (and marginal-zone B cells stay IgM).</p><p>ISOTYPE SWITCHING — matching the antibody to the site. After activation, signals tell the B cell which isotype to switch to, and the pattern is the high-yield part: IgA for mucosal/respiratory/GI, IgE for allergy and parasites, IgG for tissue. The starting point is always M and D; the switch tailors the constant region (and thus the effector function) to where the response is needed, without changing the antigen specificity set during rearrangement.</p><p>Naive B cell co-expresses IgM + IgD via alternative splicing (VDJ→Cμ or VDJ→Cδ), not re-rearrangement. (IgM/IgD co-expression) CQ Isotype switching: IgA mucosal, IgE allergy/parasite, IgG tissue — default is always IgM/IgD. (isotype switching pattern)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> IgM/IgD co-expression is alternative splicing of one transcript (no DNA change). Class switching to IgG/IgA/IgE is a later DNA-deletion event after activation. Don’t conflate the two.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The functional role of exclusion: one cell = one specificity. Co-expressing IgM and IgD doesn’t break this because both share the identical VDJ variable region.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Isotype-to-site map: IgA mucosa, IgE allergy/parasite, IgG tissue — and the naive default is always IgM + IgD (marginal-zone B cells stay IgM).</p><p>ReClaude A: A single primary transcript spanning Cμ and Cδ is alternatively spliced — to Cμ for IgM, to Cδ for IgD — so both appear with the identical VDJ variable region and no second rearrangement. Allelic and isotypic exclusion keep the cell to one heavy-chain allele and one light-chain isotype, so co-expressing two isotypes never adds a second specificity.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "8_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Walk the heavy chain from germline DNA to a surface receptor. At which single step does failure doom the cell, and why?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This LO is the ordered choreography of V(D)J recombination — the actual sequence of cuts, joins, and checkpoints. The unifying idea is that rearrangement proceeds in a fixed order with a checkpoint: the heavy chain goes first, and only a successful, in-frame heavy chain licenses the light chain to proceed. Fail the checkpoint and the cell dies. Everything else is the mechanics around that gate.</p><p>HEAVY CHAIN FIRST — D-J, THEN V-DJ. Heavy-chain rearrangement leads, and within it the order is specific: D joins J first, then V joins the DJ. You cannot skip the D segment (&gt;99% of the time). When the DNA is cut and religated, the join is only productive if it lands in frame; an out-of-frame join makes no protein. The cell gets two tries (maternal and paternal alleles), but if both heavy-chain alleles fail to produce an in-frame product, there is no heavy chain — and the cell undergoes apoptosis. This is the load-bearing checkpoint.</p><p>Heavy chain rearranges first; order is D-J then V-DJ (you cannot skip D). (heavy-chain join order) CQ An in-frame heavy chain is the checkpoint; both alleles failing → apoptosis. (heavy-chain checkpoint)</p><p>Alternative splicing of the heavy-chain transcript generates the mature IgM and IgD mRNAs.</p><p>Light-chain (kappa) rearrangement: V→J joining, then splicing removes extra J introns to the mRNA.</p><p>Heavy-chain rearrangement: D→J joining, then V→DJ; DNA is permanently altered (deleted segments are gone).</p><p>Primary transcript includes introns and extra J segments; transcribed through μ and δ for IgM/IgD.</p><p>LIGHT CHAIN SECOND — only if heavy succeeds. A successful heavy chain triggers light-chain rearrangement, which starts with kappa (isotypic exclusion suppressing lambda); lambda proceeds only if kappa fails in frame. Light chains use simple V-J joining. At every stage the rule is the same: an out-of-frame or non-productive rearrangement that exhausts the available alleles sends the cell to apoptosis — the immune system would rather kill a non-functional precursor than let it linger.</p><p>FROM DNA TO PROTEIN. Once segments are joined, the rearranged DNA is permanently altered — the intervening segments are deleted and degraded, never recovered. Transcription makes a primary RNA that still contains extra J segments and introns; splicing removes them to yield mature mRNA. For the heavy chain specifically, alternative splicing across Cμ and Cδ produces both IgM and IgD (LO 8.4); for the light chain, ordinary splicing just trims the extra J introns. Translation then sends the chains to the ER, where heavy and light pair into a complete receptor displayed on the surface. The same V(D)J choreography runs in T cells in the thymus — β/δ like a heavy chain, α/γ like a light chain.</p><p>Light chain rearranges only if heavy succeeds; starts with kappa (V-J), lambda only on kappa failure. (light-chain order) CQ Rearranged DNA is permanently altered (segments deleted); splicing trims introns/extra J to mature mRNA. (DNA-to-mRNA processing)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Fixed order with a gate: heavy first (D-J then V-DJ) → checkpoint → light second (V-J, kappa first). An in-frame heavy chain is the permission slip for everything downstream.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Heavy-chain order is D-J first, then V-DJ — not V-D first. And you cannot skip the D segment. A stem that joins V to D before D-J is describing the wrong sequence.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Failure → apoptosis. No in-frame heavy chain means no light-chain rearrangement and a dead precursor. The system discards non-functional cells rather than tolerating them.</p><p>ReClaude A: Germline DNA → D-J joining → V-DJ joining → in-frame check → (if productive) transcription, splicing to mRNA, translation, ER pairing with light chain, surface display. The doomed step is the in-frame heavy-chain checkpoint: if both alleles join out of frame there is no heavy chain, light-chain rearrangement never starts, and the cell undergoes apoptosis.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "9_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Why can the heavy chain never join a V directly to a J, yet the TCR beta/delta locus can skip its D segment entirely — with no change to the enzymes involved?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Where Lecture 8 said rearrangement is random, this LO explains what keeps it orderly: the recombination signal sequences (RSS) and the 12/23 rule. The unifying idea is that the RSS is a molecular punctuation mark flanking every V, D, and J segment, and its spacer length dictates which segments are even allowed to join. Randomness in segment choice, yes — but the grammar of joining is strictly regulated by these sequences.</p><p>RSS ARCHITECTURE. Each RSS has three parts in a fixed order: a heptamer (7 bp, always closest to the gene), a spacer, and a nonamer (9 bp, always farthest). Every V/D/J segment is flanked by an RSS. The spacer comes in two lengths — 12 bp or 23 bp — and that single difference is the regulatory lever. Because one turn of the DNA helix is ~11 bp, a 12-bp spacer is one turn and a 23-bp spacer is two turns; both place the flanking segments on the same face of the helix so the recombinase can align and cut them.</p><p>RSS = heptamer (7 bp, nearest gene) + spacer + nonamer (9 bp, farthest); flanks every V/D/J. (RSS architecture) CQ Spacer is 12 bp (one turn) or 23 bp (two turns) — puts segments on the same helical face. (spacer length / helical face)</p><p>Two spacer lengths: one-turn (12 bp) and two-turn (23 bp) — the basis of the 12/23 rule.</p><p>RSS = heptamer + spacer + nonamer; recognized by RAG1/RAG2; the heptamer is closest to the gene.</p><p>12/23 spacer layout per locus: H = V(23)-(12)D(12)-(23)J; β/δ D has 12 front, 23 back — allowing add/skip.</p><p>THE 12/23 RULE — the regulatory payoff. A segment flanked by a 12-bp-spacer RSS can only join one flanked by a 23-bp-spacer RSS (one turn pairs with two turns). Two like spacers — 12+12 or 23+23 — cannot recombine. This is what enforces correct assembly. In the heavy chain, each D has a 12 on both sides, so two Ds (12+12) cannot join and a direct V-to-J (23+23) is forbidden — you must go through the D. In the TCR β/δ loci, the D has a 12 in front and a 23 behind, which permits both a direct V-J join (skipping D) and tandem D-D joins (adding D) — a source of extra diversity, though in practice only observed in δ. Davis was explicit: you do not need to memorize which side carries which spacer, only that the geometry is what allows or forbids each join.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The RSS spacer is the regulator: 12 must pair with 23 (one turn with two). Same helical face → the recombinase can align and cut. Like-with-like (12+12, 23+23) is forbidden.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> The numbers 12 and 23 are spacer lengths in base pairs, NOT counts of gene segments or chromosome numbers. They approximate one and two helical turns (~11 bp/turn).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Heavy chain: D has 12 on both sides → cannot skip or duplicate D. TCR β/δ: D has 12 front / 23 back → can skip or add D (extra diversity, seen mainly in δ). Same RAG enzymes either way.</p><p>ReClaude A: The 12/23 rule is the reason: heavy-chain D segments carry 12-bp spacers on both sides, so V-J (23+23) and D-D (12+12) joins are forbidden and the D is obligatory; TCR β/δ D segments carry a 12 in front and 23 behind, so V-J (skipping D) and D-D (adding D) are both allowed. The recombinase (RAG1/2) is identical — only the RSS spacer geometry differs.</p><p><em>Trace a single junction from the RAG cut to the final ligation. Which enzyme adds nucleotides without a template, and why does that step so often produce a non-functional join?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This LO is the enzymatic cast list and the choreography that assembles a junction. The unifying idea: a defined sequence of enzymes cuts the DNA at the RSS, opens the resulting hairpin, then trims and adds nucleotides at the seam — and that very trimming/adding is what generates junctional diversity while frequently knocking the join out of frame. Know the cast and the order and the rest follows.</p><p>THE CUT — RAG, then Artemis. RAG1/RAG2 (the recombination-activating genes, a.k.a. the V(D)J recombinase) recognize the RSS and nick the DNA within the palindromic heptamer, generating a hairpin on the gene side. Artemis, an endonuclease, then opens the hairpin, leaving uneven overhang ends. The intervening DNA between the chosen segments loops out, is deleted, and is permanently lost — the rearranged DNA can never revert.</p><p>RAG1/RAG2 recognize the RSS and cut within the palindromic heptamer, making a hairpin. (RAG = the initial cut) CQ Artemis (endonuclease) opens the hairpin → uneven overhang ends; intervening DNA is deleted permanently. (Artemis opens the hairpin)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Artemis opens the hairpin; DNA polymerase then evens the overhang ends (templated P-nucleotides).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> RAG1/RAG2 align the palindromic heptamers, nick the DNA, and the intervening DNA is looped out and deleted.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> P-nucleotide addition: RAG cuts, leaving a hairpin; Artemis opens it, creating uneven (overhang) ends.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Junctional flexibility: exonuclease trims exposed nucleotides, varying the junction (CDR3) sequence.</p><p>THE SEAM — junctional diversity in three steps. The junction is where diversity is manufactured, in a fixed sequence. (1) P-nucleotide addition (P = palindromic): after Artemis opens the hairpin, DNA polymerase uses the longer strand as template to even the overhangs — a templated step. (2) Junctional flexibility: an exonuclease chews back exposed nucleotides (sometimes more than were added, even into the original gene). (3) N-nucleotide addition: terminal deoxynucleotidyl transferase (TdT) adds non-templated nucleotides (N = non-templated) — it simply invents 1–10 bases. DNA polymerase then fills the complementary strand and DNA ligase seals the join. Because P/N steps add and subtract nucleotides, &gt;90% of attempts land out of frame and the cell dies — the price of diversity. This junctional machinery acts only at the seam, so it modifies CDR3 alone.</p><p>Junction order: P-addition (polymerase, templated) → junctional flexibility (exonuclease) → N-addition (TdT, non-templated) → ligase.</p><p>(junctional-diversity order) CQ TdT adds non-templated nucleotides; add/subtract at the seam → &gt;90% out of frame, and affects CDR3 only. (TdT / out-of-frame / CDR3)</p><p>N-nucleotide addition: TdT adds non-templated bases; DNA polymerase fills the gap; ligase joins the ends.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> P-nucleotide addition occurs within the palindromic heptamer at both gene ends (D and J, or V and DJ).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Junctional flexibility uses exonuclease to remove nucleotides — same V/D/J genes can yield different specificities.</p><p>WHY IT MATTERS. The cast is the answer to most regulation questions: a defect in any one component has predictable consequences. Lose RAG1/2 and recombination never starts in either B or T cells — the result is SCID. Lose Artemis and hairpins cannot open. The same junctional steps run in both B and T cells (junctional diversity is shared), with P/N addition far more common in heavy chains than light. Hold the thread: the enzymes that make a junction also decide whether the cell survives the attempt.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> P-nucleotides are templated (polymerase, palindromic); N-nucleotides are NON-templated (TdT). Don’t swap them. &quot;N&quot; = non-templated is the memory hook.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> A complete RAG loss → no V(D)J in B OR T cells → SCID. The add/subtract at the junction is why &gt;90% of rearrangements fail in frame — diversity has a high mortality cost.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Cast in order: RAG1/2 cut → Artemis opens the hairpin → polymerase evens ends (P) → exonuclease trims (flexibility) → TdT adds non-templated (N) → polymerase + ligase finish.</p><p>ReClaude A: Order: RAG1/2 nick the RSS heptamer (hairpin) → Artemis opens the hairpin → DNA polymerase evens the overhangs (templated P-nucleotides) → exonuclease trims (junctional flexibility) → TdT adds non-templated N-nucleotides → polymerase fills and ligase seals. TdT is the template-independent adder; because P/N steps add and remove nucleotides, the join is out of frame &gt;90% of the time and the cell undergoes apoptosis.</p><p><em>RAG cuts the DNA, but what actually decides WHICH two segments RAG is allowed to bring together — and why is the heptamer’s palindromic sequence essential to that step?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This LO draws the line between the components that regulate rearrangement and the enzymes that execute it. The regulators are the recombination signal sequences themselves — the heptamer, spacer, and nonamer — working through the 12/23 rule. They carry no enzymatic activity; their job is purely to specify which joins are permitted and to align the DNA so the recombinase can act.</p><p>THE REGULATING COMPONENTS. The spacer length (12 vs 23) is the gatekeeper: it enforces that a one-turn segment joins only a two-turn segment, so the wrong segments never come together. The heptamer is palindromic, which lets the two heptamers align (roughly) so the RAG complex can nick within them — alignment is the prerequisite for cutting. The nonamer provides an additional RAG-recognition anchor. Together these sequences also keep the joining segments on the same helical face, which is why the spacer must be a whole number of turns. None of this is coding sequence; the RSS is signal, not protein.</p><p>The RSS (heptamer/spacer/nonamer) regulates joining; the spacer length enforces the 12/23 rule. (RSS regulates which segments join) CQ Palindromic heptamers align the two segments so RAG can nick; the nonamer anchors recognition. (palindromic heptamer alignment)</p><p>Palindromic heptamers align the two segments and play a key role in starting recombination and adding diversity.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Heptamers align, RAG cuts, intervening DNA is removed and the chosen segments are joined and repaired.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Kappa V and J heptamers align (approximately) and are cut by the RAG1/RAG2 recombinase complex.</p><p>ROLE IN THE PROCESS. The regulatory logic comes first, the enzymes second: the RSS spacers decide the legal pairing, the palindromic heptamers align the partners, and only then does RAG nick the DNA to begin the cut-loop-delete-join sequence from LO 9.2. The same palindromic heptamer that aligns the segments is also where P-nucleotide diversity is later generated — so the regulator of joining is structurally continuous with the source of junctional diversity. Regulation and diversity are built into the same short sequence.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Don’t conflate the regulators (RSS sequences) with the executors (RAG, Artemis, TdT, ligase). The RSS decides what is allowed; the enzymes carry it out.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> The palindromic heptamer does double duty: it aligns the two segments for cutting AND is the site where P-nucleotide junctional diversity later arises.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Regulators = the RSS (heptamer, spacer, nonamer) and the 12/23 rule. They specify which segments may join and align them — but they are signal, not enzyme. RAG does the cutting.</p><p>ReClaude A: The RSS spacer lengths (the 12/23 rule) decide which two segments are eligible to join, and the palindromic heptamers let those two segments align on the same helical face so RAG can nick within them — alignment is the prerequisite for the cut. The RSS regulates; RAG executes.</p><p><em>Both B and T cells use combinatorial and junctional diversity. Name the two mechanisms B cells have that T cells lack — and explain why T cells are forbidden from using one of them.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This is the lecture’s big DISTINGUISH: B and T cells generate receptor diversity by overlapping but not identical mechanisms. The unifying idea is timing and constraint — B cells can keep editing their receptors even after meeting antigen, while T cells are locked once educated, because changing a TCR risks losing the MHC recognition the thymus selected for. That single constraint explains every difference in the table.</p><p>THE FOUR B-CELL MECHANISMS. Three are antigen-independent and happen in the bone marrow: combinatorial diversity (random V(D)J joining, a DNA/gene-level event), combinatorial association (any heavy-chain protein pairing with any light chain, a protein-level event), and junctional diversity (P/N nucleotide add/subtract at the seam). The fourth, somatic hypermutation (the molecular basis of affinity maturation), is antigen-dependent and happens later in secondary lymphoid follicles — point mutations across the whole V region that let antibodies improve with each exposure.</p><p>B-cell diversity = combinatorial diversity (DNA) + combinatorial association (protein) + junctional + somatic hypermutation. (four B-cell mechanisms) CQ Three are antigen-independent (marrow); somatic hypermutation is antigen-dependent (follicles). (independent vs dependent)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Combinatorial diversity: random V(D)J joining at the DNA/gene level — shared by B and T cells. Combinatorial association: any heavy chain pairs with any light chain at the protein level — B cells only.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> TCR diversity: more J genes, plus β/δ D-skip or multiple-D via RSS config (multiple-D seen only in δ).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Four B-cell diversity mechanisms: three antigen-independent (combinatorial ×2, junctional) plus antigen-dependent somatic hypermutation.</p><p>WHAT T CELLS USE — AND DON’T. T cells share combinatorial diversity and junctional diversity, and they gain extra diversity from two TCR-specific routes: the α-chain bypass of allelic exclusion (one T cell can carry two α chains) and the ability to add or skip D segments in β/δ (from the RSS layout in LO 9.1, observed mainly in δ), aided by a larger pool of J segments. But T cells do NOT use combinatorial association (chains pair strictly αβ or γδ, never mix-and-match) and do NOT use somatic hypermutation. The reason for the latter is the load-bearing concept: TCRs are educated in the thymus to recognize self-MHC, and any post-thymic mutation could destroy that recognition, leaving a useless T cell that can never be activated. So once a T cell leaves the thymus, nothing changes — no hypermutation, no isotype switching, no αβ-to-γδ conversion.</p><p>Combinatorial diversity (random V(D)J) Yes Yes DNA/gene level; shared</p><p>Combinatorial association (any H + any L) Yes No Protein level; B-cell only</p><p>Junctional diversity (P/N add/subtract) Yes Yes Affects CDR3 only; shared</p><p>Somatic hypermutation (affinity maturation) Yes No Antigen-dependent; B-cell only</p><p>α-chain allelic-exclusion bypass No Yes Two α chains on one T cell</p><p>D add/skip (β/δ via RSS) No Yes Mainly observed in δ</p><p>THE CDR RULE THAT TIES IT TOGETHER. Two diversity mechanisms hit different parts of the receptor. Junctional diversity acts only at the segment seam, so it changes CDR3 only. Somatic hypermutation scatters point mutations across the entire V region, so it can change all three CDRs (and frameworks). That contrast — same-junction vs whole-region — is a favorite test point, and it falls straight out of where each mechanism physically operates.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Somatic hypermutation: point mutations in the V region AFTER antigen exposure — antigen-dependent, B cells only. Affinity maturation: B cells with higher-affinity mutated antibodies are selected on follicular dendritic cells; the rest undergo apoptosis.</p><p>T cells use combinatorial + junctional + α-bypass + D add/skip; they lack combinatorial association and somatic hypermutation. (TCR diversity set) CQ TCRs are locked after thymic MHC education — no hypermutation, isotype switch, or αβ↔γδ change. (why TCRs are fixed)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Junctional diversity → CDR3 only (acts at the seam). Somatic hypermutation → all CDRs (point mutations across the whole V region). Where it acts determines what it changes.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Why no TCR hypermutation? TCRs are educated to self-MHC; mutating them post-thymus could break that recognition and waste the cell. After the thymus, the TCR is frozen.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> B cells have two mechanisms T cells lack: combinatorial association and somatic hypermutation. Students forget one or add somatic hypermutation to T cells — it never happens in T cells.</p><p>ReClaude A: B cells uniquely use combinatorial association (any heavy chain with any light chain, at the protein level) and somatic hypermutation (antigen-dependent affinity maturation). T cells are forbidden from somatic hypermutation because they are educated in the thymus to recognize self-MHC — a post-thymic mutation could destroy that recognition and render the T cell unable to ever be activated, so the TCR is locked once it leaves the thymus.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "10_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A thymocyte has made a β chain but has no α chain yet. How does it prove the β chain is real and in-frame — and what is the consequence if it cannot?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. T-cell ontogeny is a staged assembly line with two go/no-go checkpoints. The unifying idea: a thymocyte must first build a working TCR (the double-negative stages, gated by proving each chain is in-frame) and only then is it tested against self (selection, the next LO). Everything that follows hangs on that order — build first, select second — and on the fact that nearly all of it happens in the cortex.</p><p>WHERE AND WHAT. A hematopoietic progenitor commits to the T lineage, leaves the marrow, and enters the thymus as a thymocyte, arriving through the subcapsular region and moving into the outer cortex. Because it expresses neither co-receptor, it is double-negative (DN) — CD4− CD8−. There are four DN stages, and the TCR β chain is assembled across them in the same order as a B-cell heavy chain: D-J first, then V-DJ.</p><p>Progenitor → thymus → thymocyte; enters via subcapsular region into the outer cortex; starts double-negative. (entry / DN start) CQ DN1 Notch1 + IL-7 commit T-lineage; DN2 β D-J join (RAG up); DN3 β V-DJ join completes β. (DN1–DN3 β rearrangement)</p><p>DN2: β-chain D-J joining begins (RAG1/RAG2 upregulated); γ/δ genes rearrange in parallel.</p><p>DN3: V-DJ joining completes the β chain; splicing yields β mRNA, then β-chain protein.</p><p>DN1: progenitor expresses Notch1; cTECs express Notch ligand and IL-7, committing the cell to the T lineage.</p><p>CHECKPOINT 1 — prove the β chain (DN3). Most rearrangements fail in frame, so the cell must prove it made a real β chain before investing in an α chain. It cannot wait for the α chain, so it builds an invariant surrogate pre-T-α chain (no V(D)J — the same sequence in everyone), pairs it with the β chain plus the CD3 complex and ζ chains, and sends this pre-TCR to the surface. Reaching the surface IS the proof — “yes, there is a β chain.” Fail this checkpoint and the cell undergoes apoptosis. Success triggers a round of proliferation (one good β chain copied into many cells), because the next step also has a high failure rate.</p><p>CHECKPOINT 2 — prove the α chain (DN4). RAG1/RAG2 are re-expressed and the α chain rearranges (V-J). Now a real α chain pairs with the β chain (plus CD3/ζ) to form a complete αβ TCR — checkpoint 2 confirms an in-frame α chain. Allelic exclusion applies throughout (mom’s or dad’s allele wins), with the α-chain bypass exception from Lecture 9. Having proven both chains, the cell finally upregulates both CD4 and CD8 to become double-positive (DP) — and only now is it ready for selection.</p><p>Checkpoint 1 (DN3): β + surrogate pre-T-α + CD3/ζ → pre-TCR to surface proves β; fail → apoptosis, pass → proliferation. (checkpoint 1) CQ Checkpoint 2 (DN4): α V-J rearranges → complete αβ TCR; then upregulate CD4 + CD8 → double-positive. (checkpoint 2 → DP)</p><p>Checkpoint 1: the pre-TCR (β + pre-T-α + CD3 + ζ) on the surface confirms a successful β-chain rearrangement.</p><p>DN4: RAG re-expressed; α-chain V-J rearrangement forms a complete TCR — checkpoint 2 confirms the α chain.</p><p>Double-positive: CD4 and CD8 are both upregulated alongside the complete αβ TCR and CD3/ζ.</p><p>WHY THE ORDER MATTERS. The checkpoints exist because random rearrangement is wasteful — the cell refuses to build the second chain until the first is proven, and refuses to express co-receptors until a whole TCR exists. Proliferation after checkpoint 1 rescues yield from the high α-chain failure rate. Hold this thread into the next LO: a double-positive cell with a complete TCR has earned the right to be tested against self, and that test (positive then negative selection) is what turns a DP thymocyte into a single mature T cell.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> The pre-T-α (surrogate α) is invariant — it does NOT undergo V(D)J and is the same in everyone. Its only job is to escort the β chain to the surface for checkpoint 1.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> β-chain order mirrors the heavy chain: D-J (DN2) before V-DJ (DN3). The α chain (V-J) comes last, in DN4. Build the receptor first; selection comes only after the double-positive stage.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two checkpoints gate the build: checkpoint 1 (DN3) proves the β chain via the surrogate pre-T-α pre-TCR; checkpoint 2 (DN4) proves the α chain via the complete αβ TCR. Then CD4+CD8 → double-positive.</p><p>ReClaude A: It builds an invariant surrogate pre-T-α chain, pairs it with the β chain plus CD3 and ζ, and displays this pre-TCR on the surface — reaching the surface is the proof that an in-frame β chain was made (checkpoint 1, DN3). If it cannot, the thymocyte undergoes apoptosis; if it can, it proliferates and proceeds to rearrange the α chain at DN4.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "10_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Two thymic epithelial cell types do superficially similar jobs — presenting MHC to thymocytes — yet they sit in different regions and serve opposite halves of education. Name them and their distinct roles.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The thymus has two regions — outer cortex and inner medulla — each stocked with specific cells for specific steps. The unifying idea: cortex = build + positive selection, medulla = final negative selection + Treg induction. Knowing which cell lives where and what signal it provides answers most component questions, because the location maps directly onto the step.</p><p>CORTEX COMPONENTS. The cortical thymic epithelial cells (cTECs) are the workhorses: they express Notch ligand and secrete IL-7 to push the progenitor down the T-cell road and support development, and later they display class I and class II MHC for positive selection. Dendritic cells also present MHC-peptide during selection, and macrophages clear the many thymocytes that fail and die. The Notch1 (thymocyte) – Notch-ligand (cTEC) interaction is decisive: too little permits aberrant B-cell development in the thymus; Notch1 overexpression in marrow can drive ectopic T-cell development there.</p><p>Cortex = cTECs (Notch ligand + IL-7, then MHC I/II), dendritic cells, macrophages; site of build + positive selection. (cortex components) CQ Notch1 – Notch ligand commits T-lineage; too little → thymic B cells, marrow overexpression → marrow T cells. (Notch signaling)</p><p>Thymus structure: two regions — outer cortex and inner medulla — each with distinct cells and steps.</p><p>Medulla cells: mTECs and dendritic cells present self-peptides for negative selection; macrophages remove apoptotic cells.</p><p>Cortex cells: cTECs (express Notch ligand and IL-7, promote development), macrophages (clear apoptotic thymocytes), dendritic cells (present peptide).</p><p>MEDULLA COMPONENTS. The medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTECs) and dendritic cells present self-peptide on MHC for the second round of negative selection. Their special tool is AIRE (autoimmune regulator), which drives mTECs to express tissue-restricted self-antigens they would not normally make — so thymocytes reactive to peripheral tissues can be deleted centrally. The clinical hook: an AIRE mutation causes autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome. The medulla also contains Hassall’s corpuscles, where mTECs express thymic stromal lymphopoietin (TSLP); TSLP prompts dendritic cells to drive a small subset of thymocytes to express FoxP3 and become regulatory T cells (Tregs).</p><p>Medulla = mTECs + dendritic cells (self-peptide for negative selection) using AIRE; AIRE mutation → autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome. (medulla / AIRE) CQ Hassall’s corpuscles → mTEC TSLP → DCs induce FoxP3 → Tregs. (Hassall’s / TSLP / Tregs)</p><p>Inner medulla: Hassall’s corpuscles express TSLP, which triggers DCs to induce FoxP3+ regulatory T cells.</p><p>mTECs express AIRE (autoimmune regulator) to display tissue-restricted self-antigens for negative selection.</p><p>WHY THIS MATTERS. The component list is really a map: if a question places an event in the cortex, the actors are cTECs/DCs/macrophages and the step is build or positive selection; if in the medulla, the actors are mTECs/DCs (with AIRE) and Hassall’s corpuscles, and the step is negative selection or Treg induction. AIRE and FoxP3 are the two named molecules most likely to be tested, each tied to a clinical consequence (autoimmunity when AIRE fails; tolerance when FoxP3 drives Tregs).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Location = function. cTECs (cortex): Notch ligand + IL-7, then positive selection. mTECs (medulla): AIRE-driven self-antigen for negative selection. Hassall’s corpuscles → TSLP → Tregs.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Don’t swap cTECs and mTECs. cTEC = cortex = positive selection; mTEC = medulla = negative selection (with AIRE). The first letters line up: c-cortex, m-medulla.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Two named molecules carry clinical weight: AIRE (loss → autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome) and FoxP3 (drives Tregs; its failure → loss of tolerance). Expect both on an exam.</p><p>ReClaude A: Cortical thymic epithelial cells (cTECs) sit in the cortex and mediate positive selection (after first providing Notch ligand and IL-7); medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTECs) sit in the medulla and mediate negative selection, using AIRE to express tissue-restricted self-antigens. Same MHC-presentation activity, opposite halves of education, different regions.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "10_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>B-cell receptors keep improving after they leave the marrow, but TCRs are frozen the moment they leave the thymus. What structural/functional fact forces that difference?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This LO connects TCR structure to the developmental story. The unifying idea: the TCR is a membrane-only, MHC-dependent, two-chain receptor, and those features dictate how ontogeny must work — the cell has to assemble two equal chains, prove each at a checkpoint, and then lock the receptor permanently once it has been educated to self-MHC.</p><p>STRUCTURE THAT CONSTRAINS ONTOGENY. The αβ TCR has two chains of similar size — no heavy/light distinction — with the α chain built from V-J and the β chain from V-D-J (Lecture 8 logic). It is never secreted: unlike antibody, a TCR exists only on the T-cell surface, so there is no soluble effector form to mature. And it only recognizes peptide presented on MHC, never free antigen — which is exactly why the thymus must educate it to self-MHC. After a thymocyte matures and leaves, the TCR undergoes no further change: no somatic hypermutation, no isotype switching, no αβ↔γδ conversion.</p><p>αβ TCR = two equal-size chains (no heavy/light); α = V-J, β = V-D-J; never secreted, surface only. (TCR chain structure) CQ TCR sees peptide on MHC, never free antigen — hence thymic education to self-MHC. (MHC dependence)</p><p>~95–97% of T cells use the αβ TCR; γδ TCRs are a minority enriched in mucosa/skin.</p><p>TCR structure: two similar-size chains, each with a variable (V) and constant (C) region; never secreted.</p><p>Positive selection keeps cells recognizing self-MHC; negative selection removes self-reactive cells — together, education.</p><p>WHY TCRs ARE FROZEN. Here is the structural-functional payoff and the answer to the anchor: because the TCR’s only job is to recognize self-MHC presenting peptide, and because the thymus spends enormous effort selecting a TCR that does exactly that, any post-thymic mutation risks breaking self-MHC recognition — leaving a T cell that can never be activated. So evolution forbids editing. A B cell can afford somatic hypermutation because its antibody recognizes antigen directly and a better-binding variant is simply better; a T cell cannot, because a “better” random mutation could just as easily render it MHC-blind. Structure (MHC-restricted, surface-only) explains the rule (no post-thymic change).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> No somatic hypermutation, no class/isotype switching, no αβ↔γδ conversion in T cells. Those are B-cell (hypermutation/switch) or simply nonexistent (αβ↔γδ) processes.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> The reason TCRs can’t hypermutate: they’re educated to self-MHC, and a post-thymic mutation could destroy that recognition — making the cell useless. Structure dictates the freeze.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> TCR is membrane-only, MHC-restricted, and locked after the thymus. Two equal chains (α = V-J, β = V-D-J), assembled and checkpoint-proven during ontogeny, then never edited.</p><p>ReClaude A: The TCR recognizes only peptide presented on self-MHC (never free antigen) and exists only on the cell surface, so the thymus must educate it to self-MHC — and any post-thymic mutation could destroy that hard-won recognition, leaving an unactivatable cell. That is why TCRs undergo no somatic hypermutation or other change after the thymus, whereas membrane/secreted antibodies can safely affinity-mature.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "10_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Three double-positive thymocytes: one binds self-MHC weakly, one binds self-MHC + self-peptide strongly, one binds no MHC at all. What is each one’s fate, and where does it happen?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Selection is the test that turns a double-positive thymocyte into a safe, useful single-positive T cell. Davis flagged this hard — “hint, hint, wink, wink.” The unifying idea is a Goldilocks affinity window: too little binding to self-MHC and the cell is useless; too much and it is dangerous; just-right (low/intermediate) and it survives. Two selections enforce this, in two regions.</p><p>POSITIVE SELECTION — cortex, keep the useful. In the cortex, double-positive thymocytes test their TCR against self-MHC displayed by cortical thymic epithelial cells (and dendritic cells). A thymocyte that recognizes self-MHC with low/intermediate affinity passes — this is MHC restriction, guaranteeing the cell can engage the body’s own MHC. A thymocyte that recognizes none of the ~12 self-MHC molecules can never be activated and dies by death by neglect (apoptosis) — the most common outcome, since random TCRs rarely fit self-MHC.</p><p>Positive selection (cortex): recognize self-MHC at low affinity → pass = MHC restriction; on cTECs/DCs. (positive selection) CQ Death by neglect: recognizes no self-MHC → apoptosis — the most common fate. (death by neglect)</p><p>MHC restriction: class I recognition → only CD8 matures; class II recognition → only CD4 matures.</p><p>Three cortical outcomes: positive selection (recognize MHC, moderate affinity), negative selection (too strong), death by neglect (no MHC).</p><p>Overview: recognize MHC I → CD8 single positive; MHC II → CD4; no self-MHC → apoptosis (death by neglect).</p><p>NEGATIVE SELECTION — deleting the dangerous. The danger is a TCR that binds self-MHC plus self-peptide with high affinity — a self-reactive cell that could cause autoimmunity. Negative selection deletes these by apoptosis. It happens in two rounds: a first round in the cortex (combined with positive selection at the double-positive stage), and a second, dedicated round in the medulla on single-positive cells, where medullary thymic epithelial cells and dendritic cells present self-peptide. The medulla’s special tool is AIRE, which forces expression of tissue-restricted self-antigens so even thymocytes reactive to distant tissues are deleted centrally. Clinically, an AIRE mutation → autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome.</p><p>Feature Positive selection Negative selection</p><p>Region Cortex Cortex (round 1) + medulla (round 2)</p><p>Presenting cells cTECs, dendritic cells mTECs, dendritic cells</p><p>Recognizes Self-MHC (low affinity) Self-MHC + self-peptide (high affinity)</p><p>Outcome Survive (MHC restriction) Apoptosis (self-tolerance)</p><p>Key molecule — AIRE (tissue-restricted self-antigen)</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Hold three outcomes apart by affinity: no self-MHC binding → death by neglect; low self-MHC binding → positive selection (survive); high self-MHC + self-peptide binding → negative selection (delete). The first two are decided in the cortex (with the CD4/CD8 lineage choice folded in — next LO), and the definitive negative round happens in the medulla. A frequent confusion is that negative selection happens in the cortex too; it does, but the dedicated single-positive round is medullary, and that is where AIRE acts.</p><p>Negative selection: self-MHC + self-peptide at high affinity → apoptosis = tolerance; medullary round uses AIRE. (negative selection) CQ Three outcomes by affinity: none → neglect, low → positive (survive), high → negative (delete). (affinity window)</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Don’t collapse the three outcomes. No MHC binding = death by neglect; low = positive selection; high (MHC + self-peptide) = negative selection. Affinity is the discriminator.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> AIRE forces tissue-restricted self-antigen expression in mTECs so peripheral-reactive cells die centrally. Lose AIRE → autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Region maps to step: positive selection = cortex (cTECs, MHC restriction); the dedicated negative round = medulla (mTECs + AIRE, self-tolerance). Both delete by apoptosis when failed.</p><p>ReClaude A: The weak self-MHC binder passes positive selection (MHC restriction) in the cortex; the strong self-MHC + self-peptide binder is deleted by negative selection (the dedicated round in the medulla, AIRE-dependent); the cell that binds no MHC dies by death by neglect in the cortex — the most common fate. Affinity to self determines all three.</p><p><em>A mature CD8+ T cell is killing virus-infected cells. Trace its fate backwards: what single event in the thymus committed it to that job, and could the same precursor have become a helper cell instead?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This is the lecture’s integrative payoff and a concept Davis explicitly posed as a thinking question. The unifying idea: positive selection does more than enforce MHC restriction — it assigns the cell’s lifelong effector function. The MHC class a double-positive thymocyte happens to recognize determines which co-receptor it keeps, and that co-receptor determines whether it becomes a killer or a helper. Function is decided in the thymus, before the cell ever sees a pathogen.</p><p>THE COUPLING. A double-positive thymocyte expresses both CD4 and CD8 and tests its TCR against self-MHC. If the TCR recognizes MHC class I, the cell keeps CD8 and loses CD4, maturing into a cytotoxic T lymphocyte (CTL) that mediates cell-mediated immunity — killing infected or abnormal cells. If the TCR recognizes MHC class II, the cell keeps CD4 and loses CD8, maturing into a helper T cell that coordinates the response (largely the humoral arm). The co-receptor is not incidental: CD8 binds class I, CD4 binds class II, so keeping the matching co-receptor is what makes the mature cell functional.</p><p>Class I → keep CD8 → CTL → cell-mediated immunity; class II → keep CD4 → helper → (largely) humoral. (class → co-receptor → function) CQ CD8 binds class I, CD4 binds class II — retaining the matching co-receptor is what makes the cell work. (co-receptor matching)</p><p>Positive selection ensures MHC restriction AND sets effector function: CD4+ → helper, CD8+ → CTL when activated.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Class I recognition → lose CD4, keep CD8; class II recognition → lose CD8, keep CD4 → single positive.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Double-positive thymocytes resolve to a single co-receptor based on the MHC class their TCR recognizes.</p><p>WHY THIS IS INTEGRATIVE. The answer to the anchor: the CD8 CTL was committed when its double-positive precursor recognized self-MHC class I during positive selection, retaining CD8. The very same precursor, had its TCR instead engaged class II, would have retained CD4 and become a helper. So a single selection event — which MHC class the TCR fits — simultaneously satisfies MHC restriction, removes the unneeded co-receptor, and locks in effector identity. This is why the course treats positive selection as the moment a T cell’s destiny is set: the lineage decision (CD4 vs CD8) and the functional decision (helper vs killer) are the same decision, made long before antigen.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Effector function is fixed during positive selection in the thymus — NOT chosen later when the cell meets antigen. Antigen activates a function that was already assigned.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Memory hook: the number matches the class. CD8 ↔ class I (8 = I×?), CD4 ↔ class II — and 8×1 vs 4×2 both make 8, so CD8·classI and CD4·classII. Keep the matching co-receptor.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One event, two consequences: recognizing class I → CD8 → CTL (cell-mediated); recognizing class II → CD4 → helper (humoral). Positive selection sets BOTH MHC restriction and effector function.</p><p>ReClaude A: The CD8 CTL was committed when its double-positive precursor recognized self-MHC class I during positive selection, retaining CD8 (and losing CD4) — cell-mediated immunity. Yes: the identical precursor would have become a CD4 helper had its TCR instead recognized class II. The MHC class recognized at positive selection sets both lineage and effector function, before any antigen encounter.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "10_6": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Both lineages rearrange their TCR genes in the cortex, yet only one runs the full selection gauntlet. Which one skips it, where does it branch off, and what is it built to do?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Most of this lecture followed the αβ lineage; this LO contrasts it with the γδ minority. The unifying idea: αβ cells are the heavily-educated majority built for MHC-restricted, body-wide surveillance, while γδ cells are an early-branching minority that skip selection and guard barrier tissues. The split happens early, and the developmental shortcut matches their different job.</p><p>THE αβ PATH (the default). αβ thymocytes are ~95–97% of T cells. They run the full program from this lecture: DN stages, both checkpoints, the double-positive stage, then positive and negative selection, emerging as MHC-restricted single-positive CD4 or CD8 cells. They populate the entire body and can recognize essentially any peptide on MHC.</p><p>THE γδ PATH (the shortcut). The γ, δ, and β genes attempt rearrangement simultaneously; if a successful γδ TCR forms (before β succeeds, or because both β alleles failed), the cell commits to the γδ lineage and exits the thymus early — around DN2/DN3 — without positive or negative selection. γδ cells therefore remain largely double-negative (CD4− CD8−; rare CD8+ examples exist, never CD4+). They are enriched in mucosa and skin (gut, lung), are more prominent before birth (helping infants guard developing mucosa/flora), have a less diverse repertoire with preferred V/D/J combinations, and can recognize lipid antigens on CD1 — fitting targets like mycobacterial lipids at barrier surfaces.</p><p>αβ = ~95%, full selection → single-positive, body-wide, MHC-restricted. (αβ path) CQ γδ = exit at DN2/DN3 without selection, stay double-negative, mucosa/skin, CD1 lipids, more pre-birth. (γδ path)</p><p>γδ thymocytes branch off around DN2/DN3 and exit prior to positive/negative selection, remaining double-negative.</p><p>All thymocytes start double-negative; γδ cells exit early to periphery without the selection steps αβ cells undergo.</p><p>Summary: nearly every step is in the cortex; only the second negative-selection round (single-positive) is in the medulla.</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST — and a useful summary trick. Answering the anchor: the γδ lineage skips selection, branches off early (around DN2/DN3 in the cortex), stays double-negative, and is built to guard mucosa and skin using CD1-presented lipids. Davis offered a memory shortcut for the whole lecture: on the summary chart, almost everything happens in the cortex — the only step in the medulla is the second (single-positive) round of negative selection. So if a question asks where any stage (DN1–4, positive selection, death by neglect, the first negative round, γδ exit) occurs, the answer is the cortex unless it is specifically that single-positive medullary round. Memorize the short list (the one medullary step) and everything else is cortex by elimination.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> γδ cells do NOT undergo positive or negative selection — they leave early and stay double-negative. Don’t apply MHC restriction or CD4/CD8 commitment to them.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> αβ: ~95%, fully selected, single-positive, body-wide. γδ: minority, NO positive/negative selection, exits at DN2/DN3, stays double-negative, mucosa/skin, CD1 lipids, more before birth.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Summary shortcut: only the single-positive negative-selection round is in the medulla; everything else (DN stages, positive selection, death by neglect, γδ exit) is in the cortex. Memorize the one exception.</p><p>ReClaude A: The γδ lineage skips selection: γ/δ/β genes rearrange together, and a successful γδ TCR makes the cell exit early — around DN2/DN3 in the cortex — without positive or negative selection, remaining double-negative. γδ cells guard mucosa and skin, are enriched before birth, and recognize lipid antigens on CD1. αβ cells, by contrast, run the full selection program and become MHC-restricted single-positive cells.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "11_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A naive T cell meets its antigen on a dendritic cell, yet nothing happens — no clone army. Two explanations: the DC was immature, or a signal was missing. What are the three signals, and which two does an immature DC fail to deliver?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This is where antigen presentation (Lec 7) and the receptors (Lec 8–10) get put to use: the dendritic cell presents antigen, and the T cell responds. The unifying idea is a three-signal rule delivered by a mature APC: signal 1 = antigen, signal 2 = co-stimulation, signal 3 = cytokine. Signals 1+2 build the clone army; signal 3 weaponizes it. Miss a signal — or use an immature DC that cannot give signals 2 and 3 — and you get anergy, not activation.</p><p>THE THREE PROFESSIONAL APCs. All three present antigen, but their jobs differ. Dendritic cells are THE primary primers: they capture antigen in tissue and traffic it to the lymph node to activate naive T cells. B cells present antigen too, but “selfishly” — not to activate the T cell, but to get close enough to receive help (the T-dependent antibody response). Macrophages stay in the tissue as phagocytic soldiers, presenting locally rather than migrating. Dendritic cells prime; macrophages fight and present at the target.</p><p>3 APCs: dendritic cells (prime naive T cells, traffic to node), B cells (present to GET help), macrophages (tissue soldiers, present locally). (three professional APCs) CQ Signal 1 = antigen/peptide-MHC→TCR; Signal 2 = CD28–B7 (B7 = CD80/CD86); Signal 3 = cytokine from APC. (the three signals)</p><p>Signal 3: the APC produces a cytokine that polarizes the T cell into Th1, Th2, or Th17.</p><p>Three signals essential for T-cell activation: signal 1 (antigen), signal 2 (co-stimulation), signal 3 (cytokine) — all from the APC.</p><p>Signal 2: microbial components/cytokines induce B7 (CD80/CD86) on the APC — co-stimulation binding CD28.</p><p>SIGNALS 1+2 vs SIGNAL 3. The division of labor is testable. Signals 1 and 2 together drive clonal expansion — the proliferation (IL-2-driven) that builds a large army of T cells all recognizing the same antigen. Signal 3, the cytokine, drives differentiation — it tells the army which weapon to carry, polarizing the cells into Th1, Th2, or Th17 depending on the pathogen class. Without signal 3 you would have an army with no guns; without signals 1+2 you would have no army at all.</p><p>WHY DC MATURATION IS THE GATEKEEPER. An immature DC captures antigen well but expresses little B7 and makes no cytokine — so it can give signal 1 but not signals 2 and 3. Something must mature it, classically TLR signaling (sensing danger), which upregulates CD80/CD86, switches on cytokine genes, and raises MHC. Only a mature DC supplies all three signals. Prime a T cell on an immature DC and it becomes anergic — no clone army — which is exactly one way tumors evade immunity (they block DC maturation).</p><p>Signals 1+2 → clonal expansion (build the army); signal 3 → differentiation (Th1/Th2/Th17 — the weapon). (expansion vs differentiation) CQ Immature DC = signal 1 only → anergy; TLR signaling matures the DC → B7 + cytokine + MHC → all three signals. (DC maturation gate)</p><p>Signals 1+2 = proliferation (clone army); signal 3 = differentiation (weapons) into the effector T cell.</p><p>Maturation of the DC is required: immature DCs capture antigen; mature DCs present it with full co-stimulation.</p><p>Process overview: naive T-cell activation → clonal expansion → T-cell differentiation into effector subsets.</p><p>PRIMING AND THE TWO-PRESENTATION RULE. A subtle point Gregg stresses (textbooks gloss it): priming activates the T cell but withholds effector release. If a freshly primed cell dumped cytokine in the lymph node, systemic TNF-alpha would activate endothelium everywhere and you would bleed to death. So the effector cell leaves the node and must see antigen a second time in the tissue (e.g., on a macrophage) to release cytokine locally, at the target. CD8 cells are likewise primed in the node but only kill once they reach infected tissue — otherwise they would lyse everything in their path.</p><p>SPECIALTY ANTIGENS (the activation curveballs). Superantigens cross-link the TCR V-beta to MHC class II outside the peptide groove, forcing signaling regardless of specificity → polyclonal activation and a cytokine storm (IL-1/IL-6/TNF-alpha); the SARS-CoV-2 spike encodes one (COVID hyperinflammation), and bacterial versions cause toxic shock. Mitogens are polyclonal lab activators that bypass the antigen receptor by binding downstream signaling molecules or TLRs — used to test immune function. Haptens are small molecules that become immunogenic only when coupled to protein (e.g., penicillin on red cells → drug-induced hemolytic anemia; contact dermatitis).</p><p>Priming = activated but effectors withheld; must see antigen a 2nd time in tissue to release locally (avoids systemic TNF-alpha). (two-presentation rule) CQ Superantigen = V-beta–MHC-II cross-link → polyclonal storm; mitogen = lab polyclonal activator; hapten = small molecule + protein. (specialty antigens)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three signals from a mature APC: 1 = antigen (peptide-MHC→TCR), 2 = CD28–B7 (CD80/CD86), 3 = cytokine. Signals 1+2 → expansion; signal 3 → Th1/Th2/Th17 differentiation.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Don’t conflate the APCs: dendritic cells prime naive T cells; B cells present to GET help (selfish, T-dependent); macrophages stay in tissue presenting locally. Only the mature DC gives all three signals.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Priming ≠ effector release. A primed cell needs a second antigen encounter in tissue to act locally — otherwise systemic TNF-alpha would be lethal. This is why we don’t bleed to death every immune response.</p><p>ReClaude A: The three signals are antigen (signal 1, peptide-MHC→TCR), co-stimulation (signal 2, CD28 binding B7 = CD80/CD86), and a cytokine from the APC (signal 3). An immature dendritic cell delivers only signal 1 — it lacks B7 and makes no cytokine, so it fails signals 2 and 3 — and priming on it yields anergy rather than a clone army. TLR-driven maturation is what licenses the DC to deliver all three.</p><p><em>Trace the signal from a ligated TCR to the IL-2 gene. Which single kinase is the indispensable hub — the one whose loss abolishes the entire T-cell response — and what three transcription factors finally switch IL-2 on?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Signals 1 and 2 trigger an intracellular relay that ends at the IL-2 gene. The unifying idea is a proximal-to-distal cascade with one bottleneck (ZAP-70) that then branches into three transcription-factor arms, all of which must fire to transcribe IL-2. Learn the spine of the cascade and the three branch points and you can place any drug or deficiency on the map.</p><p>PROXIMAL SIGNALING. The TCR itself barely signals — the work is done by the associated CD3 complex and zeta chains, whose cytoplasmic ITAMs get phosphorylated. The kinase LCK (lymphocyte-specific protein tyrosine kinase), brought in by the CD4/CD8 co-receptor, phosphorylates those ITAMs, creating docking sites for ZAP-70. ZAP-70 is the hub: if ZAP-70 is deficient, there is no T-cell response. Active ZAP-70 then phosphorylates LAT (linker of activated T cells), the scaffold that launches the downstream branches. Adhesion molecules (LFA-1–ICAM-1) hold the DC–T contact together long enough for this to assemble.</p><p>TCR doesn’t signal — CD3 + zeta ITAMs do; LCK phosphorylates ITAMs → docks ZAP-70 (loss → no response) → phosphorylates LAT. (proximal cascade) CQ Adhesion (LFA-1–ICAM-1) sustains DC–T contact time; CD4/CD8 co-receptor brings in LCK and stabilizes peptide-MHC. (adhesion / co-receptor)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Active ZAP-70 phosphorylates LAT, branching into the MAPK, NF-kB, and NFAT pathways.</p><p>TCR + CD28 engagement: CD3 and the zeta chains serve as the TCR’s signaling complex (ITAMs phosphorylated).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> LCK phosphorylates CD3/zeta ITAMs, recruiting ZAP-70 — the critical docking kinase (deficiency → no response).</p><p>THE THREE TRANSCRIPTION-FACTOR ARMS. From LAT the signal splits three ways, all converging on IL-2. (1) NF-kB arm: protein kinase C (PKC) activates IkB kinase, which phosphorylates IkB; IkB is degraded, freeing NF-kB to enter the nucleus. (2) NFAT arm: phospholipase C makes IP3 → Ca2+ release → Ca2+ binds calmodulin → calmodulin activates calcineurin → calcineurin dephosphorylates NFAT, letting it enter the nucleus. (3) AP-1 arm: RAS/RAC GTPases drive the MAPK pathway (ERK/JNK) → c-Fos + c-Jun assemble into AP-1. All three bind the IL-2 promoter — and all three are required; block any one and the response is crippled. (Two of these arms are the drug targets in the next LO.)</p><p>Three arms to IL-2: PKC→NF-kB; Ca2+→calmodulin→calcineurin→NFAT; RAS/RAC→MAPK→AP-1. All required. (three TF arms)</p><p>NF-kB arm: PKC → IkB kinase → phosphorylates IkB → frees NF-kB → nucleus (glucocorticoid target).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> NFAT arm: Ca2+ → calmodulin → calcineurin dephosphorylates NFAT → nucleus (cyclosporine target).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> AP-1 arm: RAS/RAC → MAPK (ERK/JNK) → c-Fos + c-Jun = AP-1; all three arms converge on the IL-2 gene.</p><p>IL-2 AND INDUCED SURFACE PROTEINS. IL-2 is the payoff of the cascade (CD4 cells are the main producers; CD8 expansion depends on CD4 IL-2). IL-2 (1) drives clonal expansion, (2) induces anti-apoptotic BCL proteins that block BAK/BAX pores (any strongly stimulated cell defaults to apoptosis unless rescued), and (3) upregulates the IL-2 receptor alpha chain = CD25, transiently, opening a window for expansion. Meanwhile CD28 co-stimulation amplifies TCR signaling (without it, signal is too weak) — making CD28 a transplant-drug target. CD40 ligand appears too: it drives B-cell help and class switching beyond IgM, and can mature bystander DCs.</p><p>BRAKES ON THE RESPONSE. Expansion cannot run forever (that would be lymphoma), so inhibitory receptors rise ~day 3–4. CTLA-4 outcompetes CD28 for B7 (removing co-stimulation) AND recruits a phosphatase that strips the CD3/zeta ITAM phosphates — shutting down signaling. PD-1 binds its ligand on the APC and likewise recruits phosphatases. Together they convert exponential growth into a plateau, then contraction — and they reappear later as central tolerance / checkpoint-therapy targets.</p><p>IL-2: clonal expansion + anti-apoptotic BCL + upregulates CD25 (IL-2Rα, transient). CD4 is the main IL-2 source. (IL-2 actions) CQ CD28 amplifies TCR; brakes CTLA-4 (outcompetes CD28 for B7 + phosphatase) and PD-1 arrest expansion ~day 3–4. (amplifier and brakes)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> IL-2 actions: drives clonal expansion, induces anti-apoptotic BCL (survival), and prepares cells for signal 3. Brakes: CTLA-4 and PD-1 rise ~day 3–4 to arrest expansion (outcompete CD28 / recruit phosphatases).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Spine: CD3/zeta ITAMs → LCK → ZAP-70 → LAT → three arms (NF-kB, NFAT, AP-1) → IL-2. ZAP-70 is the indispensable hub; all three transcription factors are required.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> The TCR does not signal itself — CD3 and the zeta chains carry the ITAMs. And IL-2 upregulates CD25 (IL-2Rα), which is transient, not permanent.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Brakes vs gas: CD28 amplifies (gas); CTLA-4 and PD-1 brake (recruit phosphatases ~day 3–4). CTLA-4 also outcompetes CD28 for B7. Same B7, opposite effect.</p><p>ReClaude A: The indispensable hub is ZAP-70: after LCK phosphorylates the CD3/zeta ITAMs, ZAP-70 docks and phosphorylates LAT — lose ZAP-70 and the entire response fails. The cascade then branches into three transcription-factor arms — NF-kB (via PKC), NFAT (via Ca2+/calmodulin/calcineurin), and AP-1 (via MAPK) — all of which bind the IL-2 promoter and all of which are required.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "11_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Two immunosuppressants both lower IL-2 and dampen T cells, but they hit different arms of the same cascade. One blocks NF-kB; the other freezes NFAT in the cytoplasm. Name each drug and its precise target.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This LO maps two drug classes onto the signaling cascade from LO 11.2. The unifying idea: both drugs reduce IL-2 transcription, but by hitting different transcription-factor arms — glucocorticoids on the NF-kB arm, cyclosporine on the NFAT arm. Because all three arms are required for IL-2, knocking out either one cripples clonal expansion.</p><p>GLUCOCORTICOIDS — block NF-kB. Glucocorticoids block NF-kB activation/mobilization. Since NF-kB drives pro-inflammatory cytokine genes (in both innate cells and T cells), blocking it produces broad anti-inflammatory effects — hence glucocorticoids are used for allergies, asthma, autoimmune disease, and sepsis. On the T-cell cascade, no NF-kB means one of the three required IL-2 inputs is missing.</p><p>CYCLOSPORINE — inhibit calcineurin. Cyclosporine inhibits calcineurin. Normally Ca2+ → calmodulin → calcineurin dephosphorylates NFAT so it can enter the nucleus. With calcineurin blocked, NFAT stays phosphorylated in the cytoplasm and never reaches the IL-2 promoter — IL-2 falls, clonal expansion is impaired, and the anti-graft response is blunted. This is why cyclosporine is a mainstay in organ transplantation.</p><p>Glucocorticoids → block NF-kB (broad anti-inflammatory: allergy/asthma/autoimmune/sepsis). (glucocorticoid target) CQ Cyclosporine → inhibit calcineurin → NFAT stuck phosphorylated in cytoplasm → less IL-2 (transplant drug). (cyclosporine target)</p><p>Cyclosporine inhibits calcineurin, so NFAT cannot be dephosphorylated and stays out of the nucleus.</p><p>Both targets sit on the TCR-driven cascade that converges on the IL-2 gene for clonal expansion.</p><p>Glucocorticoids block NF-kB activation — reducing pro-inflammatory cytokine and IL-2 transcription.</p><p>Glucocorticoids NF-kB (blocks activation) Less pro-inflammatory cytokine + IL-2 Allergy, asthma, autoimmune, sepsis</p><p>Cyclosporine Calcineurin (inhibits) NFAT stays phosphorylated → less IL-2 Organ transplantation</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Keep the two arms straight: glucocorticoid → NF-kB; cyclosporine → calcineurin → NFAT. A clean memory hook is that cyclosporine hits calcineurin. Both ultimately lower IL-2 because the IL-2 promoter needs all three transcription factors (NF-kB, NFAT, AP-1); remove either NF-kB or NFAT and IL-2 transcription fails, so clonal expansion — and any T-cell-driven inflammation or rejection — is suppressed.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Don’t swap them. Memory hook: cyclosporine → calcineurin → NFAT. Glucocorticoids are the NF-kB blockers (broad anti-inflammatory).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two arms, two drugs: glucocorticoids block NF-kB; cyclosporine inhibits calcineurin (so NFAT can’t enter the nucleus). Both lower IL-2 → less clonal expansion.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Why it works: the IL-2 promoter needs all three (NF-kB + NFAT + AP-1). Disable either NF-kB or NFAT and IL-2 transcription collapses — no clone army, dampened rejection.</p><p>ReClaude A: Glucocorticoids block NF-kB activation (broad anti-inflammatory, used for allergy/asthma/autoimmune/sepsis); cyclosporine inhibits calcineurin, so NFAT stays phosphorylated in the cytoplasm and cannot transcribe IL-2 (used in transplantation). Both lower IL-2 because the IL-2 promoter requires all three transcription factors.</p><p><em>After a response resolves, three T-cell fates exist: short-lived effectors and two memory types. Two markers — one for survival, one for homing — sort them all out. Which marker does which job, and which cell is which?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. After expansion and the plateau, the T-cell population contracts (most effectors die), leaving a memory pool. The unifying idea is two markers, two jobs: IL-7R governs survival (who lives long-term) and CCR7 governs lymph-node homing (who stays central vs goes to tissue). Reading those two markers tells you the cell’s identity and behavior.</p><p>IL-7R — the survival switch. Naive T cells are IL-7R+, which keeps them alive in the lymph node/spleen. On activation, short-lived effector cells lose IL-7R (and CCR7) — they are IL-7R− CCR7−, go to tissue, act, and then die by apoptosis during contraction. Memory cells, by contrast, retain IL-7R, giving them the survival signal to persist long-term until the next encounter.</p><p>IL-7R = survival. Naive IL-7R+; effectors lose it (IL-7R− → short-lived); memory retains it (long-lived). (IL-7R / survival)</p><p>Population dynamics: expansion → plateau → contraction (effectors die) → a persistent memory pool remains.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Naive (IL-7R+ CCR7+) → effector (IL-7R− CCR7−, tissue, apoptosis) or memory (IL-7R+); memory splits by CCR7.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Effector and effector-memory cells use selectins/integrins/chemokine receptors to migrate into tissues.</p><p>CCR7 — the homing switch (central vs effector memory). Within the IL-7R+ memory pool, CCR7 splits the two memory subsets. Central-memory cells (T_CM) keep CCR7 — CCR7 is the receptor that homes cells to lymph nodes, so T_CM remain in the lymph nodes/spleen as a reservoir, ready to re-expand and generate fresh effectors if a response is insufficient. Effector-memory cells (T_EM) lose CCR7 — so they leave the lymph nodes and patrol peripheral tissues, poised for a rapid local recall response at sites of likely re-exposure (skin, gut, lung).</p><p>Naive + + Lymph node; awaiting first antigen</p><p>Effector − − Tissue; acts then dies (short-lived)</p><p>Central memory (T_CM) + + Lymph node reservoir; re-expands</p><p>Effector memory (T_EM) + − Tissue patrol; rapid local recall</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Two markers do all the work: IL-7R = survival (memory keeps it, effectors lose it) and CCR7 = lymph-node homing (central-memory keeps it and stays central; effector-memory loses it and goes to tissue). So T_CM = IL-7R+ CCR7+ (reservoir) and T_EM = IL-7R+ CCR7− (tissue patrol); a short-lived effector is IL-7R− CCR7−. The single most common confusion is thinking IL-7R distinguishes the memory subsets — it does not (both retain it); CCR7 is the subset discriminator.</p><p>CCR7 = lymph-node homing. T_CM CCR7+ (stay = reservoir); T_EM CCR7− (tissue = local recall). Both are IL-7R+. (CCR7 / memory split)</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> IL-7R does NOT separate the memory subsets — both T_CM and T_EM keep it. CCR7 is the discriminator (central keeps it, effector-memory loses it).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CCR7 is your ticket into the lymph node. Keep it → you stay central (T_CM, reservoir). Lose it → you head to the tissues (T_EM, fast local recall). Naive cells also need CCR7 to enter the node.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two markers: IL-7R = survival (memory+, effector−); CCR7 = lymph-node homing (T_CM+, T_EM−). So T_CM = IL-7R+CCR7+ (reservoir), T_EM = IL-7R+CCR7− (tissue), effector = IL-7R−CCR7−.</p><p>ReClaude A: IL-7R marks survival: memory cells retain it (long-lived), short-lived effectors lose it. CCR7 marks lymph-node homing: central-memory cells (T_CM) keep CCR7 and stay in the lymph nodes as a reservoir, while effector-memory cells (T_EM) lose CCR7 and patrol tissues for rapid local recall. So T_CM = IL-7R+ CCR7+, T_EM = IL-7R+</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CCR7−, and an effector = IL-7R− CCR7−.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "12_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A dendritic cell can turn the same naive T cell into a Th1, a Th2, or a Th17 — the choice is signal 3. Give the three cytokine → transcription factor → subset chains, and the effector cytokines each subset then makes.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Signals 1 and 2 (last lecture) built and expanded the clone army; signal 3 — the cytokine — weaponizes it. The unifying idea is a clean three-row map Gregg told you to memorize: the signal-3 cytokine the DC provides selects a master transcription factor, which switches on a fixed effector-cytokine profile, which defines the subset. Learn the three rows and you have the spine of the entire lecture.</p><p>THE THREE PROGRAMS. IL-12 from the DC (via STAT-4) induces T-bet → Th1, which makes IL-2, IFN-gamma, and TNF-alpha. IL-4 (via STAT-6) induces GATA3 → Th2, which makes IL-4, IL-5, and IL-13. IL-6 + TGF-beta (via STAT-3) induce ROR-gamma-T → Th17, which makes IL-17 and IL-22. Note the elegant TGF-beta twist: TGF-beta alone favors a suppressive (FoxP3) program, IL-6 alone favors inflammation, but together they yield the new factor ROR-gamma-T and the Th17 lineage.</p><p>IL-12 → T-bet → Th1 (IL-2, IFN-gamma, TNF-alpha). (Th1 program) CQ IL-4 → GATA3 → Th2 (IL-4, IL-5, IL-13); IL-6 + TGF-beta → ROR-gamma-T → Th17 (IL-17, IL-22). (Th2 and Th17 programs)</p><p>Th17 example: IL-6 + TGF-beta → ROR-gamma-T → IL-17 and IL-22 production.</p><p>CD4 Th cells: signal 3 cytokine drives a transcription factor that programs the effector cytokine profile.</p><p>The master map: DC IL-12→T-bet→Th1; IL-4→GATA3→Th2; IL-6+TGF-beta→ROR-gamma-T→Th17 — each with its effector cytokines.</p><p>Signal-3 cytokine Transcription factor Subset Effector cytokines</p><p>IL-6 + TGF-beta ROR-gamma-T Th17 IL-17, IL-22</p><p>CD8 PARALLEL AND THE TFH ASIDE. The same cytokine logic applies to CD8 cells: a CD8 cell activated in IL-12 becomes a Tc1 (same cytokine profile as Th1), and likewise Tc2 and Tc17 exist — but because the CD8 cell’s main job is killing, its cytokine output matters less, so exams focus on helper-cell cytokines and on CD8 cytotoxicity. Gregg also flagged that there are really ~10 differentiation programs (the boards test these three), and that one more — Tfh — is coming with B-cell activation. For now, the three-row map is the must-know.</p><p>CD8 parallels: Tc1/Tc2/Tc17 share the same cytokine profiles, but CD8’s main job is killing (less cytokine). (CD8 type-1/2/17)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> The TGF-beta twist: alone → suppressive (FoxP3); with IL-6 → ROR-gamma-T → Th17. Same cytokine, opposite outcome depending on its partner — a favorite exam nuance.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Don’t mix the transcription factors: T-bet = Th1, GATA3 = Th2, ROR-gamma-T = Th17. The cytokine, the factor, and the subset travel as a fixed triple.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Memorize the three rows: IL-12→T-bet→Th1 (IL-2/IFN-gamma/TNF-alpha); IL-4→GATA3→Th2 (IL-4/5/13); IL-6+TGF-beta→ROR-gamma-T→Th17 (IL-17/22). Signal 3 selects the program.</p><p>ReClaude A: IL-12 → T-bet → Th1 (makes IL-2, IFN-gamma, TNF-alpha); IL-4 → GATA3 → Th2 (makes IL-4, IL-5, IL-13); IL-6 + TGF-beta → ROR-gamma-T → Th17 (makes IL-17, IL-22). The signal-3 cytokine the DC provides selects the master transcription factor, which fixes the effector cytokine profile that defines the subset.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "12_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Three patients: one with an intracellular mycobacterial infection, one with an intestinal parasitic worm, one with an extracellular bacterial infection. Which helper subset leads each, which signature cytokines and effector cells does it deploy, and is the response pro- or anti-inflammatory?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Each subset is a specialist matched to a pathogen class. The unifying idea: Th1 fights intracellular pathogens (pro-inflammatory, macrophage-powered); Th2 fights parasitic worms (largely anti-inflammatory, IgE/eosinophil/M2-powered); Th17 fights extracellular bacteria (neutrophil-powered, barrier-reinforcing). The CD8 versions (Tc1/Tc2/Tc17) share the profiles but mainly kill. Read each subset as</p><p>target → cytokines → effector cells → tone.</p><p>TH1 — intracellular pathogens, macrophage activation. Th1 makes IFN-gamma, IL-2, and TNF-alpha and targets intracellular pathogens. Its central act is IFN-gamma activating macrophages: it drives M1 polarization and ramps up NADPH oxidase and iNOS, flooding the phagosome with ROS/RNS to overwhelm even catalase-positive organisms, and it raises MHC I and B7 (do your job, or be killed by a CD8 cell). IFN-gamma needs a partner — CD40 ligand from the T cell — for full macrophage killing. IL-2 also expands/activates NK cells; TNF-alpha sustains inflammation and, chronically, drives apoptosis (a basis of T-cell-mediated autoimmune damage).</p><p>Th1 (IFN-gamma/IL-2/TNF-alpha) → intracellular pathogens; IFN-gamma → M1 + NADPH oxidase/iNOS (ROS/RNS) + ↑MHC I/B7. (Th1 functions) CQ IFN-gamma needs CD40 ligand for full macrophage killing; Th1 is pro-inflammatory. (IFN-gamma + CD40L)</p><p>Th1 activates macrophages via IFN-gamma + CD40L signaling → killing of intracellular bacteria.</p><p>Major Th1 cytokines: IL-2 (clonal expansion + NK), IFN-gamma (macrophage activation), TNF-alpha (inflammation).</p><p>IFN-gamma effects: M1 polarization, more NADPH oxidase/iNOS (ROS/RNS), ↑MHC I — making the macrophage a better killer and a CD8 target.</p><p>TH2 — parasitic worms, anti-inflammatory and healing. Th2 makes IL-4, IL-5, and IL-13 and targets parasitic worms; overall it is anti-inflammatory and promotes wound healing. IL-4 drives B-cell IgE, which arms mast cells (Fc-epsilon receptors) to degranulate and create the inflammation that recruits worm-killers. IL-5 recruits and activates eosinophils — the parasite specialists that can reach the gut lumen and degranulate on IgE-coated worms. IL-4 + IL-13 together polarize macrophages to M2 (healing, apoptotic-cell cleanup) and drive worm expulsion (mucus + peristalsis → diarrhea; the same axis underlies allergic diarrhea). Crucially, IFN-gamma and IL-4 are mutually antagonistic — each suppresses the other, the molecular basis of the pro- vs anti-inflammatory seesaw.</p><p>Th2 (IL-4/IL-5/IL-13) → parasitic worms; IL-4→IgE→mast cells; IL-5→eosinophils; IL-4+IL-13→M2 + expulsion. (Th2 functions) CQ IFN-gamma ↔ IL-4 mutual antagonism: Th1 pro-inflammatory vs Th2 anti-inflammatory / wound-healing. (Th1–Th2 seesaw)</p><p>IL-4: drives B-cell IgE production (arming mast cells via Fc-epsilon receptors).</p><p>IL-5: recruits and activates eosinophils — the parasite specialists able to reach the gut lumen.</p><p>IL-13 (with IL-4): M2 polarization (wound healing, anti-inflammatory) and worm expulsion in the intestine.</p><p>Macrophage polarization: IFN-gamma → M1 (pro-inflammatory killing) vs IL-4/IL-13 → M2 (healing, cleanup).</p><p>TH17 — extracellular bacteria, neutrophils and barrier. Th17 makes IL-17 and IL-22 and targets extracellular bacteria (a mucosal, heavily inflammatory program). IL-17 itself does little directly — it triggers epithelial/stromal cells to release cytokines and growth factors that recruit and activate neutrophils (the anti-extracellular-bacteria effector) and pull in macrophages/DCs. IL-22 reinforces the barrier: it induces antimicrobial peptides (e.g., defensins), supports wound healing, and can loosen tight junctions to flush pathogens (watery diarrhea). The mucosal context matters — TGF-beta normally keeps the gut tolerant (favoring IgA and suppression), but when a pathogen overgrows, IL-6 rises and flips the program to ROR-gamma-T / Th17.</p><p>Th17 (IL-17/IL-22) → extracellular bacteria; IL-17 → neutrophil recruitment; IL-22 → antimicrobial peptides + barrier. (Th17 functions)</p><p>IL-17: triggers epithelial cytokines/growth factors that recruit and activate neutrophils against extracellular bacteria.</p><p>IL-22: induces antimicrobial peptides (defensins), reinforces the epithelial barrier, supports wound healing.</p><p>Major Th17 cytokines IL-17 and IL-22 — a mucosal, neutrophil-oriented, barrier-protective program.</p><p>Subset Cytokines Target Key effectors / tone</p><p>Th1 / Tc1 IFN-gamma, IL-2, TNF-alpha Intracellular pathogens M1 macrophages, ROS/RNS; pro-inflammatory</p><p>Th2 / Tc2 IL-4, IL-5, IL-13 Parasitic worms IgE/mast cells, eosinophils, M2; anti-inflammatory</p><p>Th17 / Tc17 IL-17, IL-22 Extracellular bacteria Neutrophils, barrier peptides; inflammatory</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Answering the three patients: the mycobacterial (intracellular) case is Th1 — IFN-gamma/IL-2/TNF-alpha, M1 macrophages and ROS, pro-inflammatory; the intestinal worm case is Th2 — IL-4/IL-5/IL-13, IgE/mast cells and eosinophils with M2 healing, largely anti-inflammatory (with a local inflammatory carve-out to bring eosinophils in); the extracellular bacterial case is Th17 — IL-17/IL-22, neutrophils and barrier peptides, inflammatory. Map each subset by its target pathogen first; the cytokines and effector cells follow from there, and the inflammatory tone (Th1/Th17 pro-, Th2 anti-) falls out of the IFN-gamma–IL-4 antagonism.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> The seesaw: IFN-gamma ↔ IL-4 suppress each other. Th1/Th17 are pro-inflammatory; Th2 is anti-inflammatory and healing. A Th1 response often resolves into a Th2 wound-healing phase.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Don’t cross the effector cells: eosinophils = Th2 (worms), neutrophils = Th17 (extracellular bacteria), M1 macrophages = Th1 (intracellular). Each subset, its own foot soldier.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Target-first: Th1 = intracellular (IFN-gamma, M1/ROS); Th2 = worms (IL-4/5/13, IgE/eosinophils/M2); Th17 = extracellular bacteria (IL-17/22, neutrophils/barrier).</p><p>ReClaude A: The mycobacterial (intracellular) case is led by Th1 — IFN-gamma/IL-2/TNF-alpha, M1 macrophages with ROS/RNS, pro-inflammatory. The worm case is Th2 — IL-4/IL-5/IL-13, IgE-armed mast cells and eosinophils with M2 healing, largely anti-inflammatory. The extracellular bacterial case is Th17 — IL-17/IL-22, neutrophil recruitment and barrier antimicrobial peptides, inflammatory. CD8 Tc1/Tc2/Tc17 share the profiles but mainly kill.</p><p><em>A CD8 T cell can kill a target two ways. One punches a hole to deliver enzymes; the other flips a death switch on the target’s surface. Name both pathways, the key molecules in each, and the one protein a tumor can use to block the second.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. A cytotoxic T cell kills by two routes that converge on caspases and apoptosis but enter differently. The unifying idea: perforin/granzyme delivers killer enzymes through a pore (TCR/MHC-I-directed); Fas/FasL flips a death receptor that builds the DISC and activates caspase-8. Both end in clean, low-inflammation apoptosis — and the death-receptor route has a built-in off-switch (c-FLIP) that tumors and viruses exploit.</p><p>PERFORIN / GRANZYME — the pore-and-enzyme route. After the CTL engages MHC I + antigen on the target, it releases granules. Perforin polymerizes into a pore (in the membrane or an endosome), creating a conduit for granzymes to enter the cytosol. Granzymes then activate caspases, producing DNA fragmentation and apoptotic-body formation (blebbing). Because apoptotic bodies display phosphatidylserine and are cleared by macrophages, this is a quiet, low-inflammation kill — the body removes the infected cell without collateral damage. This route is TCR/MHC-I-directed: the CTL needs to see the target’s class I.</p><p>Perforin/granzyme: needs MHC I + antigen; perforin pore → granzymes enter → caspases → apoptosis (DNA fragmentation + blebbing). (perforin/granzyme route) CQ Perforin/granzyme is a quiet, low-inflammation kill (apoptotic bodies cleared by macrophages). (quiet apoptosis)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CTL engages MHC I + antigen on the target, then releases perforin + granzyme to induce apoptosis.</p><p>Perforin/granzyme: perforin polymerizes into pores; granzymes diffuse into the cytosol → caspases → DNA fragmentation + blebbing.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> CTL recognition of microbial antigen increases Fas-ligand expression — setting up the death-receptor route.</p><p>FAS / FAS-LIGAND — the death-receptor route. The CTL upregulates Fas ligand (FasL) on activation; it binds Fas — a stress receptor that infected or tumor cells upregulate — on the target. FasL–Fas binding assembles the DISC (death-inducing signaling complex), which activates caspase-8 (the initiator — Gregg said to remember it). Caspase-8 then cleaves effector caspases-3, -6, and -7 (mainly -3), producing the same CAD-mediated DNA fragmentation and blebbing. This route can fire independent of the TCR but works better with it. Its off-switch is c-FLIP: c-FLIP outcompetes caspase-8 at the complex (and the analogous TNF-alpha complex), blocking activation. c-FLIP is induced by NF-kB/cytokine signaling — so a tumor (or virus like HIV) that drives c-FLIP, plus drops MHC I, escapes both killing routes.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Fas/FasL: FasL binds Fas → DISC assembles → caspase-8 activated → effector caspases-3/6/7 → DNA fragmentation + blebbing. c-FLIP blocks the death-receptor route by outcompeting caspase-8 at the complex — a tumor/virus escape mechanism.</p><p>Feature Perforin / granzyme Fas / Fas-ligand</p><p>Trigger TCR sees MHC I + antigen FasL binds Fas (stress receptor); can be TCR-independent</p><p>Entry / complex Perforin pore → granzymes enter DISC assembles at the receptor</p><p>Key caspase Caspases (via granzyme) Caspase-8 → caspase-3/6/7</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Both routes end in caspase-driven apoptosis, but: perforin/granzyme is the pore-and-enzyme, strictly MHC-I/TCR-directed route (granzymes activate caspases after entering); Fas/FasL is the death-receptor route (DISC → caspase-8 → effectors), which can be TCR-independent and is uniquely blockable by c-FLIP. The clinical payoff (answering the anchor): a tumor escapes Fas killing by upregulating c-FLIP, and escapes perforin/granzyme by downregulating MHC I — disabling both routes at once.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Caspase-8 is the death-receptor initiator (remember it). c-FLIP outcompetes it to block Fas/TNF-alpha apoptosis — induced by NF-kB/cytokine, exploited by tumors and HIV.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Don’t swap entry points: perforin makes the pore; granzymes are the enzymes that trigger caspases. The Fas route needs no pore — it signals through the receptor/DISC.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two routes, one endpoint: perforin pore → granzymes → caspases (MHC-I/TCR-directed); FasL–Fas → DISC → caspase-8 → caspase-3/6/7. Both → apoptosis (DNA fragmentation + blebbing).</p><p>ReClaude A: Route 1 is perforin/granzyme: after the CTL sees MHC I + antigen, perforin forms a pore and granzymes enter to activate caspases → apoptosis. Route 2 is Fas/FasL: FasL on the CTL binds Fas on the target → DISC → caspase-8 → effector caspases. A tumor blocks the second route with c-FLIP (which outcompetes caspase-8), and blocks the first by downregulating MHC I.</p><p><em>When the pathogen is cleared, the effector army must shrink. Two mechanisms do it: one is a passive consequence of losing cytokine support, the other is an active suicide. Name both, their key molecules, and which cells survive.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. After expansion (IL-2) and the CTLA-4/PD-1 plateau, the response enters contraction — most effectors die so the tissue is not inflamed forever. The unifying idea: two death routes shrink the army — passive (cytokine-withdrawal, intrinsic/mitochondrial) and active (AICD, Fas/FasL) — and memory cells are spared both.</p><p>PASSIVE CELL DEATH — cytokine withdrawal (intrinsic). Any strongly activated cell is pre-programmed to die via mitochondrial BAK/BAX pores — a cancer-prevention failsafe. While cytokine (e.g., IL-2) is present, it induces anti-apoptotic BCL-2, which blocks BAK/BAX pore formation and prevents MOMP (mitochondrial outer membrane permeabilization). As the antigen clears, cytokine falls, BCL-2 drops, BAK/BAX pores open → MOMP → cytochrome C release → apoptosome → caspase-3 → apoptosis. This is “death by neglect” for the effector — it dies because its survival signal disappeared. Tumors subvert this by overexpressing BCL-2 to stay alive despite self-driven proliferation.</p><p>Passive (cytokine-withdrawal) death: cytokine↓ → BCL-2↓ → BAK/BAX pores → MOMP → cytochrome C → caspase-3. (passive cell death) CQ Tumors overexpress BCL-2 to block MOMP and resist apoptosis despite constitutive activation. (BCL-2 in cancer)</p><p>Passive death: loss of growth/cytokine signal → BCL-2 falls → BAK/BAX pores → MOMP → cytochrome C → apoptosis.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Two mechanisms of lymphocyte apoptosis during contraction: passive (mitochondrial) and activation-induced.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Activation-induced cell death: Fas/FasL on activated T cells drives T-cell-to-T-cell suicide as the response resolves.</p><p>ACTIVATION-INDUCED CELL DEATH (AICD) — Fas/FasL suicide. The active route uses the same death-receptor machinery from LO 12.3. Activated T cells (CD4 and CD8) upregulate both Fas and Fas ligand — FasL quickly, Fas more slowly. Over time, as Fas accumulates on the surface, activated T cells engage each other Fas-to-FasL and kill one another — a suicide that drives contraction. AICD is itself cytokine-driven (cytokines upregulate Fas and FasL), and it can be blocked by c-FLIP just like the killing route. The cells spared from both passive death and AICD are the memory T cells (kept alive by IL-7R signaling), which persist for the next encounter.</p><p>Feature Passive (cytokine withdrawal) Activation-induced (AICD)</p><p>Trigger Loss of cytokine/BCL-2 support Fas/FasL engagement (T cell–T cell)</p><p>Key molecules BCL-2 ↓ → BAK/BAX → MOMP → cytochrome C Fas + FasL → DISC → caspase-8</p><p>Type Intrinsic (mitochondrial) Extrinsic (death receptor)</p><p>Spared cells Memory T cells Memory T cells</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Answering the anchor: passive cell death is the intrinsic, mitochondrial route — cytokine withdrawal lowers BCL-2, so BAK/BAX open pores (MOMP → cytochrome C → caspase-3); AICD is the extrinsic, death-receptor route — Fas/FasL drives T-cell-to-T-cell suicide via caspase-8. Both clear effectors during contraction; memory T cells survive both. A clean split: passive = “lost my survival signal” (BCL-2/mitochondria); AICD = “told to die” (Fas/FasL/caspase-8).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Mnemonic split: passive = “lost my survival signal” (mitochondrial, BCL-2); AICD = “told to die” (Fas/FasL, caspase-8). Cancer flips the first by overexpressing BCL-2.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> AICD is cytokine-driven (cytokines upregulate Fas/FasL) and uses the extrinsic (death-receptor) pathway — don’t confuse it with the intrinsic, cytokine-withdrawal route.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two contraction routes: passive (cytokine↓ → BCL-2↓ → BAK/BAX → MOMP → cytochrome C → caspase-3, intrinsic) and AICD (Fas/FasL → caspase-8, extrinsic). Memory cells survive both.</p><p>ReClaude A: Passive cell death is intrinsic: as antigen clears, cytokine and BCL-2 fall, so BAK/BAX form mitochondrial pores (MOMP) → cytochrome C → apoptosome → caspase-3. AICD is extrinsic: activated T cells upregulate Fas and FasL and kill each other (Fas→DISC→caspase-8) — a cytokine-driven suicide. Both drive contraction; memory T cells (IL-7R-supported) survive both.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "14_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A B cell starts out making IgM against a toxin and later makes IgG against the very same toxin with even higher affinity. Name the single enzyme behind both changes, and state what happened to the antibody’s specificity.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. ‘Isotype switching’ is the last step of a longer story, so this LO walks the whole T-dependent germinal-center reaction and lands on the switch. The through-line to hold onto: a single enzyme, AID (activation-induced deaminase), powers both the affinity-tuning mutations and the isotype switch. Everything else is choreography that gets the right cells together so AID can act.</p><p>FINDING EACH OTHER. Help happens in the interfollicular zone, between the T-cell paracortex and the B-cell follicle. A naive pre-TFH starts CXCR5−/CCR7+ (drawn to the T zone by DC-made CCL19/CCL21); a naive B cell is CXCR5+ (drawn to the follicle by FDC-made CXCL13). When each is activated by antigen, they reverse their chemokine receptors: the activated B cell turns CCR7 up / CXCR5 down and moves toward the T zone, while the activated pre-TFH turns CCR7 down / CXCR5 up and moves toward the follicle. They meet in between — a deliberate, reciprocal migration, not chance.</p><p>Reciprocal chemokines: activated B cell CCR7↑/CXCR5↓, activated pre-TFH CCR7↓/CXCR5↑ — they meet in the interfollicular zone. (choreography)</p><p>Unique helper T cells sit in the interfollicular zone between the T-cell paracortex and the B-cell follicle.</p><p>FDCs make CXCL13 (for CXCR5); DCs make CCL19/CCL21 (for CCR7) — setting the gradients that position pre-TFH and B cells.</p><p>On activation the B cell (CCR7↑/CXCR5↓) and pre-TFH (CCR7↓/CXCR5↑) migrate toward each other in the interfollicular zone.</p><p>THE CONJUGATE PAIR. When they meet, the activated pre-TFH and activated B cell form a conjugate pair — physically engaged through MHC II–TCR, the CD40–CD40L contact, and cytokines (IL-2/IL-4/IL-5 from the Th2-like pre-TFH binding the B cell’s IL-2R/IL-4R/IL-5R). This engagement does two decisive things. First, it induces AID in the B cell — the enzyme that all the later mutation and switching depend on. Second, the B cell pushes back on the pre-TFH: it drives Bcl-6 in the pre-TFH, which stabilizes CXCR5 and CD40L and completes differentiation into a true TFH cell. (Bcl-6 matters because the antibody response takes 7–10 days — the TFH program has to be locked in to last.)</p><p>TO THE MEDULLA, THEN BACK. The conjugate pair migrates to the medulla, where both cells divide over several days under TFH cytokines. Some B cells become B lymphoblasts → short-lived plasma cells that secrete the initial IgM seen in blood. Most conjugate pairs then traffic back to the follicle, where the rapidly proliferating B lymphoblasts seed a secondary follicle — the start of a germinal center.</p><p>Conjugate pair: pre-TFH engaged to an activated B cell via CD40–CD40L, MHC II–TCR, and IL-2/4/5 — inducing AID in the B cell.</p><p>The activated B cell drives Bcl-6 in the pre-TFH, stabilizing CXCR5/CD40L and completing differentiation into a TFH cell.</p><p>The conjugate pair migrates to the medulla; some B cells become short-lived plasma cells secreting the initial IgM.</p><p>THE GERMINAL CENTER. Back in the follicle, the fast-dividing B lymphoblasts are now centroblasts; they push naive B cells out to a surrounding mantle, forming a germinal center. A key concept Gregg flagged: a germinal center represents a B-cell response to ONE antigen (which may carry several epitopes) — it is clonal and antigen-focused. TFH cytokines (IL-2/4/5) initiate centroblast proliferation; FDC factors (IL-6, IL-15, BAFF) sustain it. Centroblasts shut off surface Ig while they divide.</p><p>SOMATIC HYPERMUTATION. Continued centroblast–TFH interaction induces more AID, which now drives somatic hypermutation: a high rate of point mutation in the variable (V) region of both heavy and light chains. This generates BCRs of varying affinity. A centroblast that has finished hypermutating and re-expresses surface Ig is renamed a centrocyte. Note the division of labor that defines the exam answer: SHM edits the V region to change affinity — distinct from the switch, which will edit the constant region to change isotype.</p><p>A germinal center = response to ONE antigen. Centroblast (proliferating, sIg-off, hypermutating) → centrocyte (sIg re-expressed). (GC vocabulary) CQ SHM = AID-driven point mutation of the V region (affinity); it does not touch the constant region. (SHM target)</p><p>A centroblast that completes hypermutation and re-expresses surface Ig is renamed a centrocyte.</p><p>Centroblasts push out naive B cells to the mantle, forming a germinal center — a response to ONE antigen (multiple epitopes).</p><p>AID drives somatic hypermutation in the V region of both chains, generating BCRs of varying affinity.</p><p>AFFINITY MATURATION — SELECTION ON THE FDC. Centrocytes now compete for antigen held intact by follicular dendritic cells on complement receptors (CR1–3) and Fc receptors. A centrocyte survives only if it gets both a strong BCR signal (its hypermutated receptor binds the FDC-displayed antigen well) and TFH help. Higher-affinity clones win; centrocytes that cannot compete undergo apoptosis and are cleared by tingible-body macrophages. This is affinity maturation: the surviving repertoire drifts toward higher affinity over the reaction. Surviving GC B cells then receive TFH IL-10/IL-21 signals (Bcl-6) that drive differentiation toward plasma cells — and it is during this interaction that isotype switching occurs.</p><p>FDCs display intact antigen on complement (CR1–3) and Fc receptors for centrocytes to test their hypermutated BCRs against.</p><p>Survival requires BOTH BCR and CR signaling — high-affinity centrocytes stay attached to FDC and TFH; the rest apoptose.</p><p>Surviving GC B cells get TFH IL-10/IL-21 (Bcl-6) to become plasma cells — and undergo isotype switching during this step.</p><p>CLASS SWITCH RECOMBINATION — THE SWITCH ITSELF. Now the actual mechanism. The heavy-chain locus has the variable region, then the constant-region exons, each preceded by a switch region. Two inputs license switching: CD40 ligation induces AID, and the TFH cytokine directs AID to the correct switch region. Before switching, alternative splicing lets the cell make IgM and IgD off the same V region. The cytokine sets the target: for example, IFN-γ drives IgG switching. Mechanistically: AID deaminates cytosine → uracil in the donor (Sμ) and acceptor (e.g., Sγ1) switch regions; uracil-DNA-glycosylase (UNG) removes the uracil, leaving an abasic site; APE1 (an endonuclease) nicks that site; nicks on both strands of both switch regions create double-strand breaks that recombine, looping out the intervening constant exons as a circle. Crucially, the V region is untouched — so the switched IgG has the same antigen specificity and affinity as the parent IgM. Only the isotype changed.</p><p>CSR steps: AID (C→U) → UNG removes uracil → APE1 nicks → double-strand breaks recombine the switch regions. (CSR mechanism) CQ CD40L induces AID; the cytokine aims it (IFN-γ→IgG). V region preserved → same specificity/affinity, new isotype. (switch control)</p><p>Heavy-chain locus: variable region, constant-region exons, and the switch regions; CD40 induces AID, cytokines direct it.</p><p>AID→uracil, UNG removes it, APE1 nicks the abasic site; double-strand nicks in both switch regions enable recombination.</p><p>Intervening constant exons loop out as circular DNA; the V region realigns with Cγ1 — same specificity/affinity, new IgG1 isotype.</p><p>PLASMA CELLS AND MEMORY — THE OUTPUTS. Two fates remain. Long-lived plasma cells home to the bone marrow, sit on stromal cells, are non-migratory, and secrete antibody for years (the ‘memory plasma cell’). Memory B cells are different: they circulate, carry a BCR, and do NOT secrete antibody, waiting as a reservoir for a fast recall response. A switch in TFH cytokine (toward IL-4/IL-21 patterns) tips GC B cells toward the memory fate rather than the plasma-cell fate. Remember the timing discriminator: short-lived plasma cells give the first IgM over several days, but antigen-specific IgM within ~2 days with no maturation points to marginal-zone (T-independent) B cells, not the germinal center.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One enzyme, two edits. AID does SHM (V region → affinity) AND CSR (switch regions → isotype). CD40L induces it; the cytokine aims it.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> The 2-day rule. IgM within ~2 days, unmatured = marginal-zone (T-independent). The germinal-center (TD) IgM is slower and matures.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> SHM vs CSR. SHM = point mutations in the V region (changes affinity). CSR = recombination of the constant region (changes isotype). Specificity is preserved by CSR.</p><p>ReClaude A: The enzyme is AID (activation-induced deaminase): it drove the somatic hypermutation that raised affinity and the class switch recombination that changed IgM to IgG. Specificity is unchanged — CSR swaps only the constant region, leaving the V region (and thus the antigen target) intact.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "15_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>If you had to predict which isotype protects a newborn&#x27;s gut versus which protected it in utero, which two isotypes would you name and where does each live?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The single organizing fact for this LO is that each isotype has a characteristic place in the body that matches its job. A B cell first makes IgM and IgD (alternative splicing of the same V region), and surface IgM is the BCR. After antigen encounter and class switching, the plasma cell can secrete any of the five classes — but where each one ends up is not random.</p><p>WHERE EACH ISOTYPE LIVES. IgG is the most abundant serum antibody and the only isotype that crosses the placenta — so it dominates the bloodstream and supplies fetal passive immunity. IgA is the secretory isotype: it dominates mucosal surfaces (gut, respiratory tract) and is roughly 90% of the immunoglobulin in breast milk. IgM is large and stays mostly intravascular (the bloodstream). IgE is present in only trace amounts in serum because it is tissue-bound on mast cells and basophils. IgD is mostly a surface receptor on naive B cells (small secreted amounts, said to be most effective in the respiratory tract).</p><p>IgG = serum + only placental crosser; IgA = mucosa + ~90% of milk Ig; IgM = intravascular; IgE = tissue-bound; IgD = surface BCR. (location map)</p><p>Surface IgM (the BCR) plus IgD are made first by alternative splicing; after antigen, plasma cells secrete soluble antibody for effector activity.</p><p>Five isotypes (defined by heavy chain) with subclasses; class switching keeps specificity but changes the constant region and thus function.</p><p>Distribution of isotypes across body compartments — serum, secretions, and tissue each have a characteristic dominant antibody.</p><p>ReClaude A: Secretory IgA protects the newborn&#x27;s gut (delivered through breast milk and dominant at mucosal surfaces), whereas IgG protected it in utero (the only isotype that crosses the placenta, and the dominant serum antibody).</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "15_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>An exam stem says ‘NK cell kills an antibody-coated tumor cell.’ Name the effector function, the Fc receptor, its CD number, and the isotype — and contrast it with how a macrophage handles the same coated cell.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The whole LO reduces to one rule: the constant region (isotype) plus the Fc receptor on the responding cell decides what happens to the antibody-bound target. Same antigen-binding end, different back end, different outcome. Walk the effector functions in order and attach each to its isotype and receptor.</p><p>NEUTRALIZATION (IgG, IgA). The simplest function: the antibody physically blocks a pathogen or toxin from attaching to host-cell receptors. Influenza must bind hemagglutinin on respiratory epithelium to infect; anti-H antibody blocks that contact (the object of the flu vaccine). Likewise, antibody against an exotoxin (tetanus, diphtheria) blocks the toxin from reaching its receptor — which is why toxin-mediated diseases are such good vaccine targets. IgG and IgA are the neutralizing isotypes.</p><p>OPSONIZATION (IgG, IgA). Antibody coats the microbe; phagocytes carrying the matching Fc receptor bind that coat and engulf the target. Macrophage/neutrophil FcγRI (CD64) and FcγRIIA engage IgG; FcαRI (CD89) engages IgA. The coat itself — the thing that enhances phagocytosis — is the opsonin.</p><p>Neutralization = block attachment (IgG, IgA). Opsonization = antibody coat that Fc receptors grab for phagocytosis (IgG via FcγRI/IIA; IgA via FcαRI).</p><p>Neutralization: antibody binds a viral surface protein (e.g., influenza HA) and blocks attachment to the host-cell receptor.</p><p>Neutralization of exotoxins (tetanus, diphtheria): antibody blocks toxin binding to host receptors — the basis of toxoid vaccines.</p><p>Opsonization: IgG/IgA coat the microbe; phagocyte Fc receptors bind the Fc and drive uptake and digestion.</p><p>ADCC — NK CELLS, FcγRIII (CD16), IgG. This is the highest-yield receptor fact in the lecture. NK cells express FcγRIII, whose alias is CD16; it binds the Fc of IgG (IgG1/IgG3) attached to a target cell. Ligation makes the NK cell release perforin and granzyme, which activate caspases and drive the target into apoptosis. Antibody-directed killing of a coated cell is antibody-dependent cellular cytotoxicity. Contrast the macrophage:</p><p>same IgG-coated target, but the macrophage eats it (opsonization) rather than puncturing it. Eosinophils run a parallel program against large parasites — IgE coats the worm, eosinophils bind via FcεRI, and degranulate to destroy it.</p><p>THE Fc-RECEPTOR MAP — LEARN THE ROWS. The exam tests the cell–receptor–isotype–outcome table directly. FcγRI (macrophages; induced on neutrophils): IgG → opsonization. FcγRIIA (macrophages, neutrophils): IgG → opsonization. FcγRIII / CD16 (NK cells): IgG → perforin/granzyme (ADCC). FcεRI (mast cells, basophils; induced on eosinophils): IgE → degranulation. FcαRI / CD89 (macrophages, neutrophils): IgA → opsonization; (on dendritic cells) uptake of neutralized antigen for processing.</p><p>ADCC = NK cell + FcγRIII (CD16) + IgG → perforin/granzyme → apoptosis. CD16 = FcγRIII is the alias to memorize. (ADCC triad) CQ FcR rows: FcγRI/IIA→opsonize (IgG); FcγRIII/CD16→ADCC (NK, IgG); FcεRI→degranulate (IgE); FcαRI/CD89→opsonize (IgA). (FcR map)</p><p>Against large worms, IgE coats the parasite and eosinophils bind via FcεRI, degranulating to destroy it.</p><p>Fc-receptor map: FcγRI/IIA (opsonization), FcγRIII/CD16 (NK ADCC), FcεRI (degranulation), FcαRI (IgA opsonization/uptake).</p><p>ADCC: NK-cell FcγRIII (CD16) binds IgG (IgG1/IgG3) on the target and releases perforin/granzyme, driving caspase-mediated apoptosis.</p><p>COMPLEMENT ACTIVATION (IgM, IgG1–3). IgM and IgG1–IgG3 bind antigen and recruit C1 to fire the classical pathway. The structural punchline: because IgM is a pentamer, it presents multiple Fc regions at once, so far fewer IgM molecules are needed to activate complement — a single bound IgM can do it, whereas IgG needs two molecules close together.</p><p>IMMUNE-COMPLEX REMOVAL (IgG). IgG binds soluble or surface-deposited antigen to form immune complexes; because IgG’s binding sites are higher-affinity than IgM’s, most complexes are IgG. C1 activation deposits C3b on the complex. Erythrocytes carry CR1, which binds that C3b and ferries the complexes to macrophages in the spleen and liver for removal. This clearance matters clinically: if complexes are not removed, they deposit in small vessels and renal glomeruli, where complement activation causes vasculitis and glomerulonephritis.</p><p>Complement: IgM (pentamer) and IgG1–3 recruit C1; fewer IgM needed. Erythrocyte CR1 clears C3b-tagged immune complexes to spleen/liver.</p><p>IgM, IgG1, IgG3 bind antigen and recruit C1; pentameric IgM needs far fewer molecules to activate the classical pathway.</p><p>IgG forms immune complexes; C1 activation deposits C3b, and phagocytes take up the complexes (cleared in spleen and liver).</p><p>Erythrocyte CR1 binds C3b on complexes and delivers them to splenic/hepatic macrophages; failure causes vasculitis and glomerulonephritis.</p><p>IgG SUBCLASSES AND THE PLACENTA. IgG1 is the most common serum subclass; IgG1 and IgG3 are the best at opsonization, complement activation, and ADCC, and are the subclasses that cross the placenta. Transfer is by FcRn (the neonatal Fc receptor): in the syncytiotrophoblast, circulating IgG is pinocytosed, FcRn binds it in the acidified endosome (protecting it from proteases), and the endosome releases the IgG into the fetal circulation at physiological pH. The same FcRn transcytosis moves IgG (and some IgA) from blood into tissues and mucosa, and recycles serum IgG — the basis of its long half-life in the next LO.</p><p>IgG subclasses: IgG1 most common; IgG1/IgG3 best for opsonization, complement, ADCC, and are the placental crossers.</p><p>FcRn transfers maternal IgG across the syncytiotrophoblast: acidified endosomes bind IgG and release it into fetal blood at physiological pH.</p><p>Placental IgG transfer is efficient (neonatal IgG approaches adult levels); a deficiency window follows as maternal IgG wanes.</p><p>SECRETORY IgA — pIgR AND THE SECRETORY PIECE. Mucosal plasma cells make dimeric IgA on the basolateral side of the epithelium; it must reach the lumen. The polymeric Ig receptor (pIgR) binds the IgA J chain, transcytoses it to the apical surface, and is then cleaved to leave a secretory piece attached to the IgA. That secretory piece protects the IgA from proteolysis and helps anchor it in mucus. (pIgR carries pentameric IgM the same way.) This is the molecular core of the next lecture, mucosal immunity.</p><p>IgM AND IgE — THE BOOKENDS. IgM is the first isotype synthesized, the first surface BCR on naive mature B cells, an efficient complement activator, and an agglutinator of microbes. IgE mediates immunity to parasites and type I allergy: it arms mast cells and basophils via FcεRI, and antigen/allergen cross-linking triggers degranulation (histamine and other mediators) — expulsion responses (sneeze, cough, vomit, diarrhea) against pathogens, and allergic symptoms against allergens in genetically predisposed people. The same IgE–FcεRI logic is the engine of type I hypersensitivity in Lec 18.</p><p>Secretory IgA: pIgR binds the J chain, transcytoses dimeric IgA, and is cleaved to leave the protective secretory piece. (secretory IgA) CQ IgM = first Ig + first BCR + complement + agglutination. IgE = parasites + allergy via FcεRI degranulation. (IgM/IgE bookends)</p><p>Secretory IgA: pIgR binds the J chain of dimeric IgA, transcytoses it, and is cleaved to leave the secretory piece that resists proteolysis.</p><p>IgM: first isotype synthesized, first surface BCR, complement activation, and agglutination of microbes.</p><p>IgE: allergen/antigen cross-links IgE on mast-cell FcεRI → degranulation — expulsion responses and allergic symptoms.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> FcRn vs pIgR. FcRn moves IgG (placenta, tissue) and recycles it (half-life). pIgR moves dimeric IgA across mucosa and leaves the secretory piece.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Isotype + Fc receptor = function. Same antigen end; the constant region and the responding cell’s Fc receptor decide neutralize / opsonize / ADCC / degranulate / fix complement.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CD16 = FcγRIII = NK ADCC for IgG. The single most tested alias in the lecture — NK cell binds IgG on the target and fires perforin/granzyme.</p><p>ReClaude A: It is ADCC: the NK cell uses FcγRIII (CD16) to bind IgG (IgG1/IgG3) on the coated cell and releases perforin/granzyme to drive apoptosis. A macrophage meeting the same IgG-coated cell instead phagocytoses it via FcγRI/FcγRIIA (opsonization) — same antibody, different Fc receptor, different fate.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "15_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Why is a well-term newborn well-protected at birth but unusually prone to infection at 3–6 months — and what single receptor underlies the answer?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Half-life decides how long a given antibody stays useful, and the headline is that IgG lasts the longest while IgE is gone quickly. Two forces set half-life: Fc-receptor clearance/recycling and protease degradation.</p><p>WHY IgG PERSISTS — FcRn RECYCLING. Circulating IgG is constantly endocytosed, but FcRn binds it inside the acidified endosome and recycles it back to the cell surface instead of letting it go to the lysosome. This salvage pathway is why IgG has the longest serum half-life of any isotype. The pentamer (IgM) and dimer (IgA) structures resist protease degradation and so persist longer than they otherwise would, but serum IgG still outlasts them. IgE has a very short serum half-life despite binding mast-cell FcεRI tightly. The clinical payoff is the neonatal window: maternal IgG transferred in utero decays over the first months while the infant’s own IgG production is still ramping up, leaving a 3–6 month period of vulnerability.</p><p>IgG has the longest half-life via FcRn recycling; IgE is shortest. Pentamer/dimer structures resist proteases. (half-life ranking)</p><p>Half-life of the antibody classes: FcRn recycling gives IgG longevity; pentamer (IgM) and dimer (IgA) structures slow protease degradation.</p><p>ReClaude A: Maternal IgG acquired across the placenta has a finite half-life and wanes over the first months, while the infant’s own IgG output is still low — creating a 3–6 month gap. The receptor behind both the transfer and IgG’s longevity is FcRn.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "16_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>An antigen lands in the gut lumen and ends up as SIgA secreted onto that same lumen days later. Trace the cell’s journey through four tissues — and explain why the B cell does NOT just proliferate where it was activated.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Because the mucosa separates where responses are induced from where they are executed, it needs a way to move cells between the two — and that way is homing, a feature largely lacking in systemic immunity. O-MALT (inductive) and D-MALT (effector) are linked by it: lymphocytes activated in the inductive site home back to the effector site to do their work.</p><p>THE HOMING MACHINERY. Homing runs on adhesion: integrins on the lymphocyte bind addressins on the mucosal vascular endothelium. When a lymphocyte is activated it changes its surface proteins: it downregulates CCR7 (the receptor that pulls cells into peripheral lymphoid organs) and upregulates gut-homing ligands — CCR9 and the α4β7 integrin, which binds the endothelial addressin MAdCAM-1. That receptor swap is what redirects the cell out of the systemic circuit and into mucosal tissue.</p><p>Homing: activated lymphocyte CCR7 down, α4β7/CCR9 up; α4β7 binds endothelial MAdCAM-1 to enter mucosa. (homing switch)</p><p>O-MALT and D-MALT are linked by homing: integrins on activated lymphocytes bind addressins on mucosal vascular endothelium.</p><p>On activation, the lymphocyte downregulates CCR7 and upregulates gut-homing ligands (CCR9, α4β7 integrin binding MAdCAM-1) to enter mucosal tissue.</p><p>Antigen uptake in GALT: M cells transcytose luminal antigen unaltered; a DC beneath takes it up and presents to T cells in the dome of the Peyer’s patch.</p><p>WHY MUCOSAL ANTIGEN FLOW IS DIFFERENT. Unlike systemic immunity, mucosal antigen must first be actively transported ACROSS the epithelial barrier (transepithelial transport) — it is not phagocytosed by an APC until after it has crossed. And the APC does not migrate to a distant lymph node; it presents antigen locally, in the O-MALT tissue (the Peyer’s patch or tonsil). So uptake, transport, and presentation are all reorganized around the epithelial barrier.</p><p>In the mesenteric lymph node: B cells leaving the patch proliferate in the germinal center and differentiate into memory IgA B cells.</p><p>Peyer’s patch layers: FAE (M cells) over the dome (T cells), the corona (naive B cells), and the follicular germinal center (activated B cells, FDCs, TFH).</p><p>GALT antigen-flow summary: uptake/presentation and switching in the patch, proliferation/memory in the node, then pIgA secretion as SIgA in the propria.</p><p>THE GALT LOOP — FOUR TISSUES IN ORDER. This ordered path is the heart of the LO. (1) Peyer’s patch (inductive site): antigen taken up by an M cell is transcytosed to a DC beneath, which presents to T cells in the dome; T–B interaction activates the B cell, and TFH cytokines drive isotype switching to IgA plus SHM/affinity maturation in the follicle. (2) Mesenteric lymph node: the switched B cells (now surface-IgA) leave the patch and travel to the mesenteric node, where they proliferate in the germinal center and differentiate into memory IgA B cells. The reason for this detour is concrete and testable: proliferating inside the Peyer’s patch would cause swelling that obstructs the small-intestinal lumen, so clonal expansion is moved to the node. (For the oral cavity, the equivalent node is the cervical lymph node.) (3) Lamina propria (effector site): memory IgA B cells re-enter the circulation, home back to the lamina propria (via the α4β7/MAdCAM-1 machinery above), are reactivated, and become plasma cells secreting dimeric pIgA. (4) The lumen: the pIgR transcytoses that pIgA across the epithelium and leaves the secretory piece → SIgA on the mucosal surface.</p><p>GALT loop: Peyer’s patch (switch/SHM) → mesenteric node (proliferate, memory) → lamina propria (secrete pIgA) → lumen (SIgA via pIgR). (GALT loop) CQ Proliferation is moved to the mesenteric node because expanding in the patch would swell it and obstruct the gut lumen. (why the node)</p><p>In the lamina propria: memory IgA B cells home back, become plasma cells, and secrete pIgA that pIgR transcytoses to the lumen as SIgA.</p><p>In the patch: the APC presents to T cells, the activated T cell helps the B cell, cytokines drive IgA switching, and the B cell undergoes switching/SHM.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Homing address. Activated mucosal lymphocyte = CCR7-down, α4β7/CCR9-up; α4β7 docks on MAdCAM-1 to enter mucosa.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Induce → proliferate → secrete, in three tissues. Peyer’s patch (switch/SHM) → mesenteric node (proliferate/memory) → lamina propria (pIgA → SIgA). Homing links them.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Why leave the patch to proliferate? Clonal expansion in the patch would swell it and block the small-intestinal lumen — so it happens in the mesenteric node.</p><p>ReClaude A: Antigen → M cell (transcytosis) → Peyer’s patch (DC presents, B cell switches to IgA + SHM) → mesenteric lymph node (clonal proliferation, memory IgA B cells) → lamina propria (plasma cells secrete pIgA → pIgR → SIgA in the lumen). The B cell leaves the patch to proliferate because expanding there would swell the patch and obstruct the gut lumen.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "17_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Two patients are protected against the same microbe — one because they were given antibodies, one because they were infected last year. Which has memory, which had immediate protection, and what are the four resulting categories?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Immunization — providing immunity to an infectious agent — can happen actively or passively, and either can be acquired naturally or artificially (deliberately induced, i.e. vaccines). The whole LO is a 2×2 grid: passive/active × natural/artificial. The defining contrast is who made the antibody.</p><p>PASSIVE IMMUNITY — BORROWED ANTIBODY. The recipient receives preformed antibody that someone (or something) else made. Consequences follow directly: protection is rapid (antibody is already there), but temporary (antibody has a short half-life and decays), and it produces no memory — no recipient B or T lymphocytes are involved, so the recipient’s immune system never learns anything. It does not rely on the recipient mounting a response at all.</p><p>ACTIVE IMMUNITY — YOUR OWN RESPONSE. An antigen is introduced and the recipient develops their own response. This is slower (it requires T- and B-lymphocyte activation, proliferation, and differentiation), but yields long-term protection because memory T and B cells form. The trade is the mirror image of passive: delayed but durable, with memory.</p><p>Passive = receive preformed antibody → immediate, temporary, no memory. Active = make your own response → slow, durable, memory. (the core contrast)</p><p>Passive immunity: receiving preformed antibody — immediate but temporary, with no memory because no recipient lymphocytes respond.</p><p>Active immunity: introducing antigen so the recipient develops their own response — slower, but long-lasting with memory T and B cells.</p><p>Passive immunity splits into natural (maternal antibody) and artificial (receiving serum/antibody preparations).</p><p>NATURAL vs ARTIFICIAL — THE FOUR BOXES. Passive-natural: maternal antibodies passed to the fetus (placenta) or infant (milk). Passive-artificial: receiving serum/antibody — human immune serum globulin, hyperimmune/convalescent serum, antitoxin/antivenom, or lab monoclonals. Active-natural: contact with antigen through the infectious process (even mild/subclinical disease can leave antibodies and memory). Active-artificial: intentional exposure to an antigen BEFORE infection, usually by vaccination.</p><p>Grid: passive-natural = maternal Ab; passive-artificial = serum/globulin; active-natural = infection; active-artificial = vaccine. (the 2×2 grid)</p><p>Active immunity splits into natural (response to real infection) and artificial (vaccination — deliberate exposure before infection).</p><p>Active-natural is infection-driven; active-artificial is intentional exposure to antigen before an infection occurs.</p><p>Sources of artificial passive immunity: immune serum globulin, hyperimmune/convalescent serum, antitoxin/antivenom, and monoclonal antibodies.</p><p>ReClaude A: The patient given antibodies had passive immunity — immediate protection, no memory. The patient infected last year has active immunity — it developed slowly but left memory. The four categories: passive-natural (maternal antibody), passive-artificial (serum/globulin), active-natural (infection), active-artificial (vaccination).</p><p><em>Someone steps on a rusty nail and has no tetanus immunity. Why might they get BOTH a shot of antibody and a shot that is a vaccine — what does each one do?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The clinical question is always a timing question: do you need protection now, or do you need it to last? Passive and active immunity answer different halves of that, and sometimes you deploy both.</p><p>PASSIVE — FOR IMMEDIATE NEED. When a non-immune patient faces an immediate threat — a wound carrying a toxin, a recent exposure, a venom — you give preformed antibody for protection that works at once. Artificial passive products are organized by source: from human serum (immune globulin / IVIG, and disease-specific immune globulins used as pre-exposure or post-exposure prophylaxis), from monoclonal antibodies (e.g. an anti-toxin mAb that binds and neutralizes a bacterial toxin), and from non-human donors (antitoxins/antivenoms raised in animals). (Per the syllabus you reason about the category and property, not which brand belongs to which class.)</p><p>ACTIVE — FOR DURABLE PROTECTION. To make protection last, you induce the patient’s own response, normally by vaccination (or by surviving the natural infection). And in high-risk post-exposure situations you combine them: immune globulin bridges the gap immediately while the vaccine builds the patient’s own durable, memory-based immunity — covering both timelines at once.</p><p>Passive = immediate need (toxin, exposure, venom); active = durable protection (vaccine). High-risk post-exposure → give both. (use-case logic)</p><p>Monoclonal-antibody passive protection: lab-made antibodies that bind and neutralize a specific pathogen or toxin.</p><p>Active protection: exposure to a pathogen (or vaccine antigen) elicits the patient’s own response, providing antibodies and memory for the future.</p><p>Artificial passive protection from human serum globulin: IVIG and disease-specific immune globulins used as pre- or post-exposure prophylaxis.</p><p>ReClaude A: They get an antibody shot (passive — immediate but temporary protection against the toxin, no memory) and a vaccine shot (active — builds their own durable, memory-based immunity). Together the globulin covers the gap now while the vaccine establishes lasting protection.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "17_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A child who cannot be vaccinated for medical reasons is still unlikely to catch measles in a highly vaccinated town. Why — and what is the term?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Herd immunity is a population-level effect: when enough individuals in a population are immune, transmission of the disease is interrupted, which protects the non-immune individuals in that population too. The key insight is that you do not need everyone immune — just enough to break the chains of transmission.</p><p>WHY IT MATTERS. It is the mechanism by which a population protects those who cannot be vaccinated (infants, the immunocompromised) or choose not to be. Vaccines are an effective way for a population to build herd immunity and interrupt a disease’s spread. The more members of the population who are immune, the better protected the whole population is from an outbreak.</p><p>Herd immunity: enough immune → transmission interrupted → the non-immune are protected too. Doesn’t require everyone. (herd immunity)</p><p>Herd immunity: the more of a population that is immune, the more transmission chains break — protecting even those who are not immune.</p><p>ReClaude A: Because enough of the town is immune, transmission chains are interrupted, so the virus is unlikely to reach the unvaccinated child. The term is herd immunity — it protects the non-immune precisely because not everyone needs to be immune.</p><p><em>Two diseases differ only in how easily they spread. Without any numbers, which needs a larger share of the population immune to reach herd immunity, and why?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Two linked ideas quantify herd immunity. R0 (basic reproduction number) is a calculation of how many people one infected individual is likely to infect in a susceptible population. The herd immunity threshold (HIT) is the fraction (or percentage) of the population that must be immune — naturally or by vaccination — for herd immunity to be effective. The relationship is the point: HIT depends on R0.</p><p>HOW THEY RELATE. The more transmissible the pathogen (the higher its R0), the higher the immune fraction needed to interrupt transmission — so HIT rises with R0. A very contagious disease therefore demands very high immune coverage to reach herd immunity, while a less transmissible one reaches it at a lower fraction. You reason from this relationship; per the syllabus you are not asked to memorize specific R0 or HIT values for particular pathogens.</p><p>R0 = average secondary cases per case. HIT = immune fraction needed. HIT rises with R0 (concept, not numbers). (R0–HIT relationship)</p><p>ReClaude A: The more transmissible disease needs a larger immune share. Because each case seeds more secondary cases (higher R0), a bigger fraction of the population must be immune to break transmission — the herd immunity threshold rises with R0.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "17_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Two vaccines target the same microbe: one replicates inside you, one does not. Predict, for each, the kind of immunity it elicits, who can safely receive it, and how many doses it likely needs — reasoning from properties, not names.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The professor is explicit that you should understand the TYPES of vaccines and their properties, not memorize which product is which type. So this LO is a set of property contrasts: the guiding principle, the route logic, the live-vs-inactivated split, and the fractional sub-types.</p><p>THE GUIDING PRINCIPLE. A vaccine is any preparation for active immunologic prophylaxis, and the design rule is simple: mimic the natural pathogen as closely — and as safely — as possible, so it stimulates a response like the real infection and produces the appropriate antibodies and memory cells.</p><p>ROUTE LOGIC. IM/SQ vaccines work well: those tissues are full of dendritic cells for efficient uptake/processing/presentation, and antigen can precipitate (increasing exposure time and phagocytosis), giving good IgG and memory. IV is NOT used: antigen is cleared too rapidly (complement, splenic macrophages), leaving too little time for uptake and presentation. Oral routes are generally less effective (few antigens survive stomach acid), but a nasal/oral route can drive a mucosal response with SIgA — appropriate when the pathogen enters at a mucosal surface (e.g. a respiratory virus).</p><p>Routes: IM/SQ = DC-rich, antigen persists → IgG/memory. IV = cleared too fast, ineffective. Nasal/oral → mucosal SIgA. (route logic)</p><p>Principle of vaccination: mimic the natural pathogen as closely and safely as possible to elicit appropriate antibodies and memory cells.</p><p>IM/SQ tissues are rich in dendritic cells and let antigen precipitate and persist — good uptake, presentation, IgG, and memory.</p><p>A nasal live-attenuated influenza vaccine drives a mucosal SIgA response in the respiratory tract, matching where influenza enters.</p><p>THE TWO MAJOR CLASSES. Live vaccines use organisms made non-pathogenic (attenuated), or a non-human vector to deliver antigens. Because the organism is alive and can replicate, it persists (longer exposure, fewer doses) and mimics natural infection — so it develops both humoral AND cell-mediated immunity and is especially good for intracellular (viral) pathogens. The costs: it may cause an inflammatory response, has the potential to revert toward a pathogenic form, and is contraindicated in the immunocompromised (the organism could replicate unchecked). Live vaccines are typically not given until 12 months of age.</p><p>INACTIVATED. These use whole killed organisms or parts of the organism (proteins, polysaccharides, toxins). Because nothing replicates, they develop mainly a humoral response, are less effective against intracellular pathogens, usually need multiple doses (3–5) and boosters, and may need an adjuvant — but they are safe for newborns and the immunocompromised. That safety-vs-strength trade is the heart of the live/inactivated contrast.</p><p>Live: replicates → humoral + CMI, fewer doses, good for intracellular, but reverts/unsafe in immunocompromised. Inactivated: no replication → mainly humoral, multi-dose ± adjuvant, safe for newborns/immunocompromised. (live vs inactivated)</p><p>Live vaccines: living organisms persist, allowing longer exposure, fewer doses, and a response that mimics natural infection (good for viral pathogens).</p><p>Live attenuated organisms multiply to emulate natural infection — a stronger, more natural response — but cannot be given to the immunocompromised.</p><p>Inactivated vaccines (dead pathogen or parts) develop mainly humoral immunity, often need boosters/adjuvant, and are safe for newborns and the immunocompromised.</p><p>LIVE SUB-TYPES. Attenuated: a disease-causing organism modified to be non-pathogenic that still multiplies. Reassortant: a combination of human and non-human viruses. Recombinant: insert gene(s) from a human pathogen into the genome of a non-pathogenic organism (e.g. baker’s yeast, baculovirus). All share the live-vaccine contraindication in the immunocompromised.</p><p>INACTIVATED — WHOLE-KILLED AND TOXOID. Whole killed: the entire pathogen is killed and used. Toxoid (a fractional protein type): the toxin is inactivated (heat or chemical, e.g. formaldehyde), or only part of it is used, so the immune system makes neutralizing antitoxin; only bacterial toxoid vaccines exist. The principle: take the dangerous functional molecule and disable it while keeping its antigenicity.</p><p>Live sub-types: attenuated / reassortant / recombinant. Toxoid = inactivated toxin → neutralizing antitoxin (bacterial only). (live + toxoid)</p><p>Whole-killed inactivated vaccines use the entire killed pathogen.</p><p>Toxoid: an inactivated bacterial toxin (or part) that elicits neutralizing antitoxin antibodies; only bacterial toxoids exist.</p><p>Live sub-types: reassortant (human + non-human viruses combined) and recombinant (a human-pathogen gene inserted into a non-pathogenic organism).</p><p>SUBUNIT, CONJUGATE, AND PURE POLYSACCHARIDE. Subunit: specific antigenic protein(s), not whole organisms. Pure polysaccharide: a bacterial capsular sugar — but it is poorly immunogenic, drives a T-independent IgM/IgG2 response, gives no booster effect, and doesn’t work well in children under 2 (infants can’t make IgG2). Conjugate: the fix — link the weak polysaccharide to a carrier protein (often part of a bacterial toxin) to recruit T-cell help, converting it into a robust T-dependent IgG response that works in young children.</p><p>DNA AND mRNA. The newest fractional types deliver genetic instructions rather than the antigen itself. DNA: a plasmid carrying the antigen gene is taken up and expressed. mRNA: mRNA encoding a pathogen protein (e.g. a surface/spike protein) is taken up by DCs and B cells, translated into protein, processed, and presented on MHC — activating T cells (and memory) and driving antibody production. The host makes the antigen; the vaccine carries only the code.</p><p>Subunit = antigenic proteins. Pure polysaccharide = weak, T-independent, poor in under-2s. Conjugate = polysaccharide + carrier → T-cell help → IgG. mRNA/DNA = host makes &amp; presents the encoded protein. (fractional types)</p><p>Conjugate: a poorly-immunogenic polysaccharide linked to a carrier protein recruits T-cell help for a strong IgG response usable in young children.</p><p>Pure polysaccharide: a T-independent IgM/IgG2 response with no booster effect and poor immunity in children under 2.</p><p>mRNA: host DCs and B cells take up the mRNA, translate and present the encoded protein on MHC, activating T cells and driving antibody and memory responses.</p><p>Subunit: specific antigenic protein(s) of the pathogen rather than the whole organism.</p><p>DNA: a plasmid carrying the antigen gene is taken up and expressed by host cells to drive a response.</p><p>A live attenuated organism can revert toward a pathogenic form — a key reason it is avoided in those without a healthy immune system.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Conjugate = polysaccharide + protein carrier. The carrier supplies T-cell help, turning a weak T-independent sugar into a T-dependent IgG response that works in infants.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Toxoid (active) vs antitoxin (passive). A toxoid makes YOU produce antitoxin; an antitoxin is preformed antibody given to you. Same toxin, opposite direction.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Sort by property, not brand. Live = replicates → CMI + humoral, unsafe in immunocompromised. Inactivated = no replication → humoral, multi-dose, safe. The fractional types just choose which safe piece to show.</p><p>ReClaude A: The replicating (live) vaccine mimics natural infection — humoral AND cell-mediated immunity, fewer doses — but is unsafe for the immunocompromised and can revert. The non-replicating (inactivated) vaccine gives mainly humoral immunity, needs multiple doses ± adjuvant, and is weaker against intracellular pathogens, but is safe for newborns and the immunocompromised.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "19_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Why does a PARTIAL complement-factor deficiency cause immune-complex disease, while a complete deficiency of the same factor would not?</em></p><p>MECHANISM. Complexes form every time an antibody binds a soluble antigen — this is normal and constant — so you need a disposal system, and Gregg spent real time on it because it is the bridge to the SLE story later. The system runs on red blood cells. A complex that has fired complement carries C3b, and erythrocytes are studded with CR1, which binds C3b. So circulating RBCs act as a shuttle: they grab C3b-opsonized complexes and carry them through the spleen and liver, where fixed macrophages live alongside high concentrations of Factor I (with its cofactor Factor H). Factor I cleaves the C3b, releasing the complex from RBC CR1; the splenic/hepatic macrophage then uses its high-density FcγRI to pull the IgG away and engulf the whole complex. The RBC is recycled, the complex is digested, and nothing deposits.</p><p>Erythrocyte CR1 binds C3b-opsonized complexes → carried to spleen/liver → Factor I cleaves C3b → macrophage engulfs the released complex. (clearance pathway)</p><p>IC clearance in spleen/liver: RBC CR1 binds C3b-tagged complexes; Factor I cleaves C3b to release the complex to fixed macrophages. Partial deficiency of Factor I, C1, or C3 reduces clearance → Type III susceptibility. THE PARTIAL-DEFICIENCY PARADOX. Here is the subtlety Gregg was careful about, and it makes a great question. A deficiency in Factor I, C1, C3 (or a CR1 defect) reduces complex clearance and predisposes to Type III disease — but it must be a partial deficiency, a lower-than-normal level, not complete loss. Why? Because the pathology of Type III depends on complement activation. If you completely ablated these factors, complement could not be activated, so no frustrated phagocytosis, no disease. A reduced level is the worst of both worlds: enough complement to drive inflammation, too little clearance to remove the complexes. So you can predict that a patient with recurrent Type III disease likely carries a partial deficiency in one or more of these factors.</p><p>A partial (not complete) deficiency of Factor I, C1, or C3 impairs clearance yet preserves enough complement to drive disease. (partial-deficiency logic)</p><p>WHEN CLEARANCE IS NORMAL. You can also get complex disease with a perfectly intact clearance system — Gregg posed exactly this as the Dumbledore-slide question. The answer is antigen load: if antigen is continuously supplied, the sheer quantity overwhelms clearance capacity. Three settings do this — a chronic or persistent infection (antigen made by ongoing replication), autoimmune disease (self-antigen is always present), and heavy seasonal/geographic exposure (spores, animal antigens taken in over time). In each, you make abundant antibody against an antigen that keeps coming, and complexes accumulate faster than they can be removed.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> CR1 vs FcγR: RBCs use CR1 to transport complexes; the effector phagocyte uses its FcγR/CR to engulf or (when blocked) to attack. Same complex, two different receptor jobs.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The clearance system is RBC-centric: CR1 on erythrocytes is the transport receptor, Factor I is the release enzyme, and the spleen/liver macrophage is the disposal site. Lose any one partially and complexes persist.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Two roads to Type III: a partial clearance deficiency, OR an intact system overwhelmed by chronic antigen (infection, self-antigen, seasonal load). A vignette with chronic hepatitis B and normal complement is testing the second road.</p><p>ReClaude A: A partial deficiency leaves enough complement to drive the inflammatory pathology of Type III but too little clearance to remove the complexes; a complete deficiency would abolish the complement activation the disease requires, so no disease results.</p><p><em>A systemic reaction appears 8 days after a foreign protein, and a localized reaction appears 6 hours after a repeat injection — which is serum sickness and which is the Arthus reaction, and what mechanism do they share?</em></p><p>TYPE III IN PRACTICE — SERUM SICKNESS VS ARTHUS. The two classic Type III reactions differ only in scale and timing, not mechanism. Serum sickness is the systemic version: historically from horse antiserum (e.g. anti-diphtheria antitoxin), now mostly from mouse monoclonal antibodies used as therapeutics. Your immune system sees the foreign antibody as antigen, makes antibody against it, and forms circulating complexes — fever, vasculitic rash, glomerulonephritis, arthritis. Symptoms appear at 7–10 days, the time needed to mount the antibody response, and resolve once the complexes clear. The Arthus reaction is the localized version: with a repeat exposure (vaccine booster, repeat serum), you already have memory B cells making antibody, so re-injection produces complexes and complement-driven vasculitis right at the site within 4–10 hours — pain, swelling, induration, sometimes necrosis.</p><p>Serum sickness = systemic, 7–10 days (foreign protein, now mouse mAbs); Arthus = localized, 4–10 hours at a repeat-injection site. (serum sickness vs Arthus)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Arthus reaction: localized complex vasculitis at a repeat-injection site, 4–10 h. C3a/C5a drive mast-cell-mediated local inflammation, swelling, bleeding.</p><p>Serum sickness: human anti-horse (or anti-mouse-mAb) response → circulating complexes → fever, vasculitis, glomerulonephritis, arthritis. Symptoms at 7–10 days; resolve on clearance.</p><p>Other Type III diseases: hepatitis B (chronic antigen), post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis (planted GBM antigen) — the same complex/complement mechanism, different antigen source. TYPE IV — CONTACT HYPERSENSITIVITY, TWO PHASES. Contact hypersensitivity (allergic contact dermatitis) is the most testable Type IV reaction, and it runs in two phases that mirror immediate hypersensitivity&#x27;s structure. The antigen is a hapten — a small reactive molecule that cannot trigger a response on its own. On the skin it conjugates to a host protein (the carrier), and the haptenated protein becomes a genuine neo-antigen. In the sensitization phase, Langerhans/dendritic cells capture the haptenated protein, process it, and present it in the draining node, generating memory Th1 cells that home back to the skin. This takes about two weeks and is completely asymptomatic — a point students miss. Only on re-exposure does the effector phase fire, within 24–72 hours.</p><p>Contact HS antigen = a hapten bound to a skin-protein carrier; sensitization (~2 wks) is asymptomatic, effector fires on re-exposure in 24–72 h. (contact HS two-phase) Gregg de-emphasized memorizing the agent list — &quot;I&#x27;m not going to ask you to memorize any of that,&quot; he said, &quot;but if you just remember poison ivy is type 4, that could be helpful.&quot; So know the concept (poison ivy = contact/Type IV, hapten mechanism), not a catalog of allergens.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Poison ivy: the canonical contact-hypersensitivity hapten (urushiol). The vesicular rash is the CD8-driven effector lesion.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Contact HS overview: response in the skin at the contact site, in two phases — sensitization (builds memory T cells) and effector (re-exposure → response within 72 h).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Sensitization: hapten conjugates to skin protein; Langerhans/dendritic cells present haptenated peptide in the node → memory Th1 home to skin. ~2 weeks, no symptoms. Effector phase: haptenated peptide presented on MHC I and II → CD4 Th1 (IFN-γ activates macrophages, TNF-α) + CD8 Tc1 (perforin/granzyme, Fas → keratinocyte apoptosis).</p><p>TYPE IV — GRANULOMATOUS HYPERSENSITIVITY. When a microbe like Mycobacterium tuberculosis resists clearance, the immune system shifts strategy from &quot;kill it&quot; to &quot;wall it off.&quot; A strong Th1/IFN-γ response drives infected macrophages to become epithelioid cells — Gregg called them &quot;super-activated macrophages&quot; — which fuse into giant cells and secrete fibroblast-activating factor to build a fibrous capsule. Around them, foamy cells accumulate LDL to form a cellular barrier that the microbe cannot infect. The whole structure is a cytokine-maintained quarantine: as long as IFN-γ and TNF-α flow, the granuloma holds. The danger is reactivation — if CD4 numbers or IFN-γ fall, the epithelioid cells stop holding the cuff, foamy cells lose their lipid, infected macrophages lyse, and the caseous necrotic center spills viable bacteria into the airway.</p><p>Granuloma = Th1/IFN-γ-maintained quarantine: epithelioid cells (fuse→giant cells, fibrous capsule) + foamy cells (LDL barrier); falling IFN-γ/CD4 → caseous spill + reactivation. (granuloma structure + failure)</p><p>Granulomatous HS: Th1 response to persistent microbe (TB). IFN-γ activates macrophages; uptake engages TLR → IL-1β/IL-6/TNF-α → inflammation.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Granuloma maturation: epithelioid cells (resemble epithelium, fuse → giant cells, secrete fibroblast-activating factor) + foamy cells (LDL bodies) wall off and starve the microbe.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Granuloma failure: ↓IFN-γ/TNF-α (↓CD4) → fibrous cuff breaks, foamy barrier fails, infected macrophages lyse → caseous center spills viable bacteria → cough/transmission (reactivation).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Type IV runs on Th1/IFN-γ activating macrophages. Contact HS and granulomatous HS are the same delayed-T-cell logic applied to a hapten vs a persistent microbe.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> In a granuloma vignette, a drop in CD4 count or IFN-γ (HIV, anti-TNF biologic) is the cue for reactivation — the wall is cytokine-maintained, so remove the cytokine and the microbe escapes.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Contact-HS sensitization is silent. A vignette where the first poison-ivy exposure causes no rash but the second does is testing whether you know the asymptomatic ~2-week sensitization phase precedes the effector response.</p><p>ReClaude A: The 8-day systemic reaction is serum sickness (time to make antibody against a foreign protein); the 6-hour localized reaction is the Arthus reaction (preformed antibody from prior sensitization). Both are complement-driven immune-complex vasculitis — the mechanism is identical, only the timing and distribution differ.</p><p>Recall the pathogenic mechanisms responsible for the symptoms of systemic lupus erythematosus, rheumatoid arthritis, and contact, granulomatous and T cell-mediated hypersensitivity.</p><p><em>A patient with SLE and a C1q deficiency makes anti-nuclear antibodies — trace the chain from the missing protein to the autoantigens that drive the disease.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This LO is the integration layer — it asks you to take a named disease and run its mechanism from upstream cause to clinical symptom. The four diseases Gregg framed are RA and SLE (Type III complex diseases) and contact/granulomatous/T-cell-mediated reactions (Type IV). The previous LOs gave you the contact and granulomatous mechanisms; here the heavy lifting is RA and SLE, and Gregg spent the most time on SLE &quot;because it brings in a lot of pieces.&quot;</p><p>RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS. RA was historically classed Type III (complexes deposit in the joint) and is increasingly also viewed as Type IV (T-cell-driven) — Gregg said you can file it under either, and he left it in Type III. The mechanistic chain that makes a great question: citrullination — the enzyme PAD (peptidylarginine deiminase) converts arginine residues to citrulline on self-protein, and smoking can induce PAD activity. HLA-DR4/DR1 (present in ~90% of patients) is especially good at presenting citrullinated peptide to T cells. T cells (Th1 and Th17) and plasma cells accumulate in the synovium; complexes deposit in articular cartilage; cytokines (TNF-α, IL-17, IL-1β) drive erosion of the proximal interphalangeal and metacarpophalangeal joints. Rheumatoid factor — antibody, mostly IgM, against the Fc region of IgG — is positive in ~80%, but it is not RA-specific (also high in SLE, systemic sclerosis, dermatomyositis).</p><p>RA chain: PAD citrullinates self-protein (smoking induces it) → HLA-DR4/DR1 presents it → synovial inflammation; RF = anti-Fc-of-IgG, ~80%, not specific. (RA mechanism + RF)</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> SLE diagnostic criteria (≥4 of: malar rash, discoid rash, photosensitivity, oral ulcers, arthritis, serositis, renal, neuro, autoantibody). Greatest susceptibility HLA-DR3 (also DR2/DR5).</p><p>RA: HLA-DR4/DR1 in ~90%; DR4 presents citrullinated self-Ag (PAD converts Arg→citrulline; smoking induces PAD). Complexes deposit in synovium; ~80% RF+ (anti-Fc-of-IgG, mostly IgM).</p><p>Normal apoptotic-body clearance: C1q/MBL/pentraxins opsonize apoptotic bodies; macrophages engulf them and release IL-10/TGF-β (anti-inflammatory, Treg-inducing) — the baseline SLE loses. SLE — APOPTOSIS IS THE KEY. The lupus story is best told upstream-to-downstream, and the upstream event is a clearance failure, not the autoantibodies themselves. Normally apoptotic bodies are opsonized by C1q, MBL, and pentraxins (CRP, SAP, PTX3) and quietly engulfed by macrophages, which release IL-10 and TGF-β to keep the process anti-inflammatory and even induce Tregs. In SLE there is a deficiency in one of these opsonins — C1q is the classic culprit. Apoptotic bodies are not cleared efficiently; their weakened membranes collide and rupture into secondary necrosis, spilling nuclear antigens and TLR ligands. This is why the rash is photosensitive and falls on sun-exposed skin — UV drives apoptosis, and the lupus patient cannot clear the resulting bodies.</p><p>SLE upstream cause = impaired apoptotic-body clearance (often C1q deficiency) → secondary necrosis spills nuclear antigens that drive the autoantibody response. (SLE upstream mechanism)</p><p>Impaired clearance in SLE: opsonin (esp. C1q) deficiency → apoptotic bodies undergo secondary necrosis, releasing TLR ligands + nuclear Ags; DCs mature and present self-Ag to T cells.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> T-cell-mediated (Type IV) autoimmune diseases: T1D (islet Ags), RA (synovial self-Ag), MS (myelin basic protein), IBD, Guillain-Barré (P2 myelin protein), autoimmune myocarditis — CD4 supports inflammation, CD8 mediates killing.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> SLE effector loop: self-reactive T and B cells activated → IgG anti-nuclear antibodies → complexes form (and accumulate via C1/C2/C4 clearance defects) → deposit → complement, frustrated phagocytosis, MAC; DCs recapture complexes → epitope spreading.</p><p>From there the loop closes: necrotic material matures local DCs, which present nuclear self-antigen to self-reactive T cells (present because of an HLA presentation defect), which help self-reactive B cells make IgG against DNA, histones, and snRNP. Complexes form, and because the same C1/C2/C4 deficiencies also impair complex clearance, they accumulate and deposit in kidney, joints, and skin — giving the classic triad of glomerulonephritis, arthritis, and malar rash. Epitope spreading keeps the disease chronic: each wave of tissue destruction releases new self-antigens, recruiting new specificities. Greatest susceptibility is HLA-DR3 (also DR2, DR5).</p><p>Epitope spreading = progressive tissue destruction releases new self-Ags in waves, broadening the response and driving SLE chronicity. Greatest susceptibility: HLA-DR3. (epitope spreading + SLE HLA)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> SLE is a clearance disease at its root: no C1q → apoptotic bodies → secondary necrosis → nuclear antigens → autoantibodies → complexes → deposition. The autoantibodies are a downstream symptom of the upstream clearance failure.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> RA vs SLE HLA + antibody: RA = DR4/DR1, anti-citrullinated/RF; SLE = DR3, anti-dsDNA/histone/snRNP. The exam loves to pair these side by side — keep the DR number with the disease.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> The photosensitive malar rash has a mechanism: UV → apoptosis → bodies the lupus patient cannot clear → local complex disease on sun-exposed skin. The rash location is a clue to the clearance defect.</p><p>ReClaude A: C1q normally opsonizes apoptotic bodies for quiet clearance; without it, apoptotic bodies undergo secondary necrosis and spill nuclear antigens (DNA, histones, snRNP). DCs present these to self-reactive T cells, B cells make IgG against them, and the resulting complexes — poorly cleared because the same complement factors are deficient — deposit and drive the disease.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "20_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>An infant with a confirmed gene mutation and an adult who became deficient after chemotherapy — which is primary and which is secondary, and what is the single most common non-biological cause of the acquired type?</em></p><p>THE CORE SPLIT. Davis framed the whole lecture around one dichotomy: immune-system disorders are either absences (immunodeficiencies) or excesses (neoplasias). Within immunodeficiencies, the sorting key is origin. A primary (congenital) immunodeficiency stems from a genetic defect — the patient is born with it, even if it does not manifest until months or years later. A secondary (acquired) immunodeficiency develops as a consequence of another condition. The hallmark of both is the same: enhanced susceptibility to infection — more frequent, longer-lasting, or more severe illness, disease from opportunistic or commensal organisms, and infections that need longer-than-normal treatment.</p><p>Primary = genetic/congenital (born with it); secondary = acquired as a consequence of another condition. Both share enhanced infection susceptibility.</p><p>(primary vs secondary) A few numbers Davis emphasized: about 1 in 500 people carry a PI, but because of immune-system redundancy and layering, only about 1 in 10,000 experience significant clinical disease. Roughly 1 in 4 people with an immunodeficiency also have an autoimmune disease — a correlation without a fully worked-out mechanism. Secondary immunodeficiencies are far more common than primary ones; the most common non-biological cause is malnutrition, and the best-known biological cause is AIDS from HIV. Health-state contributors (age, stress, alcohol, smoking, sleep loss) and therapies (monoclonal antibodies, the &quot;-nib&quot; small-molecule inhibitors) also drive secondary disease.</p><p>Immune-system disorders: absences (immunodeficiencies) vs excesses (neoplasias); loss of tolerance (Lec 21) and autoimmune disease (Lec 23) are covered separately.</p><p>Two categories: congenital/primary (genetic defect) vs acquired/secondary (consequence of another disease). ~1 in 500 have a PI; ~1 in 10,000 have significant disease.</p><p>Secondary immunodeficiency: health-state causes (age, stress, alcohol, smoking, sleep loss), biological causes (virus, diabetes, cancer, SLE), and therapies (mAbs, &quot;-nib&quot; inhibitors).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Origin is the sorting key: genetic/born-with-it = primary; acquired-from-another-condition = secondary. Secondary is far more common.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Most common non-biological secondary cause = malnutrition; best-known biological = AIDS/HIV. The &quot;-nib&quot; drugs and monoclonals are iatrogenic secondary causes worth remembering.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> A vignette where an infection needs a longer-than-usual antibiotic course, or recurs with opportunistic/commensal organisms, is pointing you at an underlying immunodeficiency.</p><p>ReClaude A: The gene-mutation infant has a primary (congenital) immunodeficiency; the post-chemotherapy adult has a secondary (acquired) one. The most common non-biological cause of secondary immunodeficiency is malnutrition.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "20_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What single feature must every SCID share, and which primary immunodeficiency is the most common overall?</em></p><p>ORGANIZING THE CATALOG. Primary immunodeficiencies are grouped by the immune compartment they damage — cellular (T/NK), humoral (B-cell/antibody), SCID (combined), phagocytic, and complement. The humoral group is by far the largest. There are ~550 recognized PIs, with the causative gene now identified for the great majority. SCID is an umbrella term, not a single disease: it describes deficiencies that always involve T cells plus at least one other arm — usually B cells (because they depend on T-cell help), sometimes NK cells. The single most common PI overall is selective IgA deficiency, which is also one of the mildest.</p><p>PIs sort by compartment (cellular/humoral/SCID/phagocytic/complement). SCID always involves T cells + another arm. Most common PI = selective IgA deficiency. (PI catalog organization)</p><p>Most common types of primary immunodeficiencies (the humoral/antibody compartment dominates). ~550 recognized PIs; gene identified for ~485.</p><p>Primary immunodeficiencies manifest in childhood and divide by compartment (humoral, cellular, complement, phagocytic). SCID always involves T cells + another arm (B or NK).</p><p>Hallmark of immunodeficiency: enhanced susceptibility — frequent/chronic illness, opportunistic or commensal organisms, infections that fail to respond normally to treatment.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> SCID is not one disease. It is any combined defect that includes T cells. HIGM-1 (CD40L) and BLS are both SCIDs because the T-cell arm is hit.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Five compartments organize every PI on the exam: cellular (T/NK), humoral (B/Ab), SCID (combined), phagocytic, complement. Humoral is the biggest bucket.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> When asked for the most common PI, the answer is selective IgA deficiency — and it is also among the mildest, which is why most carriers never know.</p><p>ReClaude A: Every SCID must involve T cells (plus at least one other compartment, usually B cells). The most common primary immunodeficiency overall is selective IgA deficiency.</p><p><em>A 9-month-old has anemia, low platelets, and splenomegaly with a perforin mutation — how does a cytotoxic-killing defect end up producing macrophage-driven pathology?</em></p><p>CELLULAR PI — HEMOPHAGOCYTIC LYMPHOHISTIOCYTOSIS (HLH). HLH is the cleanest example of Davis&#x27;s recurring lesson: what you see is not always the problem. The defect is in perforin/granzyme killing by CTLs and NK cells — either perforin cannot be made, or the perforin/granzyme vesicle cannot fuse with the cell membrane to release its cargo. Because those killers cannot clear intracellular targets, they keep secreting IFN-γ, which does not just activate macrophages but hyperactivates them. The over-driven macrophages then phagocytose red blood cells (anemia → fatigue), platelets, and neutrophils, and pile up in the spleen (splenomegaly). So the defect is in the T/NK cell, but the pathology is macrophage-mediated — a severe, potentially fatal systemic inflammatory syndrome. Treatment suppresses the inflammation (methotrexate, dexamethasone, etoposide, cyclosporine A, anti-IFN-γ mAb) or replaces the stem cells (HSCT).</p><p>HLH: defect in perforin/granzyme killing (T/NK) → unchecked targets → sustained IFN-γ → macrophage hyperactivation → phagocytosis of RBCs/platelets/neutrophils (anemia, cytopenias, splenomegaly). (HLH mechanism)</p><p>HLH cause: mutations in perforin/granzyme killing by CTLs &amp; NK cells. Without killing, CTLs/NK keep secreting IFN-γ → macrophage overactivation.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis, decoded: hemo (blood) + phagocytic cells + lympho (lymphatic) + histiocytosis (excess macrophages). Primary form: birth–18 months.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> HLH clinical: phagocytosis of RBCs → anemia/fatigue; low platelets/neutrophils/hemoglobin; splenomegaly; severe systemic inflammation. Defect in T/NK, pathology in macrophage.</p><p>HUMORAL PI — SELECTIVE IgA DEFICIENCY. The most common PI: a defect in B-cell differentiation into IgA-secreting plasma cells (the IgA genes are normal). The result is recurrent mucosal infections (GI, respiratory, ears) and a higher rate of allergy, asthma, RA, and diabetes. Labs show low IgA with normal IgM and IgG and normal peripheral B-cell numbers — the B cells exist, they just do not become IgA plasma cells.</p><p>Selective IgA deficiency: defect in differentiation to IgA plasma cells (genes normal) → low IgA, normal IgM/IgG, normal B-cell counts, mucosal infections. (selective IgA pattern) HUMORAL PI — AID HYPER-IgM SYNDROME (HIGM-2). The key concept is the ratio, not the absolute number. AID (activation-induced cytidine deaminase) performs class-switch recombination, and its expression is induced by CD40–CD40L help from the T cell. Without AID, B cells cannot switch isotypes, so they are stuck making IgM — the IgM-to-IgG/IgA ratio is elevated even when absolute IgM is within the normal range. Cell counts (CD4, CD8, CD19+ B cells) are all normal; only switching fails, and patients often develop hemolytic anemia. Treatment is IVIG (replacing the IgG they cannot make) plus antibiotics. (On any exam Ig-level question, Davis stated she provides normal-vs-patient value columns — so reason from the ratio, never from memorized absolute values.)</p><p>AID hyper-IgM: AID (induced by CD40–CD40L) drives class switching; its loss → stuck at IgM → elevated IgM:IgG/IgA ratio (absolute IgM may be normal). Counts normal; treat with IVIG. (AID hyper-IgM ratio)</p><p>AID hyper-IgM (HIGM-2): mutation in the AID enzyme in B cells. AID drives class-switch recombination, induced by CD40–CD40L interaction with the TH cell.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Other hyper-IgM forms: HIGM-1 (CD40L, T-cell defect → SCID), HIGM-3 (CD40, B-cell), HIGM-4 (switch-region DNA breaks, B-cell), HIGM-5 (UNG, B-cell).</p><p>Hyper-IgM lab logic: IgM may be high OR within normal range, but the ratio of IgM to IgG/IgA is higher than normal when isotype switching is impaired. SCID — BARE LYMPHOCYTE SYNDROME (BLS). Two types, distinguished by which MHC class is missing from the cell surface. BLS-I: no surface MHC class I, from a TAP1/TAP2 mutation — class I is made but cannot be loaded/displayed → failed positive selection of CD8 T cells. BLS-II (more common): no MHC class II, from a transcription-factor mutation — class II is never made → low CD4 T cells. In both, the MHC genes themselves are normal, and γδ T cells are normal because they do not undergo MHC-dependent positive selection. BLS-I gives necrotizing granulomatous skin lesions and bacterial respiratory infections (most reach adulthood with treatment); BLS-II causes broad bacterial/viral/fungal infections and GI infections → failure to thrive, and is fatal by adolescence without HSCT.</p><p>BLS-I = no surface MHC-I (TAP mutation) → low CD8; BLS-II = no MHC-II (Tx-factor mutation) → low CD4. Genes normal in both; γδ T cells spared (skip MHC positive selection). (BLS I vs II)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> BLS: absent surface MHC → failed positive selection → low αβ CD4/CD8 thymocytes; γδ T cells normal (they skip MHC positive selection).</p><p>BLS: class I defect = TAP mutation (MHC-I made but not displayed); class II defect = transcription-factor mutation (MHC-II not made). Both are SCID.</p><p>BLS-II (more common in Mediterranean/N. African descent): broad bacterial/viral/fungal/opportunistic + GI infections → failure to thrive; fatal by adolescence without HSCT. PHAGOCYTIC PI — CHRONIC GRANULOMATOUS DISEASE (CGD). A defect in the oxidative (respiratory) burst — classically NADPH oxidase — so phagocytosed bacteria and fungi survive inside macrophages and neutrophils. The frustrated phagocytes fuse into granulomas. Clinically: opportunistic bacterial/fungal infections, soft-tissue infections, oral/gum disease, abscesses (brain, liver, lung, bone). Treatment is prophylactic antimicrobials.</p><p>PHAGOCYTIC PI — LEUKOCYTE ADHESION DEFICIENCY (LAD). All three LADs are extravasation/migration defects. LAD-1: a CD18 mutation (CD18 is part of the LFA-1 integrin that binds ICAM-1) → neutrophils cannot adhere and leave the vessel, so they accumulate in blood (neutrophilia) but cannot reach tissue — recurrent soft-tissue infections, no pus (pus is mostly dead neutrophils), poor wound healing, delayed umbilical-cord separation; often fatal before age 1. LAD-2: a sialyl-Lewis-X/fucose-metabolism defect → cannot bind selectins (rolling fails); adds neurologic and growth defects. LAD-3: a FERMT3/KINDLIN3 signaling defect → presents like LAD-1 but adds a bleeding disorder (platelets cannot bind fibrinogen and aggregate, despite normal platelet counts).</p><p>LAD-1 (CD18/LFA-1): no extravasation → neutrophilia + no pus + delayed cord separation. LAD-3 (KINDLIN3) adds a bleeding disorder (defective platelet aggregation, normal counts). (LAD mechanisms)</p><p>CGD: defect in the oxidative burst (e.g. NADPH oxidase) → phagocytosed pathogens survive inside macrophages/neutrophils → frustrated phagocytes fuse into granulomas.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> LAD-1: CD18 (part of LFA-1) mutation → LFA-1 cannot bind ICAM-1 → loss of neutrophil migration → neutrophilia, no pus, delayed cord separation; usually fatal before age 1.</p><p>LAD-3: FERMT3/KINDLIN3 signaling defect → poor integrin upregulation (LFA-1, VLA-4) AND defective platelet aggregation (normal counts) → bleeding disorder. COMPLEMENT PI. Three patterns worth holding apart. C1, C2, or C4 deficiency → little increase in infection but immune-complex disease (RA, SLE, vasculitis), because complexes are not cleared. C5–C9 (MAC) deficiency → recurrent, invasive Neisseria infections (meningitidis, gonorrhoeae), which require MAC lysis to clear — two bouts of meningitis by 18 should prompt a complement workup. C3 deficiency is the most severe (C3 is in all pathways) → broad susceptibility to encapsulated bacteria. Among the regulatory proteins, C1-inhibitor deficiency causes hereditary angioedema: unchecked cleavage of C4 and C2 releases vasoactive C2 kinin — &quot;C4 isn&#x27;t the problem, C2 is.&quot;</p><p>Complement patterns: C1/C2/C4 → immune-complex disease; C5–C9 → Neisseria; C3 → most severe (encapsulated bacteria); C1-INH → hereditary angioedema (C2 kinin). (complement PI patterns)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> C1-inhibitor deficiency: uncontrolled C4/C2 activation releases large amounts of vasoactive C2 kinin → edema → hereditary angioedema.</p><p>Complement PIs: C1/C2/C4 → immune-complex disease (RA, SLE, vasculitis); C5–C9 MAC → recurrent invasive Neisseria; C3 (most severe) → encapsulated bacteria.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Immunodeficiency-associated issues: anemia, arthritis/joint pain, ~25% have an autoimmune disease, neoplasias (leukemias/lymphomas), growth retardation.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> &quot;Hyper-IgM&quot; does not require elevated absolute IgM. It is defined by the IgM:IgG/IgA ratio being high because switching fails — absolute IgM can sit in the normal range.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Oral/gum lesions + abscesses → think CGD; neutrophilia + no pus + delayed cord → LAD-1; recurrent Neisseria → C5–C9; non-pitting edema → C1-INH/hereditary angioedema.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Davis&#x27;s through-line: what you see is not always the problem. HLH anemia comes from macrophages, not RBC autoantibodies; LAD-1 neutrophilia comes from cells trapped in blood, not overproduction. Trace symptom → mechanism.</p><p>ReClaude A: Failed perforin/granzyme killing leaves intracellular targets unchecked, so CTLs/NK cells keep secreting IFN-γ; that sustained IFN-γ hyperactivates macrophages, which phagocytose RBCs, platelets, and neutrophils — producing the anemia, cytopenias, and splenomegaly. The defect is in the T/NK cell; the pathology is in the macrophage.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "20_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Why is a child with selective IgA deficiency treated with antibiotics-as-needed rather than IgA replacement, given that IVIG works for other antibody deficiencies?</em></p><p>MATCHING THERAPY TO DEFECT. Treatment follows directly from the mechanism. When the problem is missing antibody that can be replaced — AID hyper-IgM, where the patient cannot make IgG — the answer is IVIG, pooled donor immunoglobulin (overwhelmingly IgG). When the problem is a mucosal IgA deficit, IVIG does not help much: it is mostly IgG, and there is no reliable route to deliver protective secretory IgA to mucosal surfaces, so selective IgA deficiency is managed with antibiotics as needed. When the problem is uncontrolled inflammation (HLH), the answer is immunosuppression — methotrexate, dexamethasone, etoposide, cyclosporine A, anti-IFN-γ mAb. When the underlying defect is a bad gene in the stem cell (severe SCID such as BLS-II), the definitive option is HSCT/bone-marrow transplant, which replaces the defective stem cells but requires ablating the recipient&#x27;s immune system first — powerful but dangerous. Phagocytic defects (CGD, LAD) lean on prophylactic antimicrobials; severe respiratory damage in BLS-I may require lung transplant, and vaccines (especially respiratory) help because B cells are intact.</p><p>Therapy follows mechanism: IVIG for replaceable antibody gaps, antibiotics/prophylaxis for infection control, immunosuppression for HLH inflammation, HSCT for stem-cell-level cure. (therapy-to-defect map)</p><p>HLH treatment: methotrexate/dexamethasone (suppress inflammation), anti-IFN-γ mAb (remove excess cytokine), etoposide, cyclosporine A (reduce T-cell activation), HSC/bone-marrow transplant.</p><p>Selective IgA deficiency: low IgA, normal IgM/IgG, normal B-cell numbers; treatment is antibiotics as needed — not IgA replacement (&quot;why not just provide IgA?&quot;).</p><p>BLS-I treatment: lung transplant (respiratory infections dominate and damage lungs), antibiotics as needed, and vaccines (especially respiratory) since B cells are intact.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> HSCT is the only true cure for a genetic stem-cell defect, but it requires wiping out the recipient&#x27;s immune system first — high risk, used when nothing else works (HLH refractory, BLS-II).</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> A &quot;why not just give IgA?&quot; question is testing delivery, not purification — IVIG is mostly IgG and there is no mucosal IgA delivery route, so the answer is antibiotics-as-needed.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Four therapeutic levers: replace (IVIG), control infection (antibiotics/prophylaxis/vaccines), suppress inflammation (HLH drugs), or cure at the source (HSCT). Pick the one that matches the broken step.</p><p>ReClaude A: IVIG is pooled donor serum that is overwhelmingly IgG, and there is no reliable way to deliver protective secretory IgA to mucosal surfaces — so giving &quot;IgA&quot; is not feasible. Selective IgA deficiency is therefore managed with antibiotics as needed for infections, not antibody replacement.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "20_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A young child with clonal expansion of a B-cell progenitor in the marrow, versus an older adult with punched-out skull lesions and urinary light chains — name each malignancy.</em></p><p>LEUKEMIA VS LYMPHOMA. Immune-system cancers split by architecture: leukemias proliferate as individual cells (lymphoid or myeloid), while lymphomas proliferate as a mass of cells. The four leukemias are named by acute/chronic and by lineage, and the age clue is the exam&#x27;s favorite discriminator. ALL (acute lymphoblastic) — clonal expansion of a lymphoid progenitor (usually a B cell), the most common pediatric malignancy (~⅓ of childhood cancers). CLL (chronic lymphocytic) — mature circulating B cells that cannot undergo apoptosis, in older adults (55+); fewer healthy B cells → more infections. AML (acute myeloid) — malignant immature granulocyte precursors crowd the marrow → low WBCs, then anemia and bleeding. CML (chronic myeloid) — a family named by the affected myeloid cell (granulocytes → chronic myelocytic leukemia; megakaryocytes → malignant thrombocythemia or myeloid metaplasia; RBCs → polycythemia vera), mostly in adults.</p><p>Leukemia = individual cells; lymphoma = mass. Age clue: ALL = children (most common pediatric cancer); CLL = older adults (no apoptosis); AML/CML = adults. (leukemia types + age clues)</p><p>Neoplasms of the immune system: leukemias proliferate as individual cells (lymphoid or myeloid); lymphomas proliferate as a mass of cells.</p><p>ALL: dysregulated clonal expansion of a lymphoid progenitor (usually B cell); most common pediatric malignancy (~⅓ of childhood cancers); anemia, bruising, lymphadenopathy.</p><p>AML: malignant proliferation of immature granulocyte precursors crowd the marrow → low WBCs, increased infections, then anemia and bleeding. MULTIPLE MYELOMA. Malignant plasma cells accumulate as a mass in bone, destroying it to leave diagnostic &quot;punched-out&quot; lytic lesions (skull, spine). Normal B cells are crowded out, and the malignant plasma cells overproduce free light chains (Bence-Jones proteins) that clog the kidney → renal failure. Most common in older adults.</p><p>HODGKIN VS NON-HODGKIN LYMPHOMA. Hodgkin — typically B-cell, spreads in an orderly, predictable node-to-node pattern (often beginning cervically), shows diagnostic Reed-Sternberg cells (a lymphoblastic form of a mature B cell, often EBV-linked), and is highly treatable (~90% 5-yr survival); more common in teens/young adults. Non-Hodgkin — can be B- or T-cell, is more aggressive and less predictable, spreads beyond nodes (spleen, liver, marrow), is usually diagnosed later (~74% survival), and is ~10× more common, skewing older.</p><p>Multiple myeloma = plasma cells, punched-out lytic lesions + Bence-Jones light chains → renal failure. Hodgkin = orderly node-to-node + Reed-Sternberg; non-Hodgkin = aggressive, B- or T-cell, beyond nodes. (myeloma + Hodgkin vs non-Hodgkin)</p><p>Multiple myeloma: malignant plasma cells accumulate as a mass in bone → &quot;punched-out&quot; lytic holes (spine, skull) that are diagnostic; normal B cells cannot be made.</p><p>Multiple myeloma: mostly older adults; renal failure from Bence-Jones proteins (overproduced light chains) passing through and clogging the kidney.</p><p>Hodgkin lymphoma: spreads orderly node-to-node; diagnostic Reed-Sternberg cells (a lymphoblastic form of a mature B cell); often EBV-associated, begins cervically.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Two diagnostic findings to lock in: punched-out lytic lesions + Bence-Jones = multiple myeloma; Reed-Sternberg cells = Hodgkin lymphoma.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Age is the discriminator: a young child → ALL; an older adult with no-apoptosis mature B cells → CLL; teens/young adults with orderly nodal spread → Hodgkin.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two axes for leukemia (acute/chronic × lymphoid/myeloid) plus the age clue solve most stems. Lymphomas split Hodgkin (orderly, Reed-Sternberg, B-cell, ~90%) vs non-Hodgkin (aggressive, B-or-T, ~74%).</p><p>ReClaude A: The child with marrow clonal expansion of a B-cell progenitor has acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL); the older adult with punched-out skull lesions and urinary Bence-Jones light chains has multiple myeloma.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "21_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Why does &quot;strong binding&quot; send a B cell to apoptosis but let a T cell survive positive selection — and then kill that same T cell in negative selection?</em></p><p>WHERE AND WHY. Central tolerance happens in the generative organs — B cells in the bone marrow (though ~70% of negative selection actually occurs in the spleen) and T cells in the thymus. Tolerance is purely an adaptive phenomenon: it is the education of BCRs and TCRs to ignore self and attack foreign. The single hardest thing to keep straight is that the same phrase — &quot;strong binding&quot; — produces opposite fates depending on the step, so anchor each step to its rule.</p><p>B-CELL NEGATIVE SELECTION (three outcomes + editing). An immature B cell (IgM+) meets self-Ag held by bone-marrow/splenic stromal cells. Strong binding to multivalent surface self-Ag WITH BCR cross-linking → apoptosis (cross-linking is the key — it always gives the strongest signal). Strong binding to soluble self-Ag WITHOUT cross-linking → anergy (the cell survives as an unresponsive IgM-lo IgD+ naive B cell). Weak or no binding → survival (a normal IgM+IgD+ naive B cell). In about a third of cells slated for apoptosis/anergy, persistent RAG1/2 attempt receptor editing of the light chain to escape self-reactivity.</p><p>B-cell negative selection: strong + cross-link → apoptosis; strong, no cross-link (soluble) → anergy; weak/no → survival. Cross-linking is the determinant.</p><p>Outcome 3: weak or no binding to self-Ag → SURVIVAL (normal IgM+IgD+ naive mature B cell enters periphery).</p><p>B-cell negative selection outcome 1: strong binding to multivalent surface self-Ag WITH BCR cross-linking → APOPTOSIS. ~70% of negative selection occurs in the spleen.</p><p>Outcome 2: strong binding to soluble self-Ag WITHOUT cross-linking → ANERGY (survives as unresponsive IgM-lo IgD+ naive B cell in the periphery).</p><p>T-CELL POSITIVE SELECTION (cortex) — fate determination. Double-positive (CD4+CD8+) thymocytes engage cortical thymic epithelial cells via HLA–self-Ag–TCR. Weak/no binding → apoptosis (death by neglect); moderate/strong binding → survival, and the MHC class fit sets lineage: CD8 fit with MHC I → cytotoxic, CD4 fit with MHC II → helper. Note this is the opposite rule from B-cell negative selection — here weak binding is the one that dies.</p><p>T-CELL NEGATIVE SELECTION (medulla) — signaling test. Single-positive T cells (now CD3-high, so the TCR can signal) meet medullary thymic epithelial cells and thymic DCs. Weak binding → survival; strong OR no binding → apoptosis. Gregg framed this as a signaling test: a surviving T cell must signal weakly (proving a functional TCR) but not strongly (which would mean it recognizes self). The self-antigen breadth comes from AIRE in MTECs, a master switch that transcribes essentially all tissue-restricted self-antigens; Hassall&#x27;s corpuscles make TSLP to mature the thymic DCs.</p><p>T-cell positive selection (cortex): weak/no → apoptosis, mod/strong → survival + lineage fate. T-cell negative selection (medulla): weak → survival, strong/no → apoptosis. AIRE supplies all self-Ags. (T-cell selection rules + AIRE)</p><p>T-cell positive selection (cortex): weak/no binding → apoptosis; moderate/strong → survival. CD8 fit with MHC I → cytotoxic; CD4 fit with MHC II → helper. Fate determination.</p><p>T-cell negative selection: MTECs express AIRE → produce ALL self-Ags, present on MHC I/II and release to thymic DCs; Hassall&#x27;s corpuscles make TSLP to mature the DCs.</p><p>T-cell negative selection outcomes: weak TCR–self-Ag/MHC binding → SURVIVAL; strong OR no binding → APOPTOSIS. A surviving T cell must signal weakly but not strongly.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Positive vs negative selection are opposite on weak binding: weak loses in positive (death by neglect) but wins in negative (proof of a safe, functional TCR). Lock the step first, then the rule.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> &quot;All self-antigens in the thymus&quot; is your AIRE flag. AIRE knockout → autoimmunity; it is the master switch in MTECs that lets the thymus display tissue-restricted self.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three steps, three rules. B-cell negative: strong → die/anergy. T-cell positive: weak → die. T-cell negative: weak → live, strong/no → die. The phrase &quot;strong binding&quot; is meaningless until you name the step.</p><p>ReClaude A: &quot;Strong binding&quot; has no fixed meaning until you name the step. In B-cell negative selection it means the cell recognizes self → apoptosis/anergy. In T-cell positive selection, weak binders die (death by neglect) and moderate/strong binders survive. In T-cell negative selection, the surviving cell must signal weakly — strong binding now means self-recognition → apoptosis. So the same word maps to deletion in two steps and survival in one, because each step is testing for a different thing.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "21_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A self-reactive immature B cell re-rearranges its light-chain DNA via persistent RAG — what is this called, and can T cells do it?</em></p><p>RECEPTOR EDITING. Covered in the B-cell negative-selection arm of LO 21.1, but worth isolating because it is high-yield and uniquely B-cell. In ~⅓ of immature B cells slated for apoptosis or anergy, RAG1/2 remain expressed and re-rearrange the light-chain DNA to generate a new BCR specificity — a last-ditch rescue. If the new BCR no longer binds self → the cell survives as a naive mature B cell; if it still binds self → it falls back to apoptosis or anergy. This is B-cell-only: T cells cannot edit their TCR.</p><p>Receptor editing = persistent RAG1/2 re-rearranging the light chain to escape self-reactivity; B-cell-only. New BCR self-reactive → apoptosis/anergy; not self-reactive → survival. (receptor editing)</p><p>B-cell development in the bone marrow generates BCR+ immature B cells, each with a unique BCR — the substrate that receptor editing can revise.</p><p>After editing/selection, mature naive CXCR5+ B cells localize to follicles following the CXCL13 gradient produced by follicular dendritic cells.</p><p>Receptor editing (option 1a/2a): strong BCR binding to self-Ag → persistent RAG1/2 → re-rearrange L-chain DNA → new BCR specificity. New BCR self-reactive → apoptosis/anergy; not → survival.</p><p>ReClaude A: Persistent RAG1/2 re-rearranging the light-chain DNA to create a new BCR specificity is receptor editing — a rescue attempt. It is exclusive to B cells; T cells cannot edit their TCR, so a self-reactive thymocyte that signals strongly is simply deleted.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "21_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Which receptor/chemokine pair takes a naive B cell into the follicle, and which takes a naive T cell into the T-cell zone?</em></p><p>THE MARKERS THAT MATTER. Two homing axes anchor everything. Mature naive B cells express CXCR5 and follow the CXCL13 gradient (from follicular dendritic cells) into the follicle. Mature naive T cells express CCR7 and follow CCL19/21 into the T-cell zone. Stage markers worth holding: immature B cells are IgM+ (IgD comes later by alternative splicing → IgM+IgD+ mature); developing thymocytes go double-negative → double-positive (CD4+CD8+, CD3-low) → single-positive (CD3-high, able to signal). These same markers reappear in peripheral tolerance — losing CXCR5 is exactly what traps an anergic B cell in the T-cell zone (follicular exclusion, LO 21.5).</p><p>Homing: B cells = CXCR5/CXCL13 → follicle; T cells = CCR7/CCL19-21 → T-cell zone. Stage: immature B = IgM+; thymocyte DP = CD4+CD8+ CD3-low; SP = CD3-high. (homing + stage markers)</p><p>Naive mature CCR7+ T cells localize to the T-cell zone following the CCL19/21 gradient. (B cells use CXCR5/CXCL13 to reach the follicle.)</p><p>Bone-marrow pro-T cells migrate to the thymus to begin the selection program that tests each newly produced TCR for self-reactivity.</p><p>Thymocyte maturation: TCR rearrangement upregulates CD4/CD8 (double-positive, CD3-low); single-positive cells become CD3-high and can signal through the TCR.</p><p>ReClaude A: A naive B cell uses CXCR5 to follow the CXCL13 gradient into the follicle; a naive T cell uses CCR7 to follow CCL19/21 into the T-cell zone. The same logic drives follicular exclusion: an anergic B cell that loses CXCR5 cannot enter the follicle and is held in the T-cell zone.</p><p><em>Why does a self-reactive T cell facing chronic self-antigen tend to be tolerized rather than activated, even when a mature APC delivers all three signals?</em></p><p>WHY PERIPHERAL TOLERANCE EXISTS. Central tolerance is leaky on purpose — everyone carries self-reactive B and T cells (the trade-off is anti-cancer surveillance). Peripheral tolerance controls the escapees through three arms: anergy, deletion, and suppression.</p><p>ANERGY — TWO FLAVORS. First, the three-signal rule: full activation needs antigen (1), B7/CD28 costimulation (2), and cytokine (3). A self-reactive T cell that meets self-Ag on a resting/immature APC gets Signal 1 only → anergy (paralyzed, non-proliferative). Because resting APCs constantly present self-Ag, this is the default tolerizing encounter. Second, even with all three signals, chronic self-antigen slowly raises CTLA-4 (and PD-1) on the T cell; CTLA-4 outcompetes CD28 for B7 and recruits phosphatases that arrest the cell cycle → anergy. The slow buildup explains why autoimmunity has a slow onset, and why self-reactive T cells are &quot;more prone to tolerance than activation.&quot;</p><p>Anergy: Signal 1 only (resting APC) → paralysis; OR chronic self-Ag slowly builds CTLA-4/PD-1 that outcompete CD28 → cell-cycle arrest. Both leave the cell alive but non-proliferative. (T-cell anergy (two routes))</p><p>CTLA-4 outcompetes CD28 for B7. Self-reactive T cells carry higher basal CTLA-4 due to persistent self-Ag–TCR interaction.</p><p>CTLA-4 ligation → cell-cycle arrest (anergy): the activated/self-reactive T cell is rendered tolerant despite engaging a mature APC.</p><p>Signal 1 only (self-Ag on immature APC, no B7/cytokine) → T-cell ANERGY. The default tolerizing encounter, since resting APCs constantly present self-Ag.</p><p>DELETION — Fas/FasL (AICD). Activated T cells upregulate Fas and Fas ligand (IL-2 drives expression); under chronic stimulation, Fas–FasL interactions trigger activation-induced cell death (AICD), also called deletional self-tolerance. Anergy and deletion both ride on the chronicity of self-antigen plus the slow rise of CTLA-4/PD-1 and Fas/FasL.</p><p>SUPPRESSION — Treg cells. Tregs are made in the thymus and marked by FoxP3 (lineage transcription factor, TGF-β-inducible), constitutive CD25 (high-affinity IL-2 receptor), and CTLA-4. They carry high-affinity self-reactive TCRs, so they reach self-antigen and activate first — suppressing at the activation stage via CTLA-4 (forcing APCs to downregulate B7/MHC), CD25-mediated IL-2 sequestration (starving effectors), perforin/granzyme against APCs, and inhibitory cytokines (IL-10, TGF-β, IL-35). They are ~10% of peripheral CD4 T cells; below that threshold, autoimmunity risk rises sharply.</p><p>Deletion = Fas/FasL AICD. Suppression = Tregs (FoxP3/CD25/CTLA-4), high-affinity self-TCR so they act first; suppress via CTLA-4, IL-2 sequestration, and IL-10/TGF-β/IL-35. (deletion + Treg suppression)</p><p>Chronicity of self-Ag raises basal CTLA-4 and Fas/FasL on self-reactive T cells — making them more prone to tolerance than activation.</p><p>Activated T cells express Fas and Fas ligand (IL-2-driven). Fas–FasL interactions trigger activation-induced cell death (AICD) — the deletional arm of peripheral tolerance.</p><p>Tregs (FoxP3, CD25, CTLA-4/LAG3) suppress via APC downregulation, IL-2 uptake (CD25), perforin/granzyme, and IL-10/TGF-β/IL-35. CD25 or FoxP3 deficiency → systemic autoimmunity.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three arms: anergy (CTLA-4/PD-1, cell-cycle arrest), deletion (Fas/FasL AICD), suppression (Tregs). All exploit the chronic, low-grade nature of self-antigen presentation.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Tregs win the race because their TCRs have the highest affinity for self — they get there first and shut the response down at the activation step. Drop below ~10% of CD4 T cells and tolerance fails.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Anergy ≠ deletion. Anergy (CTLA-4/PD-1) leaves a living, paralyzed cell; deletion (Fas/FasL AICD) kills it. T1D defects hit anergy; lupus defects hit deletion (LO 21.8).</p><p>ReClaude A: Self-antigen is presented chronically at low grade, so the slow-building inhibitory molecules win the race. Signal-1-only encounters on resting APCs anergize the cell; even with full signals, chronic TCR signaling accumulates CTLA-4/PD-1 that outcompete CD28 and arrest the cycle. Meanwhile Fas/FasL delete chronically stimulated cells and high-affinity Tregs suppress at the activation step — so tolerance, not activation, is the default.</p><p><em>What two mechanisms keep anergic self-reactive B cells in check in the periphery, and what is the usual fate of each?</em></p><p>FOLLICULAR EXCLUSION + DELETION. Peripheral B-cell tolerance targets the anergic self-reactive B cells produced in negative selection. Follicular exclusion: anergic B cells down-regulate CXCR5, so they cannot follow CXCL13 into the follicle and are stuck (CCR7+) in the T-cell zone — where, without a follicular DC to concentrate antigen and without T-cell help, encountering self-Ag drives apoptosis (no survival factors). Deletional self-tolerance: activated T-cell-zone CD4+ T cells upregulate Fas ligand, which engages the moderate Fas on the anergic B cell to trigger apoptosis (the same death-receptor logic as T-cell AICD in LO 21.4). Anergic B cells are stressed, high-Fas targets — &quot;target practice&quot; for effector T cells.</p><p>B-cell peripheral tolerance: follicular exclusion (no CXCR5 → trapped in T-cell zone → apoptosis) + deletion (T-cell Fas ligand → Fas on anergic B cell → apoptosis). (B-cell peripheral tolerance)</p><p>Follicular exclusion: CXCR5- CCR7+ anergic B cells cannot enter the follicle, remain in the T-cell zone, encounter self-Ag without T-cell help → apoptosis (no survival factors).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Deletional self-tolerance: activated CD4+ T cells upregulate Fas ligand; anergic B cells express moderate Fas → Fas-ligand-positive T cells induce apoptosis of the anergic B cell.</p><p>The substrate: anergic naive mature B cells (IgM-lo IgD+) from negative selection, unresponsive to Ag — these are what peripheral B-cell tolerance must control. ReClaude A: Follicular exclusion keeps the anergic B cell (CXCR5-low) out of the follicle and in the T-cell zone, where self-Ag without T-cell help drives apoptosis; deletional self-tolerance has Fas-ligand-positive activated T cells kill the anergic, Fas-bearing B cell directly. Both end in apoptosis for lack of survival signals.</p><p><em>Walk the four steps of autoimmunity in T1D from a pool of self-reactive cells to dead beta cells — which tolerance failure does each step represent?</em></p><p>THE FOUR-STEP SPINE. Gregg&#x27;s model generalizes to any autoimmune disease; T1D is the worked example (a Type IV hypersensitivity, with some Type II/III antibody contribution). Step I — generate a pool of self-reactive lymphocytes (failure of central tolerance: self-reactive T cells escape thymic deletion, usually HLA-driven; anergic self-reactive B cells sit in the lymph-node paracortex). Step II — release and chronic presence of self-Ag (the triggering event: tissue damage liberates self-Ag and matures DCs via PAMP/cytokine signaling — e.g. a Coxsackie-A virus link to beta-cell antigen release). Step III — activation of self-reactive lymphocytes (failure of peripheral tolerance: clonal expansion and differentiation proceed; anergic B cells are rescued into autoantibody producers). Step IV — destruction of target cells: Th cytokines drive inflammation and innate action, CTLs kill, autoantibodies add complement/ADCC/opsonization.</p><p>Four steps: I generate self-reactive cells (central-tolerance failure) → II release + chronic self-Ag (trigger, DC maturation) → III activate them (peripheral-tolerance failure) → IV destroy target cells. (four-step autoimmunity model)</p><p>The four steps: I generate self-reactive lymphocytes (central failure); II release + chronic self-Ag (trigger); III activation (peripheral failure); IV destruction of target cells.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Islets of Langerhans: alpha (glucagon), beta (insulin, ~⅔ of islet), delta (somatostatin). Progressive T-cell infiltration = insulitis; slow onset given initial beta-cell excess (~10^8).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> T1D: insulin from pancreatic beta cells lowers blood glucose; autoimmune beta-cell destruction → no insulin → hyperglycemia. A Type IV hypersensitivity; onset usually childhood/adolescence.</p><p>THE DESTRUCTION DETAIL (step IV). The response begins Th17-dominant (IL-6 + TGF-β; IL-17 recruits neutrophils) and transitions to a Th1 response over time, broadening to multiple antigens and epitopes (insulin, glutamic acid decarboxylase, heat-shock proteins). CD4 drives, CD8 kills: CD8+ CTLs are the primary effectors via perforin/granzyme and Fas/FasL (cytokines IL-1/IFN-γ/TNF-α raise Fas on stressed beta cells); macrophages add IFN-γ-driven frustrated phagocytosis as a more inflammatory/bystander role.</p><p>T1D destruction: Th17 → Th1 transition; CD8 CTLs are the main killers (perforin/granzyme + Fas/FasL); CD4/Th1 drive inflammation; macrophages add bystander damage. (T1D effector mechanism)</p><p>Step III: the pool of beta-cell-Ag-specific T cells is activated and migrates to the pancreas (CD4, CD8, plus macrophages, neutrophils, NK cells).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Step II: an unknown trigger releases beta-cell Ag and matures DCs, which migrate to the draining lymph node displaying beta-cell antigen.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Step IV: beta-cell-specific CD4/CD8 T cells — IFN-γ (macrophage function), IL-2 (support CTL), TNF-α/Fas-FasL/perforin-granzyme (beta-cell death). Propagates autoimmune destruction.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Insulitis + slow onset is a clue to the model itself: ~10^8 beta cells and slow killing mean symptoms lag the autoimmune attack by a long time.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Memorize the order: cells (I) → antigen/trigger (II) → activation (III) → destruction (IV). Steps I and III are the two tolerance failures (central, then peripheral); II is the environmental trigger; IV is the payoff.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> &quot;CD4 drives, CD8 kills.&quot; In T1D the CD8 CTL is the primary beta-cell killer (perforin/granzyme + Fas/FasL); CD4/Th1 orchestrate the inflammation. The Th17→Th1 shift is why early models only saw Th1.</p><p>ReClaude A: Step I generates the self-reactive pool (central-tolerance failure — self-reactive T cells escape thymic deletion; anergic B cells persist). Step II is the trigger: tissue damage releases beta-cell self-Ag and matures DCs. Step III activates the escapees (peripheral-tolerance failure), rescuing anergic B cells into autoantibody producers. Step IV destroys the beta cells — CD8 CTLs killing via perforin/granzyme and Fas/FasL while CD4/Th1 drive inflammation — producing insulin loss and hyperglycemia.</p><p><em>Mechanistically, why does inheriting HLA-DQ2 or DQ8 generate self-reactive T cells rather than protect against them?</em></p><p>THE HLA MECHANISM — THE KEY INTEGRATE. This is Step I of the model, explained at the molecular level, and it is the concept students most often get backwards. HLA-DRB is the most polymorphic class II locus, which is why so many disease-associated alleles map to class II. For T1D, the susceptibility allotypes are HLA-DQ2 (DQA1*0501:DQB1*0201) and HLA-DQ8 (DQA1*03:DQB1*0302); having both is additive (via a recombinant DQ). The mechanism: in a resistant person, HLA holds the self-peptide firmly, so a self-reactive TCR binds strongly in the thymus → apoptosis (the self-reactive cell is correctly deleted). In a susceptible person, the HLA lacks the contact residues to hold that peptide, so it &quot;flops&quot; — the self-reactive TCR, even with high intrinsic affinity, gets only a weak signal, and weak negative-selection signaling means survival. The</p><p>self-reactive T cell escapes deletion. As Gregg put it, &quot;leaky central tolerance has everything to do with HLA presentation.&quot;</p><p>Susceptible HLA-DQ2/DQ8 holds self-peptide loosely → weak thymic signal despite high TCR affinity → survival (escapes negative selection). Resistant HLA holds it firmly → strong signal → apoptosis. (HLA susceptibility mechanism)</p><p>Susceptibility = poor presentation: in resistant individuals self-Ag is held firmly → self-reactive T cells bind strongly; in susceptible individuals self-Ag is loosely held → weak binding.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Poor presentation generates the self-reactive pool: strong binding → APOPTOSIS (resistant); weak binding → SURVIVAL (susceptible). The peptide &quot;flops&quot; when HLA cannot hold it.</p><p>T1D susceptibility allotypes: HLA-DQ2 (DQA1*0501:DQB1*0201) and HLA-DQ8 (DQA1*03:DQB1*0302). Having both is additive via a recombinant DQ. WHY THE FLIP IS THE TRAP. The same binding-strength rule from negative selection (LO 21.1) is doing the work here: weak signal → survival. The intuition that &quot;tighter HLA binding = worse disease&quot; is exactly wrong — tighter binding gives a strong thymic signal and deletes the dangerous cell. It is the loose hold that is pathogenic, because it lets a self-reactive cell slip under the deletion threshold.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Match the allele to the disease: DQ2/DQ8 → T1D; B27 → ankylosing spondylitis; DR15 → MS; A3 → hemochromatosis. Knowing the T1D pair is the high-yield one here.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Susceptibility = LOOSE self-peptide hold → weak thymic signal → the self-reactive T cell SURVIVES. T1D markers: HLA-DQ2 and DQ8 (additive together); class II (DRB) is the most polymorphic locus.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> The intuitive direction is wrong. Tighter HLA binding does NOT cause disease — it deletes the self-reactive cell (strong signal → apoptosis). Loose binding (weak signal → survival) is the pathogenic one.</p><p>ReClaude A: Susceptibility HLA-DQ2/DQ8 cannot hold the self-peptide firmly, so it flops. During thymic negative selection the self-reactive TCR therefore receives only a weak signal — and weak signaling means survival — so the dangerous cell escapes deletion instead of being apoptosed. Counterintuitively, it is the loose (not tight) HLA hold that generates the self-reactive pool.</p><p><em>T1D shows a truncated CTLA-4 while lupus shows a Fas/FasL defect — what does this say about which tolerance arm each disease breaks?</em></p><p>THE CHECKPOINT ROSTER. Peripheral tolerance runs on two arms, and the molecules sort cleanly: anergy arm = CTLA-4 and PD-1 (build slowly under chronic self-Ag, outcompete CD28, arrest the cycle); deletion arm = Fas and Fas ligand (AICD); plus Tregs for active suppression. Both arms must work — a defect in either lets self-reactive cells escape. T1D hits the anergy arm: a truncated CTLA-4 (IDDM12) that binds B7 but cannot signal, plus reduced PD-1 (Fas/FasL stay intact and do the beta-cell killing). Lupus instead shows a Fas/Fas-ligand defect (deletion fails; CTLA-4 intact). The disease reflects the broken arm.</p><p>Anergy arm = CTLA-4/PD-1; deletion arm = Fas/FasL; suppression = Tregs. T1D = anergy-arm defect (truncated CTLA-4/IDDM12); lupus = deletion-arm defect (Fas/FasL). Both arms required. (checkpoint roles in disease) CD40/CD40L AND THE B-CELL RESCUE. The same B-cell rescue from the model: a freshly activated CD4+ T cell expresses CD40 ligand before it ramps up Fas ligand, and CD40L–CD40 engagement reverses B-cell anergy (re-inducing CXCR5, cytokine receptors, and AID), letting the B cell re-enter the follicle as an autoantibody producer. Critical contrast: CD40L can reverse B-cell anergy, but T-cell anergy is essentially irreversible — once anergized, T cells stay that way (the basis of anergic/exhausted T cells in cancer).</p><p>T1D: activated self-reactive T cells require defects in CTLA-4/PD-1 — truncated CTLA-4 (IDDM12) binds B7 but cannot signal; reduced PD-1/PD-L1. The anergy arm fails.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Fas/Fas ligand: Fas is a death receptor on stressed cells; FasL on activated T/B/myeloid/NK cells drives AICD. In T1D this arm is intact and kills beta cells; in lupus it is defective. B-cell rescue: an activated CD4+ T cell with high CD40 ligand (low Fas ligand) engages CD40 on the anergic B cell — reversing anergy instead of killing it.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Sort the roster by arm: CTLA-4/PD-1 = anergy; Fas/FasL = deletion; Tregs = suppression; CD40/CD40L = B-cell rescue (reverses anergy). Both anergy and deletion arms must work.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> T1D vs lupus checkpoint defect: T1D breaks the anergy arm (truncated CTLA-4/IDDM12); lupus breaks the deletion arm (Fas/FasL). Same toolkit, different broken part, different disease.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Reversibility splits the lineages: CD40L can reverse B-cell anergy (→ autoantibody producer), but T-cell anergy is essentially permanent — which is exactly the problem with anergic/exhausted T cells in tumors.</p><p>ReClaude A: Peripheral tolerance needs both the anergy arm (CTLA-4/PD-1) and the deletion arm (Fas/FasL), and a defect in either permits escape. T1D breaks the anergy arm — a truncated, non-signaling CTLA-4 (IDDM12) plus reduced PD-1 — while leaving Fas/FasL intact to kill beta cells; lupus breaks the deletion arm (Fas/FasL defect) with</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> CTLA-4 intact. So the specific checkpoint that fails shapes which autoimmune disease develops.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "22_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Which three HLA loci are matched in transplantation, and why is HLA-DR the most immunogenic?</em></p><p>THE THREE TO MATCH. Each person&#x27;s MHC proteins can look foreign to a recipient — these are the alloantigens. Three loci dominate graft rejection and are the ones matched in tissue typing: HLA-A, HLA-B, and HLA-DR. HLA-DR is the most immunogenic because its β chain is the most polymorphic, so it harbors the most variability for the recipient to react against. Both direct and indirect recognition converge on these HLA targets. Minor (non-MHC) antigens — growth factors, structural proteins, hormones with slight sequence differences — are also targeted, but provoke weaker responses (blood-transfusion mismatches are minor-antigen examples).</p><p>Major alloantigens = HLA-A, HLA-B, HLA-DR (DR most immunogenic — most polymorphic β chain). Minor non-MHC antigens give weaker responses.</p><p>Normal T-cell activation: TCR recognizes self MHC + foreign peptide — the baseline against which alloantigen recognition is contrasted.</p><p>Graft types: autograft (self), isograft (identical twin), allograft (same species, different individual), xenograft (different species). Rejection scales with genetic distance.</p><p>MHC as alloantigens: HLA-A, HLA-B, and HLA-DR are the three biggest targets for graft rejection. The variant-allele table shows DR&#x27;s β chain is the most polymorphic. Minor non-MHC antigens give weaker responses.</p><p>ReClaude A: HLA-A, HLA-B, and HLA-DR are the three loci matched in transplantation; HLA-DR is the most immunogenic because its β chain is the most polymorphic, giving the recipient the most variability to react against.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "22_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Is the recipient T cell seeing the donor MHC whole, or seeing donor-MHC fragments on its own MHC — and which one drives acute versus chronic rejection?</em></p><p>THE CORE DISTINCTION. Both are T-cell recognition modes, and the difference is simply whose MHC the recipient TCR engages. Direct allorecognition: the recipient TCR binds the intact donor MHC displayed on graft cells (donor DCs and endothelium). The donor MHC molecule itself drops into the TCR groove &quot;as if it were antigen,&quot; and because the graft carries many copies of MHC, this is the strongest alloresponse — it drives acute rejection. Indirect allorecognition: recipient APCs take up donor MHC, process it into peptides, and present those donor-MHC peptides on recipient MHC (the normal self-MHC + foreign-peptide configuration). As the transplant ages, donor DCs die off and are replaced by recipient DCs, so direct recognition wanes and indirect comes to dominate — driving chronic rejection in wave after wave of new T-cell specificities.</p><p>Direct: recipient TCR sees INTACT donor MHC (strong; → acute). Indirect: recipient APC presents donor-MHC PEPTIDES on recipient MHC (→ chronic, dominates over time). (direct vs indirect allorecognition)</p><p>Direct recognition of alloantigens: recipient T cells recognize intact donor MHC on graft cells (donor DC/endothelium). Responsible for ACUTE rejection (solid organs).</p><p>Recipient T-cell activation to graft: the recipient TCR recognizes graft MHC directly — a strong signal because the graft carries many MHC copies (vs MHC + a single foreign peptide).</p><p>Indirect recognition: grafts express MHC that recipient APCs process and present as peptides on recipient MHC (cross-presented to CD8). Responsible for CHRONIC rejection (solid organs).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Direct is strongest (many intact MHC copies) and early → acute. Indirect takes over as donor DCs are replaced by recipient DCs → chronic. Time shifts the graft from direct- to indirect-dominant.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One question decides it: is the recipient TCR touching intact donor MHC (direct → acute) or donor-MHC peptide on recipient MHC (indirect → chronic)? &quot;Direct = donor MHC whole; indirect = donor MHC chopped.&quot;</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> The names invert the intuition some students build. Direct is the abnormal-looking one (TCR on foreign MHC); indirect is the normal-looking one (self MHC + foreign peptide). Anchor on &quot;whose MHC is in the groove.&quot;</p><p>ReClaude A: In direct allorecognition the recipient TCR sees the intact donor MHC molecule itself on graft cells — a strong, many-copy signal that drives acute rejection. In indirect allorecognition the recipient APC processes donor MHC and presents the peptides on recipient MHC; this dominates as donor DCs are replaced over time and drives chronic rejection.</p><p><em>How do CD8 CTLs, Th1 cytokines, and antibody combine in acute rejection — and how is graft-versus-host disease the mirror image of that process?</em></p><p>HYPERACUTE — antibody + complement. Pre-existing antibody binds graft endothelium → fixes complement → C3a/C5a recruit neutrophils/macrophages (frustrated phagocytosis on endothelium), platelet-activating factor drives platelet aggregation and clots, and the resulting thrombosis blocks graft vascularization → ischemic necrosis within 24 hours.</p><p>ACUTE — T cells lead, antibody assists. After revascularization, CD8+ CTLs recognize graft endothelial MHC I and lyse it via perforin/granzyme (treating the graft like an infected cell). Th1 cells supply IFN-γ (activating macrophages and raising graft MHC, creating more CTL targets) and TNF-α (graft apoptosis). Antibody binds graft antigen to fix complement and enables NK ADCC. T cells are the principal effector — hence T-cell-targeted immunosuppression.</p><p>Acute: CD8 CTLs lyse endothelium (perforin/granzyme); Th1 IFN-γ activates macrophages + raises graft MHC; TNF-α → apoptosis; antibody fixes complement + NK ADCC. T cells lead. (acute rejection effector chain) CHRONIC — chronic cytokines remodel the vessel. Soluble graft antigen from ongoing damage is captured by recipient APCs (indirect recognition) and forms immune complexes that activate complement. Sustained Th1 IFN-γ/TNF-α stimulates smooth-muscle proliferation around graft arterioles → wall thickening and occlusion (arteriosclerosis); the repeated necrosis-and-wound-healing cycle replaces tissue with fibrin/ECM (fibrosis). Together: progressive ischemic graft failure.</p><p>GVHD — the reciprocal of acute rejection. Instead of recipient-against-graft, GVHD is donor-against-recipient. When a graft (HSCT, or T-cell-rich tissue like skin, intestine, liver) carries donor T cells, those donor T cells recognize recipient HLA directly as foreign and attack recipient skin, gut, and liver (typically within ~4 weeks, up to ~3 months). Like acute rejection, it is direct recognition — no antigen processing needed — just with the donor and recipient roles swapped.</p><p>Chronic: indirect recognition + chronic Th1 → smooth-muscle proliferation (arteriosclerosis) + fibroblast wound-healing (fibrosis). GVHD = reciprocal of acute: donor T cells recognize recipient HLA directly. (chronic mechanism + GVHD)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Acute mechanism: CD8 CTLs lyse endothelium; Th1 IFN-γ activates macrophages and raises graft MHC; TNF-α → apoptosis; antibody fixes complement (+MAC) and clots vessels → necrosis.</p><p>Hyperacute mechanism: IgG → C1q → complement; C3a/C5a recruit neutrophils/macrophages; PAF drives platelet aggregation and clots → ischemic necrosis (no graft vascularization).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Chronic mechanism: chronic Th1 IFN-γ/TNF-α → smooth-muscle proliferation (vessel &quot;thickening&quot;/occlusion); necrosis → fibroblasts (FGF, TGF-β, IL-13) → fibrosis. Tissue fibrosis + arteriosclerosis = organ failure.</p><p>Graft-versus-host disease: donor T cells present in the graft (HSCT, or skin/intestine/liver tissue) recognize recipient HLA as foreign and attack recipient cells — the reciprocal of rejection.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Direct recognition (shared by acute rejection and GVHD): a TCR engages intact MHC directly — in GVHD it is donor T cells reading recipient MHC, roles swapped vs acute rejection.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Transplantation overview: organs/tissues transferred donor→recipient; immune-mediated graft destruction is rejection — and when donor T cells ride along, the reverse attack is GVHD.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Build each chain from its mediator: hyperacute = antibody→complement→thrombosis→ischemia; acute = CTL lysis + Th1 cytokines + antibody; chronic = chronic cytokines → smooth-muscle proliferation + fibrosis.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> GVHD vs acute rejection use the SAME mechanism (direct recognition) with the direction reversed: acute = recipient T cells vs graft; GVHD = donor T cells vs recipient. Watch the direction, not the mechanism.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Fibrosis + arteriosclerosis = chronic. Thrombosis + ischemic necrosis at 24h = hyperacute. CD8 lysis of endothelium at a week+ = acute. Rash/diarrhea/liver after a marrow transplant = GVHD.</p><p>ReClaude A: In acute rejection, CD8 CTLs directly lyse graft endothelium via perforin/granzyme while Th1 IFN-γ activates macrophages and upregulates graft MHC (more CTL targets) and TNF-α drives apoptosis, with antibody fixing complement and enabling NK ADCC. GVHD is the mirror image: the same direct recognition, but donor T cells carried in the graft recognize recipient HLA as foreign and attack recipient skin, gut, and liver — recipient-against-graft becomes donor-against-recipient.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "22_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What are the three tissue-typing methods, and what does trypan-blue uptake signify in the microcytotoxicity test?</em></p><p>THREE WAYS TO MATCH. You cannot prevent rejection, only delay it by matching as closely as possible — especially at HLA-A, -B, and -DR (DR mismatches dominate the first 6 months, B emerges within 2 years, A affects long-term survival). Three methods: (1) Microcytotoxicity test — donor/recipient WBCs in wells, add a specific anti-HLA antibody + complement; if the antibody binds, complement lyses the cell, which then takes up trypan blue and stains blue (so dye uptake = that HLA is expressed). (2) Genetic analysis — PCR with HLA-specific primers, compare sequence/bands (now the fast, reliable standard). (3) Cross-matching — mix donor cells with recipient serum to rule out preformed anti-donor antibody (watch for lysis).</p><p>Tissue typing = microcytotoxicity (anti-HLA + complement + trypan blue), genetic analysis (PCR/sequence, the modern standard), and cross-matching (donor cells + recipient serum → preformed antibody). (three tissue-typing methods)</p><p>HLA loci to match: A, B, and DR — the three with the greatest impact on graft loss (DR β chain most polymorphic).</p><p>Compatibility testing (classical): forward typing (patient RBC + anti-A/anti-B) and reverse typing (patient serum + A/B cells); cross-matching rules out preformed anti-donor antibody.</p><p>Tissue typing: HLA-A/B/DR matter most (DR first 6 months, B within 2 years, A long-term). Methods: microcytotoxicity (anti-HLA + complement → trypan-blue uptake), genetic analysis (PCR), cross-matching (donor cells + recipient serum).</p><p>ReClaude A: The three methods are the microcytotoxicity test, genetic (PCR/sequence) analysis, and cross-matching. In the microcytotoxicity test, trypan-blue uptake means the anti-HLA antibody bound and complement lysed the cell — so that cell expresses the tested HLA allele.</p><p><em>How do cyclosporine/tacrolimus and corticosteroids each block T-cell activation, and what is serum sickness?</em></p><p>MOSTLY T-CELL TARGETED. Because T cells drive acute and chronic rejection, immunosuppressants mostly hit T-cell activation — and blocking even one activation transcription factor (NFAT, NF-κB, or AP-1) cripples the response. Cyclosporine and tacrolimus (FK506): inhibit calcineurin → block NFAT → no IL-2 → no proliferation. Corticosteroids: raise IκB → keep NF-κB out of the nucleus → block inflammatory/proliferative genes (and block lymphocyte homing). Therapeutic antibodies: anti-CD3 (depletes T cells), anti-IL-2R/CD25 (blocks proliferation), CTLA-4-Ig (blocks B7→CD28), anti-CD40 (limits macrophage help). The cost: susceptibility to infection (CMV) and oncogenic-virus</p><p>cancers. A large foreign-protein (therapeutic Ig) dose can also cause serum sickness — immune-complex deposition (Type III) 7–10 days later, with fever, rash, arthritis, vasculitis, glomerulonephritis.</p><p>Cyclosporine/tacrolimus → calcineurin → block NFAT; corticosteroids → ↑IκB → block NF-κB. Both stop IL-2-driven T-cell proliferation. Serum sickness = Type III immune-complex reaction at 7–10 d. (immunosuppressant mechanisms)</p><p>Why target T cells: Th1 IFN-γ/TNF-α and CD8 CTLs are the principal acute effectors, so blocking T-cell activation blunts rejection.</p><p>Acute rejection is mediated by B and T cells, but T cells dominate — which is why immunosuppression centers on T-cell activation pathways (calcineurin/NFAT, NF-κB).</p><p>Immunosuppressive therapy: cyclosporine/tacrolimus inhibit calcineurin → block NFAT; corticosteroids ↑IκB → block NF-κB and lymphocyte homing; therapeutic Ig can cause serum sickness (immune-complex deposition).</p><p>ReClaude A: Cyclosporine and tacrolimus inhibit calcineurin to block NFAT activation; corticosteroids raise IκB to block NF-κB activation — both shut down IL-2-driven T-cell proliferation. Serum sickness is a Type III immune-complex reaction (fever, rash, arthritis, vasculitis) appearing 7–10 days after a large foreign-protein/therapeutic-Ig dose.</p><p><em>When is transfusion indicated, and what are the findings and first step in an acute hemolytic transfusion reaction?</em></p><p>WHEN, AND WHAT GOES WRONG. Transfusion is indicated for hemorrhage (trauma, surgery, bleeding disorders, thrombocytopenia), anemia from RBC destruction, and inadequate marrow production. It is the most common inpatient procedure and the #1 allogeneic tissue transplant — so it exposes patients to alloantigens more than all other transplants combined. The key reaction is the acute hemolytic transfusion reaction (AHTR): onset within ~15 minutes (or 50 mL), with fever and rising pulse, then chills, dyspnea, rash/hives, chest/flank pain, anxiety — and possible progression to shock. The cause is usually an ABO/Rh mismatch, most often from human error (mislabeled blood, wrong patient ID); as little as 10 mL can trigger it. First step: STOP the transfusion, then monitor vitals, maintain IV/diuresis, and recheck the blood and paperwork.</p><p>Transfusion indications: hemorrhage, hemolytic anemia, marrow failure. AHTR: fever + ↑pulse → chills/flank pain within 15 min; cause = ABO/Rh mismatch (human error); first step = STOP. (transfusion indications + AHTR)</p><p>Transfusions are the most common inpatient procedure and the #1 allogeneic tissue transplant; most reactions are caused by human error (mislabeled blood, unconfirmed patient ID).</p><p>Transfusion indications: hemorrhage (trauma, surgery, bleeding disorders, thrombocytopenia), anemia from erythrocyte destruction, and inadequate marrow blood-cell production.</p><p>Acute hemolytic transfusion reaction (&lt;24h): onset within 15 min/50 mL; fever + ↑pulse, then chills, dyspnea, rash, chest/flank pain, possible shock. Cause = ABO/Rh mismatch (mostly human error). Treatment = STOP the transfusion.</p><p>ReClaude A: Transfusions are indicated for hemorrhage, anemia from RBC destruction, and inadequate marrow production. An acute hemolytic transfusion reaction presents within ~15 minutes with fever and a rising pulse, then chills, flank/chest pain, and hives; it is usually an ABO/Rh mismatch from human error, and the first step is to STOP the transfusion.</p><p><em>Using Landsteiner&#x27;s rule, who is the universal RBC donor and recipient — and what actually lyses the cells in an ABO-incompatible transfusion?</em></p><p>THE RULE AND THE LYSIS. ABO antigens are carbohydrates built on the H antigen: O = H alone, A = N-acetylgalactosamine on H, B = D-galactose on H, AB = both (codominant). Landsteiner&#x27;s rule: you form antibodies against the ABO antigens you do not possess (driven by constant environmental exposure to similar structures). So type O RBCs (no A/B antigen) are the universal RBC donor, and type AB (no anti-A/anti-B) is the universal RBC recipient. ABO and Rh(D) together account for ~98% of transfusion reactions. The lysis mechanism: pre-existing IgM/IgG binds the blood-group antigen and fixes C1 → classical complement → MAC lysis (Type II). This is complement-mediated, not macrophage — contrast hemolytic disease of the newborn, where anti-D drives macrophage opsonization.</p><p>Landsteiner: antibodies vs antigens you LACK → O = universal RBC donor, AB = universal recipient. ABO-incompatible lysis = pre-existing Ig + classical complement → MAC (not macrophage). (Landsteiner&#x27;s rule + lysis)</p><p>ABO antigens are carbohydrates on the H antigen: O = H alone; A = N-acetylgalactosamine; B = D-galactose; AB = both (codominant). The terminal sugar sets the blood group.</p><p>ABO-incompatible lysis: IgM/IgG binds the blood-group antigen, C1 initiates the classical complement pathway → MAC lysis of RBCs (Type II). Pre-existing Ig overwhelms normal inhibition.</p><p>ABO agglutination/compatibility table: forward typing (RBC + anti-A/anti-B) and reverse typing (serum + A/B cells). Landsteiner&#x27;s rule predicts which antibodies each type carries. ReClaude A: By Landsteiner&#x27;s rule you make antibodies against the ABO antigens you lack, so type O (no A/B antigens) is the universal RBC donor and type AB (no anti-A/anti-B) is the universal recipient. In an ABO-incompatible transfusion, pre-existing IgM/IgG fixes C1 and drives the classical complement pathway to MAC-mediated lysis — complement, not macrophages (the latter is the anti-D mechanism in hemolytic disease of the newborn).</p><p><em>Is the antibody already stuck to the red cell, or floating free in the serum — and which Coombs test detects each?</em></p><p>WHY COOMBS AT ALL. The Coombs reagent is a cocktail of antibodies against human IgG/IgM and C3. It exists because many clinically important anti-RBC antibodies are IgG, which has only two binding sites and often cannot bridge red cells into a visible clump (&quot;incomplete&quot; antibodies) — unlike pentameric IgM with its ten sites. The Coombs reagent binds the cell-bound IgG and cross-links the cells, so agglutination becomes visible.</p><p>DIRECT (DAT) vs INDIRECT (IAT). The split is simply where the antibody is. Direct Coombs (DAT): detects antibody (IgG) or C3 already bound to the patient&#x27;s RBCs in vivo — you add Coombs reagent directly to the patient&#x27;s washed cells. Classic uses: confirming anti-D coating a newborn&#x27;s RBCs in hemolytic disease of the newborn, or an immune transfusion reaction (usually DAT-positive). Indirect Coombs (IAT): detects antibody free in the patient&#x27;s serum — you first incubate the serum with reagent/donor RBCs (so the free antibody can bind), then add Coombs reagent to reveal agglutination. Uses: pretransfusion antibody screening and cross-matching, and checking an Rh-negative mother&#x27;s serum for anti-D.</p><p>Direct (DAT): antibody/C3 ALREADY ON the RBC in vivo (add reagent directly). Indirect (IAT): antibody FREE in serum (incubate serum + cells first, then reagent) — pretransfusion screen + cross-match. (direct vs indirect Coombs)</p><p>IAT in cross-matching: e.g. type A recipient serum (anti-B) + type B donor cells → anti-B binds donor RBCs → Coombs reagent agglutinates the incomplete Ig. Used pretransfusion.</p><p>Direct antiglobulin test (DAT / direct Coombs): detects IgG or C3 already bound to the RBC in vivo. Coombs reagent (anti-IgG/IgM/C3) cross-links the bound incomplete antibody → agglutination.</p><p>Indirect antiglobulin test (IAT / indirect Coombs): detects antibody free in patient serum. Recipient serum is incubated with donor/reagent cells, then Coombs reagent is added → agglutination if antibody present.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One question: is the antibody already on the cell (DAT/direct) or free in the serum (IAT/indirect)? Direct = test the patient&#x27;s cells; indirect = test the patient&#x27;s serum (incubate with cells first).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> &quot;Direct&quot; = direct to the cell (antibody already bound). &quot;Indirect&quot; = an extra incubation step is needed to load the free serum antibody onto cells first. Map the word to the number of steps.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Clinical mapping: newborn RBCs in HDN, or a suspected immune transfusion reaction → DAT. Pretransfusion screen, cross-match, or an Rh-negative mother&#x27;s anti-D screen → IAT.</p><p>ReClaude A: The direct Coombs test (DAT) detects antibody or C3 already bound to the patient&#x27;s red cells in vivo — you add Coombs reagent directly to the cells (e.g. a newborn&#x27;s RBCs in HDN). The indirect Coombs test (IAT) detects antibody free in the patient&#x27;s serum — you incubate the serum with reagent/donor cells first so the antibody can bind, then add Coombs reagent; it is used for pretransfusion screening and cross-matching.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "23_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Across the disorders Davis covered, which are systemic and which are organ-specific, and what defines each?</em></p><p>THE ROSTER. Davis grouped the lecture&#x27;s diseases into systemic (rheumatoid arthritis, autoimmune hemolytic anemia, Guillain-Barré) and organ-specific (vitiligo, Crohn disease, ulcerative colitis). Each has a defining lesion: RA = symmetric inflammatory arthritis (citrullinated-peptide and rheumatoid-factor immune complexes); AIHA = antibody-mediated RBC destruction; Guillain-Barré = acute ascending paralysis from anti-ganglioside mimicry; vitiligo = CTL-mediated melanocyte destruction (depigmentation); Crohn/UC = the two forms of inflammatory bowel disease. Roughly 3% of the population is affected, women 2:1.</p><p>Systemic: RA, AIHA, Guillain-Barré. Organ-specific: vitiligo, Crohn, UC. Each has a defining lesion — match the disease to its target tissue and effector.</p><p>Systemic vs organ-specific: systemic = RA, AIHA, Guillain-Barré; organ-specific = vitiligo, Crohn disease, ulcerative colitis.</p><p>Autoimmune disease arises from failure to develop tolerance OR dysregulation that breaks tolerance; the response is chronic because self-antigen cannot be removed.</p><p>Examples of autoimmune disorders: Sjögren, scleroderma, celiac, Behçet, T1D, atrophic gastritis, psoriasis, MS, IBD, Guillain-Barré, ALPS, pemphigus vulgaris. ~3% of the US population, 2:1 female bias.</p><p>ReClaude A: Davis grouped the diseases as systemic (rheumatoid arthritis, autoimmune hemolytic anemia, Guillain-Barré) or organ-specific (vitiligo, Crohn disease, ulcerative colitis); each is defined by its target tissue and dominant effector — e.g. RA by citrullinated-peptide/RF immune complexes in joints, vitiligo by CTL destruction of melanocytes.</p><p><em>A patient has IBD — what location, depth, and bleeding pattern tell you Crohn disease from ulcerative colitis?</em></p><p>THE CROHN vs UC DISTINCTION (Davis&#x27;s explicit focus). She taught these two side by side &quot;because it can be very confusing as to which one somebody has.&quot; Sort them on three axes: location, depth, and bleeding. Crohn disease: any GI segment, mouth to anus (often the terminal ileum/proximal colon junction), skip lesions, transmural (full bowel-wall thickness → cobblestoning, strictures, thickened wall/mesentery), and rectal bleeding is rare with more continuous pain. Ulcerative colitis: limited to the colon and rectum, spreads continuously from the rectum proximally, involves only the mucosa/submucosa, and rectal bleeding is characteristic with intermittent pain that coincides with bowel movements.</p><p>Crohn: mouth-to-anus, transmural, cobblestone, rectal bleeding RARE. UC: colon/rectum continuous-from-rectum, mucosa/submucosa, rectal bleeding CHARACTERISTIC. Location + depth + bleeding. (Crohn vs UC clinical)</p><p>Crohn disease lesions: crypt inflammation/abscesses → focal aphthoid ulcers → &quot;cobblestone&quot; appearance; transmural spread thickens the bowel wall and mesentery.</p><p>Ulcerative colitis: chronic inflammatory disorder of the colonic mucosa, usually beginning in the rectum and extending proximally in a continuous manner.</p><p>Crohn vs UC comparison: Crohn = any GI segment (mouth→anus), transmural, rectal bleeding rare, continuous pain, NOD2 link, IL-21→granzyme-B+ B cells. UC = colon/rectum, mucosa/submucosa, rectal bleeding characteristic, intermittent pain, elevated TNF-α, atypical Th2/NKT IL-4/IL-13.</p><p>OTHER DEFINING FEATURES. RA: symmetric inflammatory arthritis, typically older onset; ~40% have extra-articular disease (skin, eyes, lungs, heart, kidneys, vessels — including vasculitis with petechial hemorrhages). Vitiligo: patchy depigmentation of skin/hair (non-segmental = symmetric/bilateral, more common; segmental = one area); ~50% appear before age 20, and onset after 40 links to autoimmune thyroid disease. Guillain-Barré: acute, progressive, usually temporary ascending paralysis after an antecedent infection, with autonomic dysfunction (arrhythmia, respiratory failure) in two-thirds.</p><p>Rheumatoid arthritis: ~40% of patients have extra-articular symptoms — skin, eyes, lungs, heart, kidneys, salivary glands, blood vessels, bone marrow.</p><p>Vitiligo: melanocyte destruction → patchy depigmentation of skin and hair follicles; non-segmental (symmetric, more common) vs segmental (one area).</p><p>Guillain-Barré: acute, progressive, monophasic paralytic neuropathy after a causative infection (most often C. jejuni); autonomic dysfunction in two-thirds (ileus, arrhythmia, respiratory failure).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Crohn vs UC on three axes — location (Crohn anywhere mouth→anus / UC colon-rectum), depth (Crohn transmural / UC mucosa-submucosa), bleeding (Crohn rare / UC characteristic).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Rectal bleeding is the fast discriminator. Characteristic in UC, rare in Crohn. Pair it with &quot;continuous from the rectum, mucosa-only&quot; (UC) vs &quot;skip lesions, transmural, cobblestone&quot; (Crohn).</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Crohn = &quot;Cobblestone, full-thickness, anywhere.&quot; UC = &quot;continUous, colon-only, bleeds.&quot; NOD2 is associated with both (so it does not distinguish them).</p><p>ReClaude A: In Crohn disease the inflammation can occur anywhere from mouth to anus (often the ileocolic junction), is transmural (producing cobblestoning and strictures), and rarely causes rectal bleeding, with more continuous pain. Ulcerative colitis is confined to the colon and rectum, spreads continuously from the rectum, involves only mucosa/submucosa, and characteristically causes rectal bleeding with intermittent pain — so location, depth, and bleeding pattern separate them.</p><p><em>For AIHA, vitiligo, Crohn, and UC, which effector arm does the damage — and which detail distinguishes Crohn&#x27;s mechanism from UC&#x27;s?</em></p><p>AIHA — IgG vs IgM determines the death pathway. Autoantibodies against RBC antigens cause destruction two ways: IgG → mostly Fc-receptor-mediated opsonization by splenic macrophages (the Fc protrudes, macrophages grab it), though IgG can fix complement; IgM → mostly complement fixation → MAC lysis. Drug-induced AIHA works by haptenation (the drug — cephalosporins now most common, IV penicillin, methyldopa, insulin — binds the RBC → IgG → splenic opsonization). About half of AIHA is idiopathic; the rest is secondary (neoplasm, infection, RA/SLE, drugs).</p><p>AIHA: IgG → opsonization (splenic macrophages, FcγR); IgM → complement/MAC lysis. Drug-induced = haptenation → IgG → opsonization. RhoGAM context: anti-D IgG crosses placenta (HDN); ABO antibodies are IgM (don&#x27;t cross). (AIHA mechanism)</p><p>AIHA: antibodies against RBC membrane antigens (e.g. Rh) — autoantibodies (autoimmune) or alloantibodies received from a donor (alloimmune) — accelerate RBC removal/destruction.</p><p>AIHA: IgG autoantibodies → Fc-receptor-mediated opsonization in spleen/liver (can also fix complement); IgM autoantibodies → complement activation → MAC lysis (less common with IgG).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Drug-induced AIHA: haptenation of a drug to the RBC surface generates IgG → Fc-receptor-mediated opsonization by splenic macrophages. Common drugs: cephalosporins (most common now), IV penicillin, methyldopa, insulin.</p><p>VITILIGO — CTLs do the damage. A trigger makes melanocytes express altered self-antigens/DAMPs (heat-shock proteins) during apoptosis; APCs present these to CD4 and CD8 T cells. CD4 cells release pro-inflammatory cytokines and B cells make anti-melanocyte antibodies — but the main effector is the CD8+ CTL, permitted by downregulated regulatory T cells that normally restrain it. Guillain-Barré is anti-ganglioside molecular mimicry (post-C. jejuni), with γδ T cells prominent because the trigger is mucosal/GI.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Vitiligo: a trigger makes melanocytes express altered self-antigens and DAMPs (histones, ATP, uric acid, heat-shock proteins) during apoptosis; APCs present them to CD8 and CD4 T cells.</p><p>Vitiligo: B cells make anti-melanocyte antibodies and CD4 cells release pro-inflammatory cytokines, but CTLs are the MAIN effector damaging melanocytes (Tregs are downregulated, removing the brake).</p><p>Guillain-Barré mechanism: cross-reactive antibodies to a C. jejuni epitope (molecular mimicry) bind nerve cells; T cells, B cells, macrophages, and complement participate, with γδ T cells prominent. CROHN vs UC — the mechanistic split (the key INTEGRATE). Crohn disease: Th1/Th17-driven inflammation against luminal bacteria, with innate involvement — NOD2 mutations and MUC2 variants (less mucus) — overproduced IL-12/IL-23/IL-34/TNF-α, and a signature step: IL-21 converts B cells into granzyme-B-expressing (cytotoxic) B cells that damage the mucosa. Ulcerative colitis: an atypical Th2 response by non-classical NKT cells (recognize lipid on CD1) producing IL-4 and IL-13; IL-13 is cytotoxic to epithelium (apoptosis, disrupted tight junctions) and feeds back to amplify the NKT cells, while MadCAM-1 recruits leukocytes and TNF-α is elevated in blood/stool.</p><p>Crohn = Th1/Th17, NOD2/MUC2, IL-21→granzyme-B+ B cells. UC = atypical Th2 via non-classical NKT (IL-4/IL-13), IL-13 cytotoxic + self-amplifying, MadCAM-1, TNF-α elevated. (NOD2 is in both.) (Crohn vs UC mechanism)</p><p>Crohn disease: overproduced IL-12/IL-23/IL-34/TNF-α (IL-34 highest in active inflammation); IL-21 converts B cells into granzyme-B-expressing cytotoxic B cells that damage the intestinal mucosa.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Ulcerative colitis: reduced mucin, disrupted tight junctions; atypical Th2 response by non-classic NKT cells producing IL-4 and IL-13; IL-13 is cytotoxic to epithelium (apoptosis, altered tight junctions).</p><p>UC: pro-inflammatory cytokines upregulate adhesion molecules like MadCAM-1 on mucosal vessels, capturing leukocytes and promoting extravasation — perpetuating the inflammatory cycle.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One effector per disease: AIHA = IgG opsonization / IgM complement; vitiligo = CD8 CTL; GBS = anti-ganglioside antibody (γδ T cells); Crohn = Th1/Th17 + granzyme-B+ B cells; UC = atypical Th2/NKT (IL-4/IL-13).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Crohn vs UC mechanism: Th1/Th17 + NOD2 + IL-21→granzyme-B+ B cells = Crohn; atypical Th2 via non-classical NKT (IL-4/IL-13, IL-13 cytotoxic) = UC. The Th-bias flips between the two.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> AIHA isotype rule reuses the antibody-valence logic: IgG (2 arms) → opsonization; IgM (pentamer, complement-efficient) → MAC lysis. Same rule explains why ABO (IgM) doesn&#x27;t cross the placenta but anti-D (IgG) does.</p><p>ReClaude A: AIHA: IgG drives Fc-receptor opsonization by splenic macrophages while IgM fixes complement for MAC lysis. Vitiligo: CD8 CTLs are the main effector (Tregs downregulated), despite CD4 cytokines and anti-melanocyte antibodies. Crohn disease is Th1/Th17-driven with NOD2/MUC2 variants and IL-21-induced granzyme-B+ cytotoxic B cells; ulcerative colitis is an atypical Th2 response via non-classical NKT cells making IL-4/IL-13 (IL-13 cytotoxic to epithelium) with MadCAM-1 recruitment — so the Th-bias and signature cells distinguish the two IBDs.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "23_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Across these diseases, how do the DMARD classes, the anti-TNF-α biologics, and the antibody-removal therapies each work?</em></p><p>NOTE ON DRUG NAMES. Davis stated plainly that only the generic name is tested (as on boards) — trade names appear here only in parentheses. So learn the mechanism + generic, not the brand.</p><p>THE RA / IBD LADDER. Conventional DMARDs (methotrexate, hydroxychloroquine) are first-line oral anti-inflammatories. &quot;-nib&quot; small molecules (tofacitinib) are oral JAK inhibitors that block T-cell (and downstream B-cell) activation. &quot;-mab&quot; biologics are injectable monoclonal antibodies, usually anti-cytokine: adalimumab/infliximab bind the TNF-α cytokine directly; etanercept is a soluble TNF-α receptor decoy; tocilizumab blocks the IL-6 receptor. For IBD the same logic applies (anti-TNF-α and related biologics). Vitiligo adds JAK inhibitors (ruxolitinib) and calcineurin inhibitors (block IL-2 → suppress T-cell activation).</p><p>DMARDs (methotrexate/hydroxychloroquine, oral, first-line) → JAK inhibitors (-nib, oral) → biologics (-mab, injectable): anti-TNF-α antibodies bind the cytokine; etanercept = soluble receptor decoy; tocilizumab blocks IL-6R. (treatment ladder + mechanisms) ANTIBODY-REMOVAL THERAPIES (Guillain-Barré). Because GBS is antibody-mediated: plasmapheresis (plasma exchange physically removes autoantibodies), IVIg (pooled nonspecific antibody that clogs Fc receptors and dilutes the autoantibody effect), and anti-inflammatory corticosteroids.</p><p>Guillain-Barré treatment: plasmapheresis (removes autoantibodies), IVIg (pooled antibody dilutes/blocks autoantibodies), and anti-inflammatory corticosteroids.</p><p>Vitiligo treatment: corticosteroids (control inflammation), JAK inhibitors (ruxolitinib), and calcineurin inhibitors (disrupt IL-2 transcription → block T-cell activation/proliferation).</p><p>RA treatment: conventional DMARDs (methotrexate, hydroxychloroquine); &quot;-nib&quot; small-molecule JAK inhibitors (tofacitinib); &quot;-mab&quot; biologics — adalimumab/infliximab bind TNF-α, etanercept is a soluble TNF-α receptor, tocilizumab blocks IL-6R.</p><p>ReClaude A: Treatment escalates from conventional DMARDs (methotrexate, hydroxychloroquine — oral, first-line) to &quot;-nib&quot; JAK inhibitors (oral) to &quot;-mab&quot; biologics (injectable): anti-TNF-α antibodies (adalimumab, infliximab) bind the TNF-α cytokine, etanercept is a soluble TNF-α receptor decoy, and tocilizumab blocks the IL-6 receptor. For antibody-mediated Guillain-Barré, plasmapheresis removes autoantibodies, IVIg dilutes/blocks them, and corticosteroids reduce inflammation.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "24_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A neonate has truncus arteriosus, hypocalcemic seizures, dysmorphic facies, and &lt;1% CD3 with normal B cells — what is it, and why are vaccine antibodies low?</em></p><p>THE PRESENTATION + LABS. A term neonate with low birth weight develops feeding difficulty, cyanosis, and a severe heart defect (truncus arteriosus), then seizures at 4 days. Dysmorphic facies (low-set ears, small &quot;fish mouth,&quot; undersized jaw). Labs: low calcium, very low PTH, severe T-cell lymphopenia (CD3+ &lt;1%), and normal CD19+ B cells. This is DiGeorge syndrome, a 22q11.2 deletion affecting structures from that region: the heart (truncus arteriosus), the parathyroids (low PTH → hypocalcemia → seizures, which is why the seizures are metabolic, not neurologic — a normal neuro exam and no response to anti-epileptics), and the thymus.</p><p>LOCALIZING THE DEFECT. CD3 marks all mature T cells, so CD3 &lt;1% with normal B cells localizes the problem to the thymus: thymic aplasia/hypoplasia prevents T-cell maturation, and because both CD4 and CD8 lineages mature in the thymus, both are reduced. The marrow is fine, so B cells are normal. (X-ray shows an absent or small thymic shadow.)</p><p>DiGeorge = 22q11.2 deletion → heart (truncus arteriosus) + parathyroid (low PTH → hypocalcemic seizures) + thymus (CD3 &lt;1%, both CD4 &amp; CD8 low). B cells normal. (DiGeorge diagnosis)</p><p>Case 4: dysmorphic facial features — low-set ears, small &quot;fish mouth,&quot; undersized lower jaw; very low/absent vaccine antibodies.</p><p>Case 4 labs: low calcium (6.2 mg/dL), very low PTH, severe T-cell lymphopenia (CD3 &lt;1%), normal naive CD19+ B cells.</p><p>Case 4 presentation: term neonate with low birth weight, feeding difficulty, cyanosis, severe heart defect (truncus arteriosus), and seizures at 4 days of age.</p><p>WHY LOW VACCINE ANTIBODIES (the recurring CD4-help thread). Even with normal B cells, antibody titers are low because there is no CD4+ T-cell help to drive B cells into plasma cells — the same &quot;no CD4 help → no antibody&quot; logic that explains why BLS-I (which keeps CD4) makes good vaccine antibody but DiGeorge does not. MANAGEMENT: thymic transplant is the definitive long-term fix (restoring T-cell development); supportive IVIg (compensating for absent CD4-dependent antibody), prophylactic antibiotics, and inactivated vaccines bridge until transplant.</p><p>Case 4 management: prophylactic antibiotics, IVIg, thymic transplant (the definitive solution for the T-cell defect), and inactivated vaccines.</p><p>Case 4 diagnosis: DiGeorge syndrome (22q11.2 deletion) — the deleted region governs heart and parathyroid development; low PTH → low calcium → seizures. Vaccine antibodies are low from lack of CD4 help.</p><p>Case 4 course: at 6 months still below normal weight and behind on milestones; neuro exam normal with no CNS inflammation — confirming the seizures were metabolic (hypocalcemia), not neurologic.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> DiGeorge is the T-cell case: 22q11.2 deletion → cardiac (truncus arteriosus) + parathyroid (low PTH/Ca → seizures) + thymic aplasia (CD3 &lt;1%, both CD4 and CD8). B cells normal.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Low antibody despite normal B cells = no CD4 help. This is why DiGeorge has LOW vaccine titers but BLS-I (CD4 intact) has HIGH ones — the same rule, opposite outcomes.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Metabolic seizures: hypocalcemia from low PTH, with a normal neuro exam and no response to anti-epileptics. The definitive fix is a thymic transplant; IVIg/antibiotics bridge to it.</p><p>ReClaude A: The neonate has DiGeorge syndrome: a 22q11.2 deletion produces the cardiac (truncus arteriosus), parathyroid (low PTH → hypocalcemia → seizures), and thymic (aplasia → CD3 &lt;1%, both CD4 and CD8 low; normal B cells) triad. Vaccine antibodies are low because, without CD4 help, normal B cells still cannot be driven to make antibody — the inverse of BLS-I, which keeps CD4 and makes antibody well. Thymic transplant is the definitive treatment, with IVIg and antibiotics as a bridge.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_1": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Name the two branches of the immune system and give the single defining feature that separates them.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Davis opens the whole course from 30,000 feet, and the single idea she wants you to carry out of this lecture is that the immune system is built in two branches — the innate system at the top of Dr. Gregg’s master figure and the adaptive (also called acquired) system at the bottom. Almost everything in the next fifteen-odd lectures hangs off this one split, so the goal here is to install the scaffolding, not to memorize details you haven’t earned yet.</p><p>The purpose of the whole apparatus is narrower than it sounds: prevent or control infection, and patrol for things that shouldn’t be there. Davis makes the point vividly — 100% of us have a tumor right now, and almost none of us will ever need treatment for it, because the immune system clears it before it declares itself. That patrol-and-clear job is carried out by cells, organs, tissues, and molecules working together, which is the cast of characters the rest of the course introduces one at a time.</p><p>The two branches of immunity are innate and adaptive (acquired). (branch dichotomy — the course spine)</p><p>Every response is two activities: recognize that something is non-self, THEN respond to it.</p><p>Role of the immune system: defense against infection and tumors, immunosurveillance, and the autoimmunity/transplant flip side.</p><p>Layering — within each branch there are multiple means of protection (barriers, enzymes) and effector mechanisms.</p><p>TWO ACTIVITIES, IN ORDER. Before any branch can do anything, the response has to clear a two-step bar. First, recognize that something is non-self — distinguish “us” from “them.” Then respond to it, whether that means an innate response or an adaptive one. Hold onto the order, because it explains the system’s two failure modes: fail to recognize non-self and you get infection; mistakenly react against self and you get autoimmunity. The same recognition machinery that protects you is the thing that, turned the wrong way, attacks you.</p><p>LAYERING AND REDUNDANCY. Davis keeps returning to the word layering: within each branch there are multiple, overlapping ways to fight the same pathogen. Staphylococcus aureus is her running example — it causes skin infections, pneumonia, osteomyelitis, even meningitis, so the body needs different defenses in different tissues that can all recognize and clear it. That redundancy is deliberate: a defense available in the skin (say, the oxidative burst) may not be available across the blood–brain barrier, so the system layers physical barriers, enzymes, effector mechanisms, cells, and molecules so that something can respond wherever the pathogen lands.</p><p>An immune response has two steps in fixed order: recognize non-self, then respond. (recognition precedes response) CQ Failure to recognize non-self → infection; reaction against self → autoimmunity. (the two failure modes)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The innate/adaptive split is the organizing axis of the entire course. Map every later cell, molecule, and pathway onto “which branch, and what does it do there.”</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> “Two branches” = innate vs adaptive. It does NOT mean humoral vs cell-mediated (that’s a split WITHIN adaptive) or cells vs molecules (a component split).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> “100% of us have a tumor right now” — immunosurveillance runs constantly; you only need clinical help when a tumor escapes it. A memorable anchor for why the system patrols, not just defends.</p><p>ReClaude A: The two branches are innate (fast, generic, no memory) and adaptive/acquired (slow on first exposure, antigen-specific, memory-forming). They are defined by speed, specificity, and the presence or absence of memory — not by anatomy or by the cells-vs-molecules split.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_2": {
  "answer": "<p><em>For speed, specificity, and memory, which branch owns which property — and why does &quot;specific&quot; not mean &quot;fast&quot;?</em></p><p>THE CONTRAST. If LO 1.1 named the two branches, this LO is about telling them apart on the dimensions that actually get tested: specificity, speed, memory, and what does the recognizing. Davis’s framing device is military — innate is a grenade (generic, hits everything in the vicinity, causes collateral damage), adaptive is a sniper or marksman (one precise target). That single image carries most of the distinction, and the collateral-damage half of it is where immunopathology comes from.</p><p>Innate immunity: rapid but generalized — acts within minutes to hours on the first encounter.</p><p>Innate = the grenade: non-specific, present at birth, always on, responds to conserved PAMPs, no memory.</p><p>Adaptive = the sniper: specific and targeted, acquired on encounter, improves and remembers — but slower.</p><p>HOW EACH BRANCH RECOGNIZES. This is the heart of the distinction. Innate immunity reads conserved patterns, not identities. Faced with a gram-negative Klebsiella, the innate system does not say “Klebsiella” — it says “I see LPS, and LPS isn’t human, so this is non-self.” The same goes for teichoic acid on gram-positives and mannose on fungi. These conserved structures are pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs), and the receptors that read them are pattern-recognition receptors (PRRs). So the rule is short: PRRs recognize PAMPs, and the answer they return is always generic — “bacterium” or “fungus,” never the species. Adaptive immunity, by contrast, recognizes the specific pathogen through B-cell and T-cell receptors, so only the cells that match that pathogen respond.</p><p>Innate PRRs recognize conserved PAMPs (LPS, teichoic acid, mannose) and report non-self/bacterium, never the species. (PRR–PAMP recognition)</p><p>BORN WITH IT vs ACQUIRING IT. You are born with your innate defenses — skin, tears, mucus, lysozyme — and they are always on at basal levels. The adaptive system is called acquired precisely because you are immunologically naive to a given pathogen until you encounter it; only then do you develop (acquire) immunity to it. This is why the flu shot is annual: the virus undergoes antigenic drift, so last year’s acquired immunity no longer matches, and the vaccine must be updated. The textbook calls it adaptive for a second reason — it gets better with each exposure, a point Dr. Gregg will unpack when he covers how antibodies improve over a response.</p><p>THE TIMING PAYOFF — MEMORY. The crown jewel of the adaptive branch is the memory cell. A primary (first-time) adaptive response takes about 7–10 days to develop — far too slow to be your only defense, which is exactly why innate has to act first and buy time. But once memory cells exist, a re-exposure is handled in about 2–3 days (the anamnestic response). That is the entire logic of vaccination: manufacture memory now so the real encounter is fast. Memory is faster than a primary response but still never as instant as the always-ready innate barriers — your skin is already there.</p><p>Primary adaptive response ≈ 7–10 days; memory (anamnestic) response ≈ 2–3 days; innate is faster still (already present). (the timing hierarchy) CQ Annual flu vaccination is needed because influenza undergoes antigenic drift. (why “acquired” immunity must be updated)</p><p>Representative PAMPs by class — nucleic acids, cell-wall lipids (LPS, teichoic acid), carbohydrates (mannose). Conserved, non-self, broadly shared.</p><p>Clonal expansion: one antigen-specific naive cell proliferates into many identical clones — one cell isn’t enough.</p><p>Clones differentiate into effector cells (act now, terminal) and memory cells (persist, re-activatable).</p><p>CLONAL EXPANSION AND THE EFFECTOR/MEMORY SPLIT. Here is the mechanical core of how the specific branch scales up. A naive lymphocyte (one that has never seen its pathogen) carries an antigen receptor; when that receptor finds its match, the cell undergoes clonal expansion (also called clonal proliferation) — it makes many copies of itself, all with the same specificity, because one B cell making antibody is not enough when you need billions of molecules. The expanded clones then differentiate into two fates: effector cells that do the job right now (and are terminally differentiated — they act, then die by apoptosis) and memory cells that persist, sometimes for decades, ready to re-activate. Every time you re-encounter the antigen, you remake both — so you always keep a memory bank for the next round.</p><p>HUMORAL vs CELL-MEDIATED. The adaptive branch itself splits in two by where the pathogen lives. Humoral immunity — antibodies made by plasma cells — handles extracellular threats. Davis’s room analogy is worth keeping: if the cell is this room and the hallway is outside it, antibody can stick to anything in the hallway but cannot pass through the wall. Cell-mediated immunity — cytotoxic T cells — handles intracellular threats like viruses, which must live inside a host cell to replicate. Critically, the T cell does not reach inside and kill the virus; it kills the infected host cell, and the pathogen dies with it. The kill is indirect — a point the exam loves.</p><p>Humoral immunity (antibody/plasma cells) = extracellular pathogens; cell-mediated immunity (cytotoxic T cells) = intracellular pathogens. (the where-it-lives split) CQ Cytotoxic T cells kill the infected host cell, not the pathogen directly. (indirect kill — high-yield)</p><p>Innate vs adaptive at a glance: non-specific/specific, rapid/slow, no-memory/memory, PAMP-sensing cells vs lymphocytes.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Specificity, speed, and memory are the three axes that separate the branches. Innate = generic, fast, no memory. Adaptive = specific, slow-then-fast, memory.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Do NOT equate “specific” with “fast.” Adaptive is the specific one but the SLOW one on first encounter (7–10 days). Innate leads because it’s already on.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Pathogen inside a cell (virus) → think cell-mediated (CTL kills the host cell). Pathogen outside (extracellular bacterium, toxin) → think humoral (antibody neutralizes/opsonizes).</p><p>ReClaude A: Innate is generic (PRRs read conserved PAMPs, returning “non-self,” never the species), fast, present at birth, and memoryless. Adaptive is antigen-specific (BCR/TCR recognize the exact target), slow on first exposure (7–10 days) but fast on recall via memory (2–3 days), and improves with each encounter. Grenade vs sniper.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_3": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Give one way innate signaling shapes the adaptive response and one way adaptive output redirects innate cells.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This is the conceptual heart of the lecture: the two branches do not act in a vacuum. They talk to each other constantly, in both directions, using secreted molecules — chiefly cytokines and complement — as the language. One branch tells the other “here’s what we’ve got, here’s what I need you to do.” Getting the direction of each example right (innate→adaptive vs adaptive→innate) is exactly what the exam tests, so we’ll keep flagging which way the arrow points.</p><p>WHO GOES FIRST. On a first-ever (naive) encounter, the innate system always responds first, and the adaptive system follows only if the innate response can’t contain the pathogen. The reason is timing: a primary adaptive response needs 7–10 days, and “we’d be sick and dying all the time” if that were our first line. Innate is the right-there, ready-to-go response that buys the days adaptive needs. The one twist: on a re-exposure, adaptive memory can effectively lead, then recruit innate — so “innate first” is a first-encounter rule, not an absolute.</p><p>On a naive encounter, innate responds first; adaptive follows (7–10 days) only if innate fails to contain the pathogen. (innate-first timing)</p><p>Dr. Gregg’s master figure — innate at top, adaptive at bottom; the through-line for the first ~15 lectures.</p><p>Inflammation is initiated in the innate response and can carry over into the adaptive response; it both clears and contains pathogens.</p><p>The two branches do not act in isolation — innate generally responds first and then informs/regulates the adaptive response.</p><p>IMMUNOPATHOLOGY — WHEN THE GRENADE HURTS YOU. Before the directional examples, anchor the cost side. When you have the flu and feel achy, feverish, and chilled, that is not the bug — that is your immune system. The body aches and fever are your cytokines at work; the inflammation that clears pathogens also damages your own tissue, and that damage is immunopathology. Davis notes you’ll meet it again throughout pathology — a great deal of organ damage in disease is the immune response, not the pathogen. Even fever is a deliberate immune tactic: pathogens grow best at 37°C, so raising body temperature slows their replication — the same logic as a refrigerator slowing food spoilage — buying the adaptive system time to catch up.</p><p>Flu malaise (aches, fever, chills) is host cytokine activity — immunopathology, not direct viral damage. (“that’s not the bug”) CQ Fever slows pathogen replication (optimal growth ≈ 37°C), buying the adaptive response time. (fever ≈ refrigerator analogy)</p><p>INNATE REGULATES ADAPTIVE. Now the first arrow. Innate outputs shape the adaptive response in two concrete ways. First, complement proteins can activate B cells — they lower the B-cell activation threshold, so less antigen is needed to switch a B cell on. Second, phagocytes (macrophages, neutrophils) and infected cells secrete cytokines that direct which way B and T cells differentiate — whether a CD4 cell becomes a TH1, TH2, or TH17, and which antibody isotype a B cell should make (IgA in the mucosa, IgG in tissue). In other words, the innate response doesn’t just buy time; it instructs the adaptive response on what to become.</p><p>ADAPTIVE REGULATES INNATE. The reverse arrow runs whether it’s a first encounter or a memory response. T cells produce cytokines that order macrophages and neutrophils to be more aggressive — “you’re not killing fast enough, ramp it up.” And antibodies bound to a pathogen act as handles: macrophages and neutrophils (innate cells) grab those antibody handles to phagocytose and destroy the pathogen by oxidative burst. So the specific branch reaches back and makes the generic branch both harder-hitting and better-aimed. The whole point: the branches form one integrated, mutually-regulating system, not two parallel machines.</p><p>Innate→adaptive: complement lowers the B-cell activation threshold; innate cytokines steer B/T differentiation and isotype. (direction: innate regulates adaptive) CQ Adaptive→innate: antibody handles let phagocytes grab pathogens; T-cell cytokines push macrophages to kill harder. (direction: adaptive regulates innate)</p><p>The innate response can inform and regulate the adaptive response, and vice versa — a two-way regulatory loop.</p><p>Innate regulates adaptive: complement activates B cells; innate-cell cytokines guide B/T activation and differentiation.</p><p>Adaptive regulates innate: T-cell cytokines boost phagocyte killing; antibodies opsonize — “handles” for phagocytes.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The branches form one integrated system that regulates itself in BOTH directions. The exam tests which way the arrow points, so tag every example innate→adaptive or adaptive→innate.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Fever as a refrigerator: pathogens grow best at body temp, so a fever slows them like a fridge slows spoilage — immunopathology that’s actually working for you.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Innate→adaptive = complement activating B cells + innate cytokines steering differentiation. Adaptive→innate = antibody opsonization + T-cell cytokines driving phagocytes. Don’t flip them.</p><p>ReClaude A: Innate→adaptive: complement proteins activate B cells and lower their activation threshold, and innate cytokines direct B/T differentiation and antibody isotype. Adaptive→innate: T-cell cytokines make phagocytes more aggressive, and antibody bound to a pathogen opsonizes it, giving phagocytes handles to grab. The two branches continuously regulate each other.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_4": {
  "answer": "<p><em>How does the defensin mechanism differ from the lysozyme mechanism?</em></p><p>THE UNIFYING IDEA. Almost every chemical barrier in this lecture kills the same cheap way: it disrupts or perforates the membrane, and then ordinary physiologic fluid shifts do the rest by osmotic lysis. Gregg keeps returning to this — “you just create a pore and a cell lyses” — because it explains why so much of innate immunity (defensins, cathelicidins, fatty acids, and later the complement MAC) converges on pore formation: it is low-energy, you let chemistry finish the kill. Lysozyme is the one enzymatic exception, and it is the one he says shows up on boards constantly.</p><p>DEFENSINS. Defensins are antimicrobial peptides (AMPs). In the gut they are produced largely by Paneth cells in the intestinal crypts at a constitutive basal level (epithelial cells and neutrophils can be induced to make more). For the exam, the one thing to lock down is the mechanism: defensins create pores in microbial membranes. Once the pore is open the microbe cannot control fluid movement, and osmotic lysis follows. Gregg said it almost verbatim — what you need to know for the exam is that they create pores.</p><p>Defensins (Paneth cells, constitutive) kill by creating pores in membranes → osmotic lysis. (defensin mechanism — exam-flagged)</p><p>Defensins (AMPs) from Paneth cells insert into the microbial membrane and form pores; loss of fluid control → osmotic lysis.</p><p>Lysozyme hydrolyzes the β(1–4) bond between NAM and NAG in peptidoglycan, weakening the wall so the cell lyses.</p><p>Other chemical barriers: phospholipase A2, cathelicidins (LL-37), lactic/fatty acids, lactoferrin/transferrin (iron), and HCl.</p><p>LYSOZYME — the board favorite. Lysozyme is the enzyme in saliva, tears, and mucus that targets peptidoglycan. It hydrolyzes the linkage between N-acetylmuramic acid (NAM) and N-acetylglucosamine (NAG), the repeating backbone of the wall. Weaken peptidoglycan and the cell can no longer resist its own osmotic pressure, so it lyses. Because gram-positives carry thick, exposed peptidoglycan, they are the most susceptible; gram-negatives have peptidoglycan too, but it sits behind an outer membrane. Gregg flagged this one specifically — it is one he sees on the board exam all the time.</p><p>Lysozyme hydrolyzes the NAM–NAG bond in peptidoglycan; gram-positives (thick exposed wall) are most susceptible. (lysozyme target + mechanism)</p><p>THE REST OF THE CHEMICAL TOOLKIT. Phospholipase A2 clips a fatty acid off membrane phospholipids, distorting the membrane toward a leaky micelle and also generating the very fatty acids that coat skin. Cathelicidins (the human one is LL-37, a 37-amino-acid peptide) do the same membrane-disrupting, micelle-forming job, concentrated in mucosa. Lactic and fatty acids in sebaceous and sweat secretions disrupt membranes and even limit bacterial conjugation (plasmid transfer), slowing the spread of resistance. Lactoferrin (secretions/tissue) and transferrin (blood) lock up iron, a nutrient bacteria depend on — driving a literal arms race where bacteria deploy siderophores to steal iron back and the host counters with “stealth siderophores.” And hydrochloric acid in the stomach wrecks the structure of anything swallowed.</p><p>Lactoferrin/transferrin sequester iron; bacteria counter with siderophores, host counters with stealth siderophores. (iron arms race)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Defensins make pores; lysozyme is an enzyme that cleaves the NAM–NAG peptidoglycan bond. Different mechanism, different target — don’t blur “antimicrobial peptide” with “wall enzyme.”</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> The recurring innate killing motif is membrane perforation/disruption → osmotic lysis. Defensins, cathelicidins/LL-37, fatty acids, and the complement MAC all use it; lysozyme is the enzymatic exception.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Two board-flagged items live here: lysozyme (“on the board exam all the time”) and the pore principle. If a stem describes peptidoglycan-bond cleavage, think lysozyme; if it describes membrane pores, think defensins/AMPs.</p><p>ReClaude A: Defensins form pores in the membrane (osmotic lysis); lysozyme is an enzyme that cleaves the NAM–NAG peptidoglycan bond (most effective against gram-positives). One perforates the membrane, the other digests the wall — both end in osmotic lysis.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_5": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What are complement’s three functions, and which complement defect causes recurrent Neisseria?</em></p><p>THE THREE FUNCTIONS. Everything complement does sorts into three jobs, and Gregg wants them cold: lysis (kill the microbe outright), opsonization (tag it for phagocytes), and inflammation (recruit the cells that do the killing). They work hand in hand — inflame to bring in phagocytes, opsonize so those phagocytes can grab on, and lyse what you can directly. The two phagocytes that get recruited are the same ones from micro: neutrophils and macrophages.</p><p>Complement’s three functions: lysis (MAC), opsonization (C3b/CR1), inflammation (C3a/C5a). (three functions — memorize)</p><p>OPSONIZATION NEEDS A RECEPTOR. Coating a microbe in C3b only matters because phagocytes carry complement receptor 1 (CR1), which is essentially a C3b receptor. CR1 binds the surface C3b, giving the cell a handle to engulf the organism into a phagosome that fuses with a lysosome. Gregg defines it crisply — opsonization is enhancing phagocytosis through the complement system. This is exactly why encapsulated bacteria are complement-dependent: a capsule exists to mask the surface so phagocytes have nothing to grab; C3b deposited on the capsule restores a handle. The C3a released during cleavage is the chemotactic signal pulling neutrophils and macrophages in.</p><p>Opsonization = C3b coats the microbe and phagocyte CR1 binds it → why encapsulated bacteria depend on complement. (C3b/CR1 + capsule logic)</p><p>Macrophage CR1 (C3b receptor) binds surface-bound C3b on the bacterium, driving complement-mediated phagocytosis (opsonization).</p><p>The phagosome fuses with a lysosome; H+ pumped in lowers the pH and activates hydrolytic enzymes that destroy the microbe.</p><p>Adding one C3b to C3bBb makes the C5 convertase (C3bBb3b), which cleaves C5 → C5a (chemotaxis) + C5b (seeds the MAC).</p><p>LYSIS — THE MEMBRANE ATTACK COMPLEX. The C5 convertase (C3bBb3b) cleaves C5 into C5a (a potent chemoattractant, even stronger than C3a) and C5b, which stays near the surface and seeds the terminal cascade. The assembly order is pure recruitment, only one cleavage having happened: C5b → C6 → C7 (C7 inserts into the membrane and anchors the complex) → C8 (solidifies the insertion) → C9, which polymerizes into a pore. Pores again — fluid rushes in and out and the cell dies by osmotic lysis, the free kill. That terminal C5b–C9 structure is the membrane attack complex (MAC).</p><p>MAC assembles C5b→C6→C7 (membrane insertion)→C8→C9 (polymerizes into the lytic pore). (MAC order)</p><p>Membrane attack complex: C5b–C8 anchors the complex; polymerized C9 forms the transmembrane pore → osmotic lysis.</p><p>C3a/C5a as anaphylatoxins: locally recruit neutrophils/macrophages and activate mast cells to promote inflammation.</p><p>Complement-deficiency table: terminal (C5–C9/MAC) defects → recurrent Neisseria; early defects → broad encapsulated-organism susceptibility.</p><p>NEISSERIA, AND THE ANAPHYLATOXIN PARALLEL. The deficiency table has one board-critical row: a defect anywhere in C5–C9 wrecks the MAC and gives recurrent Neisseria meningitidis — Gregg says remember that for boards, because the MAC is the primary way you kill meningococcus. Separately, C3a and C5a are anaphylatoxins: locally they recruit phagocytes and activate mast cells (which sit around blood</p><p>vessels) to release histamine and drive inflammation. Let them go systemic and you activate mast cells body-wide → vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, adhesion-molecule upregulation → anaphylactic shock. That is the same three-effect vascular collapse TNF-α produces in septic shock (LPS-driven) — different trigger, identical hemodynamics, and a comparison worth holding onto for Lec 3.</p><p>A C5–C9 (MAC) defect → recurrent Neisseria meningitidis. (terminal-complement board flag) CQ Systemic C3a/C5a → mast-cell histamine → anaphylactic shock (same triad as TNF-α septic shock). (anaphylatoxin ↔ septic-shock parallel)</p><p>Anaphylactic shock: systemic mast-cell activation → vasodilation, capillary leak, bronchoconstriction → hypotension and airway compromise.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three functions, three mediators: lysis = MAC (C5b–C9), opsonization = C3b–CR1, inflammation = C3a/C5a. Anchor every complement detail to which of these three it serves.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Terminal (C5–C9 / MAC) deficiency → recurrent Neisseria. Don’t default to “C3” for this stem — early-component loss gives broad encapsulated-organism problems, not the meningococcal signature.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Anaphylatoxin shock (C3a/C5a) and septic shock (TNF-α) converge on the SAME three vascular effects. If a stem lists vasodilation + capillary leak + adhesion upregulation, identify the trigger, not a new mechanism.</p><p>ReClaude A: Lysis (the MAC, C5b–C9 forming a pore), opsonization (C3b bound by phagocyte CR1), and inflammation (C3a/C5a recruiting neutrophils/macrophages and activating mast cells). The cells involved are neutrophils and macrophages (phagocytes) and mast cells (anaphylatoxin targets).</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_6": {
  "answer": "<p><em>How do the early regulators (DAF vs MCP/factor H) differ from the late one (CD59)?</em></p><p>THE UNIFYING IDEA. Complement runs spontaneously on every surface, so the question that keeps you alive is: why doesn’t it destroy your own cells? The answer is a panel of host-cell regulators that either decay the convertase or block the MAC. Two jobs at once: protect self, and ration C3 so amplification doesn’t exhaust it. Lose these regulators and the failure is not weaker defense — it is self-lysis.</p><p>EARLY REGULATORS — DAF and MCP (and factor H/I). On host surfaces, DAF (decay-accelerating factor) dissociates Bb from the convertase, decaying C3bBb so it stops cleaving C3. MCP (membrane cofactor protein) works differently — it is a cofactor that recruits factor I to cleave the surface C3b. (Soluble factor H does the H-side of the same job in fluid phase, again with factor I.) The distinction is the testable point: DAF decays the enzyme; MCP/factor H recruit factor I to cleave C3b. A student asked whether C3b inactivated by DAF can still opsonize — Gregg’s answer: DAF acts so early (on the first convertase) that you never amplify enough C3a/C3b to actually recruit and feed phagocytes, so it dies down fast.</p><p>DAF dissociates Bb (decays the convertase); MCP/factor H recruit factor I to cleave C3b. (decay vs cofactor — distinguish)</p><p>Host regulators DAF and MCP on the human cell surface: DAF dissociates Bb; MCP recruits factor I to cleave C3b — stopping the convertase on self.</p><p>PNH: a GPI-anchor synthesis defect prevents DAF/CD59 from sitting on the RBC surface, so complement lyses the red cells.</p><p>LATE REGULATORS — blocking the MAC. If the cascade reaches C5b–C8 on a host cell, two more checkpoints stop the pore. CD59 (and HRF) block C9 from joining and polymerizing, so no pore forms. S-protein, clusterin, and factor J (three distinct proteins, three sites on C7) prevent C7 from anchoring the complex to the membrane in the first place. Five molecules total guard the terminal step on self.</p><p>CD59 blocks C9 from joining C5b-8 (no MAC pore) on host cells. (late-stage MAC regulator)</p><p>PNH AND FACTOR I DEFICIENCY — the two clinical mirrors. Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria (PNH) is the regulator-loss disease: a defect in GPI-anchor synthesis means DAF and CD59 cannot be tethered to the cell surface, so complement lyses the most numerous blood cells — red cells. The lesion is the missing anchor, not a missing complement protein. The other clinically loaded regulator is factor I: deficiency both depletes C3 (unchecked consumption) and blunts the antibody response, because factor I generates the C3b cleavage product C3d, and C3d lowers</p><p>the B-cell activation threshold. That is the promised payoff from LO 2.4 — lose factor I and you become highly susceptible to encapsulated bacteria from both a complement and an antibody direction.</p><p>PNH = GPI-anchor defect → no surface DAF/CD59 → complement lyses RBCs. (PNH mechanism) CQ Factor I deficiency → depleted C3 + blunted antibody response (no C3d to lower the B-cell threshold). (factor I → antibody link)</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> PNH is a GPI-anchor defect, not a missing complement component. The regulators (DAF, CD59) are present in the body but can’t attach, so the patient’s own complement lyses their RBCs.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Recurrent encapsulated-bacteria infection + low C3 + poor antibody response → think factor I deficiency (C3d link). Recurrent Neisseria alone → think terminal MAC (C5–C9).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Regulators do two jobs: protect host cells and ration C3. Sort them by stage — early (DAF decays Bb; MCP/factor H + factor I cleave C3b) vs late (CD59 blocks C9; S-protein/clusterin/factor J block C7).</p><p>ReClaude A: Early regulators act on the convertase — DAF dissociates Bb; MCP and factor H recruit factor I to cleave C3b. Late regulators block the MAC — CD59 stops C9 polymerizing; S-protein/clusterin/factor J block C7 anchoring. They protect host cells and ration C3; losing the GPI anchor for DAF/CD59 causes PNH.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_7": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Trace LPS recognition through to cytokine transcription, naming each molecule.</em></p><p>THE RECOGNITION COMPLEX. TLR4 doesn’t touch LPS directly — it needs accessory molecules. LBP (LPS-binding protein) grabs LPS and delivers it to CD14, which sits near the TLR4 homodimer. Then MD2 stabilizes the LPS on TLR4. That assembled complex (LPS·CD14·MD2·TLR4) changes the shape of TLR4’s cytoplasmic TIR domain, and the conformational change is what lets the adaptor MyD88 dock. Recognition is therefore a small committee, not a single handshake.</p><p>TLR4 recognizes LPS via accessories: LBP → CD14, with MD2 stabilizing LPS → TIR-domain change → MyD88 docks. (TLR4 recognition complex)</p><p>TLR signaling output: the NF-κB–induced cytokines that drive the inflammatory response.</p><p>LPS recognition by TLR4: LBP hands LPS to CD14; MD2 stabilizes it on the TLR4 homodimer, changing the TIR domain.</p><p>Signaling cascade: MyD88 → IKK → phosphorylates IκB → frees NF-κB → nucleus → cytokine transcription.</p><p>THE NF-κB CASCADE. Once MyD88 binds, the cascade is worth knowing as a clean chain: MyD88 → activates IKK (IκB kinase) → IKK phosphorylates IκB → phosphorylated IκB releases NF-κB. Free NF-κB, a cytoplasmic transcription factor, translocates through the nuclear pore, binds gene promoters, and drives cytokine production. The one inhibitor to keep straight is IκB — it holds NF-κB hostage until IKK phosphorylates it. The five cytokines this produces are the subject of LO 3.4: IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8, IL-12.</p><p>Cascade: MyD88 → IKK → phosphorylates IκB → releases NF-κB → cytokine transcription. (NF-κB cascade order)</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> If a stem gives “LPS recognition needs which helper molecules?” the answer set is LBP, CD14, MD2 (not a kinase, not a cytokine).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Read it as one inhibitor being removed: NF-κB is chained to IκB; IKK phosphorylates IκB, NF-κB is freed, cytokines get transcribed. This same cascade later triggers NLRP3.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> IKK (the kinase) phosphorylates IκB (the inhibitor). Students invert these or phosphorylate NF-κB itself — it’s IκB that gets phosphorylated and lets NF-κB go.</p><p>ReClaude A: LPS is presented by LBP→CD14 with MD2 stabilizing it on the TLR4 dimer, changing the TIR domain so MyD88 docks. Cascade: MyD88 → IKK → phosphorylates IκB → releases NF-κB → nucleus → transcription of IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8, IL-12.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_8": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Which cytokine drives the acute phase, and where do CRP, MBL, and SAA each route?</em></p><p>IL-6 REPROGRAMS THE LIVER. The acute-phase response is IL-6 telling hepatocytes to switch production: up with acute-phase proteins (pentraxins) and complement, down with transport proteins like albumin — more immune reactivity, less housekeeping. The three acute-phase proteins to know route into three different effector arms: C-reactive protein (CRP) → classical complement, mannose-binding lectin (MBL) → lectin complement, and serum amyloid A (SAA) → TLR signaling and phagocytosis. Pentraxins also flag apoptotic cells for clearance — a detail that returns with lupus, where faulty apoptotic-cell uptake matters.</p><p>IL-6 drives the acute phase: ↑ pentraxins (CRP, SAA, MBL) + complement, ↓ albumin. (acute-phase driver)</p><p>IL-1β (with IL-6, TNF-α) raises PGE2 → hypothalamic set point → fever; PGE2 also drives myalgia/arthralgia.</p><p>Acute-phase proteins: CRP → classical pathway, MBL → lectin pathway, SAA → TLR signaling/phagocytosis; albumin falls.</p><p>All three complement pathways (alternative, lectin, classical) converge on a C3 convertase and the membrane attack complex.</p><p>THE LECTIN PATHWAY. Once the acute phase is running, MBL becomes biologically meaningful (basal level is low). MBL complexes with the serine proteases MASP and binds surface mannose (and similar carbohydrates) on pathogens. MASP then cleaves C4 — C4b attaches to the surface (just as C3b did in the alternative pathway) — and cleaves C2. Here the nomenclature is deliberately confusing: the larger fragment is C2a. C2a binds C4b to form C4b2a, the classical C3 convertase. So the lectin pathway builds the classical convertase. From there it behaves like any C3 convertase: cleave C3, deposit C3b, and the presence of C3b lets the alternative pathway amplify alongside — two systems now spreading C3b together.</p><p>Lectin: MBL+MASP binds mannose → cleaves C4 (C4b attaches) + C2 → C4b2a = classical C3 convertase. (lectin pathway → C4b2a)</p><p>Lectin pathway: MBL+MASP binds mannose, cleaves C4 (C4b attaches) and C2 → C4b2a, the classical C3 convertase.</p><p>Classical pathway (innate-triggered here): CRP binds phosphocholine → recruits C1 → cleaves C4/C2 → the same C4b2a convertase.</p><p>THE CLASSICAL PATHWAY (innate-triggered). CRP closes the loop. CRP binds phosphocholine head groups on pathogen surfaces; bound CRP then recruits C1 (the C1q architecture plus serine proteases C1r/C1s, made by dendritic cells). C1 does exactly what MASP did: cleave C4 and C2 to build C4b2a, the classical C3 convertase — and everything proceeds to opsonization and the MAC. So three pathways, one convergence:</p><p>alternative (spontaneous, Lec 2), lectin (MBL→mannose), and classical (here, CRP→C1) all build a C3 convertase. The board-flagged corollary recurs: MBL or any complement deficiency → encapsulated-bacteria susceptibility, with terminal C5–C9 → Neisseria.</p><p>Classical (innate-triggered): CRP binds phosphocholine → C1 → C4/C2 cleavage → same C4b2a convertase. (classical via CRP/C1)</p><p>BAND NEUTROPHILS — the practical readout. Because IL-6 also drives neutrophil output, an overwhelming infection forces the marrow to release immature band neutrophils. Gregg’s rule: more than 5% bands means you are losing — the microbe is outpacing the response. It is the clinical “left shift,” and neutrophil elevations track bacterial infection.</p><p>&gt;5% band (immature) neutrophils = left shift = the infection is winning. (band-neutrophil rule)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> IL-6 is the acute-phase conductor. Route the three proteins: CRP → classical, MBL → lectin, SAA → TLR/phagocytosis — and remember lectin + classical both build C4b2a.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Watch the C2 nomenclature: the LARGER fragment is C2a, so the classical/lectin C3 convertase is C4b2a (not C4b2b). Different from the alternative pathway’s C3bBb.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> &gt;5% bands = you’re losing. A clean, testable readout of an overwhelming (usually bacterial) infection driven by IL-6 boosting neutrophil output.</p><p>ReClaude A: IL-6 drives the acute-phase response: hepatocytes make CRP (→ classical), MBL (→ lectin), and SAA (→ TLR/phagocytosis) while albumin falls. Lectin (MBL+MASP→mannose) and classical (CRP→C1) both cleave C4/C2 to build C4b2a, the classical C3 convertase. &gt;5% band neutrophils signals a losing infection.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_9": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Put the trafficking steps in order and name the board-flagged integrin/ligand pair.</em></p><p>THE THREE-STEP. Getting a blood leukocyte into infected tissue is a fixed sequence, and the cytokine-activated endothelium makes it possible. Step 1 — rolling: selectins on activated endothelium bind carbohydrate ligands on the leukocyte, a weak interaction that lets the cell tether and roll along the vessel wall, slowing down. Step 2 — firm arrest: a chemokine signal flips the leukocyte’s integrins to high-affinity, and they grip endothelial ligands to stop the cell. Step 3 — diapedesis: the arrested cell squeezes between endothelial cells (through the thinned tight junctions TNF-α loosened) into the tissue.</p><p>Trafficking: selectin rolling → integrin firm arrest → chemokine signal → diapedesis. (the three-step)</p><p>Step 1 — rolling: selectins on activated endothelium bind leukocyte carbohydrate ligands, a weak tether that slows the cell.</p><p>Step 2 — firm arrest: chemokines raise integrin affinity; LFA-1 binds ICAM-1 to stop the cell on the endothelium.</p><p>Step 3 — diapedesis: the arrested cell follows the chemokine gradient and transmigrates between endothelial cells into tissue.</p><p>THE BOARD PAIR. The integrin/ligand interaction to lock down is LFA-1 (on the leukocyte) binding ICAM-1 (on endothelium) — Gregg flags it as the one that shows up most on boards, with the bonus that ICAM-1 is also the rhinovirus receptor. The chemokine that activates integrins and arrests neutrophils is IL-8/CXCL8, made by the same macrophages. Neutrophils go first — they are 50–70% of blood leukocytes and arrive within about two hours — with monocytes and NK cells following. This three-step is previewed here and detailed as extravasation in Lec 4; the molecules (selectin/integrin/chemokine) are the takeaway.</p><p>Board pair: LFA-1 (leukocyte) → ICAM-1 (endothelium); ICAM-1 is also the rhinovirus receptor. (LFA-1/ICAM-1)</p><p>Summary table — the major innate cytokines (IL-1β, IL-6, TNF-α, IL-8, IL-12, type I IFN): releasing cell, target, and primary effects.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> LFA-1 → ICAM-1 is the board-flagged firm-arrest pair, and ICAM-1 is the rhinovirus receptor — a frequently tested two-for-one.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three molecules, three steps, in order: selectins (rolling) → integrins (arrest) → chemokine (activation/diapedesis). Neutrophils lead because they’re most abundant and fastest.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> If a stem describes weak, reversible tethering/rolling, that’s selectins; firm stop is integrins (LFA-1/ICAM-1); the cell then transmigrates (diapedesis).</p><p>ReClaude A: Selectins on activated endothelium mediate rolling (weak), chemokines (IL-8) then raise integrin affinity for firm arrest (LFA-1–ICAM-1), and the cell undergoes diapedesis into tissue. Neutrophils traffic first (most abundant, fastest), followed by monocytes and NK cells.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_10": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Trace the respiratory burst from NADPH oxidase to HOCl, naming each enzyme and product.</em></p><p>THE MOST IMPORTANT REACTIVITY OF THE SEMESTER. Gregg says it outright — phagocytosis is the single most important immune reactivity of the whole unit, and “everything is geared towards it.” The killing happens in two stages with a clear logic: paralyze first, then digest. Stage one is the respiratory burst (oxygen-dependent); stage two is acid digestion in the phagolysosome.</p><p>Phagocytosis logic: paralyze replication first (respiratory burst), then digest (acid hydrolases). (two-stage logic)</p><p>Late reactions: the vacuolar ATPase pumps H+ in to acidify the phagosome — required for the next step.</p><p>Phagosome–lysosome fusion delivers acid hydrolases (active at low pH) plus defensins and lysozyme to digest the microbe.</p><p>Early O2-dependent reactions (respiratory burst): NADPH oxidase → superoxide; SOD → H2O2; catalase → water; MPO → HOCl; iNOS → NO (RNS).</p><p>THE RESPIRATORY BURST. Once a microbe is in the phagosome, the cell takes a big breath of oxygen to fuel a cascade of reactive oxygen species (ROS). NADPH oxidase (phagocyte oxidase) makes superoxide (O2−); SOD converts it to H2O2; catalase detoxifies H2O2 to water, while myeloperoxidase (MPO) converts H2O2 to hypochlorous acid (HOCl) (bleach). Separately, iNOS makes nitric oxide and downstream</p><p>reactive nitrogen species (RNS). All of these damage nucleic acid — the point is to stop replication so the microbe can’t out-grow the response. (Clinically, NADPH-oxidase deficiency is the lesion behind chronic granulomatous disease — a good one to remember.)</p><p>ROS chain: NADPH oxidase→O2−; SOD→H2O2; catalase→water; MPO→HOCl; iNOS→NO (RNS). (respiratory-burst enzymes)</p><p>EVASION, AND THE IFN-γ COUNTER. Bacteria that live with oxygen carry the same protective enzymes. Staphylococcus is catalase-positive (and SOD-positive), so it detoxifies ROS and resists the early burst. The host’s answer is volume: NK-derived IFN-γ ramps ROS production to overwhelm the bacterium’s finite catalase/SOD — the macrophage–NK loop (LO 4.8). A second evasion is anatomical: Mycobacterium tuberculosis blocks phagosome acidification AND lysosome fusion, which is exactly why it survives inside macrophages.</p><p>Staph (catalase+) resists the burst; IFN-γ overwhelms it. M. tuberculosis blocks acidification + lysosome fusion. (evasion + counter)</p><p>ACIDIFY, THEN DIGEST. Before the lysosome fuses, the vacuolar ATPase pumps H+ into the phagosome to acidify it — critical, because the next step depends on low pH. The lysosome then fuses and delivers acid hydrolases (the “acid” means they work at low pH): nucleases, proteases, lipases, glycosidases — enough to dismantle every macromolecule of the now-paralyzed microbe — along with more defensins and lysozyme for good measure. No acidification, no digestion: that single dependency is what M. tuberculosis exploits.</p><p>Vacuolar ATPase acidifies the phagosome → acid hydrolases (low-pH nucleases/proteases/lipases) digest the microbe. (acidify → digest)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two stages, in order: burst (ROS/RNS) paralyzes the microbe by damaging nucleic acid; then acidification + acid hydrolases digest it. Memorize the ROS enzyme chain as the spine.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Keep the enzymes distinct: NADPH oxidase makes superoxide (deficiency → CGD); SOD → H2O2; catalase detoxifies H2O2; MPO → HOCl. Bacterial catalase/SOD is what blunts the burst.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Recurrent catalase-positive infections → think failed respiratory burst (NADPH-oxidase / CGD). A bug surviving inside macrophages by blocking acidification → M. tuberculosis.</p><p>ReClaude A: The respiratory burst (NADPH oxidase→superoxide; SOD→H2O2; catalase→water; MPO→HOCl; iNOS→NO/RNS) damages nucleic acid to paralyze replication. The vacuolar ATPase then acidifies the phagosome, and the fused lysosome delivers low-pH acid hydrolases (plus defensins/lysozyme) to digest the microbe. Paralyze first, then digest.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_11": {
  "answer": "<p><em>List the granules in developmental order and say why band neutrophils can kill but not migrate.</em></p><p>WHY GRANULES MAKE THE NEUTROPHIL SUPERIOR. Macrophages phagocytose and that’s it; the neutrophil is the premier phagocyte because it adds granules. Granule biology is organized around development: granules appear in a fixed order, and the order maps onto neutrophil maturity. Appearance order is azurophilic (primary) → specific (secondary) → gelatinase (tertiary) → secretory/ficolin. On activation, release runs the reverse, gated by intracellular calcium — highest calcium fires the secretory/ficolin granule first.</p><p>Development order: azurophilic → specific → gelatinase → secretory/ficolin; release reverses it (calcium-gated). (granule order)</p><p>Granule appearance maps to neutrophil maturity: azurophilic → specific → gelatinase → secretory/ficolin (bands lack the last).</p><p>First released (highest Ca2+): secretory/ficolin — supplies selectin ligands and integrins for adhesion/extravasation.</p><p>Last released (lowest Ca2+): azurophilic fuses with the phagolysosome — acid hydrolases, defensins, MPO (kept inside to protect host tissue).</p><p>RELEASE ORDER = FUNCTION. At activation (highest calcium) the secretory/ficolin granule fuses first, placing selectin ligands and integrins on the neutrophil surface for adhesion/extravasation. As calcium falls, gelatinase (MMP-9) is released to break down CD31 and loosen tight junctions for transit (arginase-1 then helps reseal the junctions behind it). Specific granules supply chemokine receptors (to follow the gradient) plus lactoferrin and NGAL (which blocks bacterial siderophores, denying iron). Finally azurophilic granules fuse with the phagolysosome — not the surface — delivering acid hydrolases, defensins, and MPO; keeping them internal protects host tissue.</p><p>Secretory/ficolin = adhesion (selectin ligands/integrins); azurophilic = phagolysosome killing (kept internal). (first vs last granule)</p><p>THE BAND-NEUTROPHIL DEFECT. This is the high-yield payoff. Band (immature) neutrophils stop at the gelatinase stage — they have not yet made the secretory/ficolin granule, so they lack the selectin ligands and integrins needed to roll and arrest. The consequence: bands can phagocytose and kill, but they can’t migrate out of the blood to where the microbe is. That is why a left shift (&gt;5% bands) signals trouble — the marrow is dumping cells that can’t reach the fight.</p><p>Band neutrophils stop at gelatinase → no secretory/ficolin → can kill but can’t migrate. (band-neutrophil defect)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Development = azurophilic→specific→gelatinase →secretory/ficolin; release reverses it. First out (secretory/ficolin) = adhesion molecules; last out (azurophilic) = phagolysosome killing.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Bands CAN kill — they just can’t migrate. The missing secretory/ficolin granule means no selectin ligands/integrins, so they’re stuck in the vessel. The defect is trafficking, not killing.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Azurophilic granules fuse with the phagolysosome, not the membrane — their toxic contents are kept internal to avoid damaging host tissue (frustrated phagocytosis dumps them out — seen later in rejection).</p><p>ReClaude A: Granules appear azurophilic → specific → gelatinase → secretory/ficolin during development; release reverses this, gated by calcium. Secretory/ficolin (first) supplies selectin ligands/integrins for migration; azurophilic (last) fuses with the phagolysosome to kill. Band neutrophils stop at gelatinase, lack secretory/ficolin, and so can kill but cannot migrate.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_12": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Why does a cell that loses MHC class I get killed by NK but hide from cytotoxic T cells?</em></p><p>THE MISSING-SELF DETECTIVE. NK cells solve a problem antibodies and T cells can’t: a virus or tumor that hides by switching off MHC class I. Cytotoxic T cells need to see peptide on MHC I to kill; a cell that drops MHC I becomes invisible to T cells. NK cells do the opposite — they read MHC I as a “don’t kill me” license, so a cell missing MHC I gets killed. This is the missing-self hypothesis, and it is the conceptual heart of the objective. Surface markers: CD56+, CD16+, CD3− (the CD3-negative is what separates NK from T cells).</p><p>NK missing-self: loss of MHC I (which licenses “don’t kill”) → NK kills. Markers CD56+ CD16+ CD3−. (missing-self + NK markers)</p><p>NK cells: CD56+ CD16+ CD3− lymphocytes that survey MHC class I and kill cells that have lost it.</p><p>Missing-self: normal MHC I delivers an inhibitory “don’t kill” signal; virus/tumor downregulation of MHC I removes the brake.</p><p>Killing uses perforin to breach the membrane and granzymes to trigger apoptosis — the same lethal hit cytotoxic T cells use.</p><p>HOW THEY KILL — AND THE TWO BALANCING SIGNALS. NK killing is governed by a balance of activating and inhibitory receptors. MHC I engages the inhibitory receptor and shuts the NK cell off; stress ligands engage activating receptors. When a cell loses MHC I, the inhibitory brake is released and activation wins. The lethal hit is the same one cytotoxic T cells use: perforin punches pores and granzymes enter to trigger apoptosis. NK cells also kill by ADCC through CD16 (FcγRIII), binding antibody-coated targets.</p><p>NK killing = perforin + granzyme → apoptosis; also ADCC via CD16. Balance of activating vs inhibitory (MHC I) receptors decides. (perforin/granzyme + ADCC)</p><p>THE IL-12 → NK → IFN-γ LOOP. Don’t lose the cytokine circuit Gregg stressed: macrophages and dendritic cells make IL-12, IL-12 drives NK cells to secrete IFN-γ, and IFN-γ activates macrophages (the M1 program) to kill what they’ve eaten. It is a feed-forward amplifier linking the phagocyte and the NK cell before adaptive immunity arrives — and the same IFN-γ later becomes the signature Th1 cytokine.</p><p>IL-12 (macrophage/DC) → NK secretes IFN-γ → M1 macrophage activation. Feed-forward innate amplifier. (IL-12→NK→IFN-γ loop)</p><p>The IL-12 → NK → IFN-γ → M1 loop: dendritic cells and macrophages and NK cells amplify each other ahead of adaptive immunity.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> NK = the missing-self killer. MHC I licenses “don’t kill”; lose it (virus/tumor) and NK kills via perforin/granzyme. CD56+ CD16+ CD3−. Also ADCC via CD16. IL-12 → NK → IFN-γ → M1.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> See downregulated/absent MHC I on a virus-infected or tumor cell → think NK killing. See antibody-coated target → think NK ADCC via CD16.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> NK is the mirror image of cytotoxic T cells. CTLs kill cells that show the wrong peptide-MHC; NK kills cells that lack MHC I. A cell hiding from T cells by dropping MHC I walks straight into the NK cell.</p><p>ReClaude A: NK cells (CD56+ CD16+ CD3−) kill by missing-self recognition: MHC class I engages an inhibitory receptor that licenses “don’t kill,” so cells that lose MHC I (virus/tumor) are killed via perforin/granzyme-induced apoptosis. They also perform ADCC through CD16, and the IL-12 → NK → IFN-γ loop activates M1 macrophages.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_13": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Match each splenic and nodal compartment to its resident cells and primary function.</em></p><p>THE COMPARTMENTALIZATION PRINCIPLE. Immature B cells leave the marrow and travel to the spleen, which has two zones with two jobs. The red pulp is the blood-handling zone: it filters blood, holds a blood reserve for trauma, and is where macrophages remove aged (~120-day) red cells. Dendritic cells and macrophages there also survey for microbes — a TLR hit triggers cytokines and phagocytosis on the spot, and dendritic cells carry captured microbes to the white pulp to prime T cells.</p><p>Red pulp = blood filter + aged-RBC removal (macrophages) + blood reserve. (red pulp function)</p><p>Newly formed naive B cells exit the bone marrow and enter the spleen as transitional cells.</p><p>Red pulp filters blood, stores a blood reserve, and is where macrophages remove aged red cells.</p><p>White pulp is the immune tissue: follicles (B cells), PALS (T cells), and the marginal zone (rapid-IgM B cells).</p><p>WHITE PULP — FOLLICLE, PALS, MARGINAL ZONE. The white pulp is the immune tissue, and B and T cells are kept separate. Follicles = B cells; the periarteriolar lymphatic sheath (PALS) = T cells. Surrounding both is the marginal zone, home to marginal-zone B cells — the emergency cell. They recognize mostly carbohydrate, respond to blood-borne antigen within hours (a normal B cell takes 7–10 days), and make only IgM, the complement-activating antibody. Something dangerous in the blood needs a response now; the marginal-zone B cell provides it.</p><p>White pulp: follicle = B, PALS = T. Marginal-zone B cell = rapid IgM vs blood-borne carbohydrate (hours, not days). (white pulp + emergency IgM)</p><p>Splenic white-pulp anatomy around the central arteriole: follicle, PALS, and marginal zone.</p><p>T cells arriving from the thymus populate the PALS (T-cell zone).</p><p>Transitional B cells become follicular (FO) or marginal-zone (MZ) B cells — and are tested for self-reactivity here.</p><p>THE LYMPH NODE — SAME LOGIC, NEW NAMES. The lymph node compartmentalizes B and T cells just like the spleen, but the names change. Follicle = B cells; paracortex = T cells; and when cells get activated they move into the medulla and exit through the efferent lymphatics into the blood, where they circulate until they find inflamed tissue. Antigen arrives the other way — via afferent lymphatics, carried almost entirely by dendritic cells (a few macrophages), which deliver microbial components to the paracortical T cells. One clinical aside Gregg flagged: damaged lymph nodes do not regenerate, though new lymphoid aggregates can form at sites of chronic infection.</p><p>Lymph node: follicle = B, paracortex = T, activated cells exit via medulla → efferent. Antigen enters via afferent (dendritic cells). (node compartments + flow)</p><p>Lymph-node compartments: B cells in follicles (germinal centers), T cells in the paracortex, and activated cells exiting through the medulla.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> PALS (spleen) = paracortex (node) = T-cell zone. Follicle = B-cell zone in both. Don’t put lymphocytes in the red pulp — red pulp is blood-handling, white pulp is immune tissue.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Marginal-zone B cell = the emergency cell. Blood-borne carbohydrate → IgM within hours. It’s why splenectomy raises the risk from encapsulated (polysaccharide-coated) bacteria.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two organs, one rule: B cells in follicles, T cells in the T-zone (PALS in spleen, paracortex in node). Red pulp filters blood; white pulp mounts the response; the marginal zone holds the emergency-IgM B cell.</p><p>ReClaude A: Spleen red pulp filters blood, removes aged RBCs (macrophages), and stores a blood reserve; white pulp is immune tissue with follicles (B cells), PALS (T cells), and a marginal zone (rapid-IgM B cells). In the lymph node, the follicle holds B cells, the paracortex holds T cells, and activated cells exit via the medulla into efferent lymphatics.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_14": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Name the three functions of the lymphatic system and one effect of OMM lymphatic-pump techniques.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW — THREE JOBS, NO PUMP. The lymphatic system is a network of vessels that drains fluid from tissues to lymph nodes, and it does three things: maintain fluid balance, absorb dietary fat, and provide immune surveillance. The key mechanical fact: unlike the cardiovascular system, the lymphatics have no heart pump. Flow is driven by skeletal-muscle movement, breathing, and a little smooth muscle, and kept one-directional by a valve system. Sedentary patients move lymph slowly — which is exactly why activity (and osteopathic manipulation) matters.</p><p>Lymphatics: no heart pump — muscle/breathing/smooth muscle + one-way valves drive flow. Backup → edema. (lymph propulsion)</p><p>One-way valves keep lymph moving forward; muscle/respiratory movement supplies the force.</p><p>Lymph is a clear, multi-component fluid — mostly interstitial fluid drained from tissues back toward the blood.</p><p>Fluid balance: afferent lymphatics drain interstitial fluid to prevent edema — the lymphatics are the tissue’s drain.</p><p>FAT ABSORPTION. Dietary lipids can’t simply diffuse into blood capillaries. They’re packaged into chylomicrons (triglyceride wrapped with cholesterol and other lipids), released, and picked up by gut lacteals — the intestinal lymphatic vessels. The lymphatics then deliver them to the blood for transport to the liver. After a fatty meal the mesenteric lymphatics run milky-white with chylomicrons. So the lymphatic system isn’t just immune plumbing; it’s the absorptive route for fat.</p><p>Dietary fat → chylomicrons → gut lacteals (lymphatics) → blood → liver. (fat absorption route)</p><p>Osteopathic manipulation can drive lymph flow — a central reason to keep patients moving.</p><p>Abdominal lymphatic-pump treatment measurably increases lymph flow (thoracic-duct data).</p><p>Dietary fat is packaged into chylomicrons and absorbed by intestinal lacteals, then delivered to the blood.</p><p>OMM AND THE LYMPHATICS — the osteopathic hook. Because lymph depends on movement, osteopathic lymphatic-pump techniques (thoracic, abdominal, pedal pumps) exaggerate respiratory motion to push lymph through. This isn’t hand-waving — Gregg cited data: pump techniques increase thoracic-duct flow (measured in dogs), improve vaccine efficacy, and reduce the duration of infectious disease. In his own mouse cancer work, the lymphatic pump mobilized NK cells into the blood and blocked cancer development in about half the animals. The takeaway for boards: OMM lymphatic techniques promote lymph movement, which clears waste, reduces edema, and improves immune surveillance.</p><p>OMM lymphatic pumps ↑ thoracic-duct flow, ↑ vaccine efficacy, ↓ infection duration; mobilize NK cells. (OMM pump evidence)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three lymphatic jobs: fluid balance (drain → prevent edema), fat absorption (chylomicrons via lacteals), immune surveillance. No heart pump — movement + valves drive flow.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Stem about a sedentary or post-op patient with swelling → think impaired lymphatic drainage → edema, and OMM lymphatic-pump techniques as a movement-promoting intervention.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> OMM lymphatic-pump data are board-relevant: increased thoracic-duct flow, improved vaccine efficacy, reduced infection duration, and NK mobilization. Damaged lymph nodes, by contrast, do not regenerate.</p><p>ReClaude A: The lymphatic system maintains fluid balance (draining interstitial fluid to prevent edema), absorbs dietary fat (chylomicrons via gut lacteals), and provides immune surveillance. It has no heart pump — muscle/respiratory movement and one-way valves drive flow — which is why OMM lymphatic-pump techniques (shown to raise thoracic-duct flow, improve vaccine efficacy, and shorten infections) help.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_16": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What distinguishes a superantigen from a mitogen, and what is an alloantigen?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW — a slide-sourced objective. Gregg ran out of time and deferred alloantigens, superantigens, mitogens, and haptens to the start of the T-cell lectures — so the depth here is built from his slides plus the framework you need, flagged as such. The objective names five special immunogen categories beyond “ordinary” antigen. Alloantigens are antigens that differ between individuals of the same species (the basis of transplant rejection). Autoantigens are self-antigens (the targets in autoimmunity). Heterophile antigens are shared across species (cross-reacting).</p><p>Allo = differs within a species (transplant). Auto = self (autoimmunity). Heterophile = shared across species. (allo/auto/heterophile)</p><p>Superantigens cross-link the TCR Vβ region directly to MHC II, polyclonally activating up to ~20% of T cells (toxic-shock mechanism).</p><p>Mitogens drive polyclonal lymphocyte proliferation by binding stimulatory receptors (e.g., TLR), independent of antigen specificity.</p><p>Haptens are small molecules that need a carrier protein to become immunogenic — the mechanism behind contact (type IV) hypersensitivity.</p><p>SUPERANTIGENS AND MITOGENS — the two polyclonal activators. A superantigen bypasses normal peptide specificity by bridging the TCR Vβ region directly to MHC class II, outside the peptide groove. The result is polyclonal activation of up to ~20% of all T cells at once — a cytokine storm, the mechanism behind toxic-shock syndrome. A mitogen also causes polyclonal proliferation, but through stimulatory receptors such as TLR, driving cell-cycle progression independent of antigen specificity. And a hapten is the small-molecule case: too small to be immunogenic alone, it must couple to a carrier protein to provoke a response — the basis of contact dermatitis (a type IV hypersensitivity).</p><p>Superantigen = TCR Vβ–MHC II bridge → ~20% T cells (toxic shock). Mitogen = TLR-type polyclonal proliferation. Hapten = needs carrier. (superantigen vs mitogen vs hapten)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Superantigen vs mitogen: both polyclonal, different routes. Superantigen bridges TCR Vβ to MHC II directly; mitogen acts through stimulatory receptors like TLR — not via Vβ–MHC.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> This LO is slide-built — Gregg deferred it. He covers superantigens, mitogens, and haptens at the start of the T-cell lectures; the definitions here come from his slides, not the recorded lecture.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Five categories: alloantigen (within species), autoantigen (self), heterophile (across species), superantigen (Vβ–MHC II bridge, polyclonal), mitogen (TLR-type polyclonal). Hapten = needs a carrier.</p><p>ReClaude A: The five types: alloantigens differ between individuals of the same species (transplant), autoantigens are self-antigens (autoimmunity), heterophile antigens are shared across species, superantigens bridge the TCR Vβ region to MHC II for polyclonal activation of ~20% of T cells, and mitogens drive polyclonal proliferation via stimulatory receptors like TLR. (Slide-sourced — Gregg deferred this to the T-cell lectures.)</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_17": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Rank the four antigen classes and state which class T cells can respond to.</em></p><p>FOUR CLASSES, ONE HIERARCHY. Antigens come in four chemical classes, and their immunogenicity ranks proteins &gt; polysaccharides &gt; nucleic acids &gt; lipids. Proteins are the most immunogenic and the only class T cells respond to — and they must be larger than about 10 kDa. Polysaccharides are second-strongest but are B-cell only (T cells can’t see carbohydrate). The rule to anchor: T cells respond ONLY to protein (as processed peptide); B cells respond to all four classes.</p><p>Immunogenicity: protein &gt; polysaccharide &gt; nucleic acid &gt; lipid. T cells = protein only (&gt;10 kDa); B cells = all four. (antigen-class hierarchy)</p><p>Proteins are most immunogenic (B + T cells, &gt;10 kDa); polysaccharides are second but B-cell only.</p><p>Nucleic acids and lipids are B-cell only — lupus anti-DNA antibodies show B-cell response to nucleic acids; lipids respond best with protein.</p><p>NUCLEIC ACIDS AND LIPIDS — B-cell territory. Nucleic acids are B-cell only, and you already know the proof: systemic lupus erythematosus, where B cells make antibodies against DNA. T cells can’t respond to DNA. Lipids are also B-cell only, and they respond best when associated with protein — if a lipid carries some protein, you can pull T-cell involvement in, but the T cell is still only seeing the protein part. The single unifying rule for the whole lecture: T cells never respond to anything but protein.</p><p>Nucleic acids (lupus anti-DNA) and lipids = B-cell only; lipids respond best protein-associated. T cells: protein only, always. (nucleic acids + lipids)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Lupus anti-dsDNA is the board-favorite proof that B cells answer nucleic-acid antigens — something T cells can never do.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Protein &gt; polysaccharide &gt; nucleic acid &gt; lipid. The load-bearing rule: T cells respond ONLY to protein (processed peptide); B cells respond to all four classes.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Lipids CAN pull in T-cell help, but only when protein-associated — and even then the T cell sees the protein, not the lipid. T cells never recognize lipid, carbohydrate, or nucleic acid alone.</p><p>ReClaude A: Antigen classes rank protein &gt; polysaccharide &gt; nucleic acid &gt; lipid in immunogenicity. Proteins are most immunogenic, must exceed ~10 kDa, and are the only class T cells respond to (as processed peptide); polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and lipids are B-cell only (lupus anti-DNA proves the nucleic-acid case).</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_18": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Name the recognition and signaling parts of the TCR and the chains of the BCR.</em></p><p>NEARSIGHTED T CELLS, PERFECT-VISION B CELLS. Before the receptors themselves, hold the metaphor Gregg leaned on. T cells are nearsighted: they cannot see free antigen — it must be processed into peptide and displayed on MHC by an antigen-presenting cell, which holds it up close so the TCR can read it. B cells have perfect vision: the BCR binds native, unprocessed antigen directly, no helper needed. That difference shapes the structure and behavior of both receptors.</p><p>T cells nearsighted (need peptide on MHC via APC); B cells perfect vision (bind native antigen directly). (T vs B antigen access)</p><p>B cells recognize native antigen directly through the BCR — no processing or presentation required.</p><p>T cells express a TCR that reads antigen only as peptide displayed on MHC by an antigen-presenting cell.</p><p>TCR components: an αβ recognition heterodimer plus CD3 and zeta (ζ) signaling chains that dock ZAP-70 on activation.</p><p>THE TCR — recognition plus signaling. The T-cell receptor has two functional parts. The α and β chains form the antigen-recognition heterodimer; each chain has a variable region (changes to recognize different antigens) and a constant region (fixed), anchored by a transmembrane segment. Bolted alongside are the CD3 and zeta (ζ) signaling chains — when the αβ dimer engages peptide-MHC, the CD3/zeta cytoplasmic tails get phosphorylated and dock adaptors like ZAP-70, launching activation → proliferation → effector function. The whole αβ receptor is assembled by random V(D)J recombination in the thymus, then tested against self.</p><p>TCR: αβ = recognition (variable + constant); CD3 + zeta = signaling (dock ZAP-70). Built by V(D)J in the thymus. (TCR components)</p><p>BCR components: two heavy and two light chains, each with a variable (antigen-binding) and a constant region.</p><p>THE BCR — heavy and light chains. The B-cell receptor is built from two heavy chains and two light chains, each chain again split into a variable (antigen-binding) region and a constant region. The variable regions of the heavy and light chains together form the antigen-binding site; the constant region is fixed. Like the TCR, a transmembrane segment anchors it in the membrane — and that anchor is exactly what gets removed when the B cell becomes a plasma cell and secretes the receptor as antibody (LO 6.9).</p><p>BCR: two heavy + two light chains, each with variable (antigen-binding) + constant regions. (BCR components)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Don’t mix the chains: αβ belong to the TCR; heavy/light belong to the BCR. CD3 and zeta are TCR signaling chains, not recognition chains.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> TCR = αβ recognition + CD3/zeta signaling. BCR = 2 heavy + 2 light chains, each variable + constant. Both assembled by random V(D)J; both have a transmembrane anchor.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Nearsighted T, perfect-vision B is the single best way to remember why T cells need an APC + MHC and B cells don’t — and it explains the whole presentation story in Lec 7.</p><p>ReClaude A: The TCR has an αβ heterodimer for antigen recognition (each chain with variable and constant regions) plus CD3 and zeta chains for signaling. The BCR has two heavy and two light chains, each with variable (antigen-binding) and constant regions. T cells need processed peptide on MHC; B cells bind native antigen directly.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_19": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A bacterium is growing inside a macrophage’s phagosome. Is its antigen endogenous or exogenous, and why does the answer NOT depend on the fact that it is “inside a cell”?</em></p><p>THE UNIFYING DISTINCTION. There are two presentation pathways, and the single fact that sorts every antigen between them is where the protein is made or held — cytosol versus vesicle. The endogenous pathway handles protein synthesized in the cytosol (your own proteins, or a</p><p>virus replicating in the cytoplasm), routes it through class I, and shows it to CD8 cells for cell-mediated killing. The exogenous pathway handles protein taken into a vesicle — either phagocytosed from outside or growing inside a phagosome — routes it through class II, and shows it to CD4 cells for help. Hold onto the location rule and the rest follows.</p><p>Endogenous = cytosolic protein → class I → CD8; exogenous = vesicular protein → class II → CD4. (the master sorting rule)</p><p>T cells are MHC-restricted AND class-restricted: CD4→class II, CD8→class I (“it always has to equal 8”).</p><p>APC presenting on class I is recognized by a CD8 cell → clonal proliferation into cytotoxic T lymphocytes.</p><p>APC presenting on class II is recognized by a CD4 cell → differentiation into helper subsets that license B cells.</p><p>CLASS RESTRICTION — the “equal 8” hook. T cells are not only restricted to self-MHC, they are class-restricted: a CD4 cell reads class II, a CD8 cell reads class I, and they cannot cross over. Davis’s mnemonic is the one students actually remember on exam day — the numbers always multiply to 8: 4×2 and 8×1. The architectural reason the pairing is enforced is the set of “knobs” on the MHC that engage the correct co-receptor, but the test reward is just getting the direction right under pressure.</p><p>THE TWO ENDPOINTS. Once a naive cell is activated in the lymph node or spleen, it undergoes clonal proliferation and differentiation. A class I–activated CD8 becomes a cytotoxic T lymphocyte (CTL) that circulates and kills any cell displaying the same peptide-MHC that activated it — this is cell-mediated immunity. A class II–activated CD4 becomes a helper subset (Th1, Th2, Th17, Treg) that licenses B cells and shapes which antibody isotype they make — this is the gateway to humoral immunity. Recall from the first lecture that this is the same clonal-proliferation-then-differentiate logic; we will see CD8 effector killing again in LO 12.3 and CD4 differentiation in LO 12.1.</p><p>Class restriction: CD4→class II, CD8→class I — “it always has to equal 8” (4×2, 8×1). (class-restriction mnemonic) CQ Activated CD8 → CTL (cell-mediated); activated CD4 → helper subsets (gateway to humoral). (pathway endpoints)</p><p>Endogenous pathway overview: cytosolic protein → proteasome → TAP → class I in ER → surface → CD8.</p><p>Exogenous pathway overview: phagocytosed antigen → phagolysosome → class II loading → surface → CD4.</p><p>Class I vs class II side by side — the single best summary slide: uptake, processing, loading compartment, and which T cell reads each.</p><p>THE CYTOSOL-VS-INSIDE TRAP. Here is where the exam loves to set you up. “Inside the cell” is not the same as “in the cytosol.” Mycobacterium and Listeria grow inside a macrophage, but they sit in a vesicle, making their proteins in the phagosome rather than the cytosol. That makes them exogenous / class II / CD4, even though they are physically intracellular. Davis calls these intravesicular pathogens and contrasts them with a cytosolic virus, which is endogenous. If a stem stresses that the organism is “growing inside the phagosome,” the location rule — vesicle, not cytosol — gives you class II.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One rule sorts everything: location of the protein. Cytosol → endogenous → class I → CD8. Vesicle (phagocytosed OR intravesicular) → exogenous → class II → CD4.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> “Inside a cell” ≠ “in the cytosol.” Intravesicular pathogens (Mycobacterium, Listeria) grow inside the cell but in a vesicle → exogenous → class II / CD4. Only cytosolic protein is endogenous / class I.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> On a vignette, find the antigen’s compartment first. Cytosolic virus → CD8/CTL answer. Phagocytosed or intravesicular bug → CD4/helper answer. Decide compartment, then everything else falls out.</p><p>ReClaude A: Exogenous. Although the bacterium is physically inside the cell, it resides in a vesicle (phagosome) and makes its proteins there, not in the cytosol — and the pathway is decided by compartment (cytosol vs vesicle), not by whether the antigen is intracellular. Vesicular location → class II → CD4.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_20": {
  "answer": "<p><em>HLA-DM carries the “HLA-D” name of the class II family — so why is it a mistake to call it an MHC class II molecule, and what does it actually do?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Each pathway is a little assembly line, and the testable content here is the named worker at each station. The trap the exam exploits is that several of these workers are accessory molecules — chaperones and transporters — not MHC molecules themselves. Keep the class I line and the class II line on separate tracks in your head and assign each molecule to one.</p><p>THE CLASS I LINE (endogenous). A cytosolic protein is tagged with ubiquitin and fed into the proteasome — Davis’s “wood chipper,” big protein in, small peptides out. During infection, IFN-γ remodels it into the immunoproteasome, which preferentially cuts after hydrophobic or basic</p><p>residues so the fragments carry good class I anchors. Those peptides then cross from cytosol into the ER through TAP1/TAP2, the ATP-dependent transporter associated with antigen processing. Waiting in the ER, the empty class I α chain is held by the chaperone calnexin, which stabilizes it until β2-microglobulin binds and also keeps empty molecules from leaving prematurely; tapasin then tethers the class I molecule near the TAP channel so peptides can be tried on as they arrive.</p><p>Class I peptides are made by the proteasome/immunoproteasome; IFN-γ induces the immunoproteasome for better anchors. (class I peptide generation) CQ TAP1/TAP2 moves peptides cytosol→ER (ATP-dependent); calnexin stabilizes class I until β2m binds; tapasin docks it at TAP. (class I ER machinery)</p><p>Calnexin stabilizes the class I α chain in the ER; tapasin positions it at the TAP gateway for loading.</p><p>Endogenous antigen processing: cytosolic protein degraded by the proteasome into peptides for class I.</p><p>IFN-γ converts the proteasome to the immunoproteasome; IFN-α/β drive the antiviral state.</p><p>Full class I trafficking: proteasome → TAP into ER → assembly with β2m/chaperone/tapasin → surface → CD8.</p><p>THE CLASS II LINE (exogenous). Antigen taken into a vesicle meets the phagolysosome, where the pH is dropped and cathepsins — enzymes, not a structure — do the cutting that the proteasome does on the other track. Meanwhile class II is also built in the ER (both classes are), so the cell must stop cytosolic peptides from loading into class II by mistake. It does this with the invariant chain (Ii), which has three jobs: it chaperones class II folding, blocks the binding cleft from endogenous peptide, and routes the class II molecule to the endosomal compartment. In the vesicle the invariant chain is trimmed down to a remnant called CLIP still sitting in the groove.</p><p>HLA-DM — the molecule Davis flags hardest. The class II molecules are DP, DQ, DR. HLA-DM shares that “HLA-D” naming but is not an MHC class II molecule — it is an accessory molecule, “kind of like tapasin or calnexin.” Its job is to remove CLIP and facilitate peptide loading into the now-open class II cleft. Davis stops and says “now remember this is important” precisely because the name invites you to mis-file it as a presenting molecule. Once loaded, the class II–peptide complex moves to the APC surface for a CD4 cell.</p><p>Class II peptides are cut by cathepsins in the phagolysosome (the enzyme analog of the proteasome). (class II peptide generation) CQ Invariant chain (Ii) chaperones class II, blocks the cleft, and routes it to the vesicle; its remnant is CLIP. (invariant chain three roles) CQ HLA-DM is an accessory molecule (NOT a class II molecule) that removes CLIP and loads peptide. (HLA-DM identity + job)</p><p>In the vesicle, invariant chain is trimmed to CLIP, which still blocks the binding cleft until exchange.</p><p>Invariant chain occupies the class II cleft in the ER, blocking endogenous peptide and routing class II to the vesicle.</p><p>HLA-DM removes CLIP and facilitates loading of antigenic peptide — then class II moves to the surface for CD4.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> HLA-DM is NOT an MHC class II molecule. The class II presenting molecules are DP/DQ/DR. HLA-DM is an accessory molecule (like tapasin/calnexin) that swaps out CLIP. The shared “HLA-D” name is the bait.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Same job, different track: proteasome (class I, cytosol) and cathepsins (class II, vesicle) both cut protein into peptides. TAP (class I) and HLA-DM (class II) both make loading possible — on opposite lines.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Both class I and class II are built in the ER. The difference is where they load — class I in the ER, class II in the vesicle — which is exactly why the invariant chain has to guard the class II cleft until it reaches the vesicle.</p><p>ReClaude A: HLA-DM shares the HLA-D family name but is an accessory molecule, like tapasin or calnexin — not a peptide-presenting class II molecule (those are DP/DQ/DR). Its job is to remove CLIP from the class II cleft and facilitate loading of antigenic peptide in the acidic vesicle.</p><p><em>A cytotoxic T cell finds a virally infected epithelial cell in the throat. Trace why this is “cell-mediated immunity” and how it differs from what a CD4 cell would have done.</em></p><p>THE TWO ARMS. The pathway you load determines the kind of immunity you get. Class I → CD8 → CTL → killing of infected cells is cell-mediated immunity. Class II → CD4 → helper subsets → B-cell licensing is the gateway to humoral immunity. Davis returns to her day-one line here as the anchor: “T cells don’t kill pathogens, they kill infected cells.” A CTL does not chase a free virus; it recognizes the peptide-MHC on a host cell that has been hijacked and destroys that cell.</p><p>Class I/CD8 → cell-mediated immunity (CTL kills infected cells); class II/CD4 → humoral (B-cell help). (pathway → immune arm) CQ CTLs kill infected cells, not free pathogens — they recognize peptide-MHC on a hijacked host cell. (core CTL principle)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Class II peptide binding: longer peptides in an open-ended cleft — the CD4/humoral arm.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> MHC class I molecules (HLA-A/B/C) on all nucleated cells — the cell-mediated arm read by CD8 cells.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Class I peptide binding: ~8–10 aa held by anchor residues, optimal length 9, ends pinned in a closed cleft. Anchor residues with defined chemistry (hydrophobic/basic/charged) let one groove bind many peptides.</p><p>WHY HEALTHY CELLS STILL PRESENT. Every nucleated cell constantly shows self-peptide on class I even when uninfected. That is not wasted effort — it is the signal NK cells read. A cell that downregulates class I to hide from CD8 surveillance (a favorite viral and tumor trick) triggers the NK “missing-self” response and gets killed anyway. Davis frames it as plan A (CTL) and plan B (NK): lose your MHC to dodge the T cell, and the NK cell finishes the job. On the CD4 side, the helper cell that recognizes class II goes on to license B cells and steer isotype switching — IgA at mucosa, IgG in tissue, IgE in allergy/parasite settings — which is how presentation choice ultimately shapes the antibody response.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> “T cells don’t kill pathogens — they kill infected cells.” Davis’s day-one line and the spine of LO 7.4. Class I/CD8 = cell-mediated killing; class II/CD4 = humoral help.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Constant self-peptide on class I is the NK “billboard.” Downregulate class I to dodge CD8 (plan A) and you trip NK missing-self (plan B). Evasion of one arm exposes you to the other.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Stem says “kills the infected cell directly” → CD8/CTL/class I. Stem says “helps B cells / drives antibody isotype” → CD4/class II. Match the verb to the arm.</p><p>ReClaude A: The virus is made in the infected cell’s cytosol → class I → the CD8 CTL recognizes peptide-MHC on that host cell and lyses it: killing an infected host cell is cell-mediated immunity. A CD4 cell, by contrast, would have read class II on an APC and helped B cells make antibody — it would not itself kill the infected cell.</p><p><em>If a patient loses TAP function entirely, which arm of adaptive immunity collapses, which is spared, and what infection pattern results?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This is the LO Davis builds toward with the self-study prompt on the class I-vs-II slide: “what happens if a mutation prevents class I or class II expression on the APCs?” The way to answer any presentation-deficiency question is to ask which line is broken and then read off the downstream arm. Break the class I line and you lose CD8/cell-mediated immunity; break the class II line and you lose CD4 help, which takes the antibody response down with it because most antibody responses are T-dependent.</p><p>WORKED CASES. Lose TAP and peptides never reach the ER → class I cannot be loaded → low CD8/CTL responses and recurrent viral infections, while the class II/CD4/antibody arm — which loads in the vesicle independent of TAP — is comparatively spared. Lose class II (bare lymphocyte syndrome, class II) and CD4 cells are not primed → low CD4 and failed T-dependent antibody responses, with class I/CD8 relatively intact. The pattern is always the same: a presentation defect knocks out the arm it feeds, and the spared arm tells you which line stayed open. NK cells can blunt but not replace antigen-specific CTL immunity, so “NK fully compensates” is never the right answer.</p><p>TAP loss → no class I loading → low CD8/CTL → viral susceptibility; CD4/antibody spared (TAP-independent). (TAP-deficiency phenotype) CQ Class II loss (bare lymphocyte syndrome II) → no CD4 priming → low CD4 + poor T-dependent antibody. (class II-deficiency phenotype)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CD1 follows the class II vesicular pathway but has a class I-like structure including β2-microglobulin. CD1 is recognized by invariant NKT cells (invariant α chain + β chain TCR); also involved in anti-tumor surveillance.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Nonclassical antigens: lipid/glycolipid/phospholipid presented on CD1 (not classical MHC) — relevant to mycobacterial cell-wall lipids.</p><p>NONCLASSICAL FOOTNOTE. Davis closes with a brief, low-emphasis aside (Tier 1): not every antigen is a protein. Lipid and glycolipid antigens — think mycobacterial cell wall — are too hydrophobic for the classical grooves and are instead presented on CD1, a non-polymorphic molecule with a class I-like structure (including β2m) that nonetheless trafficks through the class II vesicular pathway. CD1 is read by invariant NKT cells. It is worth recognizing, not memorizing in depth.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> CD1 presents lipid antigen to invariant NKT cells: class I-like structure (with β2m) but class II-style vesicular trafficking. Recognize it; don’t over-study it (Tier 1).</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Presentation-defect question? Ask which line broke. Class I line down → CD8/cell-mediated fails (viral infections). Class II line down → CD4 help fails → antibody fails. The spared arm reveals the open line.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> “NK cells fully compensate for absent class I” is a distractor. NK cells exploit missing-self and help, but they do not replace antigen-specific CTL immunity — TAP/class I patients still get sick with viruses.</p><p>ReClaude A: Cell-mediated immunity collapses: no TAP → no peptide into the ER → no class I loading → deficient CD8/CTL responses and recurrent viral infections. The class II/CD4/antibody arm is spared because class II loads in the vesicle independent of TAP. NK cells help via missing-self but cannot fully substitute for antigen-specific CTLs.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_23": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Walk the heavy chain from germline DNA to a surface receptor. At which single step does failure doom the cell, and why?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This LO is the ordered choreography of V(D)J recombination — the actual sequence of cuts, joins, and checkpoints. The unifying idea is that rearrangement proceeds in a fixed order with a checkpoint: the heavy chain goes first, and only a successful, in-frame heavy chain licenses the light chain to proceed. Fail the checkpoint and the cell dies. Everything else is the mechanics around that gate.</p><p>HEAVY CHAIN FIRST — D-J, THEN V-DJ. Heavy-chain rearrangement leads, and within it the order is specific: D joins J first, then V joins the DJ. You cannot skip the D segment (&gt;99% of the time). When the DNA is cut and religated, the join is only productive if it lands in frame; an out-of-frame join makes no protein. The cell gets two tries (maternal and paternal alleles), but if both heavy-chain alleles fail to produce an in-frame product, there is no heavy chain — and the cell undergoes apoptosis. This is the load-bearing checkpoint.</p><p>Heavy chain rearranges first; order is D-J then V-DJ (you cannot skip D). (heavy-chain join order) CQ An in-frame heavy chain is the checkpoint; both alleles failing → apoptosis. (heavy-chain checkpoint)</p><p>Alternative splicing of the heavy-chain transcript generates the mature IgM and IgD mRNAs.</p><p>Light-chain (kappa) rearrangement: V→J joining, then splicing removes extra J introns to the mRNA.</p><p>Heavy-chain rearrangement: D→J joining, then V→DJ; DNA is permanently altered (deleted segments are gone).</p><p>Primary transcript includes introns and extra J segments; transcribed through μ and δ for IgM/IgD.</p><p>LIGHT CHAIN SECOND — only if heavy succeeds. A successful heavy chain triggers light-chain rearrangement, which starts with kappa (isotypic exclusion suppressing lambda); lambda proceeds only if kappa fails in frame. Light chains use simple V-J joining. At every stage the rule is the same: an out-of-frame or non-productive rearrangement that exhausts the available alleles sends the cell to apoptosis — the immune system would rather kill a non-functional precursor than let it linger.</p><p>FROM DNA TO PROTEIN. Once segments are joined, the rearranged DNA is permanently altered — the intervening segments are deleted and degraded, never recovered. Transcription makes a primary RNA that still contains extra J segments and introns; splicing removes them to yield mature mRNA. For the heavy chain specifically, alternative splicing across Cμ and Cδ produces both IgM and IgD (LO 8.4); for the light chain, ordinary splicing just trims the extra J introns. Translation then sends the chains to the ER, where heavy and light pair into a complete receptor displayed on the surface. The same V(D)J choreography runs in T cells in the thymus — β/δ like a heavy chain, α/γ like a light chain.</p><p>Light chain rearranges only if heavy succeeds; starts with kappa (V-J), lambda only on kappa failure. (light-chain order) CQ Rearranged DNA is permanently altered (segments deleted); splicing trims introns/extra J to mature mRNA. (DNA-to-mRNA processing)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Fixed order with a gate: heavy first (D-J then V-DJ) → checkpoint → light second (V-J, kappa first). An in-frame heavy chain is the permission slip for everything downstream.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Heavy-chain order is D-J first, then V-DJ — not V-D first. And you cannot skip the D segment. A stem that joins V to D before D-J is describing the wrong sequence.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Failure → apoptosis. No in-frame heavy chain means no light-chain rearrangement and a dead precursor. The system discards non-functional cells rather than tolerating them.</p><p>ReClaude A: Germline DNA → D-J joining → V-DJ joining → in-frame check → (if productive) transcription, splicing to mRNA, translation, ER pairing with light chain, surface display. The doomed step is the in-frame heavy-chain checkpoint: if both alleles join out of frame there is no heavy chain, light-chain rearrangement never starts, and the cell undergoes apoptosis.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_27": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A thymocyte has made a β chain but has no α chain yet. How does it prove the β chain is real and in-frame — and what is the consequence if it cannot?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. T-cell ontogeny is a staged assembly line with two go/no-go checkpoints. The unifying idea: a thymocyte must first build a working TCR (the double-negative stages, gated by proving each chain is in-frame) and only then is it tested against self (selection, the next LO). Everything that follows hangs on that order — build first, select second — and on the fact that nearly all of it happens in the cortex.</p><p>WHERE AND WHAT. A hematopoietic progenitor commits to the T lineage, leaves the marrow, and enters the thymus as a thymocyte, arriving through the subcapsular region and moving into the outer cortex. Because it expresses neither co-receptor, it is double-negative (DN) — CD4− CD8−. There are four DN stages, and the TCR β chain is assembled across them in the same order as a B-cell heavy chain: D-J first, then V-DJ.</p><p>Progenitor → thymus → thymocyte; enters via subcapsular region into the outer cortex; starts double-negative. (entry / DN start) CQ DN1 Notch1 + IL-7 commit T-lineage; DN2 β D-J join (RAG up); DN3 β V-DJ join completes β. (DN1–DN3 β rearrangement)</p><p>DN2: β-chain D-J joining begins (RAG1/RAG2 upregulated); γ/δ genes rearrange in parallel.</p><p>DN3: V-DJ joining completes the β chain; splicing yields β mRNA, then β-chain protein.</p><p>DN1: progenitor expresses Notch1; cTECs express Notch ligand and IL-7, committing the cell to the T lineage.</p><p>CHECKPOINT 1 — prove the β chain (DN3). Most rearrangements fail in frame, so the cell must prove it made a real β chain before investing in an α chain. It cannot wait for the α chain, so it builds an invariant surrogate pre-T-α chain (no V(D)J — the same sequence in everyone), pairs it with the β chain plus the CD3 complex and ζ chains, and sends this pre-TCR to the surface. Reaching the surface IS the proof — “yes, there is a β chain.” Fail this checkpoint and the cell undergoes apoptosis. Success triggers a round of proliferation (one good β chain copied into many cells), because the next step also has a high failure rate.</p><p>CHECKPOINT 2 — prove the α chain (DN4). RAG1/RAG2 are re-expressed and the α chain rearranges (V-J). Now a real α chain pairs with the β chain (plus CD3/ζ) to form a complete αβ TCR — checkpoint 2 confirms an in-frame α chain. Allelic exclusion applies throughout (mom’s or dad’s allele wins), with the α-chain bypass exception from Lecture 9. Having proven both chains, the cell finally upregulates both CD4 and CD8 to become double-positive (DP) — and only now is it ready for selection.</p><p>Checkpoint 1 (DN3): β + surrogate pre-T-α + CD3/ζ → pre-TCR to surface proves β; fail → apoptosis, pass → proliferation. (checkpoint 1) CQ Checkpoint 2 (DN4): α V-J rearranges → complete αβ TCR; then upregulate CD4 + CD8 → double-positive. (checkpoint 2 → DP)</p><p>Checkpoint 1: the pre-TCR (β + pre-T-α + CD3 + ζ) on the surface confirms a successful β-chain rearrangement.</p><p>DN4: RAG re-expressed; α-chain V-J rearrangement forms a complete TCR — checkpoint 2 confirms the α chain.</p><p>Double-positive: CD4 and CD8 are both upregulated alongside the complete αβ TCR and CD3/ζ.</p><p>WHY THE ORDER MATTERS. The checkpoints exist because random rearrangement is wasteful — the cell refuses to build the second chain until the first is proven, and refuses to express co-receptors until a whole TCR exists. Proliferation after checkpoint 1 rescues yield from the high α-chain failure rate. Hold this thread into the next LO: a double-positive cell with a complete TCR has earned the right to be tested against self, and that test (positive then negative selection) is what turns a DP thymocyte into a single mature T cell.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> The pre-T-α (surrogate α) is invariant — it does NOT undergo V(D)J and is the same in everyone. Its only job is to escort the β chain to the surface for checkpoint 1.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> β-chain order mirrors the heavy chain: D-J (DN2) before V-DJ (DN3). The α chain (V-J) comes last, in DN4. Build the receptor first; selection comes only after the double-positive stage.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two checkpoints gate the build: checkpoint 1 (DN3) proves the β chain via the surrogate pre-T-α pre-TCR; checkpoint 2 (DN4) proves the α chain via the complete αβ TCR. Then CD4+CD8 → double-positive.</p><p>ReClaude A: It builds an invariant surrogate pre-T-α chain, pairs it with the β chain plus CD3 and ζ, and displays this pre-TCR on the surface — reaching the surface is the proof that an in-frame β chain was made (checkpoint 1, DN3). If it cannot, the thymocyte undergoes apoptosis; if it can, it proliferates and proceeds to rearrange the α chain at DN4.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_28": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Two thymic epithelial cell types do superficially similar jobs — presenting MHC to thymocytes — yet they sit in different regions and serve opposite halves of education. Name them and their distinct roles.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The thymus has two regions — outer cortex and inner medulla — each stocked with specific cells for specific steps. The unifying idea: cortex = build + positive selection, medulla = final negative selection + Treg induction. Knowing which cell lives where and what signal it provides answers most component questions, because the location maps directly onto the step.</p><p>CORTEX COMPONENTS. The cortical thymic epithelial cells (cTECs) are the workhorses: they express Notch ligand and secrete IL-7 to push the progenitor down the T-cell road and support development, and later they display class I and class II MHC for positive selection. Dendritic cells also present MHC-peptide during selection, and macrophages clear the many thymocytes that fail and die. The Notch1 (thymocyte) – Notch-ligand (cTEC) interaction is decisive: too little permits aberrant B-cell development in the thymus; Notch1 overexpression in marrow can drive ectopic T-cell development there.</p><p>Cortex = cTECs (Notch ligand + IL-7, then MHC I/II), dendritic cells, macrophages; site of build + positive selection. (cortex components) CQ Notch1 – Notch ligand commits T-lineage; too little → thymic B cells, marrow overexpression → marrow T cells. (Notch signaling)</p><p>Thymus structure: two regions — outer cortex and inner medulla — each with distinct cells and steps.</p><p>Medulla cells: mTECs and dendritic cells present self-peptides for negative selection; macrophages remove apoptotic cells.</p><p>Cortex cells: cTECs (express Notch ligand and IL-7, promote development), macrophages (clear apoptotic thymocytes), dendritic cells (present peptide).</p><p>MEDULLA COMPONENTS. The medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTECs) and dendritic cells present self-peptide on MHC for the second round of negative selection. Their special tool is AIRE (autoimmune regulator), which drives mTECs to express tissue-restricted self-antigens they would not normally make — so thymocytes reactive to peripheral tissues can be deleted centrally. The clinical hook: an AIRE mutation causes autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome. The medulla also contains Hassall’s corpuscles, where mTECs express thymic stromal lymphopoietin (TSLP); TSLP prompts dendritic cells to drive a small subset of thymocytes to express FoxP3 and become regulatory T cells (Tregs).</p><p>Medulla = mTECs + dendritic cells (self-peptide for negative selection) using AIRE; AIRE mutation → autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome. (medulla / AIRE) CQ Hassall’s corpuscles → mTEC TSLP → DCs induce FoxP3 → Tregs. (Hassall’s / TSLP / Tregs)</p><p>Inner medulla: Hassall’s corpuscles express TSLP, which triggers DCs to induce FoxP3+ regulatory T cells.</p><p>mTECs express AIRE (autoimmune regulator) to display tissue-restricted self-antigens for negative selection.</p><p>WHY THIS MATTERS. The component list is really a map: if a question places an event in the cortex, the actors are cTECs/DCs/macrophages and the step is build or positive selection; if in the medulla, the actors are mTECs/DCs (with AIRE) and Hassall’s corpuscles, and the step is negative selection or Treg induction. AIRE and FoxP3 are the two named molecules most likely to be tested, each tied to a clinical consequence (autoimmunity when AIRE fails; tolerance when FoxP3 drives Tregs).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Location = function. cTECs (cortex): Notch ligand + IL-7, then positive selection. mTECs (medulla): AIRE-driven self-antigen for negative selection. Hassall’s corpuscles → TSLP → Tregs.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Don’t swap cTECs and mTECs. cTEC = cortex = positive selection; mTEC = medulla = negative selection (with AIRE). The first letters line up: c-cortex, m-medulla.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Two named molecules carry clinical weight: AIRE (loss → autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome) and FoxP3 (drives Tregs; its failure → loss of tolerance). Expect both on an exam.</p><p>ReClaude A: Cortical thymic epithelial cells (cTECs) sit in the cortex and mediate positive selection (after first providing Notch ligand and IL-7); medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTECs) sit in the medulla and mediate negative selection, using AIRE to express tissue-restricted self-antigens. Same MHC-presentation activity, opposite halves of education, different regions.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_29": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Both lineages rearrange their TCR genes in the cortex, yet only one runs the full selection gauntlet. Which one skips it, where does it branch off, and what is it built to do?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Most of this lecture followed the αβ lineage; this LO contrasts it with the γδ minority. The unifying idea: αβ cells are the heavily-educated majority built for MHC-restricted, body-wide surveillance, while γδ cells are an early-branching minority that skip selection and guard barrier tissues. The split happens early, and the developmental shortcut matches their different job.</p><p>THE αβ PATH (the default). αβ thymocytes are ~95–97% of T cells. They run the full program from this lecture: DN stages, both checkpoints, the double-positive stage, then positive and negative selection, emerging as MHC-restricted single-positive CD4 or CD8 cells. They populate the entire body and can recognize essentially any peptide on MHC.</p><p>THE γδ PATH (the shortcut). The γ, δ, and β genes attempt rearrangement simultaneously; if a successful γδ TCR forms (before β succeeds, or because both β alleles failed), the cell commits to the γδ lineage and exits the thymus early — around DN2/DN3 — without positive or negative selection. γδ cells therefore remain largely double-negative (CD4− CD8−; rare CD8+ examples exist, never CD4+). They are enriched in mucosa and skin (gut, lung), are more prominent before birth (helping infants guard developing mucosa/flora), have a less diverse repertoire with preferred V/D/J combinations, and can recognize lipid antigens on CD1 — fitting targets like mycobacterial lipids at barrier surfaces.</p><p>αβ = ~95%, full selection → single-positive, body-wide, MHC-restricted. (αβ path) CQ γδ = exit at DN2/DN3 without selection, stay double-negative, mucosa/skin, CD1 lipids, more pre-birth. (γδ path)</p><p>γδ thymocytes branch off around DN2/DN3 and exit prior to positive/negative selection, remaining double-negative.</p><p>All thymocytes start double-negative; γδ cells exit early to periphery without the selection steps αβ cells undergo.</p><p>Summary: nearly every step is in the cortex; only the second negative-selection round (single-positive) is in the medulla.</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST — and a useful summary trick. Answering the anchor: the γδ lineage skips selection, branches off early (around DN2/DN3 in the cortex), stays double-negative, and is built to guard mucosa and skin using CD1-presented lipids. Davis offered a memory shortcut for the whole lecture: on the summary chart, almost everything happens in the cortex — the only step in the medulla is the second (single-positive) round of negative selection. So if a question asks where any stage (DN1–4, positive selection, death by neglect, the first negative round, γδ exit) occurs, the answer is the cortex unless it is specifically that single-positive medullary round. Memorize the short list (the one medullary step) and everything else is cortex by elimination.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> γδ cells do NOT undergo positive or negative selection — they leave early and stay double-negative. Don’t apply MHC restriction or CD4/CD8 commitment to them.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> αβ: ~95%, fully selected, single-positive, body-wide. γδ: minority, NO positive/negative selection, exits at DN2/DN3, stays double-negative, mucosa/skin, CD1 lipids, more before birth.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Summary shortcut: only the single-positive negative-selection round is in the medulla; everything else (DN stages, positive selection, death by neglect, γδ exit) is in the cortex. Memorize the one exception.</p><p>ReClaude A: The γδ lineage skips selection: γ/δ/β genes rearrange together, and a successful γδ TCR makes the cell exit early — around DN2/DN3 in the cortex — without positive or negative selection, remaining double-negative. γδ cells guard mucosa and skin, are enriched before birth, and recognize lipid antigens on CD1. αβ cells, by contrast, run the full selection program and become MHC-restricted single-positive cells.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_30": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A naive T cell meets its antigen on a dendritic cell, yet nothing happens — no clone army. Two explanations: the DC was immature, or a signal was missing. What are the three signals, and which two does an immature DC fail to deliver?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This is where antigen presentation (Lec 7) and the receptors (Lec 8–10) get put to use: the dendritic cell presents antigen, and the T cell responds. The unifying idea is a three-signal rule delivered by a mature APC: signal 1 = antigen, signal 2 = co-stimulation, signal 3 = cytokine. Signals 1+2 build the clone army; signal 3 weaponizes it. Miss a signal — or use an immature DC that cannot give signals 2 and 3 — and you get anergy, not activation.</p><p>THE THREE PROFESSIONAL APCs. All three present antigen, but their jobs differ. Dendritic cells are THE primary primers: they capture antigen in tissue and traffic it to the lymph node to activate naive T cells. B cells present antigen too, but “selfishly” — not to activate the T cell, but to get close enough to receive help (the T-dependent antibody response). Macrophages stay in the tissue as phagocytic soldiers, presenting locally rather than migrating. Dendritic cells prime; macrophages fight and present at the target.</p><p>3 APCs: dendritic cells (prime naive T cells, traffic to node), B cells (present to GET help), macrophages (tissue soldiers, present locally). (three professional APCs) CQ Signal 1 = antigen/peptide-MHC→TCR; Signal 2 = CD28–B7 (B7 = CD80/CD86); Signal 3 = cytokine from APC. (the three signals)</p><p>Signal 3: the APC produces a cytokine that polarizes the T cell into Th1, Th2, or Th17.</p><p>Three signals essential for T-cell activation: signal 1 (antigen), signal 2 (co-stimulation), signal 3 (cytokine) — all from the APC.</p><p>Signal 2: microbial components/cytokines induce B7 (CD80/CD86) on the APC — co-stimulation binding CD28.</p><p>SIGNALS 1+2 vs SIGNAL 3. The division of labor is testable. Signals 1 and 2 together drive clonal expansion — the proliferation (IL-2-driven) that builds a large army of T cells all recognizing the same antigen. Signal 3, the cytokine, drives differentiation — it tells the army which weapon to carry, polarizing the cells into Th1, Th2, or Th17 depending on the pathogen class. Without signal 3 you would have an army with no guns; without signals 1+2 you would have no army at all.</p><p>WHY DC MATURATION IS THE GATEKEEPER. An immature DC captures antigen well but expresses little B7 and makes no cytokine — so it can give signal 1 but not signals 2 and 3. Something must mature it, classically TLR signaling (sensing danger), which upregulates CD80/CD86, switches on cytokine genes, and raises MHC. Only a mature DC supplies all three signals. Prime a T cell on an immature DC and it becomes anergic — no clone army — which is exactly one way tumors evade immunity (they block DC maturation).</p><p>Signals 1+2 → clonal expansion (build the army); signal 3 → differentiation (Th1/Th2/Th17 — the weapon). (expansion vs differentiation) CQ Immature DC = signal 1 only → anergy; TLR signaling matures the DC → B7 + cytokine + MHC → all three signals. (DC maturation gate)</p><p>Signals 1+2 = proliferation (clone army); signal 3 = differentiation (weapons) into the effector T cell.</p><p>Maturation of the DC is required: immature DCs capture antigen; mature DCs present it with full co-stimulation.</p><p>Process overview: naive T-cell activation → clonal expansion → T-cell differentiation into effector subsets.</p><p>PRIMING AND THE TWO-PRESENTATION RULE. A subtle point Gregg stresses (textbooks gloss it): priming activates the T cell but withholds effector release. If a freshly primed cell dumped cytokine in the lymph node, systemic TNF-alpha would activate endothelium everywhere and you would bleed to death. So the effector cell leaves the node and must see antigen a second time in the tissue (e.g., on a macrophage) to release cytokine locally, at the target. CD8 cells are likewise primed in the node but only kill once they reach infected tissue — otherwise they would lyse everything in their path.</p><p>SPECIALTY ANTIGENS (the activation curveballs). Superantigens cross-link the TCR V-beta to MHC class II outside the peptide groove, forcing signaling regardless of specificity → polyclonal activation and a cytokine storm (IL-1/IL-6/TNF-alpha); the SARS-CoV-2 spike encodes one (COVID hyperinflammation), and bacterial versions cause toxic shock. Mitogens are polyclonal lab activators that bypass the antigen receptor by binding downstream signaling molecules or TLRs — used to test immune function. Haptens are small molecules that become immunogenic only when coupled to protein (e.g., penicillin on red cells → drug-induced hemolytic anemia; contact dermatitis).</p><p>Priming = activated but effectors withheld; must see antigen a 2nd time in tissue to release locally (avoids systemic TNF-alpha). (two-presentation rule) CQ Superantigen = V-beta–MHC-II cross-link → polyclonal storm; mitogen = lab polyclonal activator; hapten = small molecule + protein. (specialty antigens)</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three signals from a mature APC: 1 = antigen (peptide-MHC→TCR), 2 = CD28–B7 (CD80/CD86), 3 = cytokine. Signals 1+2 → expansion; signal 3 → Th1/Th2/Th17 differentiation.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Don’t conflate the APCs: dendritic cells prime naive T cells; B cells present to GET help (selfish, T-dependent); macrophages stay in tissue presenting locally. Only the mature DC gives all three signals.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Priming ≠ effector release. A primed cell needs a second antigen encounter in tissue to act locally — otherwise systemic TNF-alpha would be lethal. This is why we don’t bleed to death every immune response.</p><p>ReClaude A: The three signals are antigen (signal 1, peptide-MHC→TCR), co-stimulation (signal 2, CD28 binding B7 = CD80/CD86), and a cytokine from the APC (signal 3). An immature dendritic cell delivers only signal 1 — it lacks B7 and makes no cytokine, so it fails signals 2 and 3 — and priming on it yields anergy rather than a clone army. TLR-driven maturation is what licenses the DC to deliver all three.</p><p><em>Trace the signal from a ligated TCR to the IL-2 gene. Which single kinase is the indispensable hub — the one whose loss abolishes the entire T-cell response — and what three transcription factors finally switch IL-2 on?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Signals 1 and 2 trigger an intracellular relay that ends at the IL-2 gene. The unifying idea is a proximal-to-distal cascade with one bottleneck (ZAP-70) that then branches into three transcription-factor arms, all of which must fire to transcribe IL-2. Learn the spine of the cascade and the three branch points and you can place any drug or deficiency on the map.</p><p>PROXIMAL SIGNALING. The TCR itself barely signals — the work is done by the associated CD3 complex and zeta chains, whose cytoplasmic ITAMs get phosphorylated. The kinase LCK (lymphocyte-specific protein tyrosine kinase), brought in by the CD4/CD8 co-receptor, phosphorylates those ITAMs, creating docking sites for ZAP-70. ZAP-70 is the hub: if ZAP-70 is deficient, there is no T-cell response. Active ZAP-70 then phosphorylates LAT (linker of activated T cells), the scaffold that launches the downstream branches. Adhesion molecules (LFA-1–ICAM-1) hold the DC–T contact together long enough for this to assemble.</p><p>TCR doesn’t signal — CD3 + zeta ITAMs do; LCK phosphorylates ITAMs → docks ZAP-70 (loss → no response) → phosphorylates LAT. (proximal cascade) CQ Adhesion (LFA-1–ICAM-1) sustains DC–T contact time; CD4/CD8 co-receptor brings in LCK and stabilizes peptide-MHC. (adhesion / co-receptor)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Active ZAP-70 phosphorylates LAT, branching into the MAPK, NF-kB, and NFAT pathways.</p><p>TCR + CD28 engagement: CD3 and the zeta chains serve as the TCR’s signaling complex (ITAMs phosphorylated).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> LCK phosphorylates CD3/zeta ITAMs, recruiting ZAP-70 — the critical docking kinase (deficiency → no response).</p><p>THE THREE TRANSCRIPTION-FACTOR ARMS. From LAT the signal splits three ways, all converging on IL-2. (1) NF-kB arm: protein kinase C (PKC) activates IkB kinase, which phosphorylates IkB; IkB is degraded, freeing NF-kB to enter the nucleus. (2) NFAT arm: phospholipase C makes IP3 → Ca2+ release → Ca2+ binds calmodulin → calmodulin activates calcineurin → calcineurin dephosphorylates NFAT, letting it enter the nucleus. (3) AP-1 arm: RAS/RAC GTPases drive the MAPK pathway (ERK/JNK) → c-Fos + c-Jun assemble into AP-1. All three bind the IL-2 promoter — and all three are required; block any one and the response is crippled. (Two of these arms are the drug targets in the next LO.)</p><p>Three arms to IL-2: PKC→NF-kB; Ca2+→calmodulin→calcineurin→NFAT; RAS/RAC→MAPK→AP-1. All required. (three TF arms)</p><p>NF-kB arm: PKC → IkB kinase → phosphorylates IkB → frees NF-kB → nucleus (glucocorticoid target).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> NFAT arm: Ca2+ → calmodulin → calcineurin dephosphorylates NFAT → nucleus (cyclosporine target).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> AP-1 arm: RAS/RAC → MAPK (ERK/JNK) → c-Fos + c-Jun = AP-1; all three arms converge on the IL-2 gene.</p><p>IL-2 AND INDUCED SURFACE PROTEINS. IL-2 is the payoff of the cascade (CD4 cells are the main producers; CD8 expansion depends on CD4 IL-2). IL-2 (1) drives clonal expansion, (2) induces anti-apoptotic BCL proteins that block BAK/BAX pores (any strongly stimulated cell defaults to apoptosis unless rescued), and (3) upregulates the IL-2 receptor alpha chain = CD25, transiently, opening a window for expansion. Meanwhile CD28 co-stimulation amplifies TCR signaling (without it, signal is too weak) — making CD28 a transplant-drug target. CD40 ligand appears too: it drives B-cell help and class switching beyond IgM, and can mature bystander DCs.</p><p>BRAKES ON THE RESPONSE. Expansion cannot run forever (that would be lymphoma), so inhibitory receptors rise ~day 3–4. CTLA-4 outcompetes CD28 for B7 (removing co-stimulation) AND recruits a phosphatase that strips the CD3/zeta ITAM phosphates — shutting down signaling. PD-1 binds its ligand on the APC and likewise recruits phosphatases. Together they convert exponential growth into a plateau, then contraction — and they reappear later as central tolerance / checkpoint-therapy targets.</p><p>IL-2: clonal expansion + anti-apoptotic BCL + upregulates CD25 (IL-2Rα, transient). CD4 is the main IL-2 source. (IL-2 actions) CQ CD28 amplifies TCR; brakes CTLA-4 (outcompetes CD28 for B7 + phosphatase) and PD-1 arrest expansion ~day 3–4. (amplifier and brakes)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> IL-2 actions: drives clonal expansion, induces anti-apoptotic BCL (survival), and prepares cells for signal 3. Brakes: CTLA-4 and PD-1 rise ~day 3–4 to arrest expansion (outcompete CD28 / recruit phosphatases).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Spine: CD3/zeta ITAMs → LCK → ZAP-70 → LAT → three arms (NF-kB, NFAT, AP-1) → IL-2. ZAP-70 is the indispensable hub; all three transcription factors are required.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> The TCR does not signal itself — CD3 and the zeta chains carry the ITAMs. And IL-2 upregulates CD25 (IL-2Rα), which is transient, not permanent.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Brakes vs gas: CD28 amplifies (gas); CTLA-4 and PD-1 brake (recruit phosphatases ~day 3–4). CTLA-4 also outcompetes CD28 for B7. Same B7, opposite effect.</p><p>ReClaude A: The indispensable hub is ZAP-70: after LCK phosphorylates the CD3/zeta ITAMs, ZAP-70 docks and phosphorylates LAT — lose ZAP-70 and the entire response fails. The cascade then branches into three transcription-factor arms — NF-kB (via PKC), NFAT (via Ca2+/calmodulin/calcineurin), and AP-1 (via MAPK) — all of which bind the IL-2 promoter and all of which are required.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_32": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Two immunosuppressants both lower IL-2 and dampen T cells, but they hit different arms of the same cascade. One blocks NF-kB; the other freezes NFAT in the cytoplasm. Name each drug and its precise target.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. This LO maps two drug classes onto the signaling cascade from LO 11.2. The unifying idea: both drugs reduce IL-2 transcription, but by hitting different transcription-factor arms — glucocorticoids on the NF-kB arm, cyclosporine on the NFAT arm. Because all three arms are required for IL-2, knocking out either one cripples clonal expansion.</p><p>GLUCOCORTICOIDS — block NF-kB. Glucocorticoids block NF-kB activation/mobilization. Since NF-kB drives pro-inflammatory cytokine genes (in both innate cells and T cells), blocking it produces broad anti-inflammatory effects — hence glucocorticoids are used for allergies, asthma, autoimmune disease, and sepsis. On the T-cell cascade, no NF-kB means one of the three required IL-2 inputs is missing.</p><p>CYCLOSPORINE — inhibit calcineurin. Cyclosporine inhibits calcineurin. Normally Ca2+ → calmodulin → calcineurin dephosphorylates NFAT so it can enter the nucleus. With calcineurin blocked, NFAT stays phosphorylated in the cytoplasm and never reaches the IL-2 promoter — IL-2 falls, clonal expansion is impaired, and the anti-graft response is blunted. This is why cyclosporine is a mainstay in organ transplantation.</p><p>Glucocorticoids → block NF-kB (broad anti-inflammatory: allergy/asthma/autoimmune/sepsis). (glucocorticoid target) CQ Cyclosporine → inhibit calcineurin → NFAT stuck phosphorylated in cytoplasm → less IL-2 (transplant drug). (cyclosporine target)</p><p>Cyclosporine inhibits calcineurin, so NFAT cannot be dephosphorylated and stays out of the nucleus.</p><p>Both targets sit on the TCR-driven cascade that converges on the IL-2 gene for clonal expansion.</p><p>Glucocorticoids block NF-kB activation — reducing pro-inflammatory cytokine and IL-2 transcription.</p><p>Glucocorticoids NF-kB (blocks activation) Less pro-inflammatory cytokine + IL-2 Allergy, asthma, autoimmune, sepsis</p><p>Cyclosporine Calcineurin (inhibits) NFAT stays phosphorylated → less IL-2 Organ transplantation</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Keep the two arms straight: glucocorticoid → NF-kB; cyclosporine → calcineurin → NFAT. A clean memory hook is that cyclosporine hits calcineurin. Both ultimately lower IL-2 because the IL-2 promoter needs all three transcription factors (NF-kB, NFAT, AP-1); remove either NF-kB or NFAT and IL-2 transcription fails, so clonal expansion — and any T-cell-driven inflammation or rejection — is suppressed.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Don’t swap them. Memory hook: cyclosporine → calcineurin → NFAT. Glucocorticoids are the NF-kB blockers (broad anti-inflammatory).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two arms, two drugs: glucocorticoids block NF-kB; cyclosporine inhibits calcineurin (so NFAT can’t enter the nucleus). Both lower IL-2 → less clonal expansion.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Why it works: the IL-2 promoter needs all three (NF-kB + NFAT + AP-1). Disable either NF-kB or NFAT and IL-2 transcription collapses — no clone army, dampened rejection.</p><p>ReClaude A: Glucocorticoids block NF-kB activation (broad anti-inflammatory, used for allergy/asthma/autoimmune/sepsis); cyclosporine inhibits calcineurin, so NFAT stays phosphorylated in the cytoplasm and cannot transcribe IL-2 (used in transplantation). Both lower IL-2 because the IL-2 promoter requires all three transcription factors.</p><p><em>After a response resolves, three T-cell fates exist: short-lived effectors and two memory types. Two markers — one for survival, one for homing — sort them all out. Which marker does which job, and which cell is which?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. After expansion and the plateau, the T-cell population contracts (most effectors die), leaving a memory pool. The unifying idea is two markers, two jobs: IL-7R governs survival (who lives long-term) and CCR7 governs lymph-node homing (who stays central vs goes to tissue). Reading those two markers tells you the cell’s identity and behavior.</p><p>IL-7R — the survival switch. Naive T cells are IL-7R+, which keeps them alive in the lymph node/spleen. On activation, short-lived effector cells lose IL-7R (and CCR7) — they are IL-7R− CCR7−, go to tissue, act, and then die by apoptosis during contraction. Memory cells, by contrast, retain IL-7R, giving them the survival signal to persist long-term until the next encounter.</p><p>IL-7R = survival. Naive IL-7R+; effectors lose it (IL-7R− → short-lived); memory retains it (long-lived). (IL-7R / survival)</p><p>Population dynamics: expansion → plateau → contraction (effectors die) → a persistent memory pool remains.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Naive (IL-7R+ CCR7+) → effector (IL-7R− CCR7−, tissue, apoptosis) or memory (IL-7R+); memory splits by CCR7.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Effector and effector-memory cells use selectins/integrins/chemokine receptors to migrate into tissues.</p><p>CCR7 — the homing switch (central vs effector memory). Within the IL-7R+ memory pool, CCR7 splits the two memory subsets. Central-memory cells (T_CM) keep CCR7 — CCR7 is the receptor that homes cells to lymph nodes, so T_CM remain in the lymph nodes/spleen as a reservoir, ready to re-expand and generate fresh effectors if a response is insufficient. Effector-memory cells (T_EM) lose CCR7 — so they leave the lymph nodes and patrol peripheral tissues, poised for a rapid local recall response at sites of likely re-exposure (skin, gut, lung).</p><p>Naive + + Lymph node; awaiting first antigen</p><p>Effector − − Tissue; acts then dies (short-lived)</p><p>Central memory (T_CM) + + Lymph node reservoir; re-expands</p><p>Effector memory (T_EM) + − Tissue patrol; rapid local recall</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Two markers do all the work: IL-7R = survival (memory keeps it, effectors lose it) and CCR7 = lymph-node homing (central-memory keeps it and stays central; effector-memory loses it and goes to tissue). So T_CM = IL-7R+ CCR7+ (reservoir) and T_EM = IL-7R+ CCR7− (tissue patrol); a short-lived effector is IL-7R− CCR7−. The single most common confusion is thinking IL-7R distinguishes the memory subsets — it does not (both retain it); CCR7 is the subset discriminator.</p><p>CCR7 = lymph-node homing. T_CM CCR7+ (stay = reservoir); T_EM CCR7− (tissue = local recall). Both are IL-7R+. (CCR7 / memory split)</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> IL-7R does NOT separate the memory subsets — both T_CM and T_EM keep it. CCR7 is the discriminator (central keeps it, effector-memory loses it).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CCR7 is your ticket into the lymph node. Keep it → you stay central (T_CM, reservoir). Lose it → you head to the tissues (T_EM, fast local recall). Naive cells also need CCR7 to enter the node.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two markers: IL-7R = survival (memory+, effector−); CCR7 = lymph-node homing (T_CM+, T_EM−). So T_CM = IL-7R+CCR7+ (reservoir), T_EM = IL-7R+CCR7− (tissue), effector = IL-7R−CCR7−.</p><p>ReClaude A: IL-7R marks survival: memory cells retain it (long-lived), short-lived effectors lose it. CCR7 marks lymph-node homing: central-memory cells (T_CM) keep CCR7 and stay in the lymph nodes as a reservoir, while effector-memory cells (T_EM) lose CCR7 and patrol tissues for rapid local recall. So T_CM = IL-7R+ CCR7+, T_EM = IL-7R+</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CCR7−, and an effector = IL-7R− CCR7−.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_33": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Three patients: one with an intracellular mycobacterial infection, one with an intestinal parasitic worm, one with an extracellular bacterial infection. Which helper subset leads each, which signature cytokines and effector cells does it deploy, and is the response pro- or anti-inflammatory?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Each subset is a specialist matched to a pathogen class. The unifying idea: Th1 fights intracellular pathogens (pro-inflammatory, macrophage-powered); Th2 fights parasitic worms (largely anti-inflammatory, IgE/eosinophil/M2-powered); Th17 fights extracellular bacteria (neutrophil-powered, barrier-reinforcing). The CD8 versions (Tc1/Tc2/Tc17) share the profiles but mainly kill. Read each subset as</p><p>target → cytokines → effector cells → tone.</p><p>TH1 — intracellular pathogens, macrophage activation. Th1 makes IFN-gamma, IL-2, and TNF-alpha and targets intracellular pathogens. Its central act is IFN-gamma activating macrophages: it drives M1 polarization and ramps up NADPH oxidase and iNOS, flooding the phagosome with ROS/RNS to overwhelm even catalase-positive organisms, and it raises MHC I and B7 (do your job, or be killed by a CD8 cell). IFN-gamma needs a partner — CD40 ligand from the T cell — for full macrophage killing. IL-2 also expands/activates NK cells; TNF-alpha sustains inflammation and, chronically, drives apoptosis (a basis of T-cell-mediated autoimmune damage).</p><p>Th1 (IFN-gamma/IL-2/TNF-alpha) → intracellular pathogens; IFN-gamma → M1 + NADPH oxidase/iNOS (ROS/RNS) + ↑MHC I/B7. (Th1 functions) CQ IFN-gamma needs CD40 ligand for full macrophage killing; Th1 is pro-inflammatory. (IFN-gamma + CD40L)</p><p>Th1 activates macrophages via IFN-gamma + CD40L signaling → killing of intracellular bacteria.</p><p>Major Th1 cytokines: IL-2 (clonal expansion + NK), IFN-gamma (macrophage activation), TNF-alpha (inflammation).</p><p>IFN-gamma effects: M1 polarization, more NADPH oxidase/iNOS (ROS/RNS), ↑MHC I — making the macrophage a better killer and a CD8 target.</p><p>TH2 — parasitic worms, anti-inflammatory and healing. Th2 makes IL-4, IL-5, and IL-13 and targets parasitic worms; overall it is anti-inflammatory and promotes wound healing. IL-4 drives B-cell IgE, which arms mast cells (Fc-epsilon receptors) to degranulate and create the inflammation that recruits worm-killers. IL-5 recruits and activates eosinophils — the parasite specialists that can reach the gut lumen and degranulate on IgE-coated worms. IL-4 + IL-13 together polarize macrophages to M2 (healing, apoptotic-cell cleanup) and drive worm expulsion (mucus + peristalsis → diarrhea; the same axis underlies allergic diarrhea). Crucially, IFN-gamma and IL-4 are mutually antagonistic — each suppresses the other, the molecular basis of the pro- vs anti-inflammatory seesaw.</p><p>Th2 (IL-4/IL-5/IL-13) → parasitic worms; IL-4→IgE→mast cells; IL-5→eosinophils; IL-4+IL-13→M2 + expulsion. (Th2 functions) CQ IFN-gamma ↔ IL-4 mutual antagonism: Th1 pro-inflammatory vs Th2 anti-inflammatory / wound-healing. (Th1–Th2 seesaw)</p><p>IL-4: drives B-cell IgE production (arming mast cells via Fc-epsilon receptors).</p><p>IL-5: recruits and activates eosinophils — the parasite specialists able to reach the gut lumen.</p><p>IL-13 (with IL-4): M2 polarization (wound healing, anti-inflammatory) and worm expulsion in the intestine.</p><p>Macrophage polarization: IFN-gamma → M1 (pro-inflammatory killing) vs IL-4/IL-13 → M2 (healing, cleanup).</p><p>TH17 — extracellular bacteria, neutrophils and barrier. Th17 makes IL-17 and IL-22 and targets extracellular bacteria (a mucosal, heavily inflammatory program). IL-17 itself does little directly — it triggers epithelial/stromal cells to release cytokines and growth factors that recruit and activate neutrophils (the anti-extracellular-bacteria effector) and pull in macrophages/DCs. IL-22 reinforces the barrier: it induces antimicrobial peptides (e.g., defensins), supports wound healing, and can loosen tight junctions to flush pathogens (watery diarrhea). The mucosal context matters — TGF-beta normally keeps the gut tolerant (favoring IgA and suppression), but when a pathogen overgrows, IL-6 rises and flips the program to ROR-gamma-T / Th17.</p><p>Th17 (IL-17/IL-22) → extracellular bacteria; IL-17 → neutrophil recruitment; IL-22 → antimicrobial peptides + barrier. (Th17 functions)</p><p>IL-17: triggers epithelial cytokines/growth factors that recruit and activate neutrophils against extracellular bacteria.</p><p>IL-22: induces antimicrobial peptides (defensins), reinforces the epithelial barrier, supports wound healing.</p><p>Major Th17 cytokines IL-17 and IL-22 — a mucosal, neutrophil-oriented, barrier-protective program.</p><p>Subset Cytokines Target Key effectors / tone</p><p>Th1 / Tc1 IFN-gamma, IL-2, TNF-alpha Intracellular pathogens M1 macrophages, ROS/RNS; pro-inflammatory</p><p>Th2 / Tc2 IL-4, IL-5, IL-13 Parasitic worms IgE/mast cells, eosinophils, M2; anti-inflammatory</p><p>Th17 / Tc17 IL-17, IL-22 Extracellular bacteria Neutrophils, barrier peptides; inflammatory</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Answering the three patients: the mycobacterial (intracellular) case is Th1 — IFN-gamma/IL-2/TNF-alpha, M1 macrophages and ROS, pro-inflammatory; the intestinal worm case is Th2 — IL-4/IL-5/IL-13, IgE/mast cells and eosinophils with M2 healing, largely anti-inflammatory (with a local inflammatory carve-out to bring eosinophils in); the extracellular bacterial case is Th17 — IL-17/IL-22, neutrophils and barrier peptides, inflammatory. Map each subset by its target pathogen first; the cytokines and effector cells follow from there, and the inflammatory tone (Th1/Th17 pro-, Th2 anti-) falls out of the IFN-gamma–IL-4 antagonism.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> The seesaw: IFN-gamma ↔ IL-4 suppress each other. Th1/Th17 are pro-inflammatory; Th2 is anti-inflammatory and healing. A Th1 response often resolves into a Th2 wound-healing phase.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Don’t cross the effector cells: eosinophils = Th2 (worms), neutrophils = Th17 (extracellular bacteria), M1 macrophages = Th1 (intracellular). Each subset, its own foot soldier.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Target-first: Th1 = intracellular (IFN-gamma, M1/ROS); Th2 = worms (IL-4/5/13, IgE/eosinophils/M2); Th17 = extracellular bacteria (IL-17/22, neutrophils/barrier).</p><p>ReClaude A: The mycobacterial (intracellular) case is led by Th1 — IFN-gamma/IL-2/TNF-alpha, M1 macrophages with ROS/RNS, pro-inflammatory. The worm case is Th2 — IL-4/IL-5/IL-13, IgE-armed mast cells and eosinophils with M2 healing, largely anti-inflammatory. The extracellular bacterial case is Th17 — IL-17/IL-22, neutrophil recruitment and barrier antimicrobial peptides, inflammatory. CD8 Tc1/Tc2/Tc17 share the profiles but mainly kill.</p><p><em>A CD8 T cell can kill a target two ways. One punches a hole to deliver enzymes; the other flips a death switch on the target’s surface. Name both pathways, the key molecules in each, and the one protein a tumor can use to block the second.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. A cytotoxic T cell kills by two routes that converge on caspases and apoptosis but enter differently. The unifying idea: perforin/granzyme delivers killer enzymes through a pore (TCR/MHC-I-directed); Fas/FasL flips a death receptor that builds the DISC and activates caspase-8. Both end in clean, low-inflammation apoptosis — and the death-receptor route has a built-in off-switch (c-FLIP) that tumors and viruses exploit.</p><p>PERFORIN / GRANZYME — the pore-and-enzyme route. After the CTL engages MHC I + antigen on the target, it releases granules. Perforin polymerizes into a pore (in the membrane or an endosome), creating a conduit for granzymes to enter the cytosol. Granzymes then activate caspases, producing DNA fragmentation and apoptotic-body formation (blebbing). Because apoptotic bodies display phosphatidylserine and are cleared by macrophages, this is a quiet, low-inflammation kill — the body removes the infected cell without collateral damage. This route is TCR/MHC-I-directed: the CTL needs to see the target’s class I.</p><p>Perforin/granzyme: needs MHC I + antigen; perforin pore → granzymes enter → caspases → apoptosis (DNA fragmentation + blebbing). (perforin/granzyme route) CQ Perforin/granzyme is a quiet, low-inflammation kill (apoptotic bodies cleared by macrophages). (quiet apoptosis)</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CTL engages MHC I + antigen on the target, then releases perforin + granzyme to induce apoptosis.</p><p>Perforin/granzyme: perforin polymerizes into pores; granzymes diffuse into the cytosol → caspases → DNA fragmentation + blebbing.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> CTL recognition of microbial antigen increases Fas-ligand expression — setting up the death-receptor route.</p><p>FAS / FAS-LIGAND — the death-receptor route. The CTL upregulates Fas ligand (FasL) on activation; it binds Fas — a stress receptor that infected or tumor cells upregulate — on the target. FasL–Fas binding assembles the DISC (death-inducing signaling complex), which activates caspase-8 (the initiator — Gregg said to remember it). Caspase-8 then cleaves effector caspases-3, -6, and -7 (mainly -3), producing the same CAD-mediated DNA fragmentation and blebbing. This route can fire independent of the TCR but works better with it. Its off-switch is c-FLIP: c-FLIP outcompetes caspase-8 at the complex (and the analogous TNF-alpha complex), blocking activation. c-FLIP is induced by NF-kB/cytokine signaling — so a tumor (or virus like HIV) that drives c-FLIP, plus drops MHC I, escapes both killing routes.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Fas/FasL: FasL binds Fas → DISC assembles → caspase-8 activated → effector caspases-3/6/7 → DNA fragmentation + blebbing. c-FLIP blocks the death-receptor route by outcompeting caspase-8 at the complex — a tumor/virus escape mechanism.</p><p>Feature Perforin / granzyme Fas / Fas-ligand</p><p>Trigger TCR sees MHC I + antigen FasL binds Fas (stress receptor); can be TCR-independent</p><p>Entry / complex Perforin pore → granzymes enter DISC assembles at the receptor</p><p>Key caspase Caspases (via granzyme) Caspase-8 → caspase-3/6/7</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Both routes end in caspase-driven apoptosis, but: perforin/granzyme is the pore-and-enzyme, strictly MHC-I/TCR-directed route (granzymes activate caspases after entering); Fas/FasL is the death-receptor route (DISC → caspase-8 → effectors), which can be TCR-independent and is uniquely blockable by c-FLIP. The clinical payoff (answering the anchor): a tumor escapes Fas killing by upregulating c-FLIP, and escapes perforin/granzyme by downregulating MHC I — disabling both routes at once.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Caspase-8 is the death-receptor initiator (remember it). c-FLIP outcompetes it to block Fas/TNF-alpha apoptosis — induced by NF-kB/cytokine, exploited by tumors and HIV.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> Don’t swap entry points: perforin makes the pore; granzymes are the enzymes that trigger caspases. The Fas route needs no pore — it signals through the receptor/DISC.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two routes, one endpoint: perforin pore → granzymes → caspases (MHC-I/TCR-directed); FasL–Fas → DISC → caspase-8 → caspase-3/6/7. Both → apoptosis (DNA fragmentation + blebbing).</p><p>ReClaude A: Route 1 is perforin/granzyme: after the CTL sees MHC I + antigen, perforin forms a pore and granzymes enter to activate caspases → apoptosis. Route 2 is Fas/FasL: FasL on the CTL binds Fas on the target → DISC → caspase-8 → effector caspases. A tumor blocks the second route with c-FLIP (which outcompetes caspase-8), and blocks the first by downregulating MHC I.</p><p><em>When the pathogen is cleared, the effector army must shrink. Two mechanisms do it: one is a passive consequence of losing cytokine support, the other is an active suicide. Name both, their key molecules, and which cells survive.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. After expansion (IL-2) and the CTLA-4/PD-1 plateau, the response enters contraction — most effectors die so the tissue is not inflamed forever. The unifying idea: two death routes shrink the army — passive (cytokine-withdrawal, intrinsic/mitochondrial) and active (AICD, Fas/FasL) — and memory cells are spared both.</p><p>PASSIVE CELL DEATH — cytokine withdrawal (intrinsic). Any strongly activated cell is pre-programmed to die via mitochondrial BAK/BAX pores — a cancer-prevention failsafe. While cytokine (e.g., IL-2) is present, it induces anti-apoptotic BCL-2, which blocks BAK/BAX pore formation and prevents MOMP (mitochondrial outer membrane permeabilization). As the antigen clears, cytokine falls, BCL-2 drops, BAK/BAX pores open → MOMP → cytochrome C release → apoptosome → caspase-3 → apoptosis. This is “death by neglect” for the effector — it dies because its survival signal disappeared. Tumors subvert this by overexpressing BCL-2 to stay alive despite self-driven proliferation.</p><p>Passive (cytokine-withdrawal) death: cytokine↓ → BCL-2↓ → BAK/BAX pores → MOMP → cytochrome C → caspase-3. (passive cell death) CQ Tumors overexpress BCL-2 to block MOMP and resist apoptosis despite constitutive activation. (BCL-2 in cancer)</p><p>Passive death: loss of growth/cytokine signal → BCL-2 falls → BAK/BAX pores → MOMP → cytochrome C → apoptosis.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Two mechanisms of lymphocyte apoptosis during contraction: passive (mitochondrial) and activation-induced.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Activation-induced cell death: Fas/FasL on activated T cells drives T-cell-to-T-cell suicide as the response resolves.</p><p>ACTIVATION-INDUCED CELL DEATH (AICD) — Fas/FasL suicide. The active route uses the same death-receptor machinery from LO 12.3. Activated T cells (CD4 and CD8) upregulate both Fas and Fas ligand — FasL quickly, Fas more slowly. Over time, as Fas accumulates on the surface, activated T cells engage each other Fas-to-FasL and kill one another — a suicide that drives contraction. AICD is itself cytokine-driven (cytokines upregulate Fas and FasL), and it can be blocked by c-FLIP just like the killing route. The cells spared from both passive death and AICD are the memory T cells (kept alive by IL-7R signaling), which persist for the next encounter.</p><p>Feature Passive (cytokine withdrawal) Activation-induced (AICD)</p><p>Trigger Loss of cytokine/BCL-2 support Fas/FasL engagement (T cell–T cell)</p><p>Key molecules BCL-2 ↓ → BAK/BAX → MOMP → cytochrome C Fas + FasL → DISC → caspase-8</p><p>Type Intrinsic (mitochondrial) Extrinsic (death receptor)</p><p>Spared cells Memory T cells Memory T cells</p><p>THE TESTABLE CONTRAST. Answering the anchor: passive cell death is the intrinsic, mitochondrial route — cytokine withdrawal lowers BCL-2, so BAK/BAX open pores (MOMP → cytochrome C → caspase-3); AICD is the extrinsic, death-receptor route — Fas/FasL drives T-cell-to-T-cell suicide via caspase-8. Both clear effectors during contraction; memory T cells survive both. A clean split: passive = “lost my survival signal” (BCL-2/mitochondria); AICD = “told to die” (Fas/FasL/caspase-8).</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Mnemonic split: passive = “lost my survival signal” (mitochondrial, BCL-2); AICD = “told to die” (Fas/FasL, caspase-8). Cancer flips the first by overexpressing BCL-2.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> AICD is cytokine-driven (cytokines upregulate Fas/FasL) and uses the extrinsic (death-receptor) pathway — don’t confuse it with the intrinsic, cytokine-withdrawal route.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two contraction routes: passive (cytokine↓ → BCL-2↓ → BAK/BAX → MOMP → cytochrome C → caspase-3, intrinsic) and AICD (Fas/FasL → caspase-8, extrinsic). Memory cells survive both.</p><p>ReClaude A: Passive cell death is intrinsic: as antigen clears, cytokine and BCL-2 fall, so BAK/BAX form mitochondrial pores (MOMP) → cytochrome C → apoptosome → caspase-3. AICD is extrinsic: activated T cells upregulate Fas and FasL and kill each other (Fas→DISC→caspase-8) — a cytokine-driven suicide. Both drive contraction; memory T cells (IL-7R-supported) survive both.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_39": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A B cell starts out making IgM against a toxin and later makes IgG against the very same toxin with even higher affinity. Name the single enzyme behind both changes, and state what happened to the antibody’s specificity.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. ‘Isotype switching’ is the last step of a longer story, so this LO walks the whole T-dependent germinal-center reaction and lands on the switch. The through-line to hold onto: a single enzyme, AID (activation-induced deaminase), powers both the affinity-tuning mutations and the isotype switch. Everything else is choreography that gets the right cells together so AID can act.</p><p>FINDING EACH OTHER. Help happens in the interfollicular zone, between the T-cell paracortex and the B-cell follicle. A naive pre-TFH starts CXCR5−/CCR7+ (drawn to the T zone by DC-made CCL19/CCL21); a naive B cell is CXCR5+ (drawn to the follicle by FDC-made CXCL13). When each is activated by antigen, they reverse their chemokine receptors: the activated B cell turns CCR7 up / CXCR5 down and moves toward the T zone, while the activated pre-TFH turns CCR7 down / CXCR5 up and moves toward the follicle. They meet in between — a deliberate, reciprocal migration, not chance.</p><p>Reciprocal chemokines: activated B cell CCR7↑/CXCR5↓, activated pre-TFH CCR7↓/CXCR5↑ — they meet in the interfollicular zone. (choreography)</p><p>Unique helper T cells sit in the interfollicular zone between the T-cell paracortex and the B-cell follicle.</p><p>FDCs make CXCL13 (for CXCR5); DCs make CCL19/CCL21 (for CCR7) — setting the gradients that position pre-TFH and B cells.</p><p>On activation the B cell (CCR7↑/CXCR5↓) and pre-TFH (CCR7↓/CXCR5↑) migrate toward each other in the interfollicular zone.</p><p>THE CONJUGATE PAIR. When they meet, the activated pre-TFH and activated B cell form a conjugate pair — physically engaged through MHC II–TCR, the CD40–CD40L contact, and cytokines (IL-2/IL-4/IL-5 from the Th2-like pre-TFH binding the B cell’s IL-2R/IL-4R/IL-5R). This engagement does two decisive things. First, it induces AID in the B cell — the enzyme that all the later mutation and switching depend on. Second, the B cell pushes back on the pre-TFH: it drives Bcl-6 in the pre-TFH, which stabilizes CXCR5 and CD40L and completes differentiation into a true TFH cell. (Bcl-6 matters because the antibody response takes 7–10 days — the TFH program has to be locked in to last.)</p><p>TO THE MEDULLA, THEN BACK. The conjugate pair migrates to the medulla, where both cells divide over several days under TFH cytokines. Some B cells become B lymphoblasts → short-lived plasma cells that secrete the initial IgM seen in blood. Most conjugate pairs then traffic back to the follicle, where the rapidly proliferating B lymphoblasts seed a secondary follicle — the start of a germinal center.</p><p>Conjugate pair: pre-TFH engaged to an activated B cell via CD40–CD40L, MHC II–TCR, and IL-2/4/5 — inducing AID in the B cell.</p><p>The activated B cell drives Bcl-6 in the pre-TFH, stabilizing CXCR5/CD40L and completing differentiation into a TFH cell.</p><p>The conjugate pair migrates to the medulla; some B cells become short-lived plasma cells secreting the initial IgM.</p><p>THE GERMINAL CENTER. Back in the follicle, the fast-dividing B lymphoblasts are now centroblasts; they push naive B cells out to a surrounding mantle, forming a germinal center. A key concept Gregg flagged: a germinal center represents a B-cell response to ONE antigen (which may carry several epitopes) — it is clonal and antigen-focused. TFH cytokines (IL-2/4/5) initiate centroblast proliferation; FDC factors (IL-6, IL-15, BAFF) sustain it. Centroblasts shut off surface Ig while they divide.</p><p>SOMATIC HYPERMUTATION. Continued centroblast–TFH interaction induces more AID, which now drives somatic hypermutation: a high rate of point mutation in the variable (V) region of both heavy and light chains. This generates BCRs of varying affinity. A centroblast that has finished hypermutating and re-expresses surface Ig is renamed a centrocyte. Note the division of labor that defines the exam answer: SHM edits the V region to change affinity — distinct from the switch, which will edit the constant region to change isotype.</p><p>A germinal center = response to ONE antigen. Centroblast (proliferating, sIg-off, hypermutating) → centrocyte (sIg re-expressed). (GC vocabulary) CQ SHM = AID-driven point mutation of the V region (affinity); it does not touch the constant region. (SHM target)</p><p>A centroblast that completes hypermutation and re-expresses surface Ig is renamed a centrocyte.</p><p>Centroblasts push out naive B cells to the mantle, forming a germinal center — a response to ONE antigen (multiple epitopes).</p><p>AID drives somatic hypermutation in the V region of both chains, generating BCRs of varying affinity.</p><p>AFFINITY MATURATION — SELECTION ON THE FDC. Centrocytes now compete for antigen held intact by follicular dendritic cells on complement receptors (CR1–3) and Fc receptors. A centrocyte survives only if it gets both a strong BCR signal (its hypermutated receptor binds the FDC-displayed antigen well) and TFH help. Higher-affinity clones win; centrocytes that cannot compete undergo apoptosis and are cleared by tingible-body macrophages. This is affinity maturation: the surviving repertoire drifts toward higher affinity over the reaction. Surviving GC B cells then receive TFH IL-10/IL-21 signals (Bcl-6) that drive differentiation toward plasma cells — and it is during this interaction that isotype switching occurs.</p><p>FDCs display intact antigen on complement (CR1–3) and Fc receptors for centrocytes to test their hypermutated BCRs against.</p><p>Survival requires BOTH BCR and CR signaling — high-affinity centrocytes stay attached to FDC and TFH; the rest apoptose.</p><p>Surviving GC B cells get TFH IL-10/IL-21 (Bcl-6) to become plasma cells — and undergo isotype switching during this step.</p><p>CLASS SWITCH RECOMBINATION — THE SWITCH ITSELF. Now the actual mechanism. The heavy-chain locus has the variable region, then the constant-region exons, each preceded by a switch region. Two inputs license switching: CD40 ligation induces AID, and the TFH cytokine directs AID to the correct switch region. Before switching, alternative splicing lets the cell make IgM and IgD off the same V region. The cytokine sets the target: for example, IFN-γ drives IgG switching. Mechanistically: AID deaminates cytosine → uracil in the donor (Sμ) and acceptor (e.g., Sγ1) switch regions; uracil-DNA-glycosylase (UNG) removes the uracil, leaving an abasic site; APE1 (an endonuclease) nicks that site; nicks on both strands of both switch regions create double-strand breaks that recombine, looping out the intervening constant exons as a circle. Crucially, the V region is untouched — so the switched IgG has the same antigen specificity and affinity as the parent IgM. Only the isotype changed.</p><p>CSR steps: AID (C→U) → UNG removes uracil → APE1 nicks → double-strand breaks recombine the switch regions. (CSR mechanism) CQ CD40L induces AID; the cytokine aims it (IFN-γ→IgG). V region preserved → same specificity/affinity, new isotype. (switch control)</p><p>Heavy-chain locus: variable region, constant-region exons, and the switch regions; CD40 induces AID, cytokines direct it.</p><p>AID→uracil, UNG removes it, APE1 nicks the abasic site; double-strand nicks in both switch regions enable recombination.</p><p>Intervening constant exons loop out as circular DNA; the V region realigns with Cγ1 — same specificity/affinity, new IgG1 isotype.</p><p>PLASMA CELLS AND MEMORY — THE OUTPUTS. Two fates remain. Long-lived plasma cells home to the bone marrow, sit on stromal cells, are non-migratory, and secrete antibody for years (the ‘memory plasma cell’). Memory B cells are different: they circulate, carry a BCR, and do NOT secrete antibody, waiting as a reservoir for a fast recall response. A switch in TFH cytokine (toward IL-4/IL-21 patterns) tips GC B cells toward the memory fate rather than the plasma-cell fate. Remember the timing discriminator: short-lived plasma cells give the first IgM over several days, but antigen-specific IgM within ~2 days with no maturation points to marginal-zone (T-independent) B cells, not the germinal center.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One enzyme, two edits. AID does SHM (V region → affinity) AND CSR (switch regions → isotype). CD40L induces it; the cytokine aims it.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> The 2-day rule. IgM within ~2 days, unmatured = marginal-zone (T-independent). The germinal-center (TD) IgM is slower and matures.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> SHM vs CSR. SHM = point mutations in the V region (changes affinity). CSR = recombination of the constant region (changes isotype). Specificity is preserved by CSR.</p><p>ReClaude A: The enzyme is AID (activation-induced deaminase): it drove the somatic hypermutation that raised affinity and the class switch recombination that changed IgM to IgG. Specificity is unchanged — CSR swaps only the constant region, leaving the V region (and thus the antigen target) intact.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_40": {
  "answer": "<p><em>An exam stem says ‘NK cell kills an antibody-coated tumor cell.’ Name the effector function, the Fc receptor, its CD number, and the isotype — and contrast it with how a macrophage handles the same coated cell.</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The whole LO reduces to one rule: the constant region (isotype) plus the Fc receptor on the responding cell decides what happens to the antibody-bound target. Same antigen-binding end, different back end, different outcome. Walk the effector functions in order and attach each to its isotype and receptor.</p><p>NEUTRALIZATION (IgG, IgA). The simplest function: the antibody physically blocks a pathogen or toxin from attaching to host-cell receptors. Influenza must bind hemagglutinin on respiratory epithelium to infect; anti-H antibody blocks that contact (the object of the flu vaccine). Likewise, antibody against an exotoxin (tetanus, diphtheria) blocks the toxin from reaching its receptor — which is why toxin-mediated diseases are such good vaccine targets. IgG and IgA are the neutralizing isotypes.</p><p>OPSONIZATION (IgG, IgA). Antibody coats the microbe; phagocytes carrying the matching Fc receptor bind that coat and engulf the target. Macrophage/neutrophil FcγRI (CD64) and FcγRIIA engage IgG; FcαRI (CD89) engages IgA. The coat itself — the thing that enhances phagocytosis — is the opsonin.</p><p>Neutralization = block attachment (IgG, IgA). Opsonization = antibody coat that Fc receptors grab for phagocytosis (IgG via FcγRI/IIA; IgA via FcαRI).</p><p>Neutralization: antibody binds a viral surface protein (e.g., influenza HA) and blocks attachment to the host-cell receptor.</p><p>Neutralization of exotoxins (tetanus, diphtheria): antibody blocks toxin binding to host receptors — the basis of toxoid vaccines.</p><p>Opsonization: IgG/IgA coat the microbe; phagocyte Fc receptors bind the Fc and drive uptake and digestion.</p><p>ADCC — NK CELLS, FcγRIII (CD16), IgG. This is the highest-yield receptor fact in the lecture. NK cells express FcγRIII, whose alias is CD16; it binds the Fc of IgG (IgG1/IgG3) attached to a target cell. Ligation makes the NK cell release perforin and granzyme, which activate caspases and drive the target into apoptosis. Antibody-directed killing of a coated cell is antibody-dependent cellular cytotoxicity. Contrast the macrophage:</p><p>same IgG-coated target, but the macrophage eats it (opsonization) rather than puncturing it. Eosinophils run a parallel program against large parasites — IgE coats the worm, eosinophils bind via FcεRI, and degranulate to destroy it.</p><p>THE Fc-RECEPTOR MAP — LEARN THE ROWS. The exam tests the cell–receptor–isotype–outcome table directly. FcγRI (macrophages; induced on neutrophils): IgG → opsonization. FcγRIIA (macrophages, neutrophils): IgG → opsonization. FcγRIII / CD16 (NK cells): IgG → perforin/granzyme (ADCC). FcεRI (mast cells, basophils; induced on eosinophils): IgE → degranulation. FcαRI / CD89 (macrophages, neutrophils): IgA → opsonization; (on dendritic cells) uptake of neutralized antigen for processing.</p><p>ADCC = NK cell + FcγRIII (CD16) + IgG → perforin/granzyme → apoptosis. CD16 = FcγRIII is the alias to memorize. (ADCC triad) CQ FcR rows: FcγRI/IIA→opsonize (IgG); FcγRIII/CD16→ADCC (NK, IgG); FcεRI→degranulate (IgE); FcαRI/CD89→opsonize (IgA). (FcR map)</p><p>Against large worms, IgE coats the parasite and eosinophils bind via FcεRI, degranulating to destroy it.</p><p>Fc-receptor map: FcγRI/IIA (opsonization), FcγRIII/CD16 (NK ADCC), FcεRI (degranulation), FcαRI (IgA opsonization/uptake).</p><p>ADCC: NK-cell FcγRIII (CD16) binds IgG (IgG1/IgG3) on the target and releases perforin/granzyme, driving caspase-mediated apoptosis.</p><p>COMPLEMENT ACTIVATION (IgM, IgG1–3). IgM and IgG1–IgG3 bind antigen and recruit C1 to fire the classical pathway. The structural punchline: because IgM is a pentamer, it presents multiple Fc regions at once, so far fewer IgM molecules are needed to activate complement — a single bound IgM can do it, whereas IgG needs two molecules close together.</p><p>IMMUNE-COMPLEX REMOVAL (IgG). IgG binds soluble or surface-deposited antigen to form immune complexes; because IgG’s binding sites are higher-affinity than IgM’s, most complexes are IgG. C1 activation deposits C3b on the complex. Erythrocytes carry CR1, which binds that C3b and ferries the complexes to macrophages in the spleen and liver for removal. This clearance matters clinically: if complexes are not removed, they deposit in small vessels and renal glomeruli, where complement activation causes vasculitis and glomerulonephritis.</p><p>Complement: IgM (pentamer) and IgG1–3 recruit C1; fewer IgM needed. Erythrocyte CR1 clears C3b-tagged immune complexes to spleen/liver.</p><p>IgM, IgG1, IgG3 bind antigen and recruit C1; pentameric IgM needs far fewer molecules to activate the classical pathway.</p><p>IgG forms immune complexes; C1 activation deposits C3b, and phagocytes take up the complexes (cleared in spleen and liver).</p><p>Erythrocyte CR1 binds C3b on complexes and delivers them to splenic/hepatic macrophages; failure causes vasculitis and glomerulonephritis.</p><p>IgG SUBCLASSES AND THE PLACENTA. IgG1 is the most common serum subclass; IgG1 and IgG3 are the best at opsonization, complement activation, and ADCC, and are the subclasses that cross the placenta. Transfer is by FcRn (the neonatal Fc receptor): in the syncytiotrophoblast, circulating IgG is pinocytosed, FcRn binds it in the acidified endosome (protecting it from proteases), and the endosome releases the IgG into the fetal circulation at physiological pH. The same FcRn transcytosis moves IgG (and some IgA) from blood into tissues and mucosa, and recycles serum IgG — the basis of its long half-life in the next LO.</p><p>IgG subclasses: IgG1 most common; IgG1/IgG3 best for opsonization, complement, ADCC, and are the placental crossers.</p><p>FcRn transfers maternal IgG across the syncytiotrophoblast: acidified endosomes bind IgG and release it into fetal blood at physiological pH.</p><p>Placental IgG transfer is efficient (neonatal IgG approaches adult levels); a deficiency window follows as maternal IgG wanes.</p><p>SECRETORY IgA — pIgR AND THE SECRETORY PIECE. Mucosal plasma cells make dimeric IgA on the basolateral side of the epithelium; it must reach the lumen. The polymeric Ig receptor (pIgR) binds the IgA J chain, transcytoses it to the apical surface, and is then cleaved to leave a secretory piece attached to the IgA. That secretory piece protects the IgA from proteolysis and helps anchor it in mucus. (pIgR carries pentameric IgM the same way.) This is the molecular core of the next lecture, mucosal immunity.</p><p>IgM AND IgE — THE BOOKENDS. IgM is the first isotype synthesized, the first surface BCR on naive mature B cells, an efficient complement activator, and an agglutinator of microbes. IgE mediates immunity to parasites and type I allergy: it arms mast cells and basophils via FcεRI, and antigen/allergen cross-linking triggers degranulation (histamine and other mediators) — expulsion responses (sneeze, cough, vomit, diarrhea) against pathogens, and allergic symptoms against allergens in genetically predisposed people. The same IgE–FcεRI logic is the engine of type I hypersensitivity in Lec 18.</p><p>Secretory IgA: pIgR binds the J chain, transcytoses dimeric IgA, and is cleaved to leave the protective secretory piece. (secretory IgA) CQ IgM = first Ig + first BCR + complement + agglutination. IgE = parasites + allergy via FcεRI degranulation. (IgM/IgE bookends)</p><p>Secretory IgA: pIgR binds the J chain of dimeric IgA, transcytoses it, and is cleaved to leave the secretory piece that resists proteolysis.</p><p>IgM: first isotype synthesized, first surface BCR, complement activation, and agglutination of microbes.</p><p>IgE: allergen/antigen cross-links IgE on mast-cell FcεRI → degranulation — expulsion responses and allergic symptoms.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> FcRn vs pIgR. FcRn moves IgG (placenta, tissue) and recycles it (half-life). pIgR moves dimeric IgA across mucosa and leaves the secretory piece.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Isotype + Fc receptor = function. Same antigen end; the constant region and the responding cell’s Fc receptor decide neutralize / opsonize / ADCC / degranulate / fix complement.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> CD16 = FcγRIII = NK ADCC for IgG. The single most tested alias in the lecture — NK cell binds IgG on the target and fires perforin/granzyme.</p><p>ReClaude A: It is ADCC: the NK cell uses FcγRIII (CD16) to bind IgG (IgG1/IgG3) on the coated cell and releases perforin/granzyme to drive apoptosis. A macrophage meeting the same IgG-coated cell instead phagocytoses it via FcγRI/FcγRIIA (opsonization) — same antibody, different Fc receptor, different fate.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_42": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Two patients are protected against the same microbe — one because they were given antibodies, one because they were infected last year. Which has memory, which had immediate protection, and what are the four resulting categories?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. Immunization — providing immunity to an infectious agent — can happen actively or passively, and either can be acquired naturally or artificially (deliberately induced, i.e. vaccines). The whole LO is a 2×2 grid: passive/active × natural/artificial. The defining contrast is who made the antibody.</p><p>PASSIVE IMMUNITY — BORROWED ANTIBODY. The recipient receives preformed antibody that someone (or something) else made. Consequences follow directly: protection is rapid (antibody is already there), but temporary (antibody has a short half-life and decays), and it produces no memory — no recipient B or T lymphocytes are involved, so the recipient’s immune system never learns anything. It does not rely on the recipient mounting a response at all.</p><p>ACTIVE IMMUNITY — YOUR OWN RESPONSE. An antigen is introduced and the recipient develops their own response. This is slower (it requires T- and B-lymphocyte activation, proliferation, and differentiation), but yields long-term protection because memory T and B cells form. The trade is the mirror image of passive: delayed but durable, with memory.</p><p>Passive = receive preformed antibody → immediate, temporary, no memory. Active = make your own response → slow, durable, memory. (the core contrast)</p><p>Passive immunity: receiving preformed antibody — immediate but temporary, with no memory because no recipient lymphocytes respond.</p><p>Active immunity: introducing antigen so the recipient develops their own response — slower, but long-lasting with memory T and B cells.</p><p>Passive immunity splits into natural (maternal antibody) and artificial (receiving serum/antibody preparations).</p><p>NATURAL vs ARTIFICIAL — THE FOUR BOXES. Passive-natural: maternal antibodies passed to the fetus (placenta) or infant (milk). Passive-artificial: receiving serum/antibody — human immune serum globulin, hyperimmune/convalescent serum, antitoxin/antivenom, or lab monoclonals. Active-natural: contact with antigen through the infectious process (even mild/subclinical disease can leave antibodies and memory). Active-artificial: intentional exposure to an antigen BEFORE infection, usually by vaccination.</p><p>Grid: passive-natural = maternal Ab; passive-artificial = serum/globulin; active-natural = infection; active-artificial = vaccine. (the 2×2 grid)</p><p>Active immunity splits into natural (response to real infection) and artificial (vaccination — deliberate exposure before infection).</p><p>Active-natural is infection-driven; active-artificial is intentional exposure to antigen before an infection occurs.</p><p>Sources of artificial passive immunity: immune serum globulin, hyperimmune/convalescent serum, antitoxin/antivenom, and monoclonal antibodies.</p><p>ReClaude A: The patient given antibodies had passive immunity — immediate protection, no memory. The patient infected last year has active immunity — it developed slowly but left memory. The four categories: passive-natural (maternal antibody), passive-artificial (serum/globulin), active-natural (infection), active-artificial (vaccination).</p><p><em>Someone steps on a rusty nail and has no tetanus immunity. Why might they get BOTH a shot of antibody and a shot that is a vaccine — what does each one do?</em></p><p>OVERVIEW. The clinical question is always a timing question: do you need protection now, or do you need it to last? Passive and active immunity answer different halves of that, and sometimes you deploy both.</p><p>PASSIVE — FOR IMMEDIATE NEED. When a non-immune patient faces an immediate threat — a wound carrying a toxin, a recent exposure, a venom — you give preformed antibody for protection that works at once. Artificial passive products are organized by source: from human serum (immune globulin / IVIG, and disease-specific immune globulins used as pre-exposure or post-exposure prophylaxis), from monoclonal antibodies (e.g. an anti-toxin mAb that binds and neutralizes a bacterial toxin), and from non-human donors (antitoxins/antivenoms raised in animals). (Per the syllabus you reason about the category and property, not which brand belongs to which class.)</p><p>ACTIVE — FOR DURABLE PROTECTION. To make protection last, you induce the patient’s own response, normally by vaccination (or by surviving the natural infection). And in high-risk post-exposure situations you combine them: immune globulin bridges the gap immediately while the vaccine builds the patient’s own durable, memory-based immunity — covering both timelines at once.</p><p>Passive = immediate need (toxin, exposure, venom); active = durable protection (vaccine). High-risk post-exposure → give both. (use-case logic)</p><p>Monoclonal-antibody passive protection: lab-made antibodies that bind and neutralize a specific pathogen or toxin.</p><p>Active protection: exposure to a pathogen (or vaccine antigen) elicits the patient’s own response, providing antibodies and memory for the future.</p><p>Artificial passive protection from human serum globulin: IVIG and disease-specific immune globulins used as pre- or post-exposure prophylaxis.</p><p>ReClaude A: They get an antibody shot (passive — immediate but temporary protection against the toxin, no memory) and a vaccine shot (active — builds their own durable, memory-based immunity). Together the globulin covers the gap now while the vaccine establishes lasting protection.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_49": {
  "answer": "<p><em>What single feature must every SCID share, and which primary immunodeficiency is the most common overall?</em></p><p>ORGANIZING THE CATALOG. Primary immunodeficiencies are grouped by the immune compartment they damage — cellular (T/NK), humoral (B-cell/antibody), SCID (combined), phagocytic, and complement. The humoral group is by far the largest. There are ~550 recognized PIs, with the causative gene now identified for the great majority. SCID is an umbrella term, not a single disease: it describes deficiencies that always involve T cells plus at least one other arm — usually B cells (because they depend on T-cell help), sometimes NK cells. The single most common PI overall is selective IgA deficiency, which is also one of the mildest.</p><p>PIs sort by compartment (cellular/humoral/SCID/phagocytic/complement). SCID always involves T cells + another arm. Most common PI = selective IgA deficiency. (PI catalog organization)</p><p>Most common types of primary immunodeficiencies (the humoral/antibody compartment dominates). ~550 recognized PIs; gene identified for ~485.</p><p>Primary immunodeficiencies manifest in childhood and divide by compartment (humoral, cellular, complement, phagocytic). SCID always involves T cells + another arm (B or NK).</p><p>Hallmark of immunodeficiency: enhanced susceptibility — frequent/chronic illness, opportunistic or commensal organisms, infections that fail to respond normally to treatment.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> SCID is not one disease. It is any combined defect that includes T cells. HIGM-1 (CD40L) and BLS are both SCIDs because the T-cell arm is hit.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Five compartments organize every PI on the exam: cellular (T/NK), humoral (B/Ab), SCID (combined), phagocytic, complement. Humoral is the biggest bucket.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> When asked for the most common PI, the answer is selective IgA deficiency — and it is also among the mildest, which is why most carriers never know.</p><p>ReClaude A: Every SCID must involve T cells (plus at least one other compartment, usually B cells). The most common primary immunodeficiency overall is selective IgA deficiency.</p><p><em>A 9-month-old has anemia, low platelets, and splenomegaly with a perforin mutation — how does a cytotoxic-killing defect end up producing macrophage-driven pathology?</em></p><p>CELLULAR PI — HEMOPHAGOCYTIC LYMPHOHISTIOCYTOSIS (HLH). HLH is the cleanest example of Davis&#x27;s recurring lesson: what you see is not always the problem. The defect is in perforin/granzyme killing by CTLs and NK cells — either perforin cannot be made, or the perforin/granzyme vesicle cannot fuse with the cell membrane to release its cargo. Because those killers cannot clear intracellular targets, they keep secreting IFN-γ, which does not just activate macrophages but hyperactivates them. The over-driven macrophages then phagocytose red blood cells (anemia → fatigue), platelets, and neutrophils, and pile up in the spleen (splenomegaly). So the defect is in the T/NK cell, but the pathology is macrophage-mediated — a severe, potentially fatal systemic inflammatory syndrome. Treatment suppresses the inflammation (methotrexate, dexamethasone, etoposide, cyclosporine A, anti-IFN-γ mAb) or replaces the stem cells (HSCT).</p><p>HLH: defect in perforin/granzyme killing (T/NK) → unchecked targets → sustained IFN-γ → macrophage hyperactivation → phagocytosis of RBCs/platelets/neutrophils (anemia, cytopenias, splenomegaly). (HLH mechanism)</p><p>HLH cause: mutations in perforin/granzyme killing by CTLs &amp; NK cells. Without killing, CTLs/NK keep secreting IFN-γ → macrophage overactivation.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis, decoded: hemo (blood) + phagocytic cells + lympho (lymphatic) + histiocytosis (excess macrophages). Primary form: birth–18 months.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> HLH clinical: phagocytosis of RBCs → anemia/fatigue; low platelets/neutrophils/hemoglobin; splenomegaly; severe systemic inflammation. Defect in T/NK, pathology in macrophage.</p><p>HUMORAL PI — SELECTIVE IgA DEFICIENCY. The most common PI: a defect in B-cell differentiation into IgA-secreting plasma cells (the IgA genes are normal). The result is recurrent mucosal infections (GI, respiratory, ears) and a higher rate of allergy, asthma, RA, and diabetes. Labs show low IgA with normal IgM and IgG and normal peripheral B-cell numbers — the B cells exist, they just do not become IgA plasma cells.</p><p>Selective IgA deficiency: defect in differentiation to IgA plasma cells (genes normal) → low IgA, normal IgM/IgG, normal B-cell counts, mucosal infections. (selective IgA pattern) HUMORAL PI — AID HYPER-IgM SYNDROME (HIGM-2). The key concept is the ratio, not the absolute number. AID (activation-induced cytidine deaminase) performs class-switch recombination, and its expression is induced by CD40–CD40L help from the T cell. Without AID, B cells cannot switch isotypes, so they are stuck making IgM — the IgM-to-IgG/IgA ratio is elevated even when absolute IgM is within the normal range. Cell counts (CD4, CD8, CD19+ B cells) are all normal; only switching fails, and patients often develop hemolytic anemia. Treatment is IVIG (replacing the IgG they cannot make) plus antibiotics. (On any exam Ig-level question, Davis stated she provides normal-vs-patient value columns — so reason from the ratio, never from memorized absolute values.)</p><p>AID hyper-IgM: AID (induced by CD40–CD40L) drives class switching; its loss → stuck at IgM → elevated IgM:IgG/IgA ratio (absolute IgM may be normal). Counts normal; treat with IVIG. (AID hyper-IgM ratio)</p><p>AID hyper-IgM (HIGM-2): mutation in the AID enzyme in B cells. AID drives class-switch recombination, induced by CD40–CD40L interaction with the TH cell.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Other hyper-IgM forms: HIGM-1 (CD40L, T-cell defect → SCID), HIGM-3 (CD40, B-cell), HIGM-4 (switch-region DNA breaks, B-cell), HIGM-5 (UNG, B-cell).</p><p>Hyper-IgM lab logic: IgM may be high OR within normal range, but the ratio of IgM to IgG/IgA is higher than normal when isotype switching is impaired. SCID — BARE LYMPHOCYTE SYNDROME (BLS). Two types, distinguished by which MHC class is missing from the cell surface. BLS-I: no surface MHC class I, from a TAP1/TAP2 mutation — class I is made but cannot be loaded/displayed → failed positive selection of CD8 T cells. BLS-II (more common): no MHC class II, from a transcription-factor mutation — class II is never made → low CD4 T cells. In both, the MHC genes themselves are normal, and γδ T cells are normal because they do not undergo MHC-dependent positive selection. BLS-I gives necrotizing granulomatous skin lesions and bacterial respiratory infections (most reach adulthood with treatment); BLS-II causes broad bacterial/viral/fungal infections and GI infections → failure to thrive, and is fatal by adolescence without HSCT.</p><p>BLS-I = no surface MHC-I (TAP mutation) → low CD8; BLS-II = no MHC-II (Tx-factor mutation) → low CD4. Genes normal in both; γδ T cells spared (skip MHC positive selection). (BLS I vs II)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> BLS: absent surface MHC → failed positive selection → low αβ CD4/CD8 thymocytes; γδ T cells normal (they skip MHC positive selection).</p><p>BLS: class I defect = TAP mutation (MHC-I made but not displayed); class II defect = transcription-factor mutation (MHC-II not made). Both are SCID.</p><p>BLS-II (more common in Mediterranean/N. African descent): broad bacterial/viral/fungal/opportunistic + GI infections → failure to thrive; fatal by adolescence without HSCT. PHAGOCYTIC PI — CHRONIC GRANULOMATOUS DISEASE (CGD). A defect in the oxidative (respiratory) burst — classically NADPH oxidase — so phagocytosed bacteria and fungi survive inside macrophages and neutrophils. The frustrated phagocytes fuse into granulomas. Clinically: opportunistic bacterial/fungal infections, soft-tissue infections, oral/gum disease, abscesses (brain, liver, lung, bone). Treatment is prophylactic antimicrobials.</p><p>PHAGOCYTIC PI — LEUKOCYTE ADHESION DEFICIENCY (LAD). All three LADs are extravasation/migration defects. LAD-1: a CD18 mutation (CD18 is part of the LFA-1 integrin that binds ICAM-1) → neutrophils cannot adhere and leave the vessel, so they accumulate in blood (neutrophilia) but cannot reach tissue — recurrent soft-tissue infections, no pus (pus is mostly dead neutrophils), poor wound healing, delayed umbilical-cord separation; often fatal before age 1. LAD-2: a sialyl-Lewis-X/fucose-metabolism defect → cannot bind selectins (rolling fails); adds neurologic and growth defects. LAD-3: a FERMT3/KINDLIN3 signaling defect → presents like LAD-1 but adds a bleeding disorder (platelets cannot bind fibrinogen and aggregate, despite normal platelet counts).</p><p>LAD-1 (CD18/LFA-1): no extravasation → neutrophilia + no pus + delayed cord separation. LAD-3 (KINDLIN3) adds a bleeding disorder (defective platelet aggregation, normal counts). (LAD mechanisms)</p><p>CGD: defect in the oxidative burst (e.g. NADPH oxidase) → phagocytosed pathogens survive inside macrophages/neutrophils → frustrated phagocytes fuse into granulomas.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> LAD-1: CD18 (part of LFA-1) mutation → LFA-1 cannot bind ICAM-1 → loss of neutrophil migration → neutrophilia, no pus, delayed cord separation; usually fatal before age 1.</p><p>LAD-3: FERMT3/KINDLIN3 signaling defect → poor integrin upregulation (LFA-1, VLA-4) AND defective platelet aggregation (normal counts) → bleeding disorder. COMPLEMENT PI. Three patterns worth holding apart. C1, C2, or C4 deficiency → little increase in infection but immune-complex disease (RA, SLE, vasculitis), because complexes are not cleared. C5–C9 (MAC) deficiency → recurrent, invasive Neisseria infections (meningitidis, gonorrhoeae), which require MAC lysis to clear — two bouts of meningitis by 18 should prompt a complement workup. C3 deficiency is the most severe (C3 is in all pathways) → broad susceptibility to encapsulated bacteria. Among the regulatory proteins, C1-inhibitor deficiency causes hereditary angioedema: unchecked cleavage of C4 and C2 releases vasoactive C2 kinin — &quot;C4 isn&#x27;t the problem, C2 is.&quot;</p><p>Complement patterns: C1/C2/C4 → immune-complex disease; C5–C9 → Neisseria; C3 → most severe (encapsulated bacteria); C1-INH → hereditary angioedema (C2 kinin). (complement PI patterns)</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> C1-inhibitor deficiency: uncontrolled C4/C2 activation releases large amounts of vasoactive C2 kinin → edema → hereditary angioedema.</p><p>Complement PIs: C1/C2/C4 → immune-complex disease (RA, SLE, vasculitis); C5–C9 MAC → recurrent invasive Neisseria; C3 (most severe) → encapsulated bacteria.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Immunodeficiency-associated issues: anemia, arthritis/joint pain, ~25% have an autoimmune disease, neoplasias (leukemias/lymphomas), growth retardation.</p><p><strong>Trap:</strong> &quot;Hyper-IgM&quot; does not require elevated absolute IgM. It is defined by the IgM:IgG/IgA ratio being high because switching fails — absolute IgM can sit in the normal range.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Oral/gum lesions + abscesses → think CGD; neutrophilia + no pus + delayed cord → LAD-1; recurrent Neisseria → C5–C9; non-pitting edema → C1-INH/hereditary angioedema.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Davis&#x27;s through-line: what you see is not always the problem. HLH anemia comes from macrophages, not RBC autoantibodies; LAD-1 neutrophilia comes from cells trapped in blood, not overproduction. Trace symptom → mechanism.</p><p>ReClaude A: Failed perforin/granzyme killing leaves intracellular targets unchecked, so CTLs/NK cells keep secreting IFN-γ; that sustained IFN-γ hyperactivates macrophages, which phagocytose RBCs, platelets, and neutrophils — producing the anemia, cytopenias, and splenomegaly. The defect is in the T/NK cell; the pathology is in the macrophage.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_51": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A young child with clonal expansion of a B-cell progenitor in the marrow, versus an older adult with punched-out skull lesions and urinary light chains — name each malignancy.</em></p><p>LEUKEMIA VS LYMPHOMA. Immune-system cancers split by architecture: leukemias proliferate as individual cells (lymphoid or myeloid), while lymphomas proliferate as a mass of cells. The four leukemias are named by acute/chronic and by lineage, and the age clue is the exam&#x27;s favorite discriminator. ALL (acute lymphoblastic) — clonal expansion of a lymphoid progenitor (usually a B cell), the most common pediatric malignancy (~⅓ of childhood cancers). CLL (chronic lymphocytic) — mature circulating B cells that cannot undergo apoptosis, in older adults (55+); fewer healthy B cells → more infections. AML (acute myeloid) — malignant immature granulocyte precursors crowd the marrow → low WBCs, then anemia and bleeding. CML (chronic myeloid) — a family named by the affected myeloid cell (granulocytes → chronic myelocytic leukemia; megakaryocytes → malignant thrombocythemia or myeloid metaplasia; RBCs → polycythemia vera), mostly in adults.</p><p>Leukemia = individual cells; lymphoma = mass. Age clue: ALL = children (most common pediatric cancer); CLL = older adults (no apoptosis); AML/CML = adults. (leukemia types + age clues)</p><p>Neoplasms of the immune system: leukemias proliferate as individual cells (lymphoid or myeloid); lymphomas proliferate as a mass of cells.</p><p>ALL: dysregulated clonal expansion of a lymphoid progenitor (usually B cell); most common pediatric malignancy (~⅓ of childhood cancers); anemia, bruising, lymphadenopathy.</p><p>AML: malignant proliferation of immature granulocyte precursors crowd the marrow → low WBCs, increased infections, then anemia and bleeding. MULTIPLE MYELOMA. Malignant plasma cells accumulate as a mass in bone, destroying it to leave diagnostic &quot;punched-out&quot; lytic lesions (skull, spine). Normal B cells are crowded out, and the malignant plasma cells overproduce free light chains (Bence-Jones proteins) that clog the kidney → renal failure. Most common in older adults.</p><p>HODGKIN VS NON-HODGKIN LYMPHOMA. Hodgkin — typically B-cell, spreads in an orderly, predictable node-to-node pattern (often beginning cervically), shows diagnostic Reed-Sternberg cells (a lymphoblastic form of a mature B cell, often EBV-linked), and is highly treatable (~90% 5-yr survival); more common in teens/young adults. Non-Hodgkin — can be B- or T-cell, is more aggressive and less predictable, spreads beyond nodes (spleen, liver, marrow), is usually diagnosed later (~74% survival), and is ~10× more common, skewing older.</p><p>Multiple myeloma = plasma cells, punched-out lytic lesions + Bence-Jones light chains → renal failure. Hodgkin = orderly node-to-node + Reed-Sternberg; non-Hodgkin = aggressive, B- or T-cell, beyond nodes. (myeloma + Hodgkin vs non-Hodgkin)</p><p>Multiple myeloma: malignant plasma cells accumulate as a mass in bone → &quot;punched-out&quot; lytic holes (spine, skull) that are diagnostic; normal B cells cannot be made.</p><p>Multiple myeloma: mostly older adults; renal failure from Bence-Jones proteins (overproduced light chains) passing through and clogging the kidney.</p><p>Hodgkin lymphoma: spreads orderly node-to-node; diagnostic Reed-Sternberg cells (a lymphoblastic form of a mature B cell); often EBV-associated, begins cervically.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> Two diagnostic findings to lock in: punched-out lytic lesions + Bence-Jones = multiple myeloma; Reed-Sternberg cells = Hodgkin lymphoma.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Age is the discriminator: a young child → ALL; an older adult with no-apoptosis mature B cells → CLL; teens/young adults with orderly nodal spread → Hodgkin.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Two axes for leukemia (acute/chronic × lymphoid/myeloid) plus the age clue solve most stems. Lymphomas split Hodgkin (orderly, Reed-Sternberg, B-cell, ~90%) vs non-Hodgkin (aggressive, B-or-T, ~74%).</p><p>ReClaude A: The child with marrow clonal expansion of a B-cell progenitor has acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL); the older adult with punched-out skull lesions and urinary Bence-Jones light chains has multiple myeloma.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_52": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Why does &quot;strong binding&quot; send a B cell to apoptosis but let a T cell survive positive selection — and then kill that same T cell in negative selection?</em></p><p>WHERE AND WHY. Central tolerance happens in the generative organs — B cells in the bone marrow (though ~70% of negative selection actually occurs in the spleen) and T cells in the thymus. Tolerance is purely an adaptive phenomenon: it is the education of BCRs and TCRs to ignore self and attack foreign. The single hardest thing to keep straight is that the same phrase — &quot;strong binding&quot; — produces opposite fates depending on the step, so anchor each step to its rule.</p><p>B-CELL NEGATIVE SELECTION (three outcomes + editing). An immature B cell (IgM+) meets self-Ag held by bone-marrow/splenic stromal cells. Strong binding to multivalent surface self-Ag WITH BCR cross-linking → apoptosis (cross-linking is the key — it always gives the strongest signal). Strong binding to soluble self-Ag WITHOUT cross-linking → anergy (the cell survives as an unresponsive IgM-lo IgD+ naive B cell). Weak or no binding → survival (a normal IgM+IgD+ naive B cell). In about a third of cells slated for apoptosis/anergy, persistent RAG1/2 attempt receptor editing of the light chain to escape self-reactivity.</p><p>B-cell negative selection: strong + cross-link → apoptosis; strong, no cross-link (soluble) → anergy; weak/no → survival. Cross-linking is the determinant.</p><p>Outcome 3: weak or no binding to self-Ag → SURVIVAL (normal IgM+IgD+ naive mature B cell enters periphery).</p><p>B-cell negative selection outcome 1: strong binding to multivalent surface self-Ag WITH BCR cross-linking → APOPTOSIS. ~70% of negative selection occurs in the spleen.</p><p>Outcome 2: strong binding to soluble self-Ag WITHOUT cross-linking → ANERGY (survives as unresponsive IgM-lo IgD+ naive B cell in the periphery).</p><p>T-CELL POSITIVE SELECTION (cortex) — fate determination. Double-positive (CD4+CD8+) thymocytes engage cortical thymic epithelial cells via HLA–self-Ag–TCR. Weak/no binding → apoptosis (death by neglect); moderate/strong binding → survival, and the MHC class fit sets lineage: CD8 fit with MHC I → cytotoxic, CD4 fit with MHC II → helper. Note this is the opposite rule from B-cell negative selection — here weak binding is the one that dies.</p><p>T-CELL NEGATIVE SELECTION (medulla) — signaling test. Single-positive T cells (now CD3-high, so the TCR can signal) meet medullary thymic epithelial cells and thymic DCs. Weak binding → survival; strong OR no binding → apoptosis. Gregg framed this as a signaling test: a surviving T cell must signal weakly (proving a functional TCR) but not strongly (which would mean it recognizes self). The self-antigen breadth comes from AIRE in MTECs, a master switch that transcribes essentially all tissue-restricted self-antigens; Hassall&#x27;s corpuscles make TSLP to mature the thymic DCs.</p><p>T-cell positive selection (cortex): weak/no → apoptosis, mod/strong → survival + lineage fate. T-cell negative selection (medulla): weak → survival, strong/no → apoptosis. AIRE supplies all self-Ags. (T-cell selection rules + AIRE)</p><p>T-cell positive selection (cortex): weak/no binding → apoptosis; moderate/strong → survival. CD8 fit with MHC I → cytotoxic; CD4 fit with MHC II → helper. Fate determination.</p><p>T-cell negative selection: MTECs express AIRE → produce ALL self-Ags, present on MHC I/II and release to thymic DCs; Hassall&#x27;s corpuscles make TSLP to mature the DCs.</p><p>T-cell negative selection outcomes: weak TCR–self-Ag/MHC binding → SURVIVAL; strong OR no binding → APOPTOSIS. A surviving T cell must signal weakly but not strongly.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Positive vs negative selection are opposite on weak binding: weak loses in positive (death by neglect) but wins in negative (proof of a safe, functional TCR). Lock the step first, then the rule.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> &quot;All self-antigens in the thymus&quot; is your AIRE flag. AIRE knockout → autoimmunity; it is the master switch in MTECs that lets the thymus display tissue-restricted self.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Three steps, three rules. B-cell negative: strong → die/anergy. T-cell positive: weak → die. T-cell negative: weak → live, strong/no → die. The phrase &quot;strong binding&quot; is meaningless until you name the step.</p><p>ReClaude A: &quot;Strong binding&quot; has no fixed meaning until you name the step. In B-cell negative selection it means the cell recognizes self → apoptosis/anergy. In T-cell positive selection, weak binders die (death by neglect) and moderate/strong binders survive. In T-cell negative selection, the surviving cell must signal weakly — strong binding now means self-recognition → apoptosis. So the same word maps to deletion in two steps and survival in one, because each step is testing for a different thing.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_59": {
  "answer": "<p><em>Across the disorders Davis covered, which are systemic and which are organ-specific, and what defines each?</em></p><p>THE ROSTER. Davis grouped the lecture&#x27;s diseases into systemic (rheumatoid arthritis, autoimmune hemolytic anemia, Guillain-Barré) and organ-specific (vitiligo, Crohn disease, ulcerative colitis). Each has a defining lesion: RA = symmetric inflammatory arthritis (citrullinated-peptide and rheumatoid-factor immune complexes); AIHA = antibody-mediated RBC destruction; Guillain-Barré = acute ascending paralysis from anti-ganglioside mimicry; vitiligo = CTL-mediated melanocyte destruction (depigmentation); Crohn/UC = the two forms of inflammatory bowel disease. Roughly 3% of the population is affected, women 2:1.</p><p>Systemic: RA, AIHA, Guillain-Barré. Organ-specific: vitiligo, Crohn, UC. Each has a defining lesion — match the disease to its target tissue and effector.</p><p>Systemic vs organ-specific: systemic = RA, AIHA, Guillain-Barré; organ-specific = vitiligo, Crohn disease, ulcerative colitis.</p><p>Autoimmune disease arises from failure to develop tolerance OR dysregulation that breaks tolerance; the response is chronic because self-antigen cannot be removed.</p><p>Examples of autoimmune disorders: Sjögren, scleroderma, celiac, Behçet, T1D, atrophic gastritis, psoriasis, MS, IBD, Guillain-Barré, ALPS, pemphigus vulgaris. ~3% of the US population, 2:1 female bias.</p><p>ReClaude A: Davis grouped the diseases as systemic (rheumatoid arthritis, autoimmune hemolytic anemia, Guillain-Barré) or organ-specific (vitiligo, Crohn disease, ulcerative colitis); each is defined by its target tissue and dominant effector — e.g. RA by citrullinated-peptide/RF immune complexes in joints, vitiligo by CTL destruction of melanocytes.</p><p><em>A patient has IBD — what location, depth, and bleeding pattern tell you Crohn disease from ulcerative colitis?</em></p><p>THE CROHN vs UC DISTINCTION (Davis&#x27;s explicit focus). She taught these two side by side &quot;because it can be very confusing as to which one somebody has.&quot; Sort them on three axes: location, depth, and bleeding. Crohn disease: any GI segment, mouth to anus (often the terminal ileum/proximal colon junction), skip lesions, transmural (full bowel-wall thickness → cobblestoning, strictures, thickened wall/mesentery), and rectal bleeding is rare with more continuous pain. Ulcerative colitis: limited to the colon and rectum, spreads continuously from the rectum proximally, involves only the mucosa/submucosa, and rectal bleeding is characteristic with intermittent pain that coincides with bowel movements.</p><p>Crohn: mouth-to-anus, transmural, cobblestone, rectal bleeding RARE. UC: colon/rectum continuous-from-rectum, mucosa/submucosa, rectal bleeding CHARACTERISTIC. Location + depth + bleeding. (Crohn vs UC clinical)</p><p>Crohn disease lesions: crypt inflammation/abscesses → focal aphthoid ulcers → &quot;cobblestone&quot; appearance; transmural spread thickens the bowel wall and mesentery.</p><p>Ulcerative colitis: chronic inflammatory disorder of the colonic mucosa, usually beginning in the rectum and extending proximally in a continuous manner.</p><p>Crohn vs UC comparison: Crohn = any GI segment (mouth→anus), transmural, rectal bleeding rare, continuous pain, NOD2 link, IL-21→granzyme-B+ B cells. UC = colon/rectum, mucosa/submucosa, rectal bleeding characteristic, intermittent pain, elevated TNF-α, atypical Th2/NKT IL-4/IL-13.</p><p>OTHER DEFINING FEATURES. RA: symmetric inflammatory arthritis, typically older onset; ~40% have extra-articular disease (skin, eyes, lungs, heart, kidneys, vessels — including vasculitis with petechial hemorrhages). Vitiligo: patchy depigmentation of skin/hair (non-segmental = symmetric/bilateral, more common; segmental = one area); ~50% appear before age 20, and onset after 40 links to autoimmune thyroid disease. Guillain-Barré: acute, progressive, usually temporary ascending paralysis after an antecedent infection, with autonomic dysfunction (arrhythmia, respiratory failure) in two-thirds.</p><p>Rheumatoid arthritis: ~40% of patients have extra-articular symptoms — skin, eyes, lungs, heart, kidneys, salivary glands, blood vessels, bone marrow.</p><p>Vitiligo: melanocyte destruction → patchy depigmentation of skin and hair follicles; non-segmental (symmetric, more common) vs segmental (one area).</p><p>Guillain-Barré: acute, progressive, monophasic paralytic neuropathy after a causative infection (most often C. jejuni); autonomic dysfunction in two-thirds (ileus, arrhythmia, respiratory failure).</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> Crohn vs UC on three axes — location (Crohn anywhere mouth→anus / UC colon-rectum), depth (Crohn transmural / UC mucosa-submucosa), bleeding (Crohn rare / UC characteristic).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Rectal bleeding is the fast discriminator. Characteristic in UC, rare in Crohn. Pair it with &quot;continuous from the rectum, mucosa-only&quot; (UC) vs &quot;skip lesions, transmural, cobblestone&quot; (Crohn).</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Crohn = &quot;Cobblestone, full-thickness, anywhere.&quot; UC = &quot;continUous, colon-only, bleeds.&quot; NOD2 is associated with both (so it does not distinguish them).</p><p>ReClaude A: In Crohn disease the inflammation can occur anywhere from mouth to anus (often the ileocolic junction), is transmural (producing cobblestoning and strictures), and rarely causes rectal bleeding, with more continuous pain. Ulcerative colitis is confined to the colon and rectum, spreads continuously from the rectum, involves only mucosa/submucosa, and characteristically causes rectal bleeding with intermittent pain — so location, depth, and bleeding pattern separate them.</p><p><em>For AIHA, vitiligo, Crohn, and UC, which effector arm does the damage — and which detail distinguishes Crohn&#x27;s mechanism from UC&#x27;s?</em></p><p>AIHA — IgG vs IgM determines the death pathway. Autoantibodies against RBC antigens cause destruction two ways: IgG → mostly Fc-receptor-mediated opsonization by splenic macrophages (the Fc protrudes, macrophages grab it), though IgG can fix complement; IgM → mostly complement fixation → MAC lysis. Drug-induced AIHA works by haptenation (the drug — cephalosporins now most common, IV penicillin, methyldopa, insulin — binds the RBC → IgG → splenic opsonization). About half of AIHA is idiopathic; the rest is secondary (neoplasm, infection, RA/SLE, drugs).</p><p>AIHA: IgG → opsonization (splenic macrophages, FcγR); IgM → complement/MAC lysis. Drug-induced = haptenation → IgG → opsonization. RhoGAM context: anti-D IgG crosses placenta (HDN); ABO antibodies are IgM (don&#x27;t cross). (AIHA mechanism)</p><p>AIHA: antibodies against RBC membrane antigens (e.g. Rh) — autoantibodies (autoimmune) or alloantibodies received from a donor (alloimmune) — accelerate RBC removal/destruction.</p><p>AIHA: IgG autoantibodies → Fc-receptor-mediated opsonization in spleen/liver (can also fix complement); IgM autoantibodies → complement activation → MAC lysis (less common with IgG).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Drug-induced AIHA: haptenation of a drug to the RBC surface generates IgG → Fc-receptor-mediated opsonization by splenic macrophages. Common drugs: cephalosporins (most common now), IV penicillin, methyldopa, insulin.</p><p>VITILIGO — CTLs do the damage. A trigger makes melanocytes express altered self-antigens/DAMPs (heat-shock proteins) during apoptosis; APCs present these to CD4 and CD8 T cells. CD4 cells release pro-inflammatory cytokines and B cells make anti-melanocyte antibodies — but the main effector is the CD8+ CTL, permitted by downregulated regulatory T cells that normally restrain it. Guillain-Barré is anti-ganglioside molecular mimicry (post-C. jejuni), with γδ T cells prominent because the trigger is mucosal/GI.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Vitiligo: a trigger makes melanocytes express altered self-antigens and DAMPs (histones, ATP, uric acid, heat-shock proteins) during apoptosis; APCs present them to CD8 and CD4 T cells.</p><p>Vitiligo: B cells make anti-melanocyte antibodies and CD4 cells release pro-inflammatory cytokines, but CTLs are the MAIN effector damaging melanocytes (Tregs are downregulated, removing the brake).</p><p>Guillain-Barré mechanism: cross-reactive antibodies to a C. jejuni epitope (molecular mimicry) bind nerve cells; T cells, B cells, macrophages, and complement participate, with γδ T cells prominent. CROHN vs UC — the mechanistic split (the key INTEGRATE). Crohn disease: Th1/Th17-driven inflammation against luminal bacteria, with innate involvement — NOD2 mutations and MUC2 variants (less mucus) — overproduced IL-12/IL-23/IL-34/TNF-α, and a signature step: IL-21 converts B cells into granzyme-B-expressing (cytotoxic) B cells that damage the mucosa. Ulcerative colitis: an atypical Th2 response by non-classical NKT cells (recognize lipid on CD1) producing IL-4 and IL-13; IL-13 is cytotoxic to epithelium (apoptosis, disrupted tight junctions) and feeds back to amplify the NKT cells, while MadCAM-1 recruits leukocytes and TNF-α is elevated in blood/stool.</p><p>Crohn = Th1/Th17, NOD2/MUC2, IL-21→granzyme-B+ B cells. UC = atypical Th2 via non-classical NKT (IL-4/IL-13), IL-13 cytotoxic + self-amplifying, MadCAM-1, TNF-α elevated. (NOD2 is in both.) (Crohn vs UC mechanism)</p><p>Crohn disease: overproduced IL-12/IL-23/IL-34/TNF-α (IL-34 highest in active inflammation); IL-21 converts B cells into granzyme-B-expressing cytotoxic B cells that damage the intestinal mucosa.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Ulcerative colitis: reduced mucin, disrupted tight junctions; atypical Th2 response by non-classic NKT cells producing IL-4 and IL-13; IL-13 is cytotoxic to epithelium (apoptosis, altered tight junctions).</p><p>UC: pro-inflammatory cytokines upregulate adhesion molecules like MadCAM-1 on mucosal vessels, capturing leukocytes and promoting extravasation — perpetuating the inflammatory cycle.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> One effector per disease: AIHA = IgG opsonization / IgM complement; vitiligo = CD8 CTL; GBS = anti-ganglioside antibody (γδ T cells); Crohn = Th1/Th17 + granzyme-B+ B cells; UC = atypical Th2/NKT (IL-4/IL-13).</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Crohn vs UC mechanism: Th1/Th17 + NOD2 + IL-21→granzyme-B+ B cells = Crohn; atypical Th2 via non-classical NKT (IL-4/IL-13, IL-13 cytotoxic) = UC. The Th-bias flips between the two.</p><p><strong>Clinical pearl:</strong> AIHA isotype rule reuses the antibody-valence logic: IgG (2 arms) → opsonization; IgM (pentamer, complement-efficient) → MAC lysis. Same rule explains why ABO (IgM) doesn&#x27;t cross the placenta but anti-D (IgG) does.</p><p>ReClaude A: AIHA: IgG drives Fc-receptor opsonization by splenic macrophages while IgM fixes complement for MAC lysis. Vitiligo: CD8 CTLs are the main effector (Tregs downregulated), despite CD4 cytokines and anti-melanocyte antibodies. Crohn disease is Th1/Th17-driven with NOD2/MUC2 variants and IL-21-induced granzyme-B+ cytotoxic B cells; ulcerative colitis is an atypical Th2 response via non-classical NKT cells making IL-4/IL-13 (IL-13 cytotoxic to epithelium) with MadCAM-1 recruitment — so the Th-bias and signature cells distinguish the two IBDs.</p>",
  "why": ""
 },
 "99_61": {
  "answer": "<p><em>A neonate has truncus arteriosus, hypocalcemic seizures, dysmorphic facies, and &lt;1% CD3 with normal B cells — what is it, and why are vaccine antibodies low?</em></p><p>THE PRESENTATION + LABS. A term neonate with low birth weight develops feeding difficulty, cyanosis, and a severe heart defect (truncus arteriosus), then seizures at 4 days. Dysmorphic facies (low-set ears, small &quot;fish mouth,&quot; undersized jaw). Labs: low calcium, very low PTH, severe T-cell lymphopenia (CD3+ &lt;1%), and normal CD19+ B cells. This is DiGeorge syndrome, a 22q11.2 deletion affecting structures from that region: the heart (truncus arteriosus), the parathyroids (low PTH → hypocalcemia → seizures, which is why the seizures are metabolic, not neurologic — a normal neuro exam and no response to anti-epileptics), and the thymus.</p><p>LOCALIZING THE DEFECT. CD3 marks all mature T cells, so CD3 &lt;1% with normal B cells localizes the problem to the thymus: thymic aplasia/hypoplasia prevents T-cell maturation, and because both CD4 and CD8 lineages mature in the thymus, both are reduced. The marrow is fine, so B cells are normal. (X-ray shows an absent or small thymic shadow.)</p><p>DiGeorge = 22q11.2 deletion → heart (truncus arteriosus) + parathyroid (low PTH → hypocalcemic seizures) + thymus (CD3 &lt;1%, both CD4 &amp; CD8 low). B cells normal. (DiGeorge diagnosis)</p><p>Case 4: dysmorphic facial features — low-set ears, small &quot;fish mouth,&quot; undersized lower jaw; very low/absent vaccine antibodies.</p><p>Case 4 labs: low calcium (6.2 mg/dL), very low PTH, severe T-cell lymphopenia (CD3 &lt;1%), normal naive CD19+ B cells.</p><p>Case 4 presentation: term neonate with low birth weight, feeding difficulty, cyanosis, severe heart defect (truncus arteriosus), and seizures at 4 days of age.</p><p>WHY LOW VACCINE ANTIBODIES (the recurring CD4-help thread). Even with normal B cells, antibody titers are low because there is no CD4+ T-cell help to drive B cells into plasma cells — the same &quot;no CD4 help → no antibody&quot; logic that explains why BLS-I (which keeps CD4) makes good vaccine antibody but DiGeorge does not. MANAGEMENT: thymic transplant is the definitive long-term fix (restoring T-cell development); supportive IVIg (compensating for absent CD4-dependent antibody), prophylactic antibiotics, and inactivated vaccines bridge until transplant.</p><p>Case 4 management: prophylactic antibiotics, IVIg, thymic transplant (the definitive solution for the T-cell defect), and inactivated vaccines.</p><p>Case 4 diagnosis: DiGeorge syndrome (22q11.2 deletion) — the deleted region governs heart and parathyroid development; low PTH → low calcium → seizures. Vaccine antibodies are low from lack of CD4 help.</p><p>Case 4 course: at 6 months still below normal weight and behind on milestones; neuro exam normal with no CNS inflammation — confirming the seizures were metabolic (hypocalcemia), not neurologic.</p><p><strong>Key:</strong> DiGeorge is the T-cell case: 22q11.2 deletion → cardiac (truncus arteriosus) + parathyroid (low PTH/Ca → seizures) + thymic aplasia (CD3 &lt;1%, both CD4 and CD8). B cells normal.</p><p><strong>Confusion:</strong> Low antibody despite normal B cells = no CD4 help. This is why DiGeorge has LOW vaccine titers but BLS-I (CD4 intact) has HIGH ones — the same rule, opposite outcomes.</p><p><strong>Cue:</strong> Metabolic seizures: hypocalcemia from low PTH, with a normal neuro exam and no response to anti-epileptics. The definitive fix is a thymic transplant; IVIg/antibiotics bridge to it.</p><p>ReClaude A: The neonate has DiGeorge syndrome: a 22q11.2 deletion produces the cardiac (truncus arteriosus), parathyroid (low PTH → hypocalcemia → seizures), and thymic (aplasia → CD3 &lt;1%, both CD4 and CD8 low; normal B cells) triad. Vaccine antibodies are low because, without CD4 help, normal B cells still cannot be driven to make antibody — the inverse of BLS-I, which keeps CD4 and makes antibody well. Thymic transplant is the definitive treatment, with IVIg and antibiotics as a bridge.</p>",
  "why": ""
 }
};

