      "This is Davis's lymph-node-as-lymphocyte-bar point. Adaptive responses don't initiate at the site of injury — they initiate in the lymph node that drains the site. Dendritic cells in tissue pick up antigen, migrate through afferent lymphatics, and arrive in the draining node's paracortex (T-cell zone). Naive T cells entering the node via HEVs sample DCs and find their specific antigen there. The regional drainage for the left upper extremity is the left axillary nodes, which is why the tender node sits there. A — wrong because tissue can host effector activity, but naive lymphocyte priming happens in lymph nodes, not at the wound itself. B — wrong because the bone marrow is where lymphocytes are produced, not where antigen-specific responses are initiated. C — wrong because the spleen filters blood-borne antigen; tissue-borne antigen from a finger drains to lymph nodes, not the spleen. E — wrong because the thymus selects T cells against self-antigens during ontogeny — it doesn't initiate responses against foreign antigens encountered postnatally. [LO 1.4 — Roles of blood and the lymphatic system in immunity]",
