      0,
      "IL-8 (CXCL8) is the prototypical CXC chemokine - its single job is neutrophil chemotaxis. It binds CXCR1 and CXCR2 on neutrophils to direct them up a concentration gradient toward the infection site. IL-8 is made by macrophages, endothelial cells, and epithelial cells at infection sites. The pus in an abscess is the visible result: dead neutrophils + bacteria + tissue debris. (Note: TNF-α activates the endothelium upstream, which is necessary for neutrophil arrest, but the chemoattractant signal is IL-8.) B - wrong because TNF-α activates endothelium and drives fever/cachexia, but it's not the chemoattractant for neutrophils. It supports the recruitment process but doesn't pull cells along a gradient. C - wrong because IL-6 drives hepatocyte acute phase response, not neutrophil chemotaxis. D - wrong because IL-12 drives Th1 polarization in lymph nodes - adaptive shaping, not neutrophil recruitment. E - wrong because type I IFN installs antiviral state in neighbor cells - antiviral, not antineutrophil-recruitment. [LO 3.4 - Effector functions of TNF-α, IL-1β, IL-6, IL-8, type I IFN]",
      "basic"
