      1,
      "Local TNF-α is helpful. Tissue macrophages release TNF-α at the infection site → adjacent endothelium activates → upregulates selectins (E-selectin, P-selectin) and ICAM-1 for leukocyte rolling and arrest → increases vascular permeability so plasma proteins (complement, antibody) can enter the tissue and dilute toxins → directs neutrophil recruitment via IL-8 gradient. The cardinal signs of inflammation (calor, rubor, tumor, dolor) follow. This is the SAME molecule that drives septic shock when released systemically - Gregg's 'dose makes the poison' point. A - wrong because DIC + hypotension + MOF is the SYSTEMIC TNF-α picture (septic shock), the WRONG/HARMFUL outcome. C - wrong because TNF can drive apoptosis in some contexts but not as the canonical local inflammatory response. D - wrong because TNF causes vasoDILATION (warmth, redness), not vasoconstriction. Systemic vasodilation contributes to septic hypotension. E - wrong because endothelial detachment and platelet plugs aren't the canonical local TNF response; that resembles vascular injury, not inflammation. [LO 3.5 - Local vs systemic TNF-α]",
