      "NETosis: neutrophils extrude webs of decondensed chromatin studded with granule contents (elastase, MPO, defensins, histones) — NETs trap microbes for adjacent killing. Cost: neutrophil death + exposure of self-DNA and histones. In healthy hosts, DNase I clears NETs quickly. In lupus, defective NET clearance (often due to DNase I dysfunction) lets self-DNA + histones persist, driving anti-dsDNA and anti-histone antibody production. Same mechanism contributes to antiphospholipid syndrome (exposed nucleosomes drive autoantibody responses). A — wrong because classical apoptosis is non-inflammatory, with membrane-bound apoptotic bodies — doesn't extrude chromatin webs externally. B — wrong because necrosis is passive plasma-membrane rupture, not programmed chromatin extrusion. D — wrong because pyroptosis (gasdermin D-mediated) is inflammasome-driven inflammatory death — doesn't produce chromatin webs. E — wrong because ferroptosis is iron-dependent lipid peroxidation — different mechanism entirely, no chromatin extrusion. [LO 4.5 — NETosis and its role]",
