      "This is the canonical innate feedback loop: macrophage IL-12 → NK cells → IFN-γ → macrophage M1 polarization. IL-12 from PAMP-detecting macrophages activates NK cells, which release IFN-γ. IFN-γ binds the macrophage IFN-γR → STAT1 → super-activates the macrophage: enhanced phagocytosis, enhanced respiratory burst, increased MHC II, MORE IL-12 → loop closes. This is the cellular handoff that bridges innate killing to Th1-driven adaptive killing — every Th1 question on Lec 11/12 reuses this circuit. Loss of IL-12 or IFN-γ signaling → susceptibility to intracellular mycobacteria. A — wrong because IL-1β is an inflammasome-derived cytokine; TNF-α is a macrophage product, not an NK product. Wrong pair. B — wrong because IL-4 + IL-13 is the Th2 axis (allergy, parasites), not NK-macrophage. D — wrong because IL-6 + IL-17 is the Th17 axis (mucosal bacteria + fungi), not NK-macrophage. E — wrong because TGF-β + IL-10 are regulatory cytokines (suppressive), not the activating loop. [LO 4.8 — NK cell activation and macrophage collaboration]",
