      "Primary (azurophilic) granules carry the heaviest weaponry — MPO, defensins, elastase, BPI, lysozyme — and are released LAST, at the kill site or directly into the phagolysosome. The release sequence (tertiary → secondary → primary) intentionally puts the most destructive contents last to minimize collateral damage to host tissue during transit. 'Azurophilic' refers to their staining color (deep purple-blue with azure dye), reflecting their dense protein content. Primary granules are essentially modified lysosomes. A — wrong because tertiary granules carry gelatinase (MMP-9) for basement-membrane breakdown, released during ROLLING — earliest, not at the kill site. B — wrong because secondary granules carry lactoferrin, lysozyme, and NADPH oxidase precursors — released during transmigration, not at the final kill step. D — wrong because recycling endosomes are general cellular machinery, not microbicidal granules. E — wrong because lipid droplets supply arachidonic acid for lipid mediators, not microbicidal proteins. [LO 4.4 — Neutrophil granules]",
