      "A hapten is a small molecule (typically <1 kDa) that binds an antigen receptor but cannot induce an immune response by itself — it's an antigen but NOT an immunogen until it's coupled to a carrier protein. Once conjugated, the protein provides T-cell epitopes (linear peptides for MHC II presentation) while the hapten provides the B-cell-binding determinant. Classic examples: urushiol (poison ivy → type IV hypersensitivity), penicillin metabolites (drug allergy after binding RBC surface), nickel (contact dermatitis after binding skin proteins). The two-day delay + vesicular rash is the type IV (delayed) hypersensitivity tell. A — wrong because superantigens are bacterial toxins (TSST-1, SPE) that bridge MHC II and TCR Vβ — completely different mechanism, polyclonal T-cell activation. B — wrong because mitogens are TLR ligands (LPS, PHA, ConA) that drive polyclonal proliferation — not the carrier-conjugation mechanism here. D — wrong because heterophile antigens are cross-reactive between species (strep M protein ↔ cardiac myosin); urushiol isn't cross-reacting with self. E — wrong because alloantigens are differences within a species (MHC variation, blood groups) — not the small-molecule + carrier mechanism. [LO 6.1 — Antigen / immunogen / epitope definitions]",
