      "Invariant chain (Ii / CD74) is the molecular chaperone that (1) blocks the MHC II peptide-binding groove during ER assembly to prevent inappropriate binding of ER-resident peptides (which are intended for MHC I), and (2) provides a trafficking signal that directs the MHC II + Ii complex from the ER through the Golgi to the MIIC compartment. In the MIIC, cathepsins progressively cleave Ii down to a short stub called CLIP (Class II-associated Invariant chain Peptide) that remains lodged in the groove. HLA-DM then catalyzes CLIP exchange for antigenic peptides. A — wrong because calnexin holds nascent MHC I, not MHC II. B — wrong because tapasin is part of the MHC I loading complex (bridges MHC I to TAP), not MHC II. D — wrong because HLA-DM catalyzes CLIP/peptide exchange in the MIIC, AFTER Ii has already done its job. HLA-DM doesn't protect the groove from the start. E — wrong because β2-microglobulin is the light chain of MHC CLASS I, not class II. MHC II is α + β heterodimer without β2m. [LO 7.2 — Invariant chain function]",
