      0,
      "Cytokine → isotype mapping: IL-4 (Th2) → IgG1 and IgE (allergy, antiparasitic responses); IFN-γ (Th1) → IgG2/IgG3 (opsonization, complement fixation, antibacterial/antiviral); TGF-β + IL-5 (mucosal) → IgA (mucosal secretion, dimeric with J chain); IL-21 → IgG1. The Th2 axis drives IgE: IL-4 from Th2 → AID acts on the Sε switch region → B cell switches to produce IgE. Newly switched IgE then binds FcεRI on tissue mast cells, arming them for allergen-triggered degranulation. This is the mechanistic basis of allergic atopy — high IL-4 → high IgE → primed mast cells → wheeze, urticaria, anaphylaxis. B — wrong because IFN-γ drives IgG2/IgG3 (antibacterial), not IgE. C — wrong because TGF-β + IL-5 drives IgA (mucosal), not IgE. D — wrong because IL-12 drives Th1 polarization; not a direct CSR-driving cytokine for IgE. E — wrong because TNF-α doesn't drive isotype switching to IgD; IgD switching is rare and not TNF-α driven. [LO 9.4 — Cytokine-isotype mapping]",
      "basic"
