      "TCRs are MHC-restricted — every functional TCR must recognize self-MHC + non-self peptide. Random somatic hypermutation of the TCR variable region would risk breaking the self-MHC contact (loss of function — no more presentation recognition) or creating self-reactivity (mutated TCR now binds self-peptide too tightly → autoimmunity). The safer strategy is to fix TCR specificity at thymic ontogeny (where positive and negative selection enforce safe self-MHC binding) and never retouch it. TCRs also lack effector diversification (no antibody-style classes like IgM/IgG/IgA/IgE) so there's no need for class switching either. BCRs can mutate because they bind antigen directly, without MHC restriction; mutations affect only antigen binding, not MHC interaction. A — wrong because RAG is silenced in mature T cells but the reason no SHM happens isn't 'no RAG'; SHM uses AID, not RAG. The real reason is the MHC-restriction risk. B — wrong because CD40L IS on activated T helper cells; the asymmetry isn't about CD40L absence. D — wrong because T cells DO enter germinal centers — as follicular helper T cells (Tfh) — they just don't undergo SHM themselves. E — wrong because TCR gene loci lacking S regions is downstream of why; the deeper reason is the MHC-restriction risk. [LO 9.4 — Why TCRs don't undergo SHM]",
