      3,
      "IL-4 from Th2 cells drives B-cell class switching to IgE (and IgG1). The mechanism: IL-4 binds IL-4Rα on B cells → STAT6 activation → induces AID activity at the Sε switch region → CSR from μ to ε → B cell makes IgE. IgE then binds FcεRI on tissue mast cells, arming them. On allergen reencounter, allergen crosslinks the mast cell's surface IgE → mast cell degranulation → release of histamine, tryptase, leukotrienes, prostaglandins → immediate-phase allergic response (urticaria, wheeze, bronchospasm). Th2 axis biologics for severe asthma: dupilumab (anti-IL-4Rα), omalizumab (anti-IgE), mepolizumab (anti-IL-5) — each cuts a different node of the Th2 → IgE → mast cell / eosinophil axis. A — wrong because IFN-γ drives IgG2/IgG3 (Th1 isotypes for opsonization), not IgE. B — wrong because IL-17 recruits neutrophils but doesn't drive isotype switching. C — wrong because TGF-β drives suppressive responses and can drive IgA at mucosal surfaces, but doesn't drive IgE class switching. E — wrong because IL-2 is T-cell autocrine growth factor; doesn't drive B-cell isotype switching. [LO 12.2 — IL-4 → IgE class switching]",
      "basic"
